<SLUG> BC-GORE-VISITS-VALLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BACKS AFTER-SCHOOL PROGRAMS FOR L.A. YOUTHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID R. BAKER and PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Saying the nation needs to better educate and
protect its latchkey kids, Vice President Al Gore called for the
creation of more after-school programs while speaking at Sutter
Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pointed to the success of Los Angeles after-school programs
as he addressed about 900 teachers, students, parents and public
officials Saturday at the invitation-only event in the suburban
Winnetka school's shaded quad. He pushed President Clinton's
proposal to spend $1 billion during the next five years on programs
that keep children occupied and supervised before their parents
return home from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make this available to every child in every
school,'' Gore said, adding that such programs cut juvenile crime
and keep children away from drugs and alcohol. ``This ought to be
the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit to Winnetka was followed by a luncheon at the
suburban Calabasas home of Democratic fund-raiser Sim Farar,
attended by guests including actress Sally Field and singer Nancy
Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as as a ``town-hall meeting,'' the hourlong school event
drew children and parents, educators and elected officials. Among
them were Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., and Rep. Brad Sherman,
D-Woodland Hills, both of whom added their own pitches for
after-school programs, as did Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman
Block.
</P>
<P>
   They cited FBI statistics showing that most juvenile crime takes
place between 3 and 8 p.m., and praised the ability of after-school
programs to give students individual attention and bolster their
studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I visit these programs, I get choked up, because I
see these kids are getting what they need,'' Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience were sold on Gore's idea. Teachers and
school administrators from as far as Orange County arrived eager to
tout their own school districts' programs.
</P>
<P>
   One 17-year-old student from nearby Chatsworth High School
agreed with Gore's call for more after-school activities. While
some youths Scott A. Davis knows are experimenting with drugs, he
said his afternoons are taken up with volleyball at his school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volleyball practice runs into that danger time,'' Davis told
the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to promoting the need for more after-school
programs, Gore announced that the Los Angeles Unified School
District will receive more than $8 million for earthquake safety
work. The money will be used to brace bookcases and coat windows
with safety film to prevent flying glass.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the meeting involved Gore asking the audience to share
experiences and ideas while he acted as master of ceremonies. He
listened as Alesia Mayfield, a biology teacher at Inglewood High
School, described a program in which her students drafted disaster
plans for the city of Inglewood, near West Los Angeles, using a
grant from the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're setting our sights too low,'' Gore said. ``Maybe
next you'll take on world peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those in the audience, however, aimed their questions at
Gore. Speaking in Spanish through an interpreter, A. Cortes of
South Central Los Angeles asked what the federal government would
do in the wake of Proposition 227, which all but ended bilingual
education programs in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this program will help our children to become better
citizens in the future,'' Cortes said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded that the administration would work within the
limits of the new law to provide the best education possible for
children with limited English skills. But he said he believes the
one-year, English-immersion course required under the new law will
be too short to fully prepare students for learning in English-only
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe three years is the minimum,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The town-hall meeting was just one part of the Clinton
administration's efforts to bolster after-school programs. U.S.
Department of Education officials are also coordinating efforts
among teams of school administrators, law enforcement officials,
teachers and parents throughout Southern California to create plans
for expanding such programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fund-raising luncheon in Calabasas kept traffic busy on
Aspen Way, a small cul-de-sac in a gated community near Mulholland
Highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time the vice president has ever done a
fund-raiser in the San Fernando Valley,'' Farar said. The luncheon
included about 30 guests.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, about three dozen residents -- including
scores of children -- set up lawn chairs or sat on the curb to
watch Gore and the celebrities arrive.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd clapped and cheered as Gore walked in the house, and
residents said he crossed the street and shook their hands after
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sounds like a pretty good politician, but I don't know
exactly what vice presidents do,'' said 13-year-old Lisa Schopler,
who lives down the street from Farar.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors have gotten used to celebrities on their quiet street.
Farar has had other famous guests, and rapper Mack-10 moved into
the largest house on the block earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Service agents roamed, politely asking residents to stay
on their own property.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more guys with plugs in their ears than when Ted
Kennedy came last year,'' next-door neighbor Karl Reinecker said,
packing up his folding chair.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
