<SLUG> BC-GROWTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH INITIATIVE HITS TWIN ICEBERGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 and MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed like the unsinkable plan: Slapping tough controls on
uncontrolled growth.
</P>
<P>
   All the polls showed tremendous public support for a ballot
initiative to fight sprawl. It struck so much fear into business
interests and lawmakers that they put together their own competing
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But the environmentalists' plan to manage growth suddenly sank
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to collect enough signatures by the July 2 filing
deadline, they called off their petition drive to put the Citizens
Growth Management Initiative on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   It hit two icebergs: Time and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so disappointing and what's so frustrating is we know
this would be successful if it was on the ballot,'' said Sandy
Bahr, conservation coordinator for the local chapter of the Sierra
Club. ``All we needed was for one or two people to come through
early with some additional funds.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Titanic, the growth management initiative isn't
permanently scuttled.
</P>
<P>
   Right after the November elections, as soon as it's legal to
start, environmentalists say they'll launch a petition drive to put
the measure on the ballot in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we've learned is that our proposal is solid,'' said
Peter Martori, chairman of Citizens for Growth Management, the
umbrella group supporting the initiative. ``It has the basic
elements that the public is going to support.'' &QL; 
LINE IN THE SAND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, though, he fears that developers will rush to
get projects approved and bulldozers will blade away more of the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   The growth-management initiative draws a line in the sand.
Cities and counties would have to set boundaries to limit urban
sprawl, subject to voter approval. Developers would have to
shoulder the full cost of roads, schools and other new public
facilities that serve their projects. Services could not be
extended beyond the growth boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Center for Law in the Public Interest, the Sierra
Club and others worried about growth began working on the
initiative three years ago. Last year, they passed around drafts of
the initiative to a wide range of people, continually tweaking the
ideas and language.
</P>
<P>
   The target for kicking off their signature drive was the end of
1997, but the revisions dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were still fiddling around in February,'' said Pete Chasar,
a Phoenix activist. ``We should have had it finished by the end of
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The petition drive wasn't launched until March 2. That left just
four months in which to gather 113,000 signatures _ plus a healthy
cushion of names to make up for any signatures that might be
invalidated.  &QL; 
PLEASING TOO MANY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, we shouldn't have spent as long as we did trying
to get so many different groups happy with the language,'' said
Chris Gehlker, a member of the steering committee for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, the group wasted a month haggling over
language about subdivisions in the hopes of winning the Nature
Conservancy's support. When the changes were finally made, the
group explained that it doesn't make political endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney David Baron, the principal author of the initiative,
argued that it was worthwhile taking so much time for feedback on a
complex issue.
</P>
<P>
   The real question, to him, was whether it made sense to shoot
for this November's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``One might argue that we should have waited until 2000, given
the time that was left,'' said Baron, assistant director of the
Center for Law in the Public Interest.
</P>
<P>
   But he worried that people wouldn't be able to focus on a
proposal that far into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Time hurt the proposal on another front.
</P>
<P>
   Many potential supporters sat on their hands as the Legislature
worked on its own growth plan. That in itself took months.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people felt the Legislature might do something good''
so they were reluctant to lend support or dip into their wallets,
the Sierra Club's Bahr said.  &QL; 
`GROWING SMARTER' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers made no secret that one of their goals was to derail
the environmentalists' initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature finally approved a plan, called Growing Smarter,
3{ weeks ago. It requires communities to adopt general plans every
10 years with specific points, such as strategies for efficient
transportation and well-timed expansion of sewers, streets and
other infrastructure. Developers must pay their fair share of the
cost of new services for the their projects, but not the entire
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Growing Smarter includes a ballot measure: Voters will decide in
November whether to spend $20 million a year to preserve state
trust land, which might otherwise be developed. The money would be
available for 11 years as matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Baier, a policy adviser to Gov. Jane Hull, speculates that
the environmentalists pulled out partly because it was ``a pretty
intimidating prospect'' to go up against Growing Smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hull pushed Growing Smarter, and the business community was
cranking up a massive campaign for it. To complicate the fight,
Growing Smarter contains a ``poison pill,'' killing its funding if
the growth-management initiative also won.  &QL; 
TIME, MONEY RUN OUT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bahr, however, says many saw Growing Smarter as toothless once
it passed, and the money began pouring in for the
environmentalists. But time had run out.
</P>
<P>
   And the piggybank was nearly empty.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Citizens Growth Management Initiative had
commitments for $150,000. The latest financial report, to be filed
with the Secretary of State's Office at the end of June, likely
will show they actually raised about $60,000, and have about
$10,000 cash on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Sky-high expectations also hobbled the fund-raising. A private
poll in the fall showed 74 percent support for the initiative. Even
a poll by the Arizona Chamber of Commerce, a chief opponent, showed
heavy support.
</P>
<P>
   Bahr recalled, ``When I started calling people, they were
saying, `My God, you need help? I thought this was a slam dunk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The money was crucial. In Arizona politics, it takes more than
volunteers to gather signatures. It also takes paid circulators,
those folks who sit outside the library or post office with
clipboards of petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Gehlker said that up until the last weekend in May, the group
thought it was on track. &QL; 
PETITION BOMBSHELL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That was when the owner of Lee Petition Management, the company
circulating the petitions, dropped a bombshell: He had only
gathered 7,000 signatures, far less than expected.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he didn't expect to get many more unless the
environmentalists forked out more than the $1.65 per name that they
had budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   Workers get a cut of the price, so there's more incentive to
push the higher-paying causes.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Lee, owner of Lee Petition, confirmed that he said they
would have to pay as much as $3 per signature to reach their goal.
</P>
<P>
   The cost jumped this year, he said, because some candidates are
paying $4 a signature. Plus, the state's robust economy means fewer
workers are available to carry petitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were the only game in town, it would be a different
story,'' Lee said. ``There's just a lot of petitions chasing very
few petitioners.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also suffered from a lack of organization, said
Marcita Ryon, president of the Coalition of Pinnacle Peak, a group
that supported the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   With such a short time frame, supporters should have been
prepared to leap the moment they filed, she said, but ``they didn't
have a plan that I could see.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she said, people were eager to sign the petition,
but few people were circulating them.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign chairman Martori countered that ``a strategy for
getting signatures is not real complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   What eats up time is getting organizations to come on board and
training members to pass petitions.
</P>
<P>
   That work took too long for this election, but Martori predicts
it will pay off for the 2000 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen what groups really have the ability to get people
on the street and run petition drives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He and others say the ballot measure may be tuned up a bit, but
the basics won't change.
</P>
<P>
   Will the public be bored by an extended petition drive?
</P>
<P>
   Not at all, Martori said: ``They're going to still be
experiencing the same stuff that has them upset now. They're paying
the price. This uncontrolled development is eating up the natural
areas they love.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Kathleen Ingley can be reached at 444-8171 or at
kathleen.ingley &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
