<SLUG> BC-BORDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE OF U.S. MILITARY ON BORDER A `TERRIFYING IMAGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER AND MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. House wants to put troops on the Southwest border to
stem the flow of drugs and illegal immigrants, a proposal critics
say would make the region look like ``East Berlin during the Cold
War.''
</P>
<P>
   The House plan has ignited protests from Arizona Gov. Jane Hull
and officials along both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   It authorizes the U.S. military to be dispatched to join with
civilian law enforcement agencies to prevent the entry of
``terrorists, drug traffickers and illegal aliens'' into the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The border is a national security issue, and, by God, the
Congress of the United States better start securing our borders,''
said Rep. James Traficant, D-Ohio, the proposal's author, in a
speech on the House floor. He charged that the Southwest border is
``wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a few politicians in national election campaigns have
called for sending troops to the Mexican border to stem the flow of
immigrants, this is the first time the proposal has actually
approached becoming law. The plan was attached by Traficant to a
$270 billion defense budget bill that was overwhelmingly approved
by the House and will be considered by the Senate this summer _
possibly as soon as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant said his amendment would not deploy troops, but merely
authorize the Pentagon to do so if requested by the U.S. attorney
general or Treasury secretary. The troops, which would ``provide
support'' for the Border Patrol and other agencies, would receive
special law enforcement training and be accompanied by a civilian
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they (the troops) see a narcotics trafficker, they can
tackle them. They can engage,'' Traficant said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would point out that the Customs Service currently is
working hand in hand with the Florida National Guard to inspect
cargo and vehicles at points of entry on Florida. Why not expand
this successful program?''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Nogales and Douglas said they were told by the
state's Congressional delegation that the troop deployment in the
state could be 3,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Traficant's plan is opposed by the Pentagon and Gen. Barry
McCaffrey, the national drug czar. The proposal is likely to come
up Monday, when McCaffrey, a retired four-star general, meets with
Arizona mayors, journalists and law enforcement officials about his
crusade against drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is ``an affront to our relationship with Mexico, and it
wouldn't work,'' said Jim McDonough, a top McCaffrey strategist.
``We could line up every division we have in the U.S. Army and the
Marine Corps put together, and you couldn't cover that
(2,000-mile-long) border.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Mexican officials are waiting for Congress' next move.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Reyes-Heroles, Mexico's ambassador to the U.S., called it
typical election-year posturing and said, ``I'm sure that we will
get more initiatives that are contrary to U.S.-Mexico interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue for the Americans to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyes-Heroles added, ``We cannot ask the U.S. not to enforce its
migratory policies.''
</P>
<P>
   But Traficant's plan has drawn widespread criticism from Gov.
Jane Hull and the state's border cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've protested this in the strongest terms possible,'' said
Ignacio Barraza, Nogales' assistant city administrator.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., Hull wrote that the
prospect of armed, uniformed soldiers patrolling the streets of
border towns ``creates a terrifying image that threatens our very
nature as a peaceful nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull also noted in the letter that the state had worked for
years to strengthen its relationship with the neighboring Mexican
state of Sonora.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permission to militarize the border is unnecessary and
antagonistic to a country that is working to overcome the many
challenges of a developing nation,'' Hull wrote. ``It is a
confrontational action that will gravely impact relations between
the United States and Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Cruz County Board of Supervisors also sent a letter to
McCain questioning why such a move would be considered ``where many
Santa Cruz County families share commerce, work, play and have
family relatives in a connected society.''
</P>
<P>
   Traficant's plan, in the form of an amendment, was approved May
21 on a vote of 288-132 by the House, which then easily passed the
defense bill it was attached to.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Daniels, a spokesman for the U.S. Border Patrol in Tucson,
warns that there could be many problems in a combined effort by the
Border Patrol and military.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jobs and training are awfully different,'' Daniels said.
``But if we do get help, it couldn't be coming at a better time.
There hasn't been a time in recent memory when it's been more
violent on our border.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the Arizona representatives voted against the measure
except Republican Reps. Matt Salmon and John Shadegg, whose
districts are in the Valley. Several lawmakers who represent border
districts _ for example, Rep. Jim Kolbe _ said during the debate
that Traficant, a former county sheriff from Ohio, didn't seem to
realize the implications of his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front line of the war on drugs is just as much in
Youngstown, Ohio, as it is in Nogales, Arizona,'' Kolbe said. ``And
I do not think any of us believe that the 82nd Airborne should be
patrolling the streets of Youngstown, Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Texas, said Traficant's amendment could
make border regions ``look like East Berlin during the Cold War.''
</P>
<P>
   The military already performs a border function, including
intelligence. The Air Force operates aerostats looking for planes,
and the National Guard helps unload trucks so they can inspected at
the border.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say law enforcement is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because people in the military wear uniforms and carry
guns doesn't mean that this (border law enforcement) is either an
appropriate or a wise use of their resources,'' said Chuck
Blanchard, a counsel in the drug czar's office and a former Arizona
state senator. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
