<HEADER>
A8340 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      06-14 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Reds maintain hex on Reynolds, top Astros 7-4
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CINCINNATI _ The Red Plague continues to infect Shane Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   With a lack of success against Cincinnati throughout his career,
the righthander must feel like he's on his deathbed every time he
faces the Reds. There still was no cure evident Saturday night as
the Reds homered three times off Reynolds to send the Astros to
their second straight setback, a 7-4 loss before a crowd of 28,055
at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the Reds' hits went for extra bases, including
back-to-back home runs by Dmitri Young and Bret Boone in a four-run
fifth inning that turned a 3-1 Astros lead into a 5-3 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who surrendered a leadoff home run to Reggie Sanders
on his fourth pitch of the game, had his five-game winning streak
snapped while dropping to 1-8 with a 5.19 ERA lifetime against
Cincinnati. He had not lost a game since May 6 against the Chicago
Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit me pretty good,'' said Reynolds, who had gone 5-0
with a 1.89 ERA in his previous six starts. ``When I do seem to
have a pretty good game against them, their pitcher has a pretty
good game. They are one of those teams that hit you, but a lot of
it was my mistakes, making bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros dropped to 3-2 on their current seven-game road trip
and saw their lead in the National League Central recede to a game
over the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   It was tale of two Reynoldses on Saturday. The good Reynolds
settled down after Sanders' home run to limit Cincinnati to two
hits over the first four innings. The bad Reynolds gave up a
two-out single to Barry Larkin in the fifth and walked Eddie
Taubensee before Young sent a three-run bomb to right field. Two
pitches later, Boone drilled a shot to right, giving the Reds
back-to-back home runs for only the second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (7-4) allowed five runs, seven hits and four walks in a
season-low five innings. Before Saturday, he had pitched six or
more innings in his last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said most of his problems stemmed from falling behind
in the count on a number of occasions. He threw 114 pitches through
five innings before being relieved in the sixth by Trever Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't getting ahead. That's all it was,'' Reynolds said.
``If you get behind on these guys, more times than not they will
hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds was not without support, as the Astros rallied to give
him a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, who has 11 RBIs in his last seven games, tied the
score at 1 in the second inning with a sacrifice fly to left field
that scored Jeff Bagwell, who began the inning with a double.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added two more runs in the third when Craig Biggio
walked and Derek Bell sent a two-run homer 437 feet to straightaway
center field off Reds starter Scott Klingenbeck (1-1), who recorded
his first National League win.
</P>
<P>
   Klingenbeck allowed four runs on five hits in 5 innings as the
Reds won for only the third time in 11 games. But two of those
victories have come against the Astros, who entered the four-game
series on a five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker said it's not unusual for a team like
Cincinnati, which has spent almost the entire season in the NL
Central basement, to rise to the occasion in a big series. The
Reds, who have won three of four meetings with the Astros this
year, have scored 14 runs in two games after being held to eight
runs in their previous six.
</P>
<P>
   But Dierker, who got only 3 innings out of starting pitcher Jose
Lima in Friday's 7-1 loss, weren't prepared to give all the praise
to the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just playing flat,'' Dierker said. ``They look like they
are inspired. That's what we have to face right now because we are
in first place. Every team that plays us is going to get up a
little more than they might ordinarily, and we have to get up with
them. Sometimes you can't always do that. I'm not saying that we
weren't up for the game, but we were just flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty good reminder of how hard it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored their final run in the sixth when Bagwell
doubled down the right-field line and Tony Eusebio delivered a
two-out RBI single to slice the Reds' lead to 5-4. Ricky Gutierrez
walked to put the tying run at second base, but Reds reliever Danny
Graves got pinch hitter J.R. Phillips to fly out to left.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds added two insurance runs in the eighth when Boone hit a
leadoff single, pinch hitter Eduardo Perez singled, and Chris
Stynes doubled home a run off Astros reliever Mike Magnante.
Sanders had a run-scoring groundout to give the Reds a three-run
cushion.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw pitched the ninth inning for his 18th save. He has not
allowed an earned run in his last 19 appearances, a span of 25
innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
