<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGWAR-AZR &LR;      06-14 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGWAR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WEIGHS COORDINATOR FOR DRUG BATLE IN SOUTHWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States, overrun by drug traffic from
Mexico, might assign responsibility for all of its Southwest border
drug-control efforts to a single official, The Republic has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   An ``in-charge'' federal official is needed because
drug-fighting efforts by nearly a dozen federal agencies along the
2,000-mile-long border are disjointed and hampered by inter-service
rivalries, according to top strategists in the office of Gen. Barry
McCaffrey, the national drug czar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come to agreements on who does what and who answers
to whom,'' said Jim McDonough, strategic planning director for
McCaffrey. ``We're going to estab lish, at the end of all this, a
coordinator for along the border, a single person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten primary agencies are battling cocaine, marijuana, methamphet
amine and heroin traffic at 24 border entry points, but no single
individual or agency oversees the ``big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   As traffickers found increasingly sophisticated methods to evade
de tection, seizures of cocaine along the border hit a 10-year low
last year. About 57 percent of the co caine entering the United
States is estimated to cross the Southwest border. Last year,
900,000 U.S.-bound trucks _ about a quarter of the total crossing
the border _ were subjected to drug control inspec tions. Cocaine
was found in just 16.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been prod ding Mexico to aggressively
combat official corruption that hinders its fight against drug
lords. Some in Congress complained that the United States should
have withheld its recent certification of Mexico's drug-fight ing
efforts until further progress was documented.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies _ including the Border Patrol, Customs Service and
Immigration and Naturalization Service _ have been meeting since
the summer of 1996 about border issues. McDonough has set the end
of the summer as a target for finalizing a plan for a border
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably what it's going to be is, Agency X has got it for two
years, then Agency Y has got it for two years. And then there is a
staff under that singular person com prised of representatives of
(various agencies),'' McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created McCaffrey's of fice in 1988 to develop a
drug-con trol strategy. Part of his job is to minimize rivalries
among a host of federal agencies and prod them into better
supporting the drug fight.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey is scheduled to meet Monday with Arizona mayors and
law enforcement officials in the Valley about his crusade against
drugs. The retired, four-star general toured the Southwest border
in August, including a stop at Nogales, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a Southwest border viceroy is derived partly from a
memorandum prepared by the drug czar's office last October
concluding the United States needed to revamp its $1.7
billion-per-year effort to curtail the flow of drugs from Mexico
and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current interdiction efforts almost completely fail to
achieve our purpose of reducing the flow of cocaine, heroine and
methamphet amine across the (Southwest) bor der,'' said the
memorandum, which was given to Congress and to The Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum recommended better accountability and a strategy
emphasizing improved intelligence and high-tech drug-screening
equip ment. A White House task force has been studying U.S.
intelligence ca pabilities on the drug issue and is due to release
its findings June 22.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the drug czar's office said they have found alarm
ing variations in the level of efficient cooperation among federal
departments at the arrival zones. At some entry areas, federal
agencies can't agree on which one should handle even fundamental
tasks _ such as inspecting incoming vehi cles for drugs _ and so
the responsibility is split.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not smart to have one lane handled by Customs, one lane
by INS (as occurs at some entry points),'' McDonough said. ``You
will have different standard operat ing procedures in each lane.''
</P>
<P>
   Cell phone-equipped spotters working for drug traffickers ``can
figure out the pattern of the individ ual agent based on which
agency is responsible for that lane,'' he said. ``A druggie might
say of one agent, `He's a little bit loose looking under the car.'
Better to have a single, effective standard operating proce dure,
which means you put one agency in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   During the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30, $1.7 billion was
spent for federal drug-control activities along the border,
supporting more than 7,700 special agents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
