<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-TE     06-14 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS CRUSH RANGERS, 18-6
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It appears that the Rangers must implement
change.
</P>
<P>
   Their rotation demands it.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Aaron Sele, the collection's most consistent member
this season, sank to the level established by his peers during last
night's 18-6 loss to the Anaheim Angels at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   A prolific offense put the Rangers in first place.
</P>
<P>
   This rotation will apparently pitch the Rangers out of first
place, and that could occur as early as tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, who moved within a half-game of the first-place
Rangers in the American League West, generated a season-best 18
runs with a season-high 21 hits and matched their single-game team
record for doubles with eight.
</P>
<P>
   Sele (9-4) surrendered a good portion of that during his
four-inning appearance. The Rangers' rotation, which entered this
game with the league's third-worst earned-run average (5.62), saw
it rise to 5.72 after Sele's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anything we did very well tonight,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``I'm very disappointed in tonight's
performance. We didn't make a whole lot of good pitches. It was
just one of those nights, and I want to make sure we don't keep
playing that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates apparently had a closed-door meeting with the players
after the lopsided loss in which the Rangers committed three
errors. He refused to comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   Sele surrendered eight runs (seven earned) on seven hits and two
walks and failed to retire any of the six batters the Angels sent
to the plate against him during their seven-run fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, the Angels' No. 9 hitter, went 5-for-5
with two doubles and a triple and drove in four runs. Center
fielder Jim Edmonds collected four hits, including three doubles,
and drove in three runs during his six at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Angels left-hander Jarrod Washburn (2-0) kept the Rangers in
check after a shaky first inning in which he issued two walks,
including one intentional to designated hitter Juan Gonzalez, and
fell victim to an error by DiSarcina.
</P>
<P>
   A two-out walk drawn by right fielder/first baseman Mike Simms
with the bases loaded forced in the Rangers' first run, and
Washburn _ making only his third major-league start _ hurt his
cause by falling behind in the count to catcher Bill Haselman.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' opportunity for a big inning, though, melted in the
Texas heat with the next pitch. Haselman chased a 3-0 pitch out of
the strike zone and produced a harmless fly ball that settled in
the glove of Angels third baseman Dave Hollins for the inning's
final out.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn later would allow sixth- and seventh-inning solo home
runs to Simms and outfielder Roberto Kelly, respectively, but that
became moot after the Angels' seven-run fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won the first two games of this four-game set because
of the performance of their rotation. Right-hander Omar Olivares
surrendered only one run during 6 2/3 innings in Friday's 5-1
victory, and Washburn allowed three runs (two earned) on five hits
during seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander John Burkett and Sele surrendered 13 runs
(12 earned) on 14 hits in 11 2/3 innings during these two games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
