<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-14 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Fedorov scores game-winner to give Wings 3-0 finals lead over Caps
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ For eight games, Sergei Fedorov hardly was living up
to his billing as the $12 million man.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov, the Detroit Red Wings superstar, had scored one goal in
the past eight playoff games before Saturday night. That's hardly
what the Red Wings expected when they signed Fedorov to a contract
in March that had a $12 million bonus clause if Detroit advanced to
the NHL Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings advanced, but Fedorov scored only once in the
six-game victory over the Dallas Stars. He was blanked in the first
two games of the Stanley Cup finals against Washington, even though
Fedorov launched a remarkable 13 shots on goal in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 was a different matter. With the teams tied at 1 late in
the third period, Fedorov moved neatly in on Washington Capitals
goaltender Olaf Kolzig and scored to give the Red Wings a 2-1 win
and commanding 3-0 lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big-time goal by a big-time player,'' said Detroit
coach Scotty Bowman. ``He showed his speed and made a great play.
You could sense something like this was coming from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington overcame a horrific first period in which it was
outshot 13-1 and tied the score at 1 just five minutes before
Fedorov's game-winner. Brian Bellows' power-play goal at 10:35
breathed life into the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov snuffed it out with a nifty move down the right side. He
fired the puck through the legs of Washington defenseman Calle
Johansson and beat Kolzig on the glove side.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't score for a long time, there are a lot of
reasons,'' Fedorov said. ``Tonight, I generated a lot of speed
through the neutral zone and was on top of my game. Dougie (Brown)
threw me the puck, and I let it go on the near side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings became the first team to win the first three games
of a Stanley Cup finals by one goal each since the 1976 Montreal
Canadiens did it to Philadelphia. The coach of that Montreal team?
Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings will try for their second straight Stanley Cup
sweep in Game 4 on Tuesday night at Washington. Once again, they
scored the first goal Saturday night, running their record to 12-1
in this playoff season when they score first.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the sellout crowd of 19,470 at MCI Center worked
itself into a frenzy in the final moments before the puck was
dropped to start the first Stanley Cup finals game in Washington
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five seconds into the game, the building went silent _
with the exception of the 1,500 or so vocal Red Wings fans
scattered around the upper reaches of the new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Red Wings captain Steve Yzerman put on a burst of speed and flew
past Washington's Esa Tikkanen down the left side. With Tikkanen
pulling him down, Yzerman slid a weak shot toward Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the puck squirted free after Kolzig's save. Tomas
Holmstrom, who has become a major offensive factor during the
playoffs, beat Washington's Todd Krygier to the rebound and slipped
it behind Kolzig, who was lying on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's first shot of the game put Washington in an uphill
battle. Holmstrom's seventh goal of the playoffs stunned the
Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked so much about a fast start in the first period and
then _ bang! _ 35 seconds in we score a goal,'' Bowman said. ``That
gives the whole team a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever steam the Capitals should have had seemed to vaporize.
The Red Wings won nearly every battle for the puck along the
boards; the Caps were busy giving away the puck nine times in the
period.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a terribly lopsided first period, the only part of
the stats sheet Washington coach Ron Wilson could possibly have not
blanched at was the score.
</P>
<P>
   The Caps had one shot on goal _ a weak lob from the left point
20 seconds into the game. Detroit outshot Washington 13-1,
continuing the dominance of the first two games when the Wings held
a 91-50 edge.
</P>
<P>
   The single shot tied a mark for fewest shots in a regulation
period of a Stanley Cup finals game since 1968. The other club with
one shot was Detroit _ in the final period of Game 4 when New
Jersey swept the Red Wings in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically didn't show up for the first period,'' Wilson
said. ``Why? I don't know. I'll have to stay up all night tonight
to try to analyze it. I mean, you work so hard to get here, and we
have had some just not play very well at all at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   To an extent, things were better in the second period, when the
Caps took 12 shots on goal, several putting Detroit goaltender
Chris Osgood to the test. But the result was the same as the second
period ended with Detroit ahead 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   While the Wings were short-handed early in the second, a shot by
Washington's Jeff Toms deflected off the skate of a Detroit player
and skittered behind Osgood. He reacted quickly, grabbing the puck
before it crossed the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   While the Caps were on the power play midway through the period,
Osgood turned away Adam Oates on a point-blank shot. Shortly after
that, Osgood made a sliding pad save on Peter Bondra. With less
than two minutes left in the second period, Osgood robbed Bondra
again, this time with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Caps' plan in the final period seemed to be firing the puck
into the Red Wings' zone as much as possible. Long shots have been
Osgood's undoing throughout the playoffs, and Washington tried
everything possible to break through against the Detroit
goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Bellows jammed home the puck from short distance to
draw the Caps even. Darren McCarty went off at 9:22 for tripping,
giving Washington a chance. As Oates was driving toward the net,
Detroit penalty killer Kirk Maltby slid across the crease, trying
to deflect the puck away from the net.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, he deflected it to Bellows, who was at the side of
the net and stuck it behind Osgood for the tying goal at 10:35. The
Caps, ineffective all night on the power play and booed at times by
their home fans, had life.
</P>
<P>
   But only briefly. Fedorov reached down and regained his scoring
touch at just the right time for the Wings, who are poised on the
verge of back-to-back NHL titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you analyze this series, we're only one goal better than
they are each night,'' Bowman said. ``But they (the Wings) have
been in this position before. We'll remind them it's not a
three-game series. It's a four-game series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
