<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8353 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS-BO     06-14 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
FEDOROV, RED WINGS FORGE AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Nancy L. Marrapese 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Detroit Red Wings say they have won nothing
yet, that the fourth victory in the Stanley Cup finals is the
hardest to earn.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals, on the brink of becoming the fourth straight team
to be swept from the finals, say they are not dead yet, that they
still can come back and make a series of it.
</P>
<P>
   But after three games, all Detroit victories, including Saturday
night's 2-1 thriller, it appears the defending Stanley Cup champion
Red Wings will be crowned the NHL's best team again.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third straight game decided by one goal. The last
time the first three games of the finals were decided by a goal was
in 1976, the year Montreal swept the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   After a dreadful start, the Capitals made a game of it and
appeared they might make a series of it when they tied the game,
1-1, at 10:35 of the third period. Adam Oates came out of the left
corner toward the net and his shot glanced off Kirk Maltby and
right to Brian Bellows, who beat Red Wings goalie Chris Osgood at
the left post for the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   But Sergei Fedorov, who was shut out despite landing 13 shots in
Game 2, buried the Capitals with 4:51 left in regulation when he
skated the puck through the neutral zone, cut over the blue line
and snapped a shot from the right circle that went off the stick of
Calle Johansson and beat goalie Olaf Kolzig to the glove side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big-time goal by a big-time player,'' said Red Wings
coach Scotty Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 2-0, in the series, the Capitals were hoping the home
crowd, familiar ice, and desperate position would spark them in the
early going of Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen, not even close.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals came out horrendously in the first period. They put
just a single shot on Osgood _ who entered the game with a 6-0
career mark against the Capitals _ and that was in the opening 20
seconds. Only defenseman Mark Tinordi was able to get anything
through to the net. The Detroit defense was tremendous, completely
preventing the Capitals from forechecking. The one shot tied for
the fewest shots in a period of a Stanley Cup finals game since
1968. The Red Wings also landed just one shot in the third period
of the fourth and final game when they were swept by New Jersey in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their dominance, the Red Wings, who poured 14 shots on
Kolzig in the opening 20 minutes, scored just once _ on their first
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yzerman, who has had an outstanding series, skated down
through the left circle and got off a shot on Kolzig despite being
hauled down by Esa Tikkanen. The puck went into Kolzig, who was
lying on the ice, but the goalie couldn't contain it and squirted
out around his pads. Tomas Holmstrom, while being hooked from
behind by Todd Krygier, popped in the loose puck at the right post
and the Red Wings had a 1-0 lead just 35 seconds in.
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig said he didn't think Holmstrom's goal should have been
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really consider it a goal, period,'' Kolzig said. ``I
think the whistle should've been blown and I think a lot of my
teammates agree with me. I think (referee Terry Gregson) was just
maybe warming up his whistle and it hadn't gotten warm yet. It
wasn't the deciding factor in the hockey game by any means but it
did take a lot of the wind out of us early.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington coach Ron Wilson said before the game he wanted his
players to come out and be more physical than they had in Game 2.
However, instead of physical play, three of his veterans _ Chris
Simon, Dale Hunter, and Phil Housley _ took ill-advised penalties.
Kolzig, however, who entered the game 0-5 in his career against the
Red Wings, prevented Detroit from building on its lead by thwarting
the power plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals woke up in the middle period, outshooting their
guests, 12-11, but were unable to dent Osgood despite some terrific
opportunities. Their best chance came with 1:42 left during a
two-on-one break when Peter Bondra teed up a slapper high in the
left circle. Osgood, way out of his net, made a terrific glove
save, setting the stage for the dramatic third.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very tough hockey game,'' said Bowman. ``We had to
use everybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
