<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BOUT IS TARGET PRACTICE FOR DE LA HOYA
</HEADLINE>
 BOX-DELAHOYA-CHARPENTIER-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Ron Borges 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ In less than nine minutes, Oscar De La Hoya left
45,368 people on their feet by knocking Patrick Charpentier off
his.
</P>
<P>
   The World Boxing Council welterweight champion wasted little
time in ridding himself of the so-called challenge of the No. 1
contender, dropping the outgunned Charpentier three times in the
third round to force a halt to what was an utterly one-sided match
from the moment it began.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Laurence Cole was watching Charpentier closely each time
he scrambled back up off the floor of the Sun Bowl and the third
time he got up Cole stepped in quickly to make sure there would be
no fourth collapse, ending the bout at 1:56 of the round.
</P>
<P>
   When he did, the highly partisan crowd exploded. It had been
given what it had come for. It had been given an execution.
Blending right into the Hispanic flavor of the evening, it had been
more bullfight than boxing match and it was obvious from the
opening moments who was the matador because De La Hoya came in
dressed like one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did just what he was brought here for,'' said veteran
trainer Teddy Atlas, who called the fight on a national radio
broadcast. ``He was here to get annihilated and that's what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   That process began quickly. When Charpentier got back to the
safe haven of his corner after the second round, he heaved a sigh
of relief like a man who just had heard the Supreme Court had
granted him a stay of execution. That stay lasted only for the
minute he was allowed to stay in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after he reemerged in De La Hoya's sights, the champion
bounced a left hook off his head and sent him to the canvas.
Charpentier got up quickly but was soon back on the floor when De
La Hoya nailed him with two body shots followed by a perfect left
uppercut to the point of the chin.
</P>
<P>
   This was no longer a boxing match. It was target practice and
Charpentier seemed to realize it. When he got up the second time
his look was different, his eyes saying he knew he would not remain
upright for long.
</P>
<P>
   He did not.
</P>
<P>
   Now hesitant to come forward and unable to retreat quickly
enough to get to safety as De La Hoya stalked him, the challenger
finally threw a half-hearted jab and De La Hoya answered it
immediately with a crushing right hand over the top of it that
drove Charpentier to the floor for the final time.
</P>
<P>
   That punch landed so squarely in the middle of Charpentier's
face it appeared he had been under orders not to move it a
centimeter in either direction. He was a bearded target now and
Cole knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no three-knockdown rule,'' Cole said. ``I stopped
it. He was definitely dazed. After the second knockdown I stayed
close to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Charpentier, so did De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no problems out there,'' De La Hoya (28-0, 23 KOs) said.
``Once I hurt him, I knew the knockout was coming. Everything
worked perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Charpentier, who had been brought to West Texas from
France to do exactly what he did Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Fall down in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the evening, it seemed there might be no fight, which
some might say remained the case even once the first bell rang.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful wind kicked up unexpectedly at approximately 6:20
p.m., battering the metal truss above the ring that held many of
HBO's cameras. As the stanchions that held it up began to sway,
someone in HBO's control truck noticed that a situation was
developing at ringside that could lead to an unexpected knockout if
something wasn't done so executive producer Ross Greenberg ordered
that ring announcer Michael Buffer and the media and officials
evacuate the area so the truss could be lowered by 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the Sun Bowl had more obstructed view seats than the
old Boston Garden but at least it created a situation that allowed
the bouts to go on. When they did, WBC lightweight champion Stevie
Johnston was wishing a tsunami had hit.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston fought 12 less-than-scintillating rounds against
challenger Cesar Bazan on the undercard, losing a split decision
when judges David Harris and Omar Minton had the Mexican-born Bazan
a 115-113 winner, while Oren Shellenberger saw Johnston winning
easily, 116-112.
</P>
<P>
   As his title slipped away by split decision, Johnston stood
still in his silent corner. No one raised a protest.
</P>
<P>
   Kind of like Patrick Charpentier a few minutes later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8355 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-LADN     06-14 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS MAY COME TO PRETTY PASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How ``cute'' of Karl Malone to prolong Michael Jordan's career
at least one more game for the benefit of all those fans who are
fearful pro basketball will become Not Bloody Amusing once the
Chicago guard is gone for good.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Malone's 39-point performance in Friday's Game 5,
Jordan probably wouldn't have been reduced to talking like someone
who had Beanie Babies on the brain, calling the suspense
surrounding the wildly errant 3-point shot he launched for the
series-ending and maybe dynasty-dismantling win ``kind of cute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For 1.1 seconds, everybody was holding their breath,'' Jordan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it has been more like 1.1 months that everybody who
loves watching Jordan play has been waiting to exhale. Between the
seven-game battle the Indiana Pacers waged against Chicago in the
Eastern Conference finals and the overtime game that got away in
Salt Lake City 11 days ago, it's a wonder Bulls fans haven't turned
Cubs blue by now.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, disco will be on its way out again before the
Bulls finish their awkward gyrations to Donna Summer's ``Last
Dance.'' Then again, the fat lady could stop singing tonight.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to like the Bulls' chances in Game 6, even if it
is being played inside that loudspeaker otherwise known as the
Delta Center. Consider: Chicago missed 20 of its first 22 shots on
Friday and lost by only two points. Jordan and Scottie Pippen
misfired 31 times in 42 tries between them and even so, Jordan had
the ball in the final second with a chance to win the game and
claim outright the NBA's title deed for the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the script has been written since Jordan first burst
into our consciousness, as a freshman at North Carolina when, in
the 1982 NCAA title game against Georgetown, he hit a 17-foot
jumper with 15 seconds remaining to give the Tar Heels a one-point
win.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of 23,844 United Center spectators willing it to be so,
there would be no euphonious closure to Jordan's career, provided
he is, indeed, down to his final curtain calls. When his 35-foot
fallaway jumper for a one-point win over the Jazz fell short of the
rim, it botched the ending that all of Chicago had giddily written,
however prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls are lucky to have time for a quick rewrite, 1,250
miles away from the glare of a city full of eager editors. Had they
been able to distance themselves from Chicago's collective yearning
for the perfect fairy-tale ending, the Bulls might have seen that
the best conclusion in this case was the one that put the game
squarely in Toni Kukoc's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc clearly was the Bulls' best option on this night, having
made four of six shots from beyond the 3-point arc and having gone
7 for 7 from everywhere else on the floor. But the myth must be fed
and so it was Jordan got the nod despite having missed 16 of 25
shots.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, hope ran rampant that Jordan would somehow summon
the touch that had eluded him all night. From his jumper over
Cleveland's Craig Ehlo in the fifth game of the first round of the
1989 playoffs that got the wheels of this dynasty turning to his
jumper in Game 1 and 3-pointer in Game 5 of last year's finals
against Utah, Jordan has lavished his legacy with last-second
winners.
</P>
<P>
   But what tends to get lost in the lining of Superman's cape is
how Jordan's will to win has a way of rubbing off on his teammates
(sometimes as a direct result of his applying the elbow grease),
making them infinitely better. Good enough, anyway, to count on in
the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   During a tight game against Seattle in the NBA Finals two years
ago, Jordan got in Kukoc's face and said, ``Are you scared? If you
are, then sit down. If you're out here to shoot, then shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do you imagine happened next? Kukoc came off the bench
and contributed two quick 3-pointers and a dunk off a pass from
Jordan to ice Game 2 on the Bulls' way to a six-game series win
that gave them their fourth NBA title in six years.
</P>
<P>
   The mind readily conjures up the indelible images of Jordan
nailing last-second jumpers against the Jazz to win two games in
last year's finals. But it's instructive to note the Bulls' fifth
championship in seven years wasn't iced with any one of Jordan's 39
points in the decisive Game 6 but with Steve Kerr's basket off a
pass from Jordan that on Friday he probably would have recalled as
being ``kind of cute.''
</P>
<P>
   That's OK. Sometimes even those of us who employ words to make
ends meet struggle to summon the right adjective when it comes to
Jordan, whose creativity knows no bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell once said Jordan's imagination is the greatest
thing about his game. At 35, Jordan is still capable of
confounding, as he did earlier in the series by launching himself
from the free-throw line and slinging the ball from his right hand
to his left as though it were a ball of dough he was preparing for
pizza.
</P>
<P>
   As he tries tonight to satiate a city's hunger for a second
three-peat, Jordan just ought to remember, the hand he passes the
ball off to doesn't automatically have to be his own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0011 </DOCNO>
