<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8360 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MEXICO-L     06-14 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MEXICO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO WINS WORLD CUP OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France A rare taste of success, at least the way things
have been going lately, and suddenly Mexico sees itself as world
beaters.
</P>
<P>
   The Tricolor was talking World Cup championship after a crucial
3-1 triumph Saturday over South Korea, a result that ended decades
of frustration as well as that of the last couple months and placed
the Mexicans squarely atop Group E.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Hernandez, ``El Matador,'' was the hero, scoring a pair of
second-half goals as Mexico utilized a man advantage to overcome an
early deficit and notch its first World Cup win on European soil.
</P>
<P>
   It was a vital result, absolutely necessary if the Tri has any
hope or desire of reaching the second round, which is an
understatement of mammoth proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico came to win the World Cup,'' declared halftime
substitute Ricardo Pelaez, who scored six minutes into the second
half to offset the Koreans' advantage. ``If you come with no idea
of winning, then why even play?''
</P>
<P>
   With Stade Gerland decked out like a miniature Estadio Azteca
Mexican flags, and fans, just about everywhere the Tri rode the
emotion of the crowd to a dominant win that hinged on a pair of
decisions, one by Austrian referee Guenter Benko, the other, a
reaction to the first, really, by Mexico coach Manuel Lapuente.
</P>
<P>
   Benko's involved Ha Seok-ju, who had fired South Korea ahead in
the 28th minute with the most fortuitous of free kicks, a 17-yarder
that slammed off the head of Mexican defender Duilio Davino and
ricocheted into the right-side netting, leaving goalkeeper Jorge
Campos going the other way. ``We felt our hearts fall,'' Hernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, an ill-conceived challenge by Ha on Ramon
Ramirez earned a red card, the first given exclusively for a tackle
from behind in this tournament under the new FIFA guidelines. That
was just about it for the Koreans aside from a 25-yard blast just
before halftime by 19-year-old midfielder Ko Jong-soo, which forced
a sprawling save by Campos who caved in once Lapuente changed the
Mexican focus heading into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Lapuente, heavily criticized as Mexico struggled during Cup
preparations, switched from a 4-4-2 to a more offensive 4-2-4
alignment, bringing on Pelaez and Jesus Arellano. It had an
immediate impact, with Arellano causing havoc on the right and
Hernandez finally breaking free of Kim Tae-young's cover, and
Pelaez's goal, another fortunate strike, in the 51st minute turned
the tide.
</P>
<P>
   It came from a Ramirez corner kick from the left, one that
cleared Pelaez's head but struck Yoo-Sang-chul's foot and rolled
into open space in front of the goal. Pelaez ripped it home from 4
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez scored the winner in the 74th minute, volleying
Ramirez's left-wing cross from close range, slipping the ball
between goalkeeper Kim Byung-ji and the far post.
</P>
<P>
   He got another 10 minutes later, firing past Kim from 18 yards
after a Cuauhtemoc Blanco feed.
</P>
<P>
   That had Gerland rocking, with the Mexican supporters at least
two-thirds, maybe more, of the 39,133 on hand singing ``Las
Mananitas'' and waving their flags in a frenzy. They made an
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe the stadium,'' gushed Hernandez. ``I felt
so happy seeing my Mexican people. To hear them singing the Mexican
anthem (before the game) is something I'll never forget in my
entire life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, they were (ital) there (end ital),'' echoed captain
Alberto Garcia Aspe. ``It was amazing seeing all the people. How
did they get here?
</P>
<P>
   The same question could be asked of the Tri, who looked like
anything but a second-round candidate in its run-up to the
tournament. And while Belgium, their opponent next Saturday in
Bordeaux, and the Netherlands, whom they meet June 25 in
Saint-Etienne, will provide far greater challenges, the Mexicans
have no shortage of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who don't think we're a very good
team,'' Hernandez acknowledged. ``We just need to constantly know
that we have talent, that we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, the logic goes, could lead to the title?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have aspirations, of course,'' said Lapuente, ``but the
first one if to win the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8361 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-DOOLEY-L     06-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-DOOLEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOOLEY SET TO FACE HOME COUNTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France Thomas Dooley, like every good
German boy, dreamed of the day he'd walk onto the field at the
World Cup, captain's armband wrapped around his biceps, the
stirring strains of ``Das Lied der Deutschen'' echoing in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   That dream comes true on Monday, but with a twist: Dooley will
be lined up opposite the Germans at Parc des Princes in Paris, and
it will be the ``Star-Spangled Banner'' that brings tears to his
eyes, not the German anthem.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran sweeper, as German as sauerbraten for the vast
majority of his 37 years, can't hide his true colors, his true
emotions. And they have little to do with the land in which he was
born, bred and called home until last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't feel emotional (when the German anthem is played),''
he said, just days before he'll lead the United States into its
World Cup opener. ``I never had something to do for that country,
like in their army or with their national team. Now, over the last
six years in America, playing for my country, (hearing the U.S.
anthem) gives me more feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play for the U.S., and I will fight for the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' fight has been Dooley's since 1992, when U.S.
Soccer was tipped off to a German midfielder with a link to
America. Dooley's father, an American soldier who deserted his
German wife when Thomas was still an infant, provided his son a
bloodline and a birthright: As far as international soccer was
concerned, Dooley was as American as hot dogs and Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always talked to me about how I am, my
mentality,'' he says. ``They called me `Ami,' because my mentality
was American. I always felt I was American, and I liked America my
whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a full-blown love affair these days, built during more than
half a decade as one of the country's finest soccer players,
although sport is only part of the equation. In his time in the
United States --- a year in Aliso Viejo while preparing for the
1994 World Cup, another year in Ohio, where he stars in Major
League Soccer for the Columbus Crew, frequent stops on national
team business --- Dooley has found something he'd been searching
for, something he'd never been able to pinpoint: Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like an American who grew up in Germany,'' he says.
``I'm happy to go back to Germany for a vacation once a year, but
the more I live in America, the more I am in America, the more I
think I am more American than German.''
</P>
<P>
   It's his German experience --- nearly 10 years in the
Bundesliga, in stints with Kaiserslautern, Bayer Leverkusen and
Schalke 04 --- that has made him so valuable for the national team.
Since he received his passport, he's been a key figure for the
Yanks, a defensive midfielder and defender whose ability to read
the game, tackle with vigor and precision, and surge forward at the
most opportune times has helped in the Americans' climb from soccer
neophytes to burgeoning world power.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley's importance to the cause was rewarded after U.S. coach
Steve Sampson dismissed John Harkes, the Americans' captain, in
April. He didn't hesitate in passing the captain's armband Dooley's
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wonderful captain and leader,'' Sampson praises. ``He
builds confidence in the players, and he gives quality information
to them; and he's such a settling individual, they can learn by his
composure on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes playing so much easier,'' notes defensive midfielder
Brian Maisonneuve, one of Dooley's Crew teammates. ``His
experience, the way he tells you things. ... And when he talks,
everybody listens.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley's American experience nearly wasn't. Three times in the
early '90s, Germany invited him into its national team camp. Each
time, Dooley suffered an injury and had to decline the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so sad,'' Dooley says. ``My wife asked why I was so
upset. I told her that the biggest dream that I have is to play in
the World Cup. ... She said maybe it wasn't meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a philosophy Dooley had trouble accepting, until he got
the call from U.S. Soccer. But his first few months in America,
after he joined the '94 preparations, were anything but
illuminating. His son, Marco, then 12, missed his friends back
home, and his wife, Elke, was homesick.
</P>
<P>
   But after they returned to Germany following the World Cup, all
they could talk about was coming back to America. ``(Elke) told me,
when I was with Schalke, that when I finished playing, we were
going to move to California,'' Dooley says. ``Marco likes it better
here, and my youngest (6-year-old Dennis) came to us and said,
`Mom, Dad, I want to go to Germany only on vacation.' That was
great.''
</P>
<P>
   This is home now, his only home, and so when he leads the
Americans on Monday against a German squad many think will of
capture its fourth championship, he tries to downplay the emotion
of the moment. He is not totally successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be captain ... it's a big honor for me,'' he says. ``Of
course, to play against Germany is more exciting than to play
against Italy or Spain, but right now I think only about Germany as
an opponent, not as a country where I grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first time we played against Germany, in Chicago
(in 1993), I was more excited than I am now, because now I have
much more focus for our game and for our goals. ... I don't want to
put too much emotion into this game, I just want to focus on the
opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough opponent, he knows, one few think the Yanks are
capable of knocking off. That's not a view Dooley shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible,'' he says. ``We beat a couple months ago
the best team in the world. Germany is (according to the FIFA
rankings) the second best team, so why not? We need a little bit
luck and we have to play our game with a lot of confidence, a lot
of fighting, a very physical game. Then we have a chance. Of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
