<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8367 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-CARDINALS-     06-14 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CARDINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS HIT POWERBALL, HOMERS TOP CARDINALS  
 LEE HOMERS TWICE, WILLIAMS ADDS 1 TO CAP RALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX They came to Bank One Ballpark on Saturday, nearly
50,000 strong, expecting baseballs to fly off the bat of the first
baseman and out of the yard.
</P>
<P>
   The baseballs flew, to be sure. What came as a surprise was that
they were hit by the Diamondbacks' Travis Lee, not the St. Louis
Cardinals' Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's rookie sensation upstaged the incredible hulk with two
home runs, including a three-run shot in the bottom of the eighth,
as the Diamondbacks roared from behind for a 7-4 victory on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks raised their record to 22-46 entering today's
finale of the three-game series. The Cardinals fell to 31-35.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 23, enjoyed perhaps the finest day of his brief pro career.
</P>
<P>
   He literally was a one-man wrecking crew. With two outs in the
third inning, he knocked Cardinals left-handed starter Kent Mercker
from the game. His one-hop smash came off the dirt strip that runs
from the mound to the plate and bounced off the back of Mercker's
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker was on the ground for a few minutes, limped off with the
help of team trainers and later had X-rays that proved to be
negative.
</P>
<P>
   With Arizona trailing, 2-1, and Jay Bell aboard as the result of
a walk with two outs in the seventh inning, Lee crushed a fastball
from right-hander Curtis King and sent it into the right-field
stands.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals regained the lead, 4-3, on Brian Jordan's two-run
homer off right-hander Russ Springer with no outs in the eighth. It
appeared Diamondbacks left fielder David Dellucci had a chance to
catch it, but the ball went just beyond his reach into the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Lance Painter began the eighth for the Cardinals and
with one out, hit Brent Brede with his first pitch. Brede advanced
to third on a single by Karim Garcia, but Garcia was thrown out by
Willie McGee while trying to stretch it into a double.
</P>
<P>
   The call then went to right-handed closer Jeff Brantley. Bell
drew another walk, his third of the game, and Lee ripped an 0-1
pitch over the fence for his second homer and 13th of the season.
Third baseman Matt Williams followed with a home run to left on the
first pitch from Brantley (0-3), a former San Francisco Giants
teammate. It was Williams' 13th homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he knew the homer off King was gone, but wasn't sure
about the next one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw McGee move back, and I didn't know if he was going to
catch it or what,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitch was up and right down the middle, exactly where I
didn't want it,'' Brantley said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd gave Lee a standing ovation and continued to roar
until he climbed a few of the dugout steps and tipped his cap. It
was the first curtain call for a Diamondbacks player and one Lee is
certain to remember for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know whether to go out there or not,'' Lee said.
``They (teammates) were saying, `They're calling for you.' So I did
it. It was great. It gave me goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who had a grand slam in a 9-4 victory over Arizona on
Friday night _ his 31st homer of the season, was held to a single
and a pair of walks (one intentional). He was impressed with Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great talent,'' McGwire said. ``He's got a great swing
that's only going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he isn't surprised at what Lee has been able to
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travis is a good player. There will be many of these kinds of
days for him. He has a very good idea of what he wants to
accomplish out there. He goes out and works hard and is not in awe
of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Lee is a good player, Brantley said, ``Today, he was
pretty damn good.''
</P>
<P>
   After the heroics of Lee and Williams in the eighth,
right-hander Gregg Olson came on in the ninth to record his eighth
save. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
