<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8368 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-KENNEY-AZR &LR;      06-14 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-KENNEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUN HELPED CARDINALS ROOKIE TURN LIFE AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Little Moose hit rock bottom the time he stole
$1,000 from his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody understood,'' said Cardinals rookie linebacker
Marchant Kenney, whose father, ``Big Moose,'' nicknamed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a rotten kid.''
</P>
<P>
   So rotten, he ran the New Orleans streets until his 88-year-old
grandmother called the police.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't call his parents. Kenney's mother, Gretchen,
committed suicide when her son was 8. His dad, also named Marchant,
died in prison when Kenney was 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police would come and put my bike on the top of the car
and take me home,'' Kenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney wouldn't stay at his grandmother's for long. She couldn't
control him. Nobody could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd steal money from her, anybody,'' he said. ``I was around
people dealing drugs. I saw gang activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could do whatever I wanted when I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   That changed the day friends and relatives put the orphan in the
Boys Hope program, an international group home for academically
capable but at-risk children.
</P>
<P>
   It was there he met a nun who changed his life, Sister Francis
Regis Feise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Sister, without Boys Hope, I could be dead,'' he
said. &QL; 
Bob Ferguson, vice president of player personnel for the Cardinals,
knows Kenney's story is so improbable, he said, ``I'm going to
secure the movie rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Francis said Kenney, an undrafted free agent, has told
her, ``I think we ought to write a book. No one would believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The story would start on the Huey P. Long Bridge in 1981, the
day his mother jumped into the Mississippi River and died.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came home from work one day, and me and my father were
there,'' Kenney said. ``She said she was going out to visit a
friend. A few hours went by, and we wondered where she was. Three
or four hours later, there was a knock on the door and police
officers said they found her car on the bridge. They said there
were witnesses who saw her get on the bridge and jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney doesn't have a lot of fond memories of his mother. He
remembers meeting her boyfriends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd see her cheat on my father,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers his parents arguing much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was on edge all the time,'' he said. ``She wasn't in a
happy (marital) relationship. But I never thought suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney said his dad was ``devastated'' by the suicide and turned
to alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   His dad, a former pro boxer, ran with a tough crowd. He was a
bounty hunter who was caught in an FBI counterfeit sting. Police
found $2 million in counterfeit bills, but Kenney's dad never
served jail time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would bring me around things I shouldn't have seen,''
Kenney said. ``We go to hotels, and he'd take me to the game room.
It was kind of cool to me. He was `Big Moose.' I was `Little
Moose.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Kenney was 11, he came home from school with his guardian,
Aloha Ingram, to find the front door kicked in. Police had come and
taken his dad away, this time on a drug charge.
</P>
<P>
   He was found guilty and, on March 7, 1986, entered prison in
Talladega, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that was unbelievable was that they never took
(Kenney) there to see his dad,'' Sister Francis said of Kenney's
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The next time Kenney saw him was in a coffin. Big Moose died of
a heart attack while jogging in prison. He was 51 and had been
imprisoned about a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would write me letters all the time, telling me to stay
straight,'' Kenney said. ``He said he had found God, and we were
going to move to someplace else, get away from the life we lived.
He loved me to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney was shuffled from friends and relatives, eventually
winding up at his grandmother's house in Bridge City, La., a tough
town located just across the Mississippi River from New Orleans but
seemingly millions of miles away from the glitz of the French
Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   His grandmother was on welfare. He learned about food stamps and
welfare and wore ``the worst'' clothes to school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The school I went to there, some kids were there just to sell
drugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Kenney wasn't in school, he was on the streets until late
at night. His grades failed.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of one of Kenney's friends, Chad Howat, called Boys
Hope in New Orleans to see if they'd take him. Cheryl Howat knew
Boys Hope might be Kenney's last chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother didn't want me to go,'' Kenney said. ``She
thought I was her angel, when I was just a bad kid.'' &QL; 
Kirk Utzinger, the executive director of Boys Hope in Phoenix, said
the program's motto is ``Saving kids one life at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney, who was 14 at the time, didn't think he'd last there one
week. He hated being in the house with eight other boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first met Sister Francis, I was scared,'' he said.
``You know the (nun) stereotype _ black-and-white (outfit) with a
ruler in her hand. I didn't want to be there. I wanted to keep
doing what I had been doing. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, anything was better than where I'd been.''
</P>
<P>
   At Boys Hope, Sister Francis clothed and fed the boys and did
their laundry. She took little flak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marchant had to be pulled in and disciplined,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship changed during Kenney's sophomore year of
high school when the youngsters went on a retreat to Covington, La.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember (the priest) saying to me, `Marchant needs to talk
to someone and needs to talk to you,' '' Sister Francis said. ``We
found a room, and I said to him, `Let's get it out in the open.' He
spilled his beans.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney's version is slightly different.
</P>
<P>
   ``She sat me down and told me it's time to stop holding things
back, stop being so mean,'' Kenney said. ``I started talking about
how I felt about everything _ life, God, the things that had
happened to me, how I didn't think life had been fair. We were
talking and talking, and tears started flowing. I needed to open
up, and she forced it out of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that night on, we had a bond _ a mother-son
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Francis encouraged Kenney to find an outlet for all of
his energy, and he found it in football, which he never had played.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Saints offensive coordinator Danny Abramowicz was
Kenney's coach at Jesuit High School and remembers the teenager as
``ornery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like a caged tiger, undisciplined,'' Abramowicz said.
``He'd nail somebody, and I'd say, `That's great, but don't
overreact.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved his competitiveness. He was very likeable and a tough,
hard-nosed guy. He fought through so many things. He didn't wallow
around. He made something out of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney was all-state his senior year at Jesuit but wasn't highly
recruited because he was small. Only Texas Tech and Southern
Mississippi wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   Other recruiters didn't do their homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after I had that talk with Sister Francis, there still
was a wild side to me,'' Kenney said. ``It was an enjoyable wild. .
. . Football is a nasty game. I like to play like the old-time
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenney was the Defensive Player of the Year in Conference USA
last season. His junior year, he had 141 tackles, the most by a
Southern Miss player in seven years. But Kenney wasn't drafted
because he's only 6 feet 1, 232 pounds, small for a middle
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson first noticed Kenney on film when he was scouting
prospects from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were playing Southern Miss, and he was making all the
tackles, and I wondered, `Who is this guy?' '' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson watched several more films of Kenney, and then
Abramowicz called after the draft and recommended the Cardinals
sign him. Abramowicz didn't have to do much selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this kid has gone through tells you he's the kind of guy
you'd like playing for you,'' Ferguson said. ``Everything in his
life goes into every play. He realizes how special it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he big enough? Maybe not. Is he fast enough? Who knows. But
this game is about courage and heart and playing hard every down.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Kenney graduated from Southern Miss with a degree
in sports administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could have been with that child and what he is now, he
has come a long way,'' Sister Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenney knows he's already a big success story but said he's just
not happy being in an NFL training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to do whatever I can to make this team,'' he said.
``Where I get that drive from, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Moose pauses and then acknowledges that he couldn't have
done it on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sister Francis is like my mother,'' he said. ``Without her, my
life would be nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows Sister Francis. She comes to every game. She's
up in the stands and prays to St. Jude _ he's the saint for
hopeless causes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
