<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS AGAIN SET STAGE FOR UNLIKELY HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY - Drama junkies. Adrenaline addicts. A basketball
team incapable of the routine.
</P>
<P>
   What, they don't have enough excitement in their lives?
</P>
<P>
   ``We blew an opportunity,'' Michael Jordan said. ``This has
happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure has. More than they care to admit. And for all the mystique
and fire, all the cold blood and killer instinct, the Chicago Bulls
are a mere 5-4 with an NBA championship chilling on ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, they didn't seem ready to play (on Friday),''
Utah Jazz reserve Shandon Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Up, 3-0, against Seattle, they fell asleep at the wheel. Up,
3-1, against Phoenix, they lost at the Chicago Stadium, allowing
Charles Barkley to preserve the city. Now this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very hard,'' Scottie Pippen said. ``I know no
one wanted to make this trip, especially the players.''
</P>
<P>
   True. But they just can't help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As glorious as the Bulls look in the record books, their
appetite for chaos is both consistent and amazing. And if the past
is prologue, the only thing left is the unexpected assassin, the
microwave celebrity ready to zap the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hansen's been there. John Paxson's done it. Steve Kerr has
the T-shirt. So who's next? Who's going to emerge from behind the
curtain just when it appears a Game 7 is on the horizon?
</P>
<P>
   Or have the Bulls danced around the campfire one too many times?
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys have to remember, the (Jazz victory in Game 5) was a
two-point win,'' Bulls Coach Phil Jackson said. ``You don't throw
out the baby with the bath water in this situation. We're fine.
It's not a dramatic thing to say we lost a close game. We'll just
come at it, do it again, do it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Bulls can feel good about the past. Their ability to
tease, prolong, escape. They can also feel good about Toni Kukoc,
who is rounding into the wrecking ball the Bulls envisioned when
they followed him across the globe looking for his signature.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Kukoc was supposed to take the last shot, except he
couldn't get open. So, in a moment where life imitated Nike, Jordan
heaved up a prayer and the world seemed to stop. Just like the
commercial where Jordan drives to the basket and everything else is
suspended animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was cute, just thinking about it,'' Jordan
said. ``I was sitting there thinking about the whole thing, and at
1.1 (seconds), I knew I wanted the ball but no one knew what was
going to happen. ``That's part of my personality, the way things
have always happened for me in my career. I'm sure everyone was
hoping that it would end that way, except for Utah people.
Everybody was holding their breath, which is kind of cute.''
</P>
<P>
   Cute? No, these guys aren't worried at all. This is all just
part of the pattern. Seize control, let up, refocus. Go back on the
road where life is less filling and conquer the drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure we don't have to worry about the traffic,''
Jordan said. ``I'm sure it's going to be a lot different focus, and
some of the distractions will be gone. But it's not easy, walking
into Utah and trying to win. I welcome the challenge, and I hope my
teammates will, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So who will it be? Luc Longley, a man so dejected that Jordan
told him on Friday to forget everything and get drunk? Bill
Wennington? Ron Harper, a man who once was stuck in the cell block
known as the Los Angeles Clippers? ``That wasn't jail,'' Harper
said. ``That was a high-priced facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jackson should be slightly alarmed. The Jazz has yet to
unload its A game, its centers are finally waking up, and the Delta
Center is beckoning. And as silly as Karl Malone looks after
signing a deal to wrestle Dennis Rodman in San Diego next month, he
has been ridiculed once too often .
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got anger in his eyes,'' Antoine Carr said.
</P>
<P>
   Yep. The Bulls blew an opportunity. Maybe just a blip, a stage
for another unlikely hero. Or maybe cute starts looking
catastrophic. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
