<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-WOODS-ELS-AZ     06-14 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-WOODS-ELS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS-ELS RI VALRY UNLIKELY TO DEVELOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Analysis 
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever Tiger Woods and Ernie Els show up at one of golf's four
major championships, the question comes up:
</P>
<P>
   Will this be the major that launches the greatest rivalry since
Jack vs. Arnie?
</P>
<P>
   Television yearns for it. The fans would love it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, chances of it happening this week at the 98th
U.S. Open seem about as likely as the sponsoring U.S. Golf
Association avoiding controversy. Alas, no San Francisco treat at
the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for this, the chief ones being that
Woods and Els are ailing. Neither will back into this Open title
(the way this major usually is won), because their backs won't let
them.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Tiger withdrew from the Kemper Open, citing
soreness in his lower back. It marked the first time in his
professional career that the 22-year-old Woods had pulled out
because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   According to his agency, Cleveland-based IMG, the soreness was
not all that unexpected, considering the way Woods goes after the
ball, with a nuclear rotation that is second to none. Woods skipped
the Buick Classic and has been receiving treatment in Las Vegas
from his therapist, Keith Kleven.
</P>
<P>
   Els' announcement Wednesday that he would not defend his title
in the Buick was more unexpected. ``The Big Easy,'' as Els is
known, swings so slowly and smoothly that there would be no reason
to expect that his back would bear the brunt of the force at age
28.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Els' problem is different. He suffers from periodic
back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, (this week) will be a day-to-day thing at this
point,'' said Els, who will be attempting to defend his Open title,
not to mention win his third national championship in the past five
years (he also won in 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Both probably will make it to the first tee on Thursday, but how
they fare is anybody's guess. Especially when you factor in cool,
even chilly, San Francisco weather that often includes rain and fog
this time of the year. Not good for bad backs.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a better pick to win the Open is David Duval, whom
many have called America's greatest player over the past year. When
you win five times in your past 13 starts, as Duval has done, it's
pretty hard to look at Woods and Els, who have just one victory
between them (Els at Bay Hill) during that same span.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Woods and Els have won majors, and Duval has not.
Only Justin Leonard, another favorite this week, can make that
claim among professional golf's young lions, a pride that also
includes Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   But of those five players, Duval's game _ fairly long and
straight, with a superb short game _ might be best suited for the
Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   This is a relatively short (6,797 yards), hilly course that
demands accuracy, as the rough will pinch the fairways down to 20
to 30 yards wide and run as deep as 5 to 7 inches. The subtly
sloping greens have been accused of being no bigger than
``hubcaps,'' but a more accurate description of their size places
them in the range of backyard swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really makes it tough is there is not an level lie on the
course,'' Els reported after a visit last fall. ``Another thing,
there are not too many birdie-able holes (it's a par 70).
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on the weather. If the weather is going to
be wet, I can see the guys able to maybe shoot par or 2 under. But,
you know, if it is firm and the wind is blowing, I can't see a
score under par really winning.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the past three Opens at the Olympic Club have been so
unpredictable. In each (1955, '66 and '87), ``the wrong guy won,''
as sports author Dan Jenkins put it.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely scenarios were Jack Fleck beating the legendary Ben
Hogan in an 18-hole playoff in '55; Arnold Palmer blowing a 9-shot
lead in the final round of the '66 championship, then falling to
Billy Casper the next day in another playoff; and Scott Simpson
eking out a 1-shot victory over Tom Watson in '87.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody keeps talking about the young guys (being the
favorites),'' Els warned before his back flared up. ``But I think
around a course like Olympic, you need experience. It wouldn't
surprise me to see the older guys come through again.''
</P>
<P>
   Or somebody coming out of left field, like a Lee Westwood or a
Stuart Appleby, or some other guy that might be golf's next Andy
North, who won two U.S. Opens and a total of three events in 25
years on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Els said that whether he wins his third Open in five years or
not (a feat last accomplished by Ben Hogan in 1950, '51 and '53),
he plans to ``enjoy myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He also doubts that a major rivalry between himself and Woods is
in the making this week. And bad backs have nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people make too much out of that,'' Els said.
``Besides, I'll be surprised a little bit if Tiger really plays
well. (The Olympic Club) is not quite his golf course. That is not
where his strengths are.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
