<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S SOCCER, BE HAPPY WITH A TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The philosopher who said a tie is like kissing your sister
obviously doesn't understand soccer.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with a tie. In fact, a scoreless tie can
be a positive experience. Paraguay and Bulgaria battled to a 0-0
draw in the World Cup the other day and while players from both
countries expressed their frustration and disappointment each one
whispered a secret prayer of thanks and told himself, ``At least
``I'' didn't ``blow'' it.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer critics say the sport is boring. Not enough offense. Many
Americans are reluctant to embrace an endeavor which incorporates
the primary rule in bobbing for apples. No hands allowed.
</P>
<P>
   My only criticism is that it's too easy for a soccer team to
beat itself.
</P>
<P>
   The other day those two old rivals, Morocco and Norway, were
engaged in a close, fiercely-fought match when Morocco's Youssef
Chippo did something that made him feel just awful. While trying to
knock the ball out of danger with his head he accidentally
redirected the ball into the Moroccan net.
Goooooooooooooooooaaaal!!!
</P>
<P>
   Jubilant, the Norwegians ran around in circles, arms
outstretched, looking for someone to hug. Poor Chippo had scored
for them. An ``own goal'' they call it. His face burned with shame.
</P>
<P>
   The same misfortune befell a Scottish defender. Tommy Boyd
inadvertently put a rebound into his own net in the 73rd minute.
Goooooooooooooooooaaaal!!! Scotland lost, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd wanted to do a highland fling off the Eiffel Tower. He felt
as badly as Andres Escobar did in the 1994 World Cup after the
Colombian player kicked the ball backward and scored an own goal
against the United States. The favored Colombians lost, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days later, back home, Escobar was murdered. Gunmen shouted,
``Goal!'' after each pistol shot.
</P>
<P>
   Drug traffickers, known to be sore losers, reportedly had lost
millions of dollars betting on Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Chippo and Boyd may not fear for their lives. Neither has been
deported. But no words can undo what happened or deliver them from
their private purgatory. Their mistakes were embarrassing and
costly.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup is unique. You won't see Michael Jordan
accidentally make a jump shot for Utah in the NBA Finals. Rarely
does a football player score for the other team, although it has
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Riegels picked up a Georgia Tech fumble and ran the wrong
direction in the 1929 Rose Bowl _ in the stadium where Escobar
committed his gaffe. Riegels went to his grave known as ``Wrong
Way'' Riegels.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Marshall of the Vikings committed a similar blunder in a
1964 NFL game. The defensive lineman picked up a fumble, lost his
compass and took off toward the 49ers end zone, bound for glory. He
didn't stop until he got there.
</P>
<P>
   Time, they say, heals all wounds. Now, Marshall says, he is
asked about the play only three or four times a day.
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of own goals _ already there have been at least
three in the World Cup _ may be on the minds of our lads when the
United States makes its debut in the tournament on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson's team opens against Germany. Next, the U.S. plays
Iran, which will be ready for this holy war against what the late
Ayatollah Khomeini called ``the Great Satan.'' Then, the U.S. faces
Yugoslavia. The Yugoslavian team's wealth of talent almost rivals
that of defending champion Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   How did we end up in Group F? Fate. A draw was held, similar to
the one staged in Las Vegas before the 1994 World Cup when comic
Robin Williams put on a surgical glove before dipping his hand into
the bottom of a glass bowl containing several blue balls. ``Turn
your head and cough,'' he cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Can we win a match? Two?
</P>
<P>
   Seems to me our realistic goal should be to play for three ties,
and not shoot ourselves in the foot, or any other appendage. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 60-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
