<HEADLINE>
WIND NEARLY RECORDS A TKO  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ A West Texas wind nearly scored the biggest knockout.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before the  &UR; Oscar De La Hoya-Patrick Charpentier
fight on Saturday night, high winds rocked steel girding that
supported lights above a ring at the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Home Box Office executives noticed that the structure, suddenly
weaving like a sail mast in a storm, was about to collapse on
officials and media at ringside.
</P>
<P>
   A retreat was ordered to about 20 yards from the ring as lights
were lowered and the structure reinforced. The sportswriters' exit
was quicker than the one predicted for Charpentier. &QL; 
On parade &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Carbajal and  &UR; Louie Espinoza, former Ninth Street Gym
stablemates, were among several former and current Hispanic
champions honored before the opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   Espinoza, Arizona's first fighter with a major title, won the
World Boxing Association junior-featherweight championship in the
mid-1980s while training for the Valley's  &UR; Willy Borchert.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal, the lightest fighter ever to win a $1 million purse,
held the International Boxing Federation's junior-flyweight title
twice and the World Boxing Council crown once.
</P>
<P>
   Carbajal's rival,  &UR; Humberto ``Chiquita'' Gonzalez of Mexico
City, missed the ceremony
</P>
<P>
   ``Wish he were here, I'd beat him right now,'' said Carbajal,
who knocked out Gonzalez at Las Vegas and lost controversial
decisions at Los Angeles and Mexico City
</P>
<P>
   He was joking. Sort of. &QL; 
On the undercard &QL; 
In the first of two bouts on the HBO telecast, Mexican  &UR; Cesar Bazan
(32-2-1, 23 KOs) won a dull split decision to take the WBC
lightweight title from previously unbeaten  &UR; Stevie Johnston (24-1,
13 KOs) of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Before the wind delay, Puerto Rican welterweight
 &UR; Daniel Santos (15-0-1, 12 KOs) stopped Mexican  &UR; Juan Carlos
Rodriguez (32-11-2, 20 KOs) with a jackhammer-like shot for a
fifth-round KO.
</P>
<P>
   The wind continued, but the delay did not. After a 30-minute
interruption and beneath lowered lights,  &UR; Cesar Soto (51-7-2, 39
KOs), the WBC's No. 1-rated featherweight from Juarez, landed an
uppercut for a second-round KO of  &UR; Juan Polo-Prez (39-18-3, 22 KOs)
of Miami. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
