A8373 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-FIGHT-DELAHOYA-AZ     06-14 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-DELAHOYA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA WINS IN 3  
 CHAMP MAKES SHORT WORK OF CHARPENTIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ He took the border out of this town.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya practiced some powerful diplomacy Saturday with
accurate punching that unified a delirious throng of 45,368 fans
and left one lonely Frenchman feeling like a pinata.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's third-round victory by technical knockout was oh-so
predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The poor victim, Patrick Charpentier, never had a chance in a
U.S. city that borders Juarez, where the French have never had any
luck.
</P>
<P>
   From Juarez, the Mexicans successfully overthrew French rule in
1862, and they've been celebrating Cinco de Mayo on both sides of
the U.S. border ever since. De la Hoya represented just another
chance to celebrate a second time within a few months.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, politician and diplomat, knew that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, El Paso, for your support,'' De La Hoya (28-0, 23
knockouts) said as he grabbed the microphone while a wobbly
Charpentier (27-5-1, 22 knockouts) was being led away. ``I had a
wonderful, beautiful time. I promise you one thing. I will be
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Charpentier climbed into a ring at the Sun Bowl
with a French flag in one hand and another one carried aloft by a
corner man, De La Hoya arrived like a modern Pancho Villa.
</P>
<P>
   He wore a gold sombrero. From Juarez to El Paso, it could have
been a halo.
</P>
<P>
   Only the gun belts and pistols were missing.
</P>
<P>
   But De La Hoya has his own weapons. They are his hands. His
fists. They are lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Charpentier had no defense. Not much offense, either. There's
more power in a couple of croissants than there were in
Charpentier's hands. He landed only five of 111 attempted blows,
according to Punchstat, a ringside computer. De La Hoya landed 80
of 155.
</P>
<P>
   Charpentier was knocked down three times in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   The first came as the result of left-right combo.
</P>
<P>
   The second came after a wicked left uppercut by De La Hoya, who
retained his World Boxing Council welterweight title.
</P>
<P>
   The third was lightning _ a straight right hand. Referee
Lawrence Coles immediately ended it at 1:56 of the round. The
stoppage was not dictated by a three-knockdown rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' Coles said. ``I stopped it. He was hurt. He
was definitely dazed. After the second knockdown, I stayed close to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya started to celebrate as Charpentier fell into him. De
La Hoya was already waving at the the crowd when Charpentier rolled
over onto his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not hurt,'' said Charpentier, who collected $600,000,
more than $3 million less than De La Hoya's $4 million purse. ``It
was the head shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Charpentier wasn't talking about camera angles. De La Hoya's
shots were had laserlike accuracy and impact.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of questions about Charpentier's qualifications
for a shot at the mighty De La Hoya, who is often called the
world's best fighter, regardless of weight.
</P>
<P>
   Those questions will dog De La Hoya until _ or if _ he faces
well-known welterweight contenders Felix Trinidad and Ike Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really good,'' said De La Hoya, whose next bout is
probably a rematch with Julio Cesar Chavez on Sept. 18 at Las
Vegas' Caesars Palace. ``I knew I was hurting him. I had no
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite doubts about Charpentier, De La Hoya can point to the
victory as something of a milestone. Before Saturday night, four of
De La Hoya's last five fights had gone the distance.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk that he had lost some power as he moved up in
weight class from 130 pounds to 135 to 140 to his current 147.
</P>
<P>
   His promoter, Bob Arum, now can say that he has not.
</P>
<P>
   More important, perhaps, is the public impact this victory will
have. De La Hoya has been haunted by boos from Mexicans and fellow
Mexican-Americans throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   He was thought to be too slick or too well-groomed to be a
fighter.
</P>
<P>
   But on the night at the border, there was never a doubt.
</P>
<P>
   It was an Oscarfest. Or fiesta. They love him in any language. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8374 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-6-PREVIEW-AZR     06-14 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-6-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS KNOW THIS SITUATION  
 SERIES MIMICS 1993 FINALS AGAINST SUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ There aren't many obstacles Michael Jordan and
the Chicago Bulls haven't faced and overcome in the 1990s while
accumulating five NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulls unexpectedly blew their opportunity to clinch a
sixth title by losing to Utah at home Friday night in Game 6 of the
NBA Finals, it wasn't unfamiliar territory for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we blew our opportunity,'' Jordan said. ``This happened
to us before.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1993, when the Bulls lost Game 5 at home but
defeated the Suns in Game 6 at Phoenix to clinch their third
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1993, I got on the plane with a cigar and celebrated a
little bit and got everybody else to enjoy themselves and relax a
little bit,'' Jordan remembered of that last unwanted trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Finals have paralleled that championship series in
some ways.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last time the Bulls played in The Finals without
the benefit of home-court advantage. The Suns had finished with the
best regular-season record.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last year that Chicago lost a home game in the
championship round.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the last time Jordan (not to mention Phoenix
forward Charles Barkley) was seriously considering retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jordan did leave the game for two years after that
season to pursue a baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we have to go back to Utah,'' Jordan said
Friday night. ``It's a duplicate situation as in 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls won the first two games of that series in Phoenix as
Kevin Johnson totalled only 15 points combined. Chicago appeared
headed toward an easy sweep.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns stayed alive by winning Game 3 in a classic
triple-overtime duel. But Chicago won Game 4 and preparations began
for a city-wide celebration after Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Police and the National Guard were on call to quell the expected
riotous reaction.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Suns Coach Paul Westphal to establish the club's
motto for the night _ ``Save the City!''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley scrawled the words on a chalk board in the
Phoenix locker room, and after the Suns stole Game 5, they
gleefully yelled, ``We saved Chicago!'' as they ran into the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   The script was similar this year. Chicago had the opportunity to
clinch the series in Game 5, and there was more talk about
champagne, riots, parades and the possibility of breaking up the
Bulls than about the possibility that the Jazz could force the
series back to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Utah won Game 5, and now _ still trailing 3-2 in the series _
the Jazz have home-court advantage in Game 6 tonight and, if
necessary, Game 7 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 6 is important for us,'' Chicago's Scottie Pippen said.
``We still have the advantage. We don't want them to tie the series
up, even though we're very comfortable going back on their home
court. We feel very good and feel like that we have a good grasp on
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Jazz followers might question that.
</P>
<P>
   After all, while Chicago has a 3-2 lead in the series, Utah has
had the lead in the final five minutes in four of the five games.
The Jazz led in the final minute of Game 2, which Chicago won.
</P>
<P>
   And Pippen is right about how important tonight's game is for
Chicago. In that 1993 series, the Suns couldn't get to Game 7,
losing a late lead and then falling when John Paxson hit a
three-point shot.
</P>
<P>
   If Utah can win tonight, history at least is on the side of the
Jazz. No NBA team has won Game 7 of the Finals on the road since
Washington won Game 7 in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That was 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And not even Jordan can claim he's been there, done that. In
fact, about the only thing the Bulls never have had to face is a
Game 7 _ home or away _ in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we have regained the home-court advantage,'' Utah
Coach Jerry Sloan said. ``And we worked for 82 games to achieve
that. That's why you play.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 0215EDT &QL; 
