<SLUG> BC-BBO-GOMEZ-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF 2 SLUGGERS  
 MCGWIRE GOT BETTER, CANSECO GOT LOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   M &UR; ark McGwire isn't really doing anything different these days.
He's always been the decade's most prolific home run hitter. It's
just that McGwire now plays in St. Louis, arguably the best
baseball city in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't that long ago that McGwire wasn't the best home
run hitter on his own club. True, he broke into the majors in 1987
and quickly blasted 49 home runs, a mark that may stand for some
time as the most home runs hit by a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   But even during his inaugural splash, McGwire took a back seat
to then-teammate  &UR; Jose Canseco, who was favorably compared to
 &UR; Mickey
 &UR; Mantle in those days. Canseco burst onto the baseball scene with a
flair that hadn't been seen in decades.
</P>
<P>
   He ran better than any big guy had ever run before. He drove the
ball to the far reaches of any stadium, even farther than McGwire
could in those days. Everyone remembers them as the ``Bash
Brothers,'' the pair of sluggers who helped lead Oakland to three
consecutive World Series appearances.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way the two players who seemed joined at the hip,
at least on the field in those days, separated. McGwire continued
working diligently, wanting to become a better baseball player.
Canseco was more interested in the nightlife and outside interests.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, Canseco was the better player in those days,
someone who seemed headed toward a spot in Cooperstown. But then he
stopped working. He went from being an above-average right fielder
to a cartoon character who had balls bounce off his head for home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   He became so tiresome to the Athletics that the club traded him
away at age 28, a time when he should have been heading toward his
peak seasons. Canseco is finally playing like he cares again. He's
stealing bases and playing with the same abandon that made him the
American League MVP at age 24.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, when Canseco was pulling down the mega-contracts
and meeting with  &UR; Madonna late at night, McGwire worked like a
horse, wanting to continually improve as a ballplayer. Now he's the
one with an appointment in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of unrelated foot injuries came much closer to ending his
career than most people realize. But McGwire eventually was talked
out of turning in his spikes by family and close friends. Fans of
big-league ball everywhere should be thankful.
</P>
<P>
   There are no extensive films of  &UR; Babe Ruth. We know how great he
was from firsthand accounts and the thousands of stories that have
been passed down. We'll be telling stories of McGwire one day,
telling our grandkids how we were alive to watch what may turn out
to be the greatest home run hitter of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Take note of McGwire, the only player besides Ruth to ever hit
50 home runs in consecutive seasons. We're fortunate to be watching
history. &QL; 
Taking their cuts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place several New York Yankees among those disgusted with the
deplorable actions of the owner of the alleged big-league club that
plays its home games at (Semi-)Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have a certain loyalty to the city that you're
in, and I think that (breakup) shows a lack of loyalty,'' Yankees
Manager
 &UR; Joe Torre said. ``You won the World Series. Great. Hooray. But if
you only did it for yourself, then it's not right. That's not the
right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Paul O'Neill was equally peeved: ``A lot of people feel there's
no defending champion right now. Part of the fun of winning it all
is trying to repeat. It was a big motivating factor for us last
year. The game is cheated of that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Yankees owner  &UR; George Steinbrenner stood up for his
fellow owner,  &UR; Wayne  &UR; Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to run your own show and your own team, so I'll
never criticize Wayne,'' Steinbrenner said. ``He's a businessman
and he felt his costs were excessive and he didn't think he could
continue . . . He needs a domed stadium, absolutely has to have
it.'' &QL; 
A FOX-y attitude &QL; 
It turns out Los Angeles did the New York Mets a tremendous favor,
only part of which was sending  &UR; Hideo Nomo to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers agreed to assume all of the salaries of  &UR; Dave Mlicki
and
 &UR; Greg McMichael, the pitchers the Mets sent to Los Angeles in the
deal. Mlicki will earn $1.25 million this season and $2.25 million
next year.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael will earn $1.8 million this season and another $1.8
million next year if he pitches in another 29 games this season,
almost a certainty. &QL; 
The cigar room &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks followed Cincinnati into San Diego during an
early-season series. Arizona Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter complained of
the cigar stench in the visiting manager's dugout at Qualcomm
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Reds Manager  &UR; Jack McKeon, known for chain-smoking cigars, plans
to send Showalter a peace offering when the Diamondbacks visit
Cincinnati Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to send a cigar over to Buck's office,'' McKeon
joked. ``Lit.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
