<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-SIDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 D-BACKS WIGGLE OFF HOOK  
 LEE'S 2ND HOMER SAVES GARCIA, SPRINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Between Mark McGwire hitting home runs when they
didn't count, and Travis Lee and Matt Williams hitting them when
they did, there was plenty of joy to be spread among the 48,172 who
saw the Diamondbacks come back to beat the St. Louis Cardinals,
7-4, on Saturday at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   But probably the most powerful feeling was one of relief, and it
was concentrated in the Diamondbacks' dugout, wherever Karim Garcia
and Russ Springer happened to be sitting. And stewing.
</P>
<P>
   Both were removed from hooks of their own device when Lee's
second homer of the game, a three-run shot, erased a 4-3 Cardinals
lead in the eighth inning. Williams followed with a solo blast for
good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Just two batters before Lee, things looked bleak. With one out
and Brent Brede on first, Garcia, who had come in to play center
field in the top of the inning, laced a single to right off Lance
Painter. Noticing that Willie McGee had to come a long way to cut
off the ball, Garcia tried to leg the hit into a double.
</P>
<P>
   At 39, McGee doesn't cover as much ground as he used to, but he
got there quickly enough and fired a strike to second and cut
Garcia down. So, instead of the Diamondbacks having runners on
first and third and one out, opening a world of possibilities, it
was Brede on third and two out, with limited options. But Jay Bell
drew a walk, his third of the game, and Lee went deep off Jeff
Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really upset,'' said Garcia, who continues to show
progress at the plate since his recall from Tucson two weeks ago.
``I was really (expletive) with myself, to put us in that
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's teammates applauded his aggressiveness, ``but you've
got to pick the situation,'' he said. ``And that wasn't the right
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer, who had nine straight scoreless relief outings before
giving up a home run to Anaheim's Dave Hollins on Thursday, came in
for starter Brian Anderson to pitch the eighth inning with the
Diamondbacks ahead, 3-2. Springer walked the first Cardinals
hitter, McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The next hitter, Brian Jordan, hit a ball that barely made it
over the fence in left field. The two-run homer put the Cards up by
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I had it set up to get the ball in on him,'' said
Springer. ``I got it in, but not enough. He didn't even hit it off
the meat of the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer's fastball was clocked at 95 mph but had little
movement on it, he said. To his credit, he stopped the bleeding
right there, and then was able to marvel at Lee, like everyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fun to watch,'' said Springer, who earned the victory and
improved to 4-3. ``He's got one of the prettier swings I've ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson admired Lee's first homer, a two-run blast, that gave
the Diamondbacks a 3-2 lead in the seventh. He had been lifted for
a pinch-hitter, but stood to get the win after a clutch
seven-inning, eight-hit, two-run performance that kept the
Diamondbacks close.
</P>
<P>
   Before Lee came up, Anderson thought, ``Here we go. Be a hero
and get me a cheap win.''
</P>
<P>
   But after three straight victories, Anderson ended up with a
no-decision. He will, however, take it.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who hit a grand slam on Friday, singled and flied out
against Anderson after another impressive batting practice display.
Then in the fifth, with two runs in, McGee at second and two out,
Anderson walked McGwire intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the crowd booed. Then they cheered after Anderson got
Jordan to fly out and end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it,'' Anderson said of the reaction to the free pass.
``They want him to swing the bat. I kind of want him to swing, too.
Pop it up or ground out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
