<HEADLINE>
HOMERLESS MCGWIRE STILL THRILLS FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX A sellout crowd came to cheer him _ even during batting
practice although he is the ``enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been that way everywhere we've gone,'' said  &UR; Mark
McGwire, the man who figures to render moot  &UR; Roger Maris' asterisk.
``I don't know why, either. It's one of those unexplainable
things.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, after creating a hole in one of Bank One
Ballpark's center field scoreboards during an impressive batting
practice display, McGwire labeled a day in which he walked twice,
once intentionally, and had a single in two official at bats in a
7-4 loss as ``perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything so I don't have to talk to anyone,'' he
said. ``It's one of those perfect days.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, fans cheered when his rocket to center field fooled them
into thinking home run, and booed when Diamondbacks Manager  &UR; Buck
Showalter properly ordered him walked. Strange. Perhaps as strange
as Friday's game, when Arizona fans cheered his game-breaking grand
slam at the expense of Diamondbacks pitcher  &UR; Andy Benes.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter was asked whether fan fickleness bothered Benes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy understands. Fans recognize great plays and cheer them,''
Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter believes that if McGwire, who already has 31 homers in
pursuit of Maris' record of 61, stays healthy, he'll break the
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark has been healthy for an extended period of time, and it
has been awhile since he's been able to put together a streak of
healthy games '' he said. ``I don't think anyone doubts that he'll
get it if he stays healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great support system behind him. (Cardinals Manager
 &UR; Tony
 &UR; La Russa) knows how to use him and rest him accordingly. I also
think he knows, whether he breaks it or not, he'll still have the
support of the hometown fans and the people he's playing for.''
</P>
<P>
   Maris didn't enjoy that luxury _ half of the baseball public
didn't want him to break  &UR; Babe Ruth's mark and let him know it. &QL; 
Short day &QL; 
On a day when he hit two homers, Diamondbacks first baseman
 &UR; Travis &UR; Lee's hardest shot might have been off the back of
Cardinals starter
 &UR; Kent Mercker's knee, which knocked the left-hander out of the game
in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The ball one-hopped off the dirt pathway leading to the mound
and struck Mercker's leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't feel it,'' Mercker said of his foot after the
game. ``I know it's there because my shoe is on it.''
</P>
<P>
   X-rays proved negative. &QL; 
Say bye &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bob Wolcott knows that pro baseball is about
``What-have-you-done-for-us-lately.''
</P>
<P>
   After throwing eight shutout innings in his Diamondbacks
starting debut against Oakland last week, Wolcott was rocked for
seven runs in 3 innings against Anaheim in his second start and was
sent to Tucson on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona recalled right-hander  &UR; Bobby Chouinard from the
Sidewinders in his place. Chouinard, 26, was claimed on waivers
June 2 from Milwaukee and was set to start Saturday night's game
for Tucson, where he had a save and a 3.86 ERA in three
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter has ticketed Chouinard for the overworked bullpen. &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was only 84 degrees when the first pitch flew
Saturday, the roof was closed on Bank One Ballpark, making it the
the second game completely played indoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done tests with people sitting in the direct light of
the sun at 1 p.m. It's extremely uncomfortable,'' said  &UR; Bob Machen,
director of operations at the park. ``That's why the roof is there.
So we used it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
