u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRILL-LEWINSKY-BOS &LR;      06-14 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRILL-LEWINSKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE TAKES STARR, PRESS TO TASK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newly minted media critic Steven Brill Saturday attacked news
organizations' handling of the Monica S. Lewinsky story as a
``scandal'' and accused independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr of
``leaking the most damaging details of the investigation,'' in
possible violation of federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-page ``Pressgate'' article in the first issue of the
media criticism magazine, called Brill's Content, was released
Saturday and contains numerous interviews with prominent
journalists who worked on the Lewinsky story.
</P>
<P>
   Brill's article was greeted as good news by the White House and
is likely to be the talk of today's Washington pundit parade, with
Brill appearing on C-SPAN, CNN, and CBS.
</P>
<P>
   The most eye-opening section is Brill's April interview with
Starr, in which the independent counsel says he ``talked with
reporters on background on some occasions,'' and that his deputy
Jackie Bennett Jr. did most of the talking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Starr told Brill, the founder of Court TV and The American
Lawyer magazine, that there was ``nothing improper'' about those
conversations since they did not involve grand jury proceedings.
Federal law prohibits prosecutors from revealing information from
grand jury proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also argued the leaks were needed to counter
``misinformation'' being spread about his investigation. Saturday,
he said the article ``recklessly and irresponsibly'' charged him
with improper contacts with the media.
</P>
<P>
   Brill writes that the conversations are ``clearly a violation of
both Justice Department prosecutorial guidelines and the bar's
ethical code.'' And though Brill called Starr ``an old friend of
mine,'' in an interview Saturday, he stated that Starr's defense of
those conversations proves ``he's lost perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said, ``The article
raises grave concerns about Mr. Starr's entire investigation. There
are now very serious questions about the way this investigation
began and whether Mr. Starr has a conflict that prevents him from
investigating his office's conduct in this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy called for an independent investigator to evalute
Starr's pattern of ``violating grand jury secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   In Starr's statement Saturday, he said his office ``does not
release grand jury material directly or indirectly, on the record
or off the record.'' He added that his contacts with journalists
``have been legal, appropriate and consistent with Department of
Justice policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In assessing the first three weeks of coverage of the Lewinsky
story that broke in January, Brill sees a series of events that
moved from Linda Tripp _ who he says taped Lewinsky in the hopes of
writing a White House tell-all book _ to an overreaching Starr, to
a press corps so eager for salacious scoops that it became
``corrupted to its core'' and ``an enabler of Starr's abuse of
power.'' Tripp's tape recordings led to an investigation into
whether President Clinton had a sexual affair with former White
House intern Lewinsky and asked her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pressgate,'' Brill states that he saw internal memos from
three news organizations that ``cite Starr's office as a source.''
But he writes that reporters were unwilling to fully pursue the
issue of Starr leaks because they were the beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Brill's analysis also focuses on the role of Tripp and her
adviser, book agent Lucianne Goldberg, in peddling the Lewinsky
story to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Brill writes that ``it is impossible to imagine'' that the
Constitution's authors wanted a president impeached ``all because a
Linda Tripp and Lucianne Goldberg got an intern to talk into a
tapped phone about sex so they could put together a book deal.''
</P>
<P>
   In his scathing criticism of the press, Brill parcels out plenty
of blame. He reconstructs the history of such rumors as the
semen-stained dress and reports of witnesses to a White House
encounter between Lewinsky and Clinton, chalking them up to sloppy
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The story is also harshly critical of television commentators
who speculated about the scandal. Among his targets are Newsweek's
Howard Fineman, who admits in the story to saying ``things that
were unfair or worse''; NBC's Tim Russert, who was telling viewers
in late January that Clinton had only a few days to offer a
complete explanation; and ABC's Sam Donaldson, who on Jan. 25
asserted that Clinton's presidency could be ``numbered in days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The real point of this piece,'' said Brill in the interview,
``is that to me, this is a complete flip from the press's role in
Watergate.'' Not only were reporting standards stricter for
Watergate, he said, but in that case the press stood up to power.
In the Lewinsky episode, he accuses journalists of being a tool of
Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
