   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Todd C. Duncan 404-526-5456, 404-533-7872
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Art Dalglish at 301-460-6176.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Revised) CLINTON-DEVELOPING _ WASHINGTON _ On June 24 President
Clinton heads to China for the third of this year's five planned
presidential forays into the developing world. The 10-day China
visit, an extraordinary amount of time for a single country, comes
on the heels of Clinton's Africa trip in March and his visit to
South America in April. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Tuesday, June 9 in both the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WRONG-GUY _ ATLANTA _ David Smith, a Delta Airlines mechanic
from McDonough, has been in trouble with the law repeatedly since
February. The only problem is, the real criminal isn't Smith, but
someone who has assumed his identity after getting a hold of his
Social Security number. (Hardie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   KIDNAPPER _ ATLANTA _Dorothy Leonard isn't sure of a lot of
things after her father's death shattered the fragile family just
before the end of World War II, scattering her brothers and sisters
into orphanages south of Atlanta. (Scruggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST _ Checking with a few Baptist churches to see if they're
talking about the wives statement. (Brett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-BANNERS _ A vocal citizens group aligned with the religious
right is behind a move by the Gwinnett Library Board this week to
have Jim Carroll's ``The Basketball Diaries,'' a former best-seller
about a young heroin addict, banned from the county library system.
(Ippolito, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN AMERICAN STATESMAN BATS PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move Sunday, June 14.
</P>
<P>
   BAT _ From caves in northern Mexico, three-quarters of a million
bats (mostly pregnant) females fly each spring to tiny slots under
the Congress Avenue bridge to give birth and awe tourists. But in
Mexico bats are seen as livestock killers and the
Austin-headquartered Bats International sends representatives into
the schools to convince Mexican families otherwise. We meet with
Mexican conservationists and visit Cueva de la Boca, one of our
bats' winter hide-outs. BEACH
</P>
<P>
   BAT-SCIENCE _ As a maternity ward and nursing station for
Mexican free-tail bats, the 16-inch-deep, 1-inch-wide expansion
slots of the Congress Avenue bridge couldn't be more perfect. The
concrete soaks up the day's heat and keeps the pups warm while
momma bats fly nightly sorties across Central Texas to consume huge
amounts of insects, mostly plump moths, not tiny mosquitos. (Beach,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BAT-BRACKEN _ Merlin Tuttle takes Ty and Beach to Bracken Cave,
home of the largest known colony of any mammal on earth _ as many
as 40 million Mexican free-tail bats _ and talks about getting
chased by cannibals, nibbled on by flesh-eating fish and the like.
Then the bats come out. We get a rare look. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BAT-BRIDGE _ Bat Conservation International have made the
biggest urban bat colony in the country under the Congress Avenue
bridge a must-see for Austin visitors. (Beach, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   REM _ A report from the third Tibetan Freedom Concert, set for
June 13 in Washington D.C., is a coming-out of sorts for Athens
supergroup R.E.M. It's only the second time in their career they've
interrupted a recording session to make a live appearance. And this
one is the group's first public outing since drummer Bill Berry
quit the group last October. No doubt the band will test some new
material from the album-in-progress. Plus band members will be
available to answer questions. (MLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) For release Sunday, June 14.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
