<P>
   U.N.-TRIBUNAL (Rome) _ In one of the most ambitious efforts ever
to extend the rule of international law, the United Nations will
open a conference here Monday to thrash out rules for an
international criminal court to prosecute crimes against humanity.
By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-NUKE (United Nations) _ The man who is expected to become
India's next foreign minister says that the end of the Cold War has
left a power vacuum from central Asia to Africa that his government
cannot ignore. It was this change in the global security
environment, he said, that ultimately triggered India's decision to
test nuclear weapons. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-EXORCIST (Paris) _ Foreign Journal: on the exorcist of
Notre Dame. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   TEXMEX-ECON (El Paso) _ Four years after the North American Free
Trade Agreement lowered trade barriers, the cities along Texas'
long border with Mexico are struggling to become more than
glorified truck depots for the free trade era, a smoggy transfer
zone for the American economy thriving hundreds of miles to their
north. Elsewhere in Texas, as in most of the United States, the
economy is booming. But here along the border, unemployment
persists at two and three times the national rate and incomes
remain far below state and national averages. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE-FLINT (Flint, Mich.) _ The people of Flint are tired
of both sides in the current strike against a GM parts plant here.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-TAXCUTTERS (Washington) _ It's been a tough year for
Republican tax cutters. Clinton effectively put the budget surplus
off limits by claiming it for Social Security. Efforts to pay for a
tax cut by slashing spending have run into a wall of political
opposition. Other potential sources, like the money generated by
the proposed anti-smoking bill, aren't yet certain. So it was
perhaps not surprising when Gingrich and his lieutenants lashed out
in frustration last week at the Congressional Budget Office, whose
estimates of the nation's fiscal condition over the past few years
have proven consistently too pessimistic. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ Under pressure from farmers,
Congress is poised to skirt the nation's sanctions on India and
Pakistan by allowing the sale of wheat to those countries. This
would seem to undermine the administration's moral outrage against
India and Pakistan. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
