<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-MEDIA-ART-55     06-14 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-MEDIA-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BILINGUAL WAY TO ATTRACT VIEWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Maria Conchita Alonso and Dan Guerrero is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a rising number of the nation's Hispanic television viewers
now bilingual, a handful of programs are being broadcast that use
varying degrees of both English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of such programming on Spanish-language networks
and in high-profile local programming reflects efforts by
television executives to reach a younger, more culturally attuned
niche of the nation's 8 million Hispanic households. Though the
networks have been slow to attract this population, other media
like magazine publishing, radio and music are flourishing with
crossover content that reflects the Latin experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overdue,'' said Bruce Silverman, executive vice president
of Western Media International in Los Angeles, a buyer of media
time.
</P>
<P>
   The newest program is from Telemundo Group Inc., which with a 17
percent share of the Spanish market is a distant second to
Univision Communications Inc., with 83 percent. Telemundo
affiliates in 60 markets recently began broadcasting a daily
variety show whose host is Cuban-born actress Maria Conchita
Alonso, who often strays into Spanglish, a hybrid of English and
Spanish. In the program's first month, Telemundo has seen national
ratings for its time slot increase about 10 percent, according to
A.C. Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   The show was in the works even before the announcement in
November of Telemundo's planned sale to Sony Pictures Entertainment
and Tele-Communications Inc. But it reflects Sony's intent to
update the look and content of the network's programs, said Alan
Sokol, a Sony senior vice president. ``We think advertisers have a
tremendous hunger for programming other than novellas,'' he said,
referring to the lurid, low-budget, foreign-made soap operas on
both Spanish networks.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, ad agency representatives in New York will get a
look at Telemundo's first Sony-backed season lineup. Sony's
acquisition of Telemundo is expected to receive regulatory approval
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Sony is already a steady program supplier to network television
with shows like ``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Vibe.'' The company has
financed a dozen Telemundo pilots and intends to put into weekly
production enough programming to revamp at least one full night in
prime time. The shows will include one-hour dramas and be only in
Spanish. ``We hope and believe the bilingual audience will come
back,'' Sokol said, ``but we don't want to risk alienating the
Spanish-dominant audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Barry Diller's USA Networks Inc. began Citi Vision, a
local programming effort at the Miami station WAMI. Its lineup
includes ``Generation n,'' a bilingual magazine show based on a
locally popular English-language magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Univision's cable network, Galavision, began
broadcasting a group of programs on Sunday night that are nearly
all in English seasoned with Spanish phrases. The programs include
``Funny Is Funny,'' a comedy, and back-to-back reruns of ``Que
Pasa, USA?,'' a 20-year-old Miami-based sitcom from the Public
Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   The results are telling. In the first six weeks, about 55,000
viewers tuned in who do not normally watch the Spanish-language
cable network, which is available to 1.7 million Hispanic homes,
said Anne H. Corley, a spokeswoman for Univision.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Economics and politics are forcing Hispanics to embrace English
more quickly, said Alex Nogales, chairman of the National Hispanic
Media Coalition, an advocacy group. The decision this month by
California voters to ban bilingual education in schools underscores
that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media is 10 steps behind what the world is made out of,''
said Nogales, a former television producer who was consulted by
Sony on its Telemundo pilots. Because they rely on foreign shows,
Spanish networks are losing young viewers to mainstream networks,
he said, while insularity at national networks produces fare like
Fox's ``Culture Clash'' and ABC's ``Common Law,'' programs aimed at
Hispanic viewers that did not survive a season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Valdez, producer of ``Funny Is Funny,'' added: ``We have
more Latinos than Canada has citizens. How can you ignore this
market?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
