<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASHPOST-MEDIA-ART-57     06-14 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHPOST-MEDIA-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON POST'S NEW MANAGING EDITOR SETS QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(lh) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A guest seeking Steve Coll, the managing editor in
waiting at The Washington Post, turns left on leaving the
fifth-floor lobby of The Post, bypassing the main section of the
newsroom. A circuitous path through the style section's desks leads
to Coll's office, currently a parking lot for binders full of memos
about the institution he will help lead, starting June 29.
</P>
<P>
   In the Post's geography, Coll's office is an outer suburb. It is
far distant from the muscular power centers where national,
metropolitan and foreign news is gathered, edited and published _
as distant, in psychic terms, as Coll's teen-age haunts in the
mall-filled precincts of nearby Rockville, Md., were from the State
Department or the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career has been a zigzag; there is no question about
that,'' Coll (pronounced to rhyme with the first syllable in
``holly'') said in a recent interview. It began at a music industry
trade journal in Los Angeles where he typed classified ads _ ``you
know, heavy metal lead singer seeks glam bass player'' _ and took
him to the Wall Street beat, then overseas. Now he wants to add a
new dimension to The Post, although he has little management
experience to call on.
</P>
<P>
   The stock-in-trade of the 39-year-old has been exploring
journalistic territory from unusual angles and with uncommon depth.
His boss, executive editor, Leonard Downie Jr., 56, made his name
in hands-on hard-news editing. Coll, despite plenty of hard-news
experience, looks at the world through a longer lens. ``He's more
creative and imaginative than I am, and he communicates better,''
Downie said.
</P>
<P>
   And when Coll talks about his vision for The Post, he speaks
about institutionalizing the quest for remarkable, in-depth nuanced
pieces that many journalistic institutions put on a pedestal but
fewer manage to get into print.
</P>
<P>
   ``An important part of what I want to do involves changing the
attitude in the newsroom about ambitious investigative work and
projects,'' Coll said. ``Far too many reporters and editors in the
newsroom today shy away from project work or approach it with great
trepidation because they feel that projects become flypaper for
demoralizing editing and second-guessing and end up falling short
of their original ambitions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a business of sound bites, Coll speaks in full, well-turned
paragraphs. A blues pianist by avocation, he is also immersed in a
chronological study of the American presidency (currently stalled
at Zachary Taylor). And at a paper whose main franchise is breaking
stories about government, Coll made his reputation inviting readers
to understand complexity, about subjects from nuclear
nonproliferation to the Securities and Exchange Commission. His
coverage of the commission brought him and his colleague David A.
Vise a Pulitzer Prize in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, he nearly left the paper for a book-writing
career that has already produced four books. His methodology in all
endeavors: clear-cutting his way through available information,
then molding a story, told around individuals, that makes
intimidating subjects accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the newsroom wonder whether Downie, known for closely
monitoring much of the work there, will give Coll room to breathe.
Downie, however, sees no problem. ``I certainly have strong gut
instincts about where he will fill things out and where I will
recede,'' Downie said. ``Certainly he has a particular competency
in the whole business of driving enterprise reporting.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rick Atkinson, the paper's assistant managing editor for
investigations and projects, said: ``The prime attraction Steve had
for Leonard was that he was not Leonard. He's not a hard-news,
blood-and-guts, get-out-the-paper kind of guy. He has an
inclination for ways to work that won't simply be a matter of
following in Len's footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Coll came to The Post in 1985, writing for the Style section and
later covering Wall Street. By 1990, he was in India.
</P>
<P>
   From there, he wrote a magazine piece about the suburbs of his
childhood. `` `What village do you belong to?' they asked me again
and again in India,'' he wrote. ``It's an unsettling question. On
the subcontinent you aren't just `from' somewhere.'' Instead, ``you
`belong' to the place of your origins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post's newsroom asks similar questions: which
desk do you come from? Coll's resume lists none of the big downtown
desks _ the metropolitan desk, with its 150 or so journalists, or
the national staff. As the heir to Robert G. Kaiser _ who will
return to writing this summer _ he is among the first top editors
at a large metropolitan daily whose training came from covering
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest gap in Coll's resume is management
experience. The newsroom he will lead employs about 800 people. The
Washington Post Magazine, which he edited for about two years, has
20 editorial staff members. But even there, he broke molds. Coll
was the first editor of that magazine to serve as its publisher,
supervising about 10 advertising and circulation workers.
</P>
<P>
   Coll acknowledges that he faces a difficult task nursing the
institution and its new color presses through ``more manufacturing
change than any time in the paper's history'' in the next year. But
his first priority is understanding The Post's journalists.
</P>
<P>
   To encourage enterprise, he seeks to change the pessimism that
saps newsroom morale. ``You know, there's a lot of conversation in
the newsroom about our worst work,'' he said. ``Reporters say, `I
could be great the way you want me to be, but the problem is my
editors don't understand.' And editors say, `I could be great the
way you want me to be; the trouble is my reporters aren't
capable.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way of failing to take responsibility,'' he said. ``I
want to avoid this discussion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
