<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-AD-COLUMN-528&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PITCHING PRESCRIPTION DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The proliferation of prescription drug pitches aimed
directly at consumers has become one of the hottest topics in
advertising. So it was not unexpected that a seminar on the
subject, attended by more than 200 agency and pharmaceutical
industry executives, should generate its share of Zoloft zingers,
the Rx equivalents of Maalox moments.
</P>
<P>
   The seminar, grandly called the Health Summit Breakfast, was
held last week in midtown Manhattan as a cooperative project of
three magazines owned by the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner Inc.:
Time, Health and Hippocrates.
</P>
<P>
   There were speeches, a panel discussion and the release of
preliminary findings from what was described as the first major
study of consumer attitudes about prescription drugs since the Food
and Drug Administration shook up the field last August by relaxing
standards governing television spots for them.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight was an assertive keynote speech by Dr. David
Kessler, the commissioner of Food and Drugs from 1990 to 1997. He
said the drug industry might one day rue its rush to peddle
prescription products on TV amid claims that direct-to-consumer
advertising improves health care by more fully educating patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line, I will submit, is that no one today knows if
more benefit or more harm will be done by expanding
direct-to-consumer advertising,'' said Kessler, now the dean of the
Yale University School of Medicine. That is so, he added, because
the commercials may mislead or confuse the public to ask for drugs
that are inappropriate, unneeded or even dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prescription drugs are not just any consumer product; there
are real risks,'' Kessler said. ``Whenever you sell a product with
risks, you have a special responsibility. If you have doubts, ask
your lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler predicted that one day there would be a product
liability trial centered on drug commercials, warning, ``In that
courtroom, I can assure you, someone is going to roll in that VCR
and that monitor and play the ad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You want people to want your product, and that's OK,'' Kessler
said. ``But the fact is if we move to a culture that increasingly
pushes prescription drugs, I ask you whether that is in the public
health interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler, a longtime opponent of direct-to-consumer appeals for
prescription drugs, reminded the audience of his role in blocking
the loosening of the regulations for such spots while he was head
of the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably more than any other individual stood in the way''
of the changes, he said, adding that he was ``in favor of giving
patients more information about drugs'' but only ``after the
medicine is prescribed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People like me will never say, `Gee, those ads are just
great,''' Kessler said. ``But you can tip the balance toward the
benefits if you focus an ad not only on the product you're trying
to sell but on the public health interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be ashamed to run a prescription drug ad if it's
not in the public interest. You can take the high ground; you can
talk about the public health issue and also sell your product. If
you can't say your ad is in the public health interest, don't run
it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gay Kassan, marketing development director at Corporate
Marketing Intelligence, an in-house research unit at Time Inc.,
described the initial findings of the survey, which was conducted
among 1,500 consumers aged 18 and over in March and April; a
separate study of 2,760 physicians was conducted during that same
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers remain very reliant on health care professionals for
health care advice,'' Ms. Kassan said. She cited survey findings
that 66 percent of consumers said they looked to pharmacists for
advice; 65 percent said they looked to physicians; 34 percent, to
friends and relatives; 28 percent, to articles in newspapers and
magazines, and 26 percent, to television news.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what they wanted from direct-to-consumer drug advertising,
the consumers responding to the survey most often said (84 percent)
they wanted the ads to clearly state all the risks associated with
the medicine. That was followed by wanting all needed information
(76 percent); a toll-free telephone number (66 percent); time to
study the ad (65 percent) and preventing children from seeing the
ad (64 percent).
</P>
<P>
   As for the physicians surveyed, 79 percent said they were
concerned that the relaxed guidelines for commercials would cause
patients to ask for unnecessary or incorrect drugs. Only 40 percent
said they believed that the ads would help them provide the best
treatment for patients.
</P>
<P>
   And 65 percent of the doctors said they believed that the most
important purpose of direct-to-consumer advertising was building
awareness of diseases and their symptoms. That was followed by
educating patients about treatment options, at 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since no seminar would be complete without a sales pitch from
the sponsor, Ms. Kassan shared results of the survey about various
media. ``Consumers rate magazines as the most appropriate medium''
for pharmaceutical advertising, she said, at 58 percent; television
had 27 percent and newspapers, 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines like Time, Health and Hippocrates are keen to retain
their ads for prescription drugs and to slow the shift of such ad
dollars from print to TV, which has sharply accelerated since the
regulations were changed.
</P>
<P>
   That increase in commercials has fueled a substantial increase
in direct-to-consumer ad spending. A panelist, Maureen Regan, chief
executive at Regan Campbell Ward in New York _ a health care agency
that is part of the McCann-Erickson World Group unit of Interpublic
Group of Cos. _ predicted that such spending would total $1.6
billion this year, compared with an estimated $1 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would mean outspending cereals, beer and hotels and
resorts,'' Ms. Regan said.
</P>
<P>
   So, imagine the possibilities for peddling drugs like those
products. How about a commercial sung to the tune of an old Post
cereal jingle:
</P>
<P>
   ``Most any antidepressant is fine with me as long as you spell
it Z-O-L-O-F-T.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
