<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSPAN SUPPORTS RULES ON DERIVATIVE ACCOUNTING
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, has come
out in favor of the accounting rule makers, the Financial
Accounting Standards Board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Arthur Levitt Jr., the chairman of the Securities
and Exchange Commission, Greenspan said that he approved of the
accounting board's attempt to force companies to record the value
of financial derivatives in their financial statements. He is also
opposed to legislation to weaken that stand.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE EYES STILL SELLS WELL
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra has proved as popular dead as alive. When news of
his death was announced, demand was strong for both his music and
26 Sinatra book titles. Booksellers say demand ran high for most
books, including Shawn Levy's ``Rat Pack Confidential,'' ``The Way
You Wear Your Hat'' by Bill Zehme, and Kitty Kelley's unauthorized
biography ``His Way.''
</P>
<P>
   REDIRECTING THE WASHINGTON POST
</P>
<P>
   Among the things Steve Coll, the 39-year-old managing editor in
waiting at The Washington Post, wants to do when he takes over is
encourage enterprise at the daily newspaper and change the
pessimism that saps newsroom morale.
</P>
<P>
   A PRACTICAL GUIDE TO TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Many people, including business executives, do not like change.
And some officials even shy away from using new technology. Now two
consultants have written a practical guide that focuses on how all
businesses, even risk-averse old-line organizations, have an
opportunity to exploit dramatic changes wrought by technology.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC STATIONS GOING BILINGUAL
</P>
<P>
   Television programs on Hispanic stations are now being broadcast
in both English and Spanish. This reflects efforts by executives to
reach a younger niche of the nation's 8 million Hispanic
households.
</P>
<P>
   LOTUS UPDATES A NEW SUITE
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Papows, president of Lotus, says the latest version of
the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet, word processing, data base and
graphics programs, called the Smart Suite Millennium Edition,
should revive the ailing company, which has lost market share to
Microsoft's Excel and Corel's Wordperfect Suite.
</P>
<P>
   ARMSTRONG IN DEAL FOR TRIANGLE
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong World Industries, which designs and makes floors and
ceilings, plans to acquire Triangle Pacific, which makes hardwood
flooring products and kitchen and bathroom cabinets, for about $890
million.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG MAY AID IN WEIGHT LOSS
</P>
<P>
   Amgen's potential anti-obesity drug leptin, which made headlines
a few years ago by reducing body fat in mice, has been found to
contribute to weight loss in people as well. But the results
indicate that leptin will not be a sure-fire cure for obesity.
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRY RATES TV PITCHES FOR DRUGS
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of prescription drug pitches aimed directly at
consumers has become one of the hottest topics in advertising. A
seminar last week attracted 200 agency and pharmaceutical industry
executives and included a speech by the former FDA head, Dr. David
A. Kessler, who said the drug industry might one day rue its rush
to peddle prescription products on TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
