<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-950(2TAKES     06-14 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK: SINATRA BOOKS RISE AND FALL; PBS DELEGATES IN FOR
SURPRISE; SISTER SOULJAH BEHIND THE MIKE; STOOGES GOING STRONG;
LEFTIES GO TO WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Between the time Frank Sinatra died on May 14 and the television
specials began, American publishers revved up the presses. In death
was the possibility of life, with out-of-print titles resuscitated,
existing books given extra sales and unpublished death-watch titles
finalized for quick release.
</P>
<P>
   When the news broke, a flurry of demand from retailers hit all
26 Sinatra titles listed at Ingram Book Co., the nation's largest
wholesaler. Booksellers say the biggest demand was for Shawn Levy's
``Rat Pack Confidential,'' published by Doubleday; ``The Way You
Wear Your Hat,'' by Bill Zehme, a Sinatra lifestyle tip sheet
published by HarperCollins; ``His Way,'' the Bantam paperback of
Kitty Kelley's unauthorized biography; Carol Publishing's
``Sinatra: Behind the Legend,'' by J. Randy Taraborrelli, and John
Lahr's ``Sinatra: The Artist and the Man,'' published by Random
House.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Kohn, a spokeswoman for Borders Inc., said: ``Whatever was
in the stores the weekend after he died sold very, very well.'' And
the books continued to move briskly for a week. But then came June.
</P>
<P>
   As Margaret Maupin, senior buyer for the Tattered Cover in
Denver, put it: ``The window of opportunity for this kind of book
is small. And when they stop selling, they drop like a rock.'' Two
weeks after the death, the book sales dropped, too.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, publishers could find themselves with thousands of
unsold Sinatra books returning to their warehouses. Some, like News
Corp.'s HarperCollins, are hoping that a Father's Day promotion
will move their books. But lady luck didn't entirely abandon the
pack. What's really swinging _ with no sign of slowing down _ is
Sinatra's music. Both Borders and Amazon.com say the music is not
only holding its own with established fans but also playing to new
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Just Talking: Public Broadcasting
</P>
<P>
   For a year, Rep. W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, R-La., has been
trumpeting his idea for how to keep money flowing to public
television and radio without draining the federal budget: a trust
fund, perhaps endowed by fees charged to commercial broadcasters.
But the proposal has attracted little support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Tauzin, chairman of the House subcommittee on
telecommunications, will address delegates to PBS' annual meeting,
taking place this year in Miami. They expect to hear Tauzin
announce that he will introduce a bill proposing such a trust fund.
Indeed, last week's issue of Current, the journal covering public
broadcasting, said that Tauzin would announce just that.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates may be in for a surprise. Tauzin will indeed speak
to them live, by satellite from the PBS station in Baton Rouge. But
a staff member said that his bill would merely propose setting up
``a nine-member blue-ribbon commission to study the future of
public broadcasting'' and that it called for this panel to study
the trust fund idea, among others.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Tauzin's bill, which is co-sponsored by Rep.
Edward Markey, D-Mass., would only start the discussion about the
fund idea.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the bill tends to ``business as usual'' _
though with potentially a lot more money. Under current law, $250
million is budgeted for 1999 and $300 million for 2000. The bill
proposes reauthorizing federal money for public broadcasting
through the 2002 fiscal year at an amount equal to 40 percent of
the non-federal revenue raised by the system _ with a cap of $475
million. And it asks for a separate appropriation of $95 million a
year to help PBS convert to digital transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Dialing Sister Souljah
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sister Souljah, the musician, writer, political
activist and avowed ``outlaw,'' found herself as a guest host on
the noon talk show at WLIB-AM, the black-owned station in New York
City, in a week of particularly incendiary news. In New York, the
family of Yusuf Hawkins had received a letter of apology from Keith
Mondello, a member of a white gang who was recently released after
eight years in prison for his role in killing the black teen-ager
in the Bensonhurst section of Brooklyn in 1989. And in Texas, the
father of one of three white men arrested in the torture-slaying of
a black man apologized for his son's actions.
</P>
<P>
   How did Sister Souljah's week go? The incidents created a theme
that ran for several days: Is that all a black life is worth? An
apology?
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be difficult for white society to do more than say
`sorry,''' Sister Souljah said. ``In the death of a black child or
person, the victim's family is expected to be eloquent.
Sympathetic. Because the value of that black child is less.''
</P>
<P>
   Listeners weighed in frequently and sometimes furiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick of forgiving,'' one woman said bluntly. ``Thank you
for speaking the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Another caller said: ``I'm very concerned with the Texas
incident. Black people should be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Listeners addressed and asked Sister Souljah to address other
issues as well.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Nigerian dictator who died suddenly, a caller suspected
foul play and a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   What about the Bloods, the gang in Brooklyn? Were they on the
rise? another asked.
</P>
<P>
   What about rap music? ``It does perpetuate the chaos going on
today,'' Sister Souljah said. ``But it does not originate it.''
</P>
<P>
   How about the media's influence on young black women? ``Cute and
stupid are no accomplishment at all,'' the host said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of her week, Sister Souljah was ready to accentuate
the positive. ``Let's see if we can make some type of a love
connection,'' she said. So the theme of the show was black love and
relationships. She said, ``We have to be as keen in our
observations of what's right as what's wrong.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   A PBS Look at Press Behavior
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual agreement between a charitable trust and a news
program, ``The News Hour With Jim Lehrer'' on PBS has added Terence
Smith, the longtime CBS correspondent, to its staff to head a
special unit devoted to examining the performance of the news
media. The work will be financed by a two-year, $3 million grant
from Pew Charitable Trusts, an organization based in Philadelphia
devoted to supporting activities in culture, public education and
public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who worked as a correspondent and editor for The New York
Times for 20 years before joining CBS in 1985, will leave his CBS
post and report on press-related issues regularly for ``The News
Hour,'' the weeknight news and analysis program. His work is
scheduled to begin appearing in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Rebecca Rimel, the president of Pew Charitable
Trusts, said: ``What is needed is a reasoned but impassioned
examination of press behavior on a regular basis. The `News Hour'
will provide that much-needed forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he expected to examine such subjects as the content
of the news, its packaging, issues of taste, the effect of money on
the news media, the trend toward tabloid treatment of the news,
consolidation in the industry and the debate over free broadcast
time for political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Three Stooges Beer
</P>
<P>
   A company called Comedy III Entertainment is trying to bring
back the phenomenon of the Three Stooges with everything from a new
television release of the classic film shorts to items like Three
Stooges hair tonic and Three Stooges beer.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Benjamin, director of business affairs for Comedy III, said
Stooge business was surging again, as evidenced by a decision by
Columbia Studios to repackage the 190 short films made by the
Stooges from 1934 to 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our licensing and merchandising business has quadrupled in the
past three years,'' Benjamin said. The images of the three classic
Stooges _ Moe, Larry and Curly _ now grace everything from
mousepads to screen savers to slot machines and lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin expects business only to improve starting next year,
when Columbia begins syndicating the old films in a format designed
to fit the half-hour slots desired by television stations. ``Most
of the shorts are only 15 to 18 minutes long,'' Benjamin said. But
under an agreement between Columbia and Comedy III, new material,
like background stories about the making of the films, will be used
to fill out the time.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the shorts have been seen in bowdlerized form,
Benjamin said, with several sliced together illogically to make a
half-hour show. They have played most recently on the Family
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Comedy III was formed by the Stooge actors Moe Howard, Larry
Fine and Joe DeRita. DeRita was brought in to fill the role created
by Moe's brother Curly, and was followed up by his other brother
Shemp. The Curly role was also played by Joe Besser in some of the
film shorts. All the actors who played the Stooges in their heyday
are dead, but Comedy III was reinstituted as the rightful licensing
agent for the Stooges' images in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   WBAI Makes a Home on Wall Street
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Listeners to WBAI-FM's morning show were encouraged
recently to call in with slogans to celebrate the left-oriented
radio station's first day in new offices in the citadel of
capitalism: Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard White and Amy Goodman, certainly the most patient
morning show hosts in New York City, at least that morning, were
treated to suggestions like ``Not just another brick in the wall!''
and ``Taking it to the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   WBAI is now housed with Ms. magazine and the Urban League in the
easternmost building on Wall Street, with a view of passing
schooners on the East River and the Brooklyn Promenade beyond.
</P>
<P>
   In the station's old site in the garment district, the
bookkeeper was once run over by a speeding clothing rack. There are
hazards of a different variety here, like creeping capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss the hustle of midtown, but maybe moving to the heart
of capital might help enhance our dreams to attain more capital,''
said Samori Marksman, WBAI's program director. ``Whether or not we
become capitalists is another issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The move comes at an interesting time: The union representing
workers at the station recently voted to prepare for a strike over
unresolved grievances.
</P>
