<P>
   CALIF-WATERWAR (Keeler, Calif.) _ The dry bed of Owens Lake, a
crusty 110-square mile lunar landscape of brackish pools and flaky
salts and toxins, is all that is left in the center of a
once-fertile farming and mining community. There is not the
slightest mystery about where the water went: For 85 years, gravity
has pulled it through a 223-mile man-made aqueduct to build and
sustain the artificially verdant sprawl of Los Angeles, and today
it still supplies just over half the water for the nation's second
largest city. But for the first time in the history of the
longest-running water war in the West, the Owens Valley may be on
the verge of forcing Los Angeles to put some of the water back. By
Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
