<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEER-THEATER-REVIEW-     06-14 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEER-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AS THOUSANDS CHEER': 65-YEAR-OLD TOPICAL REVUE HAS AGED WELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Kevin Chamberlin and Mary Beth Peil is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hey, did you hear the one about Mahatma Gandhi and
Aimee Semple McPherson? All right, maybe they aren't names that
crop up regularly in Letterman and Leno monologues. Maybe your
13-year-old niece doesn't have a clue who they are. Still, when
these long-dead spiritual leaders of India and the United States
meet in the Drama Dept.'s refreshing revival of ``As Thousands
Cheer,'' the Moss Hart and Irving Berlin revue from 1933, you
should have no trouble getting the joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say, can you do anything besides starve?'' asks McPherson,
described here as America's ``foursquare gospel lady'' and embodied
by a gimlet-eyed Mary Beth Peil. Gandhi, represented by B.D. Wong,
has been grinning his way through a hunger strike for
photographers, but he still has the energy to demonstrate a
two-step to ``Shuffle Off to Buffalo.'' McPherson joins in, and
it's suddenly clear that this could be the beginning of a beautiful
road show.
</P>
<P>
   When the original version of ``As Thousands Cheer'' opened at
the Music Box Theater for a run of 304 performances, critic Brooks
Atkinson of The New York Times interrupted his ode of praise to
observe that one shouldn't take its skewering of contemporary
headline makers too seriously, that Broadway likes ``to find
Broadway motives in every person it satirizes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five subsequent years, however, have demonstrated that
``Broadway motives'' and show-business spin have everything to do
with making the world go round. Religion as hard-sell
entertainment? Martyrdom as a photo op? Only the names, and the
technology used to promote them, have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Topical satire, especially the kind found in musical revues,
tends to age about as well as sushi. The surprise of this winningly
modest presentation of a vintage hit, which opened Sunday night at
the Greenwich House Theater under Christopher Ashley's direction,
is that it shows no sign at all of spoilage. The comic bite in
Hart's lines and in Berlin's lyrics still clicks crisply, and the
work's portrait of the pandering ways of celebrities and the
journalists who cover them remains spot-on. Yes, cynicism was
peppier in those days, but peppy cynicism is more fun on a stage
than the wearier, end-of-the-century variety.
</P>
<P>
   The two-year-old Drama Dept. has already established itself as a
vital force in the New York theater and, in its bold reworkings of
``Uncle Tom's Cabin'' and Tennessee Williams' ``Kingdom of Earth,''
an agile practitioner of the much-abused art of deconstruction.
With ``As Thousands Cheer,'' however, there has been no attempt to
look for subtext or to make hindsight part of the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ashley and his eminently likable six-member ensemble
provide a limpid performance that lets the enduring merits of
Hart's sketches and Berlin's splendid songs sparkle without undue
interpretive interference. Each of the actors here sings and clowns
with skill, but without show-stopping aggression or descents into
camp. It's a smart, soft-pedaled approach, remarkable for letting
you feel that you have rediscovered Hart (sans Kaufman) and Berlin
on your own.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The original ``As Thousands Cheer,'' which did much to restore
Berlin's reputation as America's foremost popular songwriter, was a
much grander affair, with at least a dozen featured performers
(including Clifton Webb and Marilyn Miller) and a full dance
ensemble. This version is pared down to an intermissionless 17
sketches. It has jettisoned, among other things, the ``Easter
Parade'' number that was the show's big eye-popper and interpolated
(with considerable wit) ``Let's Have Another Cup of Coffee'' from
the earlier Hart-Berlin collaboration, ``Face the Music.''
</P>
<P>
   The production remains charmingly faithful, however, to the
work's central conceit of events springing to life from newspapers.
Allen Moyer's set makes ingenious use of silver-word-studded walls
that evoke the hot type once used to set hot copy. Kirk Bookman's
lighting, Jonathan Bixby and Gregory A. Gale's costumes and Wendall
K. Harrington's projections conspire expertly to summon a world of
smoke-filled newsrooms and black-and-white imagery.
</P>
<P>
   Hart and Berlin well understood that those who purveyed the news
were as essential to shaping the American sensibility as those who
made it, and that the lines between the two often blurred.
Accordingly, a Walter Winchell-like columnist (the appealing Howard
McGillin) slinks through shadows to sing of life framed ``Through
the Keyhole.'' A young woman (the dulcet-voice Judy Kuhn, in a
gossamer rendition) sends an abject musical prayer to a
lonely-hearts columnist. A prim weather reporter (Ms. Peil)
literally lets her hair down, as her hips sway, to report the
arrival of a tropical front, and ``Heat Wave,'' first performed by
the great Ethel Waters, finds new ways of working up a fever, with
a dancing chorus of newsmen and wily choreography by Kathleen
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is rounded out by Wong, who is terrific doing an antic
confession of love for the funny pages; Kevin Chamberlin, the
evening's true natural comic, and Paula Newsome, who drolly
captures the cultural two-sidedness of Josephine Baker in the
wonderful ``Harlem on My Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Other inflated public images that get punctured include those of
Barbara Hutton, Joan Crawford, the Herbert Hoovers and, most
deliciously, Noel Coward, whose languid, metaphor-strewn grandeur
is captured by the staff of a hotel on whom he has made quite an
impression.
</P>
<P>
   With David Evans (the show's musical director) on the piano and
Lou Bruno playing bass, the production numbers testify to the
astonishing (and often forgotten) scope of Berlin as a composer.
This is a man, after all, capable of both the blithe knowingness of
``Not for All the Rice in China'' and the haunting indirection of
``Supper Time,'' a ballad about a lynching.
</P>
<P>
   Not every sketch flies. And none of the actors (unlike, one
gathers, the original cast members) even try to impersonate their
famous subjects. This may be a mercy, and it's of a piece with
performances that never aspire to individual grandstanding. Like
all of the Drama Dept.'s productions, the first priority of this
one is to illuminate the original work that inspired it. For a show
about the American appetite for adulation, it is also remarkably
generous.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AS THOUSANDS CHEER'
</P>
<P>
   Sketches by Moss Hart; music and lyrics by Irving Berlin;
musical staging by Kathleen Marshall; directed by Christopher
Ashley; sets by Allen Moyer; costumes by Jonathan Bixby and Gregory
A. Gale; lighting by Kirk Bookman; production design by Wendall K.
Harrington; production supervision by Harris Productions Services;
stage manager, John Handy; musical director/arranger, David Evans;
producer, Ira Weitzman. Presented by the Drama Dept. At the
Greenwich House.
</P>
<P>
   With: Kevin Chamberlin, Judy Kuhn, Howard McGillin, Paula
Newsome, Mary Beth Peil, B.D. Wong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
