<P>
   SCOUT _ The Cincinnati Reds and some other small-market baseball
teams are looking for talent in an unusual place _ America's inner
cities. As more and more teams concentrate scoutingefforts in Latin
America and United States suburbs and college campuses,
underfinanced small market-teams hope to stay competitive by
discovering overlooked talent in the inner cities. We follow Jerry
Flowers, a recently hired scout for the Cincinnati Reds whose job
is to scout players in some of the toughest neighborhoods in inner
city Chicago and Detroit in hopes of finding the next Eric Davis,
Kenny Lofton or Darryl Strawberry. This story will give readers a
first-hand look at Flowers' unusual job and the challenges he and
baseball face in reviving the sport in the inner city. (Vinella,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PRO BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   NBALEDE _ Game 6 coverage, Bulls-Jazz. (Bunn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD CUP SOCCER
</P>
<P>
   USCUP _ What is considered the best American team ever to reach
the World Cup takes the field in Paris today with the aim of
equalling a surprise second-round finish in 1994. But opening with
formidable Germany is the first of three highly charged group
matches _ including Iran and Yugoslavia _ that will make that task
very difficult. Just weeks after the U.S. Soccer Federation
outlined an ambitious $50 million developmental program to win the
World Cup by 2010, this American team already is reflecting some of
the changes envisioned for the future of soccer in the U.S. A good
showing in France will help continue the progress made in this
decade. (Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
