<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK-COX06     06-14 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Wohlers talks about relief woes
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A day-and-a-half after Friday's horror, he sat at his
locker Sunday morning and pronounced himself, ''All right. I'm
surviving.'' Then Mark Wohlers opened up.
</P>
<P>
   ''As frustrating as it is, I'm fighting everything,'' he said.
''I'm fighting the situation, trying to get on track. The biggest
problem is I'm fighting myself. It'd be easy to throw in the towel,
but I'm not going to.''
</P>
<P>
   After temporarily losing his closer's job last Sunday, Wohlers
was encouraged Friday when Bobby Cox called on him in the ninth
inning with Atlanta leading 5-2. But after Wohlers promptly walked
Montreal's Chris Widger on four pitches (the second pitch hitting
the backstop), Cox pulled him in favor of Mike Cather. A hit
batter, a walk and a no-out, pinch-hit grand slam by DaRond Stovall
stunned the Braves 6-5 and left Wohlers dazed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was frustrated and upset,'' he said. ''It never happened to
me before. I'd never gone in there and faced one batter and come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Wohlers, who's had periodic control problems in the
past, has rarely struggled like this. In eight appearances since
coming off the disabled list May 24, Wohlers has had just one 1-2-3
inning. He's allowed seven earned runs in his last 5-2/3 innings,
including four in the ninth inning May 28 when the Expos rallied to
win 9-5. Wohlers' wildness has been painful to watch. He's walked
nine in 6-2/3 innings. His ERA: 5.06.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was ''grateful'' when Cox summoned him Friday. ''When
the phone rang, I felt good he had confidence in me, believed in me
in the ninth inning,'' Wohlers said. ''And I wish I could've taken
advantage of the situation. I felt good in the bullpen. I don't
know what it is. If I had the answer...It's just so frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly so because, ''When I struggled in the past, I'd
never had success in my career,'' Wohlers said. ''I didn't know
what I was missing. Now, after having a few successful years, it's
twice as bad. I know what I'm capable of doing and I want to do it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   What Wohlers knows he needs now is patience. ''Just slow stuff
down,'' he said. But he's pressing badly, overanalyzing everything.
''When I'm going good, my mind is completely blank,'' Wohlers said.
''When I see the (catcher's) sign, I go. Now, I'm worried about my
mechanics, worried about this and that. I've just gotta put a hose
in me now and flush it all out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the fastball Friday that sailed to the backstop, ''It
happens,'' said Wohlers. ''When I was going good in '95, '96 and
'97, I threw some to the backstop. But I didn't freak out. I let it
happen. When I'm at my best, I bounce balls. Now, I overreact
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Cox _ who used Dennis Martinez as the closer Saturday _
said, ''I'll just use him as I can. See how he's throwing on the
side, run him out there when I think he's ready. I just think it's
important to get some innings in now. What he needs is some
consistent innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers agrees. ''I want to pitch consistently and more often,''
he said. ''I think I've (only) got 25 innings this year and that
includes spring training.'' It's 24-2/3 innings, 9-2/3 in the
spring and 16 this season. ''I just want to get in there and pitch
and pitch and pitch and pitch. If it's the first inning, the fifth,
OK, and help this team. I know what I'm capable of doing. I just
want to pitch and get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've just got to keep working, keep fighting and not give up.
I'm going to try to do everything harder physically _ in the weight
room throwing on the side. Give it everything I've got and not
cheat myself or the organization. And I just have to not worry
about a whole bunch of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   BACK TO BACK-TO-BACK BACK-TO-BACK: When Javy Lopez and Andruw
Jones homered back-to-back in back-to-back innings Saturday, it was
the fourth time in major-league history the feat had been
accomplished and the second in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ''Really?'' asked Lopez, whose two two-run homers in the second
and third innings were immediately followed by Jones' solos. ''Most
impressive, (they were hit) in the same place.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two such big-league occurrences came in the AL: May
26, 1930 by the Washington Senators' Goose Goslin and Joe Judge,
then May 6, 1941 by Detroit's Hank Greenberg and Bruce Campbell. On
August 6, 1992, Fred McGriff was still a Padre when he and Gary
Sheffield homered back-to-back in back-to-back innings. Then came
Lopez-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   That was also the 19th time in major-league history the same two
players have homered back-to-back twice in a game; the 10th time in
NL history and the second time the Braves have done so. McGriff and
David Justice did it in the first and fifth innings off Bill Swift
in a 9-1 win over the Giants on August 25, 1993 in San Francisco.
That last time it happened anywhere: April 21, 1996, by Seattle's
Ken Griffey Jr. and Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   SMOLTZ UPDATE: John Smoltz worked his second outing of his
latest rehab assignment Sunday. Starting for the Braves' Class A
Macon affiliate, Smoltz went six innings against Capital City,
allowing seven hits and four earned runs. He struck out seven and
walked on. He left after throwing 82 pitches (59 strikes, 23 balls)
and trailing 4-3. Barring further elbow pain, Smoltz is set to
return to the rotation Friday in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
