<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8551 &Cx1f; tad-z
b a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDNAPPER-COX     06-14 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAPPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agent plays beat-the-clock with accused killer, retirementBy
Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dorothy Leonard isn't sure of a lot of things after
her father's death shattered the fragile family just before the end
of World War II, scattering her brothers and sisters into
orphanages south of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the back of her mind, she thinks there were six
children in her family, but she can only account for two brothers
and two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere along the line something happened _ something bad
happened,'' said the 63-year-old Florida woman. ``They say children
tend to block things out.''
</P>
<P>
   But her brother, Franklin Delano Floyd, wasn't so good at
blocking out the bad stuff. ``Franklin wasn't a survivor,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Orphaned about the time he started to walk, Floyd grew into an
explosive teenager and manipulative man who kidnapped children,
starting with a little girl from a Hapeville, Ga. bowling alley in
1962. Eleven years later, after serving a prison term for the first
abduction, FBI agents think he took another little girl from the
Atlanta area. He raised the delicate blond girl as his daughter
then married her and finally killed her in 1990, FBI Agent Joe
Fitzpatrick has said.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd is also believed to have killed at least two other people:
the woman's 6-year old son while in Atlanta in 1994 and a Florida
woman.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Michael Anthony Hughes has never been found, said
Fitzpatrick of the Oklahoma City FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   Although Floyd, 55, won't admit it to agents, his sister says he
has admitted he killed Michael. But Fitzpatrick says until they
find Michael's body, they can't make a case. He believes the
answers lie in the Atlanta area buried deep under Floyd's lies and
43 aliases.
</P>
<P>
   So the veteran agent is on a crusade to solve Michael's
disappearance and figure out who his mother was before he retires
in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really concerned that if we're going to do it, we need to
do it right away,'' Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd has been in trouble with the law since he ran away from a
Hapeville orphanage when he was 15. By that time his sister,
Leonard, was married and living in Sumter, S.C. ``I imagine some
things happened (in the orphanage) that he couldn't deal with
emotionally,'' she said. ``He said he was sexually abused.''
</P>
<P>
   But he only stayed with Leonard for about 10 months. She was
forced to send Floyd away for good after he harmed her son. She
won't say what he did.
</P>
<P>
   Agents believe that Floyd kidnapped Michael's mother in 1973
between Feb. 2 and June 6, but they have no hard evidence such as a
missing person report. Floyd frequently moved and changed their
names, so investigators don't even know who she was. They do know
that she stayed with him until she was killed in a hit-and-run
accident in 1990. At that time she was going by the name Tonya Dawn
Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have absolutely no idea who she might be at all,''
Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, two years after taking her, Floyd enrolled the girl in
first grade in Oklahoma City. Nine years later he enrolled her at
Forest Park High School in Atlanta where she graduated with honors
and a scholarship to Georgia Tech in aeronautical engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took her . . . not out of love, but just took her and
anytime she had a relationship, he just removed her from that
environment,'' Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Tonya had an affair with a man while she was working as a
waitress in an airport hotel bar in Phoenix, Ariz., and soon after
she became pregnant with Michael, Floyd moved the family to Tampa,
Fla. Michael was born in 1988 and the next year Floyd and Tonya
were married. Michael's biological father looked for Tonya, but
Floyd ``had pulled another one of his midnight departures,''
Fitzpatrick said. It was something Floyd did every time she got
close to another man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had had her since she was 6 years old,'' Fitzpatrick said.
``What's she going to do?'' By April 1990, the pair were living In
Oklahoma City, where she had become a stripper. As she planned to
take Michael and leave Floyd, she was killed by a hit-and-run
driver, Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was going back to Phoenix where she was happy,''
Fitzpatrick said. ``That was the only time in her life that she was
happy. She thought the world of that boy. If she had (run from
Floyd earlier), he would have killed her earlier.'
</P>
<P>
   Michael was taken into state custody, but in 1994, Floyd
kidnapped him from an Oklahoma elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   The next day he was in Atlanta, registered under a false name at
the Fulton Inn near Six Flags Over Georgia, west of Atlanta, where
he stayed a week.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapping sparked a national manhunt for Floyd, and agents
trying to follow a road map of his life, immediately found it as
difficult as maneuvering a Mack truck around mountain switch-backs.
Many times Floyd led them around blind curves, and they've yet to
catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Since his Nov. 10, 1994, capture in Louisville, Ky., Floyd has
continued to dangle his secrets in front of agents. He is serving a
52-year sentence at Atlanta Federal Penitentiary for Michael's
kidnapping and is awaiting transfer to Florida on a charge of
murdering another woman, whose skeletal remains were found. Police
linked him to that murder when they found pictures of the woman
being tortured to death among Floyd's possessions. There were also
pictures of another brunette woman, whom authorities say may also
have been abducted from the Atlanta area, but they have not been
able to identify her.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Floyd has not officially confessed to killing
anyone. He claims the boy is safe and with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   After Michael's kidnapping, Fitzpatrick contacted the boy's
father and told him what happened. Both Michael's father and his
current wife told FBI agents they wanted Michael should he be found
alive. ``She said they had a good home and two other kids and they
would take him and love him,'' Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   But that seems unlikely to occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is dead,'' Leonard, Floyd's sister, insisted. ``It
took me so long to accept it. He shouldn't have told me. When he
did, he broke any ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard said that Floyd gave her grisly details of how he drown
Michael while molesting him in a bathtub in the Fulton Inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is telling me the truth,'' Leonard continued. ``I can't
tell you what a state it put me in. I don't know where the body is.
He told me there was a lake outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents searched all the lakes around the Fulton Inn, said
Atlanta FBI agent William M. Bray. By the time they learned Floyd
had stayed there, it was too late to gather evidence from the room,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
