u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      06-14 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: PERFECTING THE WRINKLE-FREE SHIRT; SLIDING ELEVATOR
DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cotton shirt is soft, comfortable and, very often, wrinkled _
especially right after it is pulled out of the dryer. The sleeves
and panels come out faintly lined, like a dry riverbed, but it is
the cuffs, collar and pockets that take _ and show _ the real
beating. A bit of time and effort with an iron and spray starch can
restore a smooth sheen, but nothing looks as neatly tailored as a
cotton shirt fresh from the dry cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   It costs more, too. Permanent-press polyester and then
wrinkle-free cottons were hailed as eliminating the need for
ironing or dry cleaning. But even when the best of those materials
went into a shirt, the seams would pucker. That is because thread
used to sew the shirt together shrinks at a rate different from the
fabric. So, fresh from the dryer, even wrinkle-free fabrics looked
rumpled around the edges.
</P>
<P>
   This makes a prototype shirt sewn with a patented seam
technology all the more remarkable. Half the shirt is made of
ordinary fabric and thread, the other half from wrinkle-free cotton
and treated seams. After washing in warm water and ordinary
detergent, the shirt comes out of a hot tumble-dry cycle looking as
if the right side had just been removed from the store packaging.
The collar and cuff are flat and flawless. There is a temptation to
throw it back in the wash just to make sure it's not an optical
illusion.
</P>
<P>
   The patented technology belongs to TAL Apparel Ltd., a Hong-Kong
based clothing maker that produces 30 million shirts a year for
companies like Calvin Klein, Eddie Bauer, the Gap, Banana Republic
and Burberry's. The inventor is the company's textile scientist,
John Wong.
</P>
<P>
   Wong perfected the wash-and-wear cotton shirt by embedding an
adhesive material into the seams to prevent threads from shrinking
or puckering. TAL's Washington patent lawyer, Bradford Kile, said
the adhesive was applied via a fusible tape about an inch wide. He
explained that the tape was laid between adjoining pieces of
fabric, and ``the thread is sewn through the outermost layer and
the fusible bonding strip and the layer beneath it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After the stitch is made, the seam is placed under heat and
pressure, and the seam is fused together,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kile said the adhesive tape adds only pennies to a shirt's cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all my shirts laundered, and it costs a dollar a
shirt,'' Kile said. ``The starch tends to shrink the collar, and
that can be harsh and irritate the neck. The added cost to
manufacturing is saved after the first time you take the shirt to
the laundry.''
</P>
<P>
   The seam technology is designed to last for the life of the
shirt, Kile said, adding that TAL is ``using the technology
themselves and including it in all the seams that their clients
want.'' TAL makes shirts in Hong Kong, Thailand, Malaysia, Taiwan
and China. It has also licensed its patents to competitors like
Phillips-Van Heusen. Shoppers can already buy shirts with
maintenance-free seams, if they know what to look for.
</P>
<P>
   ``This just came out at the end of 1997, and it's going to have
a negative impact on the laundry industry, but I guess they'll
survive,'' Kile said. ``Brooks Brothers makes it in pink, blue,
yellow and white. But you have to ask for it, and they'll send it
to you in the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong received patents 5,713,292; 5,590,615 and 5,568,779.
</P>
<P>
   New Way to Replace Elevator Doors
</P>
<P>
   The Americans with Disabilities Act stipulates that elevator
doors must open and close automatically. But many elevators in
older apartment buildings have swinging or telescoping doors or
gates that must be operated by hand. In New York City, high-rise
public housing buildings from the 1940s and 1950s still feature
their original swinging elevator doors. Past solutions for
replacing them included taking space from inside the elevator car,
or tearing out walls in the hallway to accommodate new equipment.
Making elevator cars smaller is inconvenient for all users, not
only the disabled, and removing walls during construction is
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Friedman says he has a better solution. Friedman owns
National Elevator Cab and Door Co. in New York City and has
patented a sliding elevator door assembly and installation process
that uses the space occupied by swinging door mechanisms. He came
up with the solution after ripping open a wall to replace a swing
door the traditional way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an image of our company and my picture on the 10 o'clock
news because somebody fell down an elevator shaft,'' Friedman
explained. With his system, the old door assembly is replaced with
a frame for a sliding door. The frame is attached adjacent to the
car door, and a track and hanger system is added to the transom
area above the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door then slides into the frame like a pocket door,''
Friedman explained. The side and transom frames are covered with
the stationary panels. ``We can do it in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   The patented system has already been installed in older
buildings in New York City. Friedman received patent 5,673,770.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
