<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FISHING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FISHING WITH JOHN': FISHERMAN'S STORIES WITH EXISTENTIAL SPIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fishing as performance art? For some of us that makes more sense
than the old fishing-as-a-metaphor-for-life routine. In ``Fishing
With John,'' John Lurie (leader of the eclectic jazz group the
Lounge Lizards) takes a few pals fishing and returns with one of
the quirkiest, most inventive television series you're likely to
run across.
</P>
<P>
   He and Jim Jarmusch drive out to Montauk, N.Y., to fish for
shark. He goes ice fishing in Maine with Willem Dafoe and asks the
existential question ``There's all water in my glove; am I going to
die now?'' He hooks up with Dennis Hopper in Thailand where, as the
hyperdramatic narrator intones, they go ``in search of the elusive
giant squid.''
</P>
<P>
   Each episode _ part cinema verite, part parody _ becomes an odd
little tale echoing the independent-film spirit that made these
fishermen famous.
</P>
<P>
   Lurie, who wrote and directed the six-part series is still best
known for his acting turn in Jarmusch's benchmark 1984 film,
``Stranger Than Paradise.'' The style of ``Fishing With John'' owes
even more to Jarmusch than to Marlin Perkins and ``Wild Kingdom.''
Lurie is not exactly an expert fisherman, and these are meandering,
low-key stories of the lost leading the lost, of men in city shoes
pretending to feel at home with nature.
</P>
<P>
   As they fish, they trade quick shaggy-dog stories that mock the
grandiosity of traditional fishing tales and nature shows. Jarmusch
tells of a woman whose cancer was discovered as a result of
dolphins nudging at her breast; Lurie tells a parable about a cow
and an ant. This series does not go for raucous laughs but for dry
wit, good music and satire of macho sportsmen in action.
</P>
<P>
   Though it makes sense for Jarmusch to be the series' first
guest, the first episode is not the strongest. The narrator (Robb
Webb) is more needlessly intrusive here than in other episodes,
though from the start he assumes the right tone. ``How deep is the
ocean?'' he wonders with deadpan melodrama. ``Nobody really knows
for sure.'' In this episode, the pace is too leisurely even for
fishing, not a high-speed activity to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   But the series comes together next week when the singer Tom
Waits goes ``Fishing With John'' in Jamaica. By then viewers are
more likely to have gotten in synch with the series' rhythm, but
the improvement comes mostly because Waits is so wonderfully
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   He gets queasy in rough waters. (``A game of cards on dry land
makes Tom feel much better,'' says the stentorian narrator.) He
accuses his host of never having caught a fish. Lurie doesn't care,
because he enjoys fishing and, as he observes, ``I can write it off
my taxes now.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the men catch a red snapper in calmer water, Waits ends
by saying: ``I don't know why I ever let you talk me into this.
It's the most absurd thing I've ever done in my life.'' And as they
glide along in a canoe, Waits sings of being on a ``River of Men,''
sounding one of the series' most pronounced parodic themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are real men doing real things,'' the narrator says in
the series' best episode (set for July 6), in which Lurie and Dafoe
try to survive subzero temperatures. The men build a shelter in the
middle of a frozen lake but prove to be dismal ice fishermen. Days
later they face malnutrition and delirium because their supply of
cheese crackers has run out and they haven't caught any fish to
eat. Gradually moving further into fictional territory, the episode
becomes a neat little surreal tale.
</P>
<P>
   There is no big-bang payoff at the end of these episodes; that
is part of what makes ``Fishing With John'' such an appealing
alternative to the high-volume, laugh-track world of network
television. It is also richly photographed by some first-rate
cinematographers (including Michael Spiller, who often works with
Hal Hartley). And, with music by Lurie throughout, the series
sounds better than any fish deserves.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FISHING WITH JOHN'
</P>
<P>
   8:30 p.m. ET Monday on Independent Film Channel
</P>
<P>
   11:30 p.m. ET Friday on Bravo
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
