<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STUPID KIDS': CHURNING WORLD OF HIGH SCHOOL FANTASIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In ``Stupid Kids,'' a peppy little satire of high
school life, the playwright John C. Russell gets the opera of
adolescence to a T.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only sixth period, there's still time to do what's
right!'' says the hyperemotional cheerleader type who's dating the
high school hunk. ``Anything I say now,'' she exclaims in another
moment of wide-eyed melodrama, ``could be a lie in half an hour!''
</P>
<P>
   The stylized teenspeak of ``Stupid Kids,'' which opened on
Saturday night at the WPA Theater, suggests that Russell, who died
of AIDS in 1994, may have hidden a tape recorder under a desk in
study hall somewhere and then scoured the tapes for good
quotations. All four young actors in the piece, as a result, seem
like walking, talking yearbook pictures: Jim (James Carpinello), a
human caldron of testosterone; Judy (Shannon Burkett), his bulimic
steady; Kimberly (Mandy Siegfried), a professional misfit in nose
ring and black eye makeup, and Neechee (Keith Nobbs), the sensitive
author of execrable poetry who goes weak in the knees whenever Jim
walks by.
</P>
<P>
   They constitute the entire cast of ``Stupid Kids,'' and it is
the kids' insular, ceaselessly churning world, a pre-adult world of
Doritos and libidos, that the playwright seeks to lay bare. With
the help of Michael Mayer, the hot-hot stage director who currently
has two plays on Broadway _ ``A View From the Bridge'' and ``Side
Man'' at the Roundabout _ the work finds its purest expression in
the runaway fires of teen-age sexuality: in a clever fantasy scene,
Kimberly and Neechee get the erotic tumbles of their dreams with
the elusive objects of their affections. (At one point, the
athletic Carpinello actually juggles the smaller Nobbs.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the care that has gone into this examination of
mere children with adult bodies and desires, there isn't much of a
story here, a fact Mayer seems well aware of. His breathless
production, on a set designed by David Gallo that gives the play
the appearance of taking place inside a television set, is flashier
than it is absorbing. The teen-agers recite their awful, heartfelt
poems one (or two or three) too many times, and go on endlessly
about their romantic crises, which could, in fact, be of addictive
interest to the ``Dawson's Creek'' set but may strike anyone else
as a long walk on the precious side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid Kids'' is concocted as a tale in which two smart gay
outcasts at a generically dull suburban high school _ here
christened Joe McCarthy High _ become best friends with two of
their more popular, physically beautiful peers, who in real life
would never have been seen at the same cafeteria table with them.
It's a geek fantasy of what high school might have been, had the
rigid social hierarchies not existed. Jim and Judy, the Ken and
Barbie of the story, float through life in a carnal, dimwitted
haze, oblivious to the flesh-craving anguish of Kimberly and
Neechee, who, the playwright assures us, will emerge the more
contented in the end, the end being after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer bounces his eager young actors around the stage like
cursors gone haywire on a computer screen: ``Stupid Kids'' is at
its best when bodies are in motion. The seams start to show only in
the moments of eye-rolling and mugging that the director encourages
to cover some of the script's thinner jokes. Among the actors,
Nobbs fares best; adept at expressing the turmoil of unrequited
love, he's the moony-eyed stand-in for anyone with a mortifying
childhood memory of going ga-ga for the one person guaranteed to
make you miserable.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `STUPID KIDS'
</P>
<P>
   By John C. Russell; directed by Michael Mayer; musical staging
by Ken Roberson; sets by David Gallo; lighting by Kevin Adams;
costumes by Michael Krass; sound by Laura Grace Brown; production
stage manager, Bradley McCormick. Presented by WPA Theater, Kyle
Renick, artistic director; Lori Sherman, managing director.
</P>
<P>
   With: James Carpinello (Jim), Shannon Burkett (Judy), Mandy
Siegfried (Kimberly) and Keith Nobbs (Neechee).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
