<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOY-BOOK-REVIEW-675&AMP;A     06-14 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOY-BOOK-REVIEW-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOY WARS': PARADE OF THE PLASTIC SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try to think of another global consumer-product giant blessed
with a leader as unconventional as Alan Hassenfeld, the chief
executive of Hasbro Inc. That's the company, based in Providence,
R.I., that makes GI Joe, Mr. Potato Head, Monopoly, Scrabble and
the Star Wars line, not to mention Trivial Pursuit, Candy Land and,
yes, Raggedy Ann.
</P>
<P>
   A tennis-addicted free spirit who harbored youthful dreams of
being a writer and world traveler, Hassenfeld unexpectedly took
over the family business from his older brother, Stephen, a
marketing whiz who transformed a hit-or-miss toy company into a
Wall Street high-flier before he died of AIDS in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   One of Hassenfeld's more improbable enthusiasms was to grant a
reporter virtually free rein in his company's corridors. It is a
happy decision that has benefited not only readers but also, in the
end, Hasbro itself.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Toy Wars,'' billed as ``The Epic Struggle
Between G.I. Joe, Barbie, and the Companies That Make Them.'' The
author, G. Wayne Miller, a staff writer at The Providence
Journal-Bulletin, set out to assemble a two-year, behind-the-scenes
portrait of that quintessential boy toy, GI Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Miller found himself hanging about for five years,
and he was fortunate indeed in his timing. The book not only bears
witness to the company's desperate, and ultimately unsuccessful,
efforts to prop up grizzled old GI Joe but also presents other
milestones: Hasbro's purchase of powerhouses like Kenner, the
company's painful downsizing, the auto-da-fe of a $45 million
virtual-reality game and the fruition of deals with Steven
Spielberg and George Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Currently Hasbro is the world's second-largest toymaker behind
its archrival Mattel Inc., of El Segundo, Calif., which offers _ in
addition to the Fisher-Price line, Hot Wheels and Tyco's Sing and
Snore Ernie _ its awesome Barbie brand, the world's most successful
toy.
</P>
<P>
   The book's denouement is a vivid chronicle of the hostile and
unsuccessful 1996 takeover bid by Mattel. Miller details Hasbro's
defensive campaign against John Amerman, Mattel's chief executive,
and Jill Barad, the queen of Barbie marketing who ultimately
ascended to the summit of Mattel.
</P>
<P>
   For all the surface sparkle, and despite the charm of its
venerable worldwide brands, toyland seems in this book to look more
like a salt mine: a fad-driven, hit-or-miss fashion business
propelled by the merciless necessity to fuel earnings with
continual innovation, as toy replaces toy in the rush to cash in
and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps understandably, given Miller's access, the book's
portrait of Hassenfeld is sympathetic, if not adoring, save for the
executive's Hamlet-like dithering as he tinkers with the
organizational architecture of Hasbro. If Hassenfeld is hardly the
take-no-prisoners, drillmaster chief executive favored by
investors, he does display zest and courage and is described in the
book as being by turns ``warm, intelligent, temperamental and
sometimes endearingly goofy.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller seems squarely in the Hasbro camp in his description of
the battle for the toy market, a stance in part abetted by Mattel,
which _ perhaps fearing a Hasbro hagiography by a Rhode
Island-based reporter _ limited Miller's access to its executives.
In general, the book puts forth a chilling portrait of the
competitive corporate culture at Mattel, even as Miller highlights
the brilliance of Ms. Barad and the strong leadership of Amerman.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and critics of the industry have expressed anger at toy
companies for hawking gratuitous junk to innocent children, and
have railed against the hypermarketing of toys on television in
what appear to be show-length commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But the critics may be startled to learn, in ``Toy Wars,'' how
hard it is to turn a dollar selling toys to children. For while the
book's focus is on two successful business competitors, it is also
a Baedeker of failed toy lines, a saga of weary marketers whipsawed
by the fickle demands of juvenile customers demanding ever more
novelty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also affecting is a retelling of Hasbro's Black Tuesday, in
August 1995, when the company downsized 105 employees to save $7.5
million. It's a minor hiccup of a restructuring by the standards of
Albert J. Dunlap of Sunbeam Corp. but one that brought considerable
grief to Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   The great sadness of this book is that there is so much
agitation, angst and loathing inherent in the commerce of play.
Countless toy executives dance across the stage and then depart,
like the toy lines that jam retail shelves before they disappear.
</P>
<P>
   At its finest, ``Toy Wars'' is a primer on the toy business that
seems destined to enlighten the business-school marketing courses
of the future. But the book, skewed toward Hasbro and often
breathless in its prose, offers rather more undigested detail about
the toy business, and Rhode Island, than some general readers may
crave.
</P>
<P>
   The book's dramatic tension rides on the arc of Hasbro's
struggle for market share, rather than the urgency of a single
controlling event, like the battle in ``Barbarians at the Gate.''
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Miller has preserved for posterity many of the
toy wars' most risible moments, among them the spectacle of a sober
Dutch court as it takes measurements of the bust, waist, hips,
shoulders and legs of both Barbie and a Hasbro competitor, Sindy,
in an attempt to assess allegations of copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the preposterous (and failed) notion of hawking an
Elvis doll line with the head of the King fastened on GI Joe's
body. And preserved forever is the day when Hassenfeld appeared at
an internal meeting wearing a T-shirt emblazoned with the slogan
``Barbie Is a Slut!''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TOY WARS'
</P>
<P>
   The Epic Struggle Between G.I. Joe, Barbie, and the Companies
That Make Them
</P>
<P>
   By G. Wayne Miller
</P>
<P>
   Times Books. 348 pages. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8571 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BISHER-COLUMN-COX0615     06-14 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Braves pitcher a throwback to old days, ways
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a ''cabbage leaf day.'' It used to be that when
the weather got this miserably hot, oldtime ballplayers would ice
cabbage leaves and put them in their cap. It was hardly more than a
gesture, for in a few minutes the cabbage was sour kraut. But it
was that hot on a Sunday afternoon at the Turner ballyard, and the
kid pitching for the Atlanta Braves was straight out of the old
cabbage leaf school.
</P>
<P>
   So when they asked Kevin Millwood how he felt after the 7th
inning, he said, ''I feel fine. How do you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   He had just singled, run the bases and been thrown out sliding
home, trying to score on a wild pitch. ''I was a little winded, but
I had a little time to catch my breath . I didn't want to come out.
I was glad they had enough confidence in me to leave me in.''
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard thermometer couldn't have been right. I read 86
degrees with 68 per cent humidity. I've been more comfortable
firing a boiler. Millwood looked a little like he'd been plowing,
but his break for home showed no sign of fatigue. It was a halfback
burst, and if you asked the man in the stands, he would have
overruled Joe West's call. Millwood hit the dirt with bullish
intent.
</P>
<P>
   He beat Montreal and won his 9th game. That tied Greg Maddux and
Tom Glavine. They, two multimillionaire Cy Young winners, had
started the first two games of the series against the Expos and the
worst hitting team in the league had scored 14 runs. Millwood was
such a puzzle they could muster only four hits, and in the meantime
he improved his batting average by 46 points. This was in reply to
the home run Carlos Perez struck off him in the third, briefly
establishing a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Perez _ that name may ring a bell. He's a Perez who could find
the ball park on Sunday. It was his brother, Pascual, then a Brave,
who couldn't, who circled the city so many times trying to find the
right exit he will be known forever as ''Perimeter.'' The numerous
Perezes total up to six, four others to go with Carlos and
''Perimeter.''.
</P>
<P>
   This one is a pretty good pitcher, led the league in shutouts
last season, but for two innings and a couple of ''dying quail''
triples by Ozzie Guillen and Tony Graffanino, they might be
pitching yet. His home run was Montreal's only run.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two is, while Millwood pitches to
stay in Atlanta, Perez pitches to get out of Montreal. The
Dominican pitcher is 27, and given another good season such as
this---he's 6-and-5---he can make an exit paved with gold as have
so many Expos before him. Larry Walker, Andres Gallaraga, Pedro
Martinez, Mike Lansing, John Wetteland, Randy Johnson, to name a
few. Not just players, but general managers and farm directors as
well. Have a good season and take flight, as if to beat the plague.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, on the other hand, is only now beginning to feel like
a big leaguer. Strange as it seems, he never had a winning season
until last year, when he combined for 15-and-8 between Greenville,
Richmond and the home office. He's looking for a place to hang his
hat for a long time, not an exit. The Braves can afford him. The
Expos deal with a short treasury.
</P>
<P>
   It was ''Glove Day,'' but emphasis wasn't on defense. It was on
a tough pitcher, 23 years old, who was trained to finish what he
started.
</P>
<P>
   Furman Bisher is the Atlanta Journal Sports Editor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
