<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    As series continues, ratings rise
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Utah's win in Game 5 Friday night was somewhat
unexpected, there has been nothing surprising about the rising
viewership for the NBA Finals. Without counting Sunday's Game 6,
NBC is confident this rematch between the Jazz and Bulls will
finish atop the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won't have the national rating for Game 5 until Monday,''
said NBC vice president Ed Markey, ''but the with an overnight
rating of 20.6, we figure Game 5 will be in the low 19.0s, which
puts the series on pace to be the highest-rated NBA Finals in
history.''
</P>
<P>
   The previous high of 17.9 came in 1993 when the Bulls played the
Suns. That one featured Michael Jordan against Charles Barkley.
Obviously, the bump in this Finals comes from the possibility that
this may not only be Michael Jordan's last year, but the end of the
Bulls' dynasty in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer boots the soaps
</P>
<P>
   You know ABC has a serious commitment to the World Cup when it's
willing to pre-empt popular afternoon soap operas like ''General
Hospital'' to show the U.S. play Germany today at 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   During the pregame show before the contest between Jamaica and
Croatia, ABC hypemaster Brent Musburger called the Americans'
opener against Germany, ''The biggest match the United States has
had in the last four years.''
</P>
<P>
   A not-so-startling revelation by Musburger, considering that's
how long it has been since the last World Cup in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Blowin' in the wind
</P>
<P>
   The gusting winds of 60 mph offered more resistance to Oscar de
la Hoya than Patrick Charpentier Saturday night at the Sun Bowl in
El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, HBO announcers Jim Lampley, Larry Merchant and
Roy Jones Jr. didn't try to mask the lack of competition offered by
the French challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ''Charpentier is like a heavy bag. He lets Oscar do whatever he
wants to do,'' Jones said bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   HBO publicist Ray Stallone said the telecast was ''a bit
tricky'' because of the high winds. Needless to say, the coverage
included shots of the lights swaying in the wind, which caused the
technicians to drop it down closer to the ring. However, the lower
scaffolding did not have a noticeable impact on the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Other notables
</P>
<P>
   During Friday's Braves-Expos telecast on TBS, the unflappable
Pete Van Wieren said of pinch hitting for ailing partner Skip Caray
on the pregame radio talk show, ''Now I know why he's cranky
sometimes.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   The cameras of ESPN delievered a couple of terrific replays away
from the puck during Game 3 of the Red Wings and Capitals when it
captured Esa Tikkanen flattening Steve Yzerman at center ice and
Sergei Gonchar throwing a right-handed punch that would have been
impressive in the de la Hoya fight.
</P>
<P>
   After Sergei Federov scored the winning goal, underrated analyst
Bill Clement proclaimed, ''Federov has one thing in common with
Michael Jordan. Both do incredible things, and they both make it
look easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
