<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Americans in Paris: Wins would be nice, but respect is real goal
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last decade, they've made the giant leap from being a
Third World soccer nation and into the crowded ranks of World Cup
wannabes. But the Americans in Paris who will make their third
straight appearance on soccer's grandest stage against powerful
Germany today are seeking much more than a win, or a tie, and the
valuable points that can extend their visit to France.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S., with several heady results since playing host to the
1994 World Cup, has come to Europe demanding a certain amount of
respect since declaring itself the best American team ever put
together.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, both Argentina and Brazil have fallen to
the Americans _ the latter as recently as February _ and Mexico
suffered the indignity of a home tie during qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   But they will be judged primarily on their performance in the
World Cup, where Germany and Yugoslavia, two of Europe's best
teams, are favored in Group F.
</P>
<P>
   All week, U.S. coach Steve Sampson has taken potshots at German
coach Berti Vogts for an alleged lack of respect, although Vogts
hasn't said anything to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publicly, they say all the right things,'' Sampson said on
Sunday. ``But I don't think the Germans respect the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Brashness is not a German trademark. Detailed preparation has
yielded three World Cup championships and a spot in the finals
three straight times until a disappointing quarterfinal finish in
1994. Aging, injured and under duress with high expectations at
home, Germany has its own concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have taken steps forward (since 1994),`` German captain
Jurgen Klinsmann said of the Americans. ``We have no reason to
underestimate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike 1994, when wild card teams like the U.S. advanced in a
24-team field, the addition of eight new teams has changed the
format. Only the top two teams in each of the eight groups will
proceed to the Round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   The current U.S. team is sharply revamped from the
defensive-minded squad crafted by Bora Milutinovic in 1994, though
several key players _ especially emerging world-class goalkeeper
Kasey Keller _ will be working more to stop goals than score them.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, Milutinovic's top assistant in 1994, will be the first
American-bred coach to lead a team into the World Cup, although he
was only the third choice as his successor. Since getting the job
three years ago, he has become the winningest coach in U.S.
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're playing a more sophisticated game now,'' Sampson
said. ``It was impossible to play that way in 1994. We expect to
get to the second round. That's our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But his boss, outgoing U.S. Soccer Federation president Alan
Rothenberg, doubts the U.S. can make it out of group play. And
although Sampson's new 3-6-1 formation hasn't given up a goal in
four straight outings, neither has it produced a goal in two of the
last three warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have lost both times they played Germany, by 4-0
and 4-3 scores in the 1993 U.S. Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of insulting,'' said U.S. midfielder Claudio Reyna,
one of seven Americans with professional experience in Germany, in
response to Rothenberg. ``It's going to be tough for us to get out,
we know that. But everybody has to try to be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   No American is more positive than new captain Thomas Dooley,
until six years ago a German in every way. He took up citizenship
in 1993 as the son of a U.S. serviceman and is convinced the
Americans can exploit Germany's typically slow start in the World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be another big step for us,'' said Dooley, who has no
mixed emotions about playing his former countrymen. ``We need to
have some more success at the World Cup. We have more experience,
we have a league that has made an impact and Americans are much
more knowledgeable about and support of soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   The creation of Major League Soccer in 1996 has produced a
number of young American stars. Eddie Pope, Brian Maisonneuve,
Brian McBride and Frankie Hejduk have come into their own, leaving
more familiar names like Alexi Lalas, Marcelo Balboa and Tab Ramos
to likely reserve duty.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson dumped disruptive captain John Harkes in April, and
without him, the U.S. beat Austria 3-0 in Vienna, its first win in
Europe since 1991. He'll have to find an answer for the lack of
goals, especially if forward Eric Wynalda, who leads the U.S. with
32 international scores, isn't fully ready following a knee
ligament strain in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about the goals, because we have been creating
enough good chances,'' Sampson said. ``The goals will come. I
firmly believe we will be a surprise team in this World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
