</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Manager Cox ties wins record as Braves beat Expos 5-1
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Had he given an acceptance speech, Bobby Cox could've
thanked a lineup that looked like it was rolled out of a dice cup.
A tenacious, two-hour complete-game by Kevin Millwood, he of
beet-red face. Or a familiar, French-Canadian foil. But Cox didn't
even realize he'd managed another slice of history Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``See? I don't know,'' he said when told that Atlanta's 5-1 win
over Montreal was his 1,004th victory as the Braves' manager, tying
Cox with Frank Selee as the winningest manager in franchise
history. ``It's great to be in the lead in something. I'll take
that no matter what it is. I don't know that gentleman, though. I'd
just like to win enough games to win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He won his 1,004th not in his 13th season with the Braves. Cox's
record is 1,004-819 (a .551 percentage). As for Selee, ``What year
was that?'' Cox asked.
</P>
<P>
   That was 97 years ago. Selee managed the franchise for 12
seasons in Boston from 1890-1901, going 1,004-649 (.607). ``Well,''
Cox said, grinning, ``that's when they played 210-game schedules.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the Expos existed back then, those Braves likely would've
beaten them, too. Atlanta has taken 14 straight series from
Montreal since the start of the '95 season. This one came courtesy
of another strong outing by Millwood and some fortunate juggling by
Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very, very strong individual,'' Cox said of Millwood,
who threw a four-hitter for his second complete game and ninth win,
matching teammates Greg Maddux and Tom Glavine for the NL lead.
``The ball's got to bounce your way to get wins. But Kevin's
pitched good enough to have nine wins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd be 9-2,'' said Millwood, who gave up a
solo homer to Montreal starter Carlos Perez plus three singles,
struck out seven and lowered his ERA to 3.73. ``But I know I'm good
enough to be where I'm at right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he also knows his place in this rotation. ``You see the
other four guys we have here,'' said Millwood. ``Even Dennis
(Martinez) has 243 wins. The other guys have Cy Youngs. I haven't
done half the things they have. But that doesn't mean I can't
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Or finish, even on a brutally hot day. Even after exerting
himself while singling in the seventh, taking third on Gerald
Williams' double, then trying to score when a pitch in the dirt
bounced away from Expos catcher Chris Widger. Millwood was thrown
out at the plate and was admittedly tired after the eighth. But Cox
let him come out for the ninth and he got the side in order.
</P>
<P>
   By then, help came from a lineup that included Williams leading
off and going 2-for-4 with an RBI, one run and two steals; Tony
Graffanino batting second and tripling in a run; Danny Bautista
starting in left and making a superb catch; and Ozzie Guillen
starting again at short, going 2-for-3 with a run and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who haven't played that much always do good when they
get in,'' Cox said after a piece of managing even Frank Selee
would've enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
