 0615 &HT;    American League week in review
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   + Records: Yankees 3-1 (46-14), Red Sox 3-1 (38-26), Orioles 3-2
(32-35), Blue Jays 2-3 (33-34), Devil Rays 1-3 (27-38).
</P>
<P>
   + Interleague records: Yankees 5-1, Orioles 3-3, Red Sox, 3-3,
Devil Rays 2-4, Blue Jays 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   + The big story: The Yankees have won 23 straight series without
losing one.
</P>
<P>
   + The hot bats: The Yankees have four of the top 10 hitters in
the league - Bernie Williams (.353), Derek Jeter (.329), Paul
O'Neill (.329) and Scott Brosius (.327).
</P>
<P>
   + The big arms: Cuban defector Orlando Hernandez has won the No.
5 spot in the Yankees rotation.
</P>
<P>
   + The unexpected: Toronto's Roger Clemens was 0-3 against NL
teams last year and it appeared he would lose again Monday before
his teammates scored three in the eighth inning to take him off the
hook.
</P>
<P>
   + The injuries: The Yankees put center fielder Bernie Williams
on the disabled list with a knee sprain.
</P>
<P>
   + The scoop: The Devil Rays are 4-0 in extra inning games, their
relievers allowing just one runs in 14 innings.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   + Records: Twins 3-2 (30-35), White Sox 3-2 (27-38), Royals 2-3
(24-41), Indians 1-2 (38-26), Tigers 1-4 (24-39).
</P>
<P>
   + Interleague records: Indians 3-3, Twins 3-3, White Sox 2-4,
Tigers 2-4, Royals 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   + The big story: Royals shortstop Felix Martinez, who has been
involved in brawls and broke Otis Nixon's jaw by kicking him in the
face, has undergone some psychological evaluations. He is currently
in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   + The hot bats: Quietly, White Sox outfielder Albert Belle is
putting up some big numbers, hitting .283 with 16 homers and 55
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   + The big arms: The team may continues to struggle, but Tigers
starter Justin Thompson has thrown back-to-back complete games.
</P>
<P>
   + The unexpected: The three worst pitching staffs are in the
division - Kansas City (5.38 ERA), Detroit (5.51) and Chicago
(5.71).
</P>
<P>
   + The injuries: Royals righthander Kevin Appier, who has been
out since the spring after shoulder surgery, has started a rehab
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   + The scoop: The White Sox may be ready to deal third baseman
Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   + Records: Angels 4-1 (38-27), A's 3-3 (29-37), Rangers 2-3
(39-27), Mariners 2-4 (27-44).
</P>
<P>
   + Interleague records: Angels 5-1, Rangers 4-2, A's 3-3,
Mariners 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   + The big story: The Angels have won 13 of their last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   + The hot bats: In last week's three-game series against
Arizona, Anaheim's Darin Erstad went 10-for-14 with four RBIs and
five runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   + The big arms: Rangers closer John Wetteland had four saves in
interleague games.
</P>
<P>
   + The unexpected: Over his last three starts, Seattle's Randy
Johnson is 0-3 with a 7.40 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   + The injuries: Jay Buhner, who missed 59 games with a knee
injury, is back and drove in all three of Seattle's runs Saturday
in a 7-3 loss to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   + The scoop: Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who has the top
average in the majors at .372, will be out for three to five days
with a sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
