<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    National League week in review
 &HT;    by I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   + Records: Mets 4-2 (37-26), Marlins 3-3 (20-47), Braves 2-3
(46-22), Phillies 2-3 (30-34), Expos 2-3 (26-40).
</P>
<P>
   + Interleague records: Mets 4-2, Braves 3-3, Expos 3-3, Phillies
3-3, Marlins 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   + The big story: The Mets inched closer to the Braves, getting
great starting pitching and there is no reason it will not continue
with games coming up against struggling Montreal, Florida and
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   + The hot bats: Mets first baseman John Olerud is the only
player in the division that is in the top 10 in the league in
hitting. He has been the best at .359.
</P>
<P>
   + The big arms: In his last nine starts, Rick Reed of the Mets
has a 1.44 ERA while teammate Bobby Smith has won five straight
starts.
</P>
<P>
   + The unexpected: Braves reliever Mark Wohlers has allowed eight
runs in his last 6 2/3 inning and the club's bullpen has blown
seven saves.
</P>
<P>
   + The injuries: Mike Piazza and Bernard Gilkey of the Mets
missed the game Saturday because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   + The scoop: Marlins owner Wayne Huizenga has made an unofficial
deadline of the All-Star Game for finalizing the deal to sell the
club to team president Don Smiley.
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   + Records: Brewers 4-1 (33-31), Astros 3-2 (40-26), Cubs 2-3
(39-27), Pirates 2-3 (33-34), Cardinals 2-3 (31-35), Reds 2-3
(30-38).
</P>
<P>
   + Interleague records: Astros 5-1, Cubs 4-2, Pirates 4-2,
Brewers 3-3, Reds 1-2, Cardinals 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   + The big story: Cardinals first baseman Mark McGwire is halfway
to the home run record of 61. McGwire hit No. 31 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   + The hot bats: Pirates catcher Jason Kendall doesn't get much
respect in the All-Star voting but he is hitting .336, tops among
the league's batterymen.
</P>
<P>
   + The big arms: Over his last six games, Houston's Mike Hampton
is 5-0 with a 1.89 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   + The unexpected: Cubs rookie Kerry Wood was knocked out of his
last start in the fourth inning but he makes his next two starts at
Wrigley Field where he has a 1.00 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   + The injuries: Reds reliever Stan Belinda, saying there is a 10
percent chance he has multiple sclerosis, went on the DL with a
spinal cord inflammation.
</P>
<P>
   + The scoop: The Cardinals are making a run at Reds shortstop
Barry Larkin but first would have to trade Royce Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   WEST
</P>
<P>
   + Records: Padres 5-0 (43-25), Dodgers 3-2 (34-33), Giants 2-3
(41-27), Rockies 2-3 (28-40), Diamondbacks 2-3 (22-46).
</P>
<P>
   + Interleague records: Dodgers 4-2, Giants 2-1, Diamondbacks
2-4, Padres 1-2, Rockies 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   + The big story: The biggest baseball crowd ever in San Diego
(60,789) watched the Padre beat the Giants 10-3 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   + The hot bats: On Saturday, Arizona's Travis Lee homered in
consecutive innings and drove in a franchise-record five runs.
</P>
<P>
   + The big arms: Dodgers starter Ismael Valdez threw his first
complete game last week since Sept. 23, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   + The unexpected: Giants leftfielder Barry Bonds has reached
base in 37 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   + The injuries: San Diego's Tony Gwynn is bothered by a strained
left calf.
</P>
<P>
   + The scoop: The Dodgers turned a triple play Saturday, just
their second one in team history.
</P>
