<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The storm system that produced over 10 inches of rain at a few
spots in New England this past weekend will gradually weaken over
southern Ontario. In its wake, New York and New England will have
limited sunshine as moist air remains in place near the ground.
During the afternoon, scattered showers will develop, especially
over the hilly terrain. Temperatures will remain below seasonal
levels, especially near the Atlantic coast where onshore winds will
persist.
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms with locally strong winds, heavy downpours
and isolated tornadoes will erupt in the warm, humid air from
southern Ohio to the Middle Atlantic Coast Monday afternoon.
Farther north, less intense showers and thunderstorms will develop
north of a warm front over the interior Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Southeast will be hot and humid. There will be
little chance for rain near the coast from South Carolina to the
Gulf of Mexico. A broken band of strong thunderstorms will form
during the afternoon from the southern Appalachians to the lower
Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Locally strong thunderstorms will also develop under a jet
stream disturbance as it moves from eastern Nebraska toward the
Mississippi Valley. Weak high-level winds will result in some
slow-moving downpours that may produce local flooding. Farther
south, much of Texas will stay very hot, but cooler air will
prevail elsewhere in the southern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   A strong cold front will sweep into the Northwestern states with
a few showers and gusty winds from the north. Meanwhile, heat will
increase over the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Extreme Rain
</P>
<P>
   The rainfall records had to be rewritten in parts of eastern New
England on Saturday and early Sunday as torrential rain from a
slow-moving storm lashed the region. Saturday was the wettest June
day in Boston since regular readings began in 1872 as 5.69 inches
fell into the official rain gauge. Nearly 8 inches of rain were
recorded in some suburbs of Boston. Saturday's heavy rain is part
of a long-term nationwide trend. The percentage of the area of the
United States affected each year by extreme daily rainfall has been
increasing throughout this century; however, the reason for the
trend is a mystery. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
