<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMMER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Nike wants consumers to wear products with eased conscious
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just received a very slick packet from Nike.
Everything Nike does is slick. When CEO Phil Knight trims his
toenails, it is done with a high liklihood of slicknesss.
</P>
<P>
   It contained the latest effort by the Godzilla of the sports
apparal business to be seen as a nurturing employer. I felt it
aimed directly at me, since I often have been poked by guilt
whenever spending $80 for a pair of shoes, knowing that only
pennies were getting back to the workbench in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   This company has been irksome for a long time. A person could
readily accept the impression that it runs dingy little overseas
sweatshops and employs pre-schoolers for whatever change they might
find on the floor. Not because of any first-hand knowledge,
certainly. It's just that if Nike can buy Tiger Woods' soul, if it
can advertise during the Atlanta Olympics that the silver medal is
pointless, if it can back-door its way into college sports, then
surely it is capable of anything.
</P>
<P>
   On principle, I pooh-pooh Nike.
</P>
<P>
   Confession time. I still buy it, though.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, who can help purchasing the stuff? Especially the
father of an 11-year-old son who has been so thoroughly brainwashed
by the brand's saturation marketing and stable of superstars? If
the boy had his way, he'd be one big swoosh, with just his eyes
showing.
</P>
<P>
   The typical American kid would eat Brussels sprouts if Nike grew
them. Would gladly do all homework if Nike assigned it. Would
cheerfully floss were it possible to fit a swoosh on the string.
The power is frightening.
</P>
<P>
   You can learn more geography by reading the labels in the junior
department than by scanning a World Atlas. I don't know that Nike
is any more exploitative than the other companies -- it's just that
I'd like to think so.
</P>
<P>
   So, along comes this packet.
</P>
<P>
   It says that Nike is going to up the minimum age of workers in
its shoe factories to 18. For all other clothing manufacturing, 16.
</P>
<P>
   It says that minimum wage workers in the 12 Indonesian shoe
factories could be expecting a raise. Never said how much. Still
have the feeling the numbers would make what they charge for ugly
golf shoes seem all the more far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   It says that workers will be offered free middle and high school
equivalency courses.
</P>
<P>
   It says that the workplace will be upgraded by, for example,
introducing non-toxic shoe glues. The air quality in all factories
will be brought up to OSHA standards.
</P>
<P>
   Nike is just too slick to make itself an easy target. It was not
going to give up on those few humanitarians who might need a pair
of running shorts.
</P>
<P>
   How can we know exactly what to make of Nike's response? Here is
a company built almost completely on image. It began, legand says,
out of the trunk of Knight's 1963 Plymouth Valiant and grew to be
the most omnipresent industry in sports. It is as much an attitude
as it is a product. Where the substance to any of it?
</P>
<P>
   We might be a lot more willing to accept Nike at its word if
only it wasn't so overbearing, if it didn't desire to set the style
for the games as well as for what the people wear to them.
</P>
<P>
   At least there's an effort. The slick packet says so. Someday,
perhaps, I'll be able to buy a stinking pair of basketball shoes
and feel completely good about it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
