<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AMERICANS IN PARIS HEAR THE ROAR OF NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ They did not need the Eiffel Tower to tell them they
were in Paris. The loud noise outside their window was no longer
chickens and geese but rather cheering fans and bustling reporters.
The U.S. soccer players took that as a positive sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we were back in civilization again,'' said Mike Burns,
the U.S. defender.
</P>
<P>
   When they arrived on the high-speed train from Lyons on
Saturday, they knew the significance of the quaint six-story
buildings and the taxis and the cafes: time for the World Cup, time
for them to take their four-year test, time to see if the level of
U.S. soccer has advanced in skill, or stood still, or perhaps even
dropped back, which is quite possible.
</P>
<P>
   They are in the last of the eight groups to play their first
game. Naturally, they were itchy out there in the vineyards, where
you could hear the Beaujolais growing in the adjacent fields.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night it will be noisier. Monday night they play Germany
in the Parc des Princes, the traditional stadium at the edge of the
Bois de Boulogne. Later they play Iran in Lyons and Yugoslavia in
Nantes.
</P>
<P>
   All the trials of the past four years are over now. They have
seen old age and injuries and bad karma take away their friends and
teammates. John Harkes, who had expected to be captain here, is
back home playing for D.C. United, lopped off the team by the
coach, with no warning. It is a cold world, and the players know
how fortunate they are to be here.
</P>
<P>
   These soccer players are different from other U.S. athletes.
They look outside their own borders for the ultimate prize, the
true recognition. The World Cup is the world's most important
sporting event, and these 22 players are grateful to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw the Belgian fans and the Dutch fans with their faces
painted, and it felt like the World Cup had arrived,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Their dreams and their justifications come in foreign languages
and on foreign soil. This is where they want to be, preparing to
stop one of the world's great soccer teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be greeted by hundreds of fans, waving flags, was a great
thrill,'' said Steve Sampson, the coach. ``Then the driver took us
the long way to the hotel, to show us the Arc de Triomphe, the
Eiffel Tower, the Champs-Elysee.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the players went for a walk outside their hotel, right
off the Champs-Elysee. Burns deliberately did not wear his U.S.
blazer, to avoid being identified, but he felt the energy of this
city, more beautiful than ever, with its banks of flowers lining
the grand boulevard, its glittering cafes, its stylish men and
women. The Yanks know they are at the center of the universe right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson has tried to control them with all the psychological and
management tools that U.S. gym-teacher coaches tend to use. He has
goaded his players with statements that Germany does not respect
them, the way any U.S. basketball coach would do before playing
Kentucky or North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The players have been around. They are not innocents anymore.
Most of them have worked _ not played _ over here. Why should
Germany respect them as equals? Right now the United States has to
prove that its golden age is not fading away.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Soccer Federation's best move in recent months was to
move heaven and earth _ to say nothing of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service _ to endow citizenship on a Frenchman, David
Regis.
</P>
<P>
   There could not be a more clear sign that the U.S. pipeline is
down to a trickle. On the other hand, Regis is a terrific player,
by U.S. standards.
</P>
<P>
   So they are in Paris now, waiting for Klinsmann and Bierhoff to
come roaring down at them. Sampson said that he hoped the French
fans would root for the underdog, that is to say, his lads. Then he
was asked if facing the Germans in the first game was the stuff of
nightmares, and he responded by talking about his experience before
a big qualifying game in Mexico last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a lot of visualizing,'' Sampson said. ``Before that game
in Mexico, I imagined us holding the ball, moving it back and
forth, and the Mexican fans were chanting, `Ole! Ole!' It's the
same thing here. It's so important that we hold the ball against
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Sampson was asked, what does he imagine the French
fans chanting tonight in the Parc des Princes? ``I don't know the
language,'' said Sampson, who is quite good in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   They all see the crowds in the streets, the painted faces, the
hopes and dreams of nations. They have left the countryside. The
four years are over.
</P>
<P>
   They are in the big city now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
