<SLUG> BC-BAPTIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Georgia leader says submission call comes from Scripture
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Controversy provoked by the Southern Baptist
Convention's call for women to ``graciously submit'' to their
husbands was unexpected and unfounded, the leader of the Georgia
chapter told his Lawrenceville, Ga. congregation Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But any man who thinks the convention's action ``gave him the
right to be a dictator in the home does not understand the word of
God,'' said the Rev. Frank Cox, president of the Georgia Baptist
Convention and pastor at North Metro First Baptist Church in
Lawrenceville. He attended the Salt Lake City convention where
members last week adopted the statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why they've chose to jump on `graciously submit' for the
women, I have not the foggiest idea,'' Cox said of detractors.
``There's a whole lot more to this amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading from the statement, he said, ``A husband and wife are of
equal worth before God. A husband is to love his wife as Christ
loved the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that although the statement has prompted criticism, it
is based on Scripture and is therefore nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have said is we as Christians have a responsibility to
live according to the word of God,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   The books of Ephesians and Colossians both mention submission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wives, submit yourselves unto your own husbands,'' is the
beginning of both the 22nd verse of Ephesians's fifth chapter and
the 18th verse of Colossians' third chapter, according to the King
James Bible. Both passages go on to mention husbands' obligations
to their wives.
</P>
<P>
   Ephesians 5:25 says, ``Husbands, love your wives, even as Christ
also loved the church, and gave himself for it,'' and Colossians
3:19 says, ``Husbands, love your wives, and be not bitter against
them,'' according to the King James Bible.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist Convention's adoption of the submission
statement has proved controversial, though. Most of the 16,000
women gathered Saturday in North Carolina for a ``Renewing the
Heart'' rally roared their disapproval when a speaker asked if they
agreed with it. The gathering drew women from 44 states.
</P>
<P>
   Kim and Bob Hewitt of Alpharetta, Ga., who attended Cox's church
Sunday, said they approve of the statement. When they married two
years ago Kim Hewitt included the words ``love, honor and obey'' in
her vows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's respect for your husband,'' she said, giving her
definition of submission.
</P>
<P>
   Cox says that during wedding ceremonies he performs, he stresses
the grooms' obligations toward their brides.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's to provide for her, he is to nurture her, he is to care
for her, he is to guide her, he is to nourish her along in her
spiritual walk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
