<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNET-MINOR-MEDIA-ART-     06-14 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNET-MINOR-MEDIA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: in 1995. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minor was intent on becoming a media baron even before he
founded Cnet in 1992. While an undergraduate at the University of
Virginia in the late 1980s, he installed four computers in public
places to let people search for rental apartments. Later, Minor,
along with Jeff Bezos, then both investment banking trainees at
Merrill Lynch in New York, almost persuaded the brokerage firm to
back them in a venture to deliver news electronically to
executives. In a cost-cutting move, Merrill killed the project.
(Bezos would go on to start Amazon.com, the online bookstore.)
</P>
<P>
   Minor was crushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hopeless. He was like a colt in the stable waiting for
the gate to open for a big race,'' recalled Russell Reynolds Jr.,
the well-known head hunter, who interviewed Minor for a position as
his executive assistant a few months after he left Merrill. Looking
for a smart aide to carry his bags and write speeches, Reynolds
offered this deal: If Minor worked for two years, Reynolds would
help him develop a plan for a new business.
</P>
<P>
   The ideas were flowing from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day he came in with a stack of PC magazines, $279 worth,
that was three feet tall,'' Reynolds said. ``Halsey said, `Get it:
People are spending money on this stuff.'''
</P>
<P>
   But after his two indentured years, and despite introductions
from Reynolds, Minor's plan for Cnet was rejected by most of the
leading venture capitalists. Only after a year of living off money
from friends and credit cards did Minor attract $5 million from
Paul Allen, the billionaire co-founder of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Cnet was in business, with an ill-formed plan to start
a cable network about computers and do something online as well.
Minor set up a studio in some unused squash courts in a health club
in the North Shore district of San Francisco, not far from many
advertising agency offices. In April 1995, Cnet began a half-hour
weekly program on the USA Network cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   In June of that same year, the company began Cnet.com, its first
Web site, a sort of electronic computer magazine with product
reviews, news and helpful tips. (Today, Cnet's four weekly
television shows operate at a break-even level and are meant mainly
to promote its Web sites.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a heady time as Minor began to hire a handful of
experienced computer journalists and armies of eager young workers,
all excited by the promise of inventing a new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing sexier than a CEO who has a passion for his
product,'' said Christopher Barr, a top editor of PC World magazine
who quit to join Cnet in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Minor obsessively surfed Cnet's sites and those of its
competitors, looking for flaws and opportunities. As developers
worked, they would talk of the ``H-factor'' _ the likelihood that
Minor would bawl them out for missteps.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think I have an uncanny ability to find anything that
is broken,'' Minor said. ``I would say to the programmers, `If you
can't do it, I'll write it myself.' I'm no expert, but I can make a
credible threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the threats, accompanied by notorious temper tantrums,
have been too credible. And several senior editors, along with a
raft of junior staff members, have left Cnet in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was his decision in 1996 to slow Cnet's momentum by
building Snap that drew the most criticism to Minor inside and
outside the company. People said he was simply too late. But Minor
believed the game was only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in college, I read a lot about Michael Dell,'' he
said. ``I felt it was too bad I wasn't as smart as he was and the
PC game was already over. But at the same time I was going through
that agony, Ted Waite was starting Gateway 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Minor found only limited success in his initial strategy
_ offering Snap as a home page to Internet service providers so
that they could appear to offer their customers as much content as
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The online service Prodigy, for example, ultimately chose a deal
with Excite rather than Snap, even though Prodigy's chief
executive, Russell Pillar, is another friend from Minor's stint at
Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ears still ring,'' Pillar said of the conversation in which
he told Minor he had decided to link Prodigy to Excite rather than
Snap. ``Halsey likes to win at all costs.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, in order to get the deal done with NBC, Minor had to
confront the true cost of success. Initially, he did not want to
give up more than half the ownership in Snap. But NBC would not do
the deal if it could not own at least 60 percent, and Minor
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we said we would rather own 40 percent of No.1
than 50 percent of No. 3,'' Minor said. NBC has the option to buy
the 60 percent stake for $39 million. It has also bought 4.99
percent of Cnet's stock for $26 million. Most important, NBC will
provide extensive on-air promotion of Snap. Minor says the value of
that air time will be far higher than the $100 million over three
years that CBS traded for a stake in the Sportsline Web site.
</P>
<P>
   So what was the stock price prediction that Minor wrote on that
piece of paper? Neither he nor Rogers will say, citing laws against
promoting stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But Minor is happy to explain his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yahoo is worth $5 billion,'' he said. ``With NBC's backing, we
can get as big as Yahoo within five years, so our 40 percent turns
into $2 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   And beyond that point, it is hard to comprehend the magnitude of
Halsey Minor's ambition.
</P>
</TEXT>
