<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BANNERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book pulled from public libraries in Georgia
 &HT;    By Milo Ippolito
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gwinnett County, Ga.'s move to pull ``The Basketball
Diaries'' from its public libraries marks a victory for an
organized, conservative movement out to restrict materials on book
shelves around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the prime supporters of the county library board's vote
last week to consider banning the former best seller suggest the
action was a local decision reflecting community standards. But the
suburban Atlanta county's affiliate of a national library watchdog
group _ one led by conservative Christians with an anti-gay agenda
_ led the crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Basketball Diaries,'' published in 1978, is poet and
rocker Jim Carroll's autobiographical account of going from a young
New York City basketball star to a teen-age heroin addict who
prostituted himself to support his habit. He describes a variety of
sexual episodes that took place when he is 12 to 15 with men in
bathrooms and older women with peculiar tastes.
</P>
<P>
   The book was made into a movie starring Leonardo DiCaprio in
1995. Last year, a West Paducah, K.Y., youth claimed a violent
scene in the movie _ which was not in the book _ influenced him to
shoot and kill three classmates.
</P>
<P>
   The Gwinnett Co. library board voted 2-1 Monday to ask County
Solicitor Gerald Blaney to determine whether the book fits the
state definition of being ``harmful to minors.'' Blaney said he's
never reviewed a book or been asked for a legal opinion on any
topic before.
</P>
<P>
   The case also is unusual because libraries are exempt from a
state law restricting access to materials harmful to minors.
</P>
<P>
   One member was absent from Monday's meeting, giving two
conservative members _ Jennifer Toombs and Ann MacLeod _ a
majority. Debbie Tuschall voted against the measure, and Chairman
Andy Tourchier's hands were tied because he can only vote to break
a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a very small group of vocal people that wants to
run the libraries,'' said Tourchier, who opposes the ban. ``If you
don't like a book, that's why they do the dust covers. Put it back
on the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   Activist Judy Craft helped get about 40 residents to the
Gwinnett meeting to protest the book. Toombs called for the vote to
pull the book if the legal review determines it meets the state
standard.
</P>
<P>
   The pair founded Citizens for Family Friendly Libraries, which
has ties to the national Family Friendly Libraries, founded by
Karen Jo Gounaud of Fairfax, Va., and Phil Burress of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are affiliated in the standpoint that we share the same
philosophies,'' Toombs said. ``We exchange information.''
</P>
<P>
   The stated goals of the national group and its Gwinnett
affiliate are to keep inappropriate materials out of reach of
children and to return control of libraries to the taxpayers they
serve. Burress is an anti-pornography activist who protested the
exhibition of Robert Mapplethorpe's homo-erotic photos at the
Cincinnati Contemporary Arts Center. Gounaud started out by
protesting against a homosexual newspaper displayed in Fairfax
County libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The Gwinnett Co., Ga. group was formed about three years to
remove the children's book ``What is a Boy? What is a Girl?''
because it contained nude pictures. It also succeeded in having a
parental advisory shelf installed at the Gwinnett libraries, which
holds 10 titles.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was in New Mexico for a poetry reading and could not be
reached for comment, according to his booking agent, Bob
Fitzgerald. Carroll typically does not comment on controversies
surrounding his work, Fitzgerald said, and did not following the
Kentucky shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll was in Lawrenceville, Ga. on Jan. 21 for a poetry
reading at the Gwinnett campus of DeKalb College, his agent pointed
out. Carroll also has performed with his rock band in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald was unaware of the book ever being banned.
</P>
<P>
   The American Library Association, which monitors book banning,
also was not aware of the book being pulled elsewhere, said Cynthia
Robinson, associate director of the association's Office for
Intellectual Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``For books to be taken off the shelves of a public library is
extremely uncommon,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gwinnett library system will keep the five copies of the
book and 11 copies of an audio tape version read by the author on
the shelves during the legal review .
</P>
<P>
   PULLOUT BOX INFO
</P>
<P>
   Under Georgia law it is illegal to make books that are ``harmful
to minors'' available to anyone under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Harmful to minors means sexually explicit materials that:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Appeals to the prurient ... interest of minors.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Is ``offensive to ... the adult community as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Is ... lacking in serious literary ... value to minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Public libraries, school and university libraries are exempt
from the law. The exemption protects these institutions against
penalty for inadvertently purchasing a book falling into this
category among their numerous acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
