<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRONG-GUY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confusion over assumed identity is nightmare for Georgia man
 &HT;    By Ann Hardie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCDONOUGH, Ga. _ Meet the two Dave Smiths.
</P>
<P>
   The first, a 42-year-old, has fixed airplanes for Delta Air
Lines for two decades and never been in trouble with the law. He is
the real Dave Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The second, 41, has dealt drugs, driven drunk, and burglarized.
The police also want him for making the first Dave Smith's life
miserable by assuming his identity and committing numerous crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare began last fall when Daniel Charles Smith,
arrested in Chatham County, Ga. for drunk driving, told police that
he was actually the Dave Smith who lives in McDonough. Police
believed him.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months, $5,000, two driver's licenses and a dozen
bureaucracies later, the real Dave Smith still is trying to make
sure his name is cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in any trouble and to put up with this is
ridiculous,'' he says. ``This could go on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith learned of his predicament in February when his license
was suspended. The notice from the Georgia Department of Public
Safety said the suspension was for drunk driving in Savannah, Ga.,
but he hadn't been there in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Smith contacted his local sheriff's department in Henry Co.,
Ga., which sent his Social Security number to the Georgia Bureau of
Investigation's computerized system of criminal records and came up
with an extensive criminal history, including distributing drugs
and burglary. He even learned that he had spent November and
December in the Chatham County Jail for burglary and driving under
the influence.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, police say the crimes are the work of Daniel Charles
Smith, who uses at least three different birthdays, four Social
Security numbers and 10 identities, including Jeffrey James, Slim,
and now Dave Smith, law enforcement officials say.
</P>
<P>
   How Daniel Charles Smith got the information needed to
impersonate Dave Smith is unknown. But this kind of fraud is
becoming so common that police recommend dropping by your local
precinct to see if you have a record _ even if you've never
committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Henry County, Ga. officials needed less than a day to figure out
what was going on. They took Dave Smith's fingerprints, faxed them
to the GBI, and the computer determined he was not the man accused
of all these crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear why Chatham County law enforcement officials
didn't catch on. They had access to a computer system that
identified Daniel Charles Smith, not Dave Smith, as the man who had
been fingerprinted after these arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``That information was available to them,'' said John Bankhead,
a spokesman for the GBI. ``Whether or not they checked is the
question.''
</P>
<P>
   The Henry County Sheriff's Department went out of their way and
took Smith to Savannah to clear up the matter with local law
enforcement. ``When I left there, I felt pretty good about
everything,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling didn't last. In March, Smith was notified that his
license had been suspended again because of the other Smith. He
hired lawyers who didn't help him. He missed work attempting to
straighten things out on his own.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith appealed to Chatham County police for help, they
threatened to come get him, he says. ``I know this man has a
legitimate concern _ that this has really put his life in
turmoil,'' said Capt. Doug Burkhalter of the Chatham County police.
``We are trying to help him.''
</P>
<P>
   The police are looking for the other Smith for criminal trespass
and forging Dave Smith's name, which has been cleared for now.
</P>
<P>
   But Dave Smith knows how easily the police can be fooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is going to be over until they catch this
cat and lock him up,'' Dave Smith said. ``I don't know if this will
ever be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
