<SLUG> BC-SOC-YUGO-IRAN-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA LUCKY TO GET 1-0 WIN OVER UPSTART IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-ETIENNE, France _ A lackluster Yugoslavia, looking more like
a bunch of irritable stars than a coherent team on Sunday, beat
Iran, 1-0, in the opening match of Group F, which also includes the
United States and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Only a series of squandered chances by the Iranians, who played
with verve and growing self-belief as they dominated the first
half, allowed the favored Yugoslav team to clinch the match with a
swerving, 30-yard free kick by sweeper Sinisa Mihajlovic in the
72nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs did not look like the often majestic and
free-scoring side that qualified for the World Cup from a difficult
group. The team's stars, including striker Pedrag Mijatovic of Real
Madrid, who scored 14 goals during the qualifying rounds, often
seemed more intent on pursuing petulant disputes with each other
than winning the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not satisfied with the team,'' said Slobodan Santrac,
Yugoslavia's coach. ``It's not easy putting together players who
play in different national leagues.'' Asked about the apparently
frayed team spirit, he said the squabbles merely reflected ``the
Yugoslav temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Yugoslavia _ which now consists of the truncated
federation of Serbia and Montenegro _ may merely be starting
slowly, as Italy did in the 1994 World Cup. But the match suggested
that the United States, which opens its World Cup campaign against
the powerful German side in Paris on Monday, could have a difficult
time advancing to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, and the three points, give Yugoslavia some
breathing room while Iran will be playing a desperate game next
Sunday against the Americans. Perhaps the only positive thing the
United States can draw from the game is that Yugoslavia scored only
one goal. Goal differential is the tie breaker, if one is needed,
to determine who advances to the second round. So the United States
may have an increased chance for a surprise qualification in a
group where Yugoslavia and Germany are widely favored.
</P>
<P>
   The group features an unusual concentration of political
enmities. The games between the United States and Iran next Sunday,
United States and Yugoslavia on June 25, and Iran and Germany on
the same day will scarcely be friendly picnics. Still, players and
managers alike seem determined to keep the vitriol off the field.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both teams started nervously Sunday in a blustery
Geoffroy-Cuichard Stadium in this old industrial town in
south-central France. In soccer terms, they were coming in from the
cold; Iran returning after a 20-year absence from the World Cup
finals, and Yugoslavia emerging from an eight-year absence marked
by a two-year international ban imposed because of the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Iran strung four players across the back and another four in
midfield, leaving the two strikers, the towering Ali Daei and the
stocky Khodadad Azizi somewhat isolated. Still, the darting Azizi
was often dangerous and will clearly be a man who the United States
needs to watch closely.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Azizi, Savo Milosevic, the big Yugoslav striker
who played last season in England, seemed to have lead in his
shoes. The Yugoslav side looked strangely static, not even coming
to life after defender Goran Djorovic hit the bar with a looping
header in the 15th minute.
</P>
<P>
   As the first half progressed, Iran took charge, looking much
better than its last-ditch qualification for the World Cup
suggested. Put through on the left, midfielder Mehrdad Minavand
Chal had only the goalkeeper to beat, but blasted his shot wide.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yugoslavs looking shell-shocked, Daei shot straight at
the Yugoslav goalkeeper, Ivica Krajl, in the 36th minute. A big
Iranian crowd had started to believe in the unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Halftime brought relief for the Yugoslavs, and three
substitutions early in the second half finally brought the team to
life. Milosevic, who seemed to spend most of the game sulking, and
Captain Dragan Stojkovic, who had also looked in a permanent bad
temper, were both taken off, allowing the young Dejan Stankovic and
Perica Ognjenovic to inject some much-needed energy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it took a free kick for the Yugoslavs to break the
deadlock. Sinisa Mihajlovic's left-footed shot was good but
scarcely devastating, and the Iranian goalkeeper Nima Nakisa moved
the wrong way, perhaps screened by his team's defensive wall.
Perhaps unsighted by a teammate, he pounded the field in
understandable frustration as the ball hit the net.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranians tried to raise their game, but only once did they
worry the Yugoslavs with a sharp header from Daei that was saved by
Kralj.
</P>
<P>
   ``The result was not shameful for us,'' said Jalal Talebi,
Iran's coach. ``I thought we could win after 15 minutes, but it did
not happen, and now we look forward to winning against the United
States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
