<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Williams proves to be clutch player off bench
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About once every five games, the Atlanta Braves let Gerald
Williams start. They have yet to be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he merely turned a game around by himself in the early
stages, driving in a tying run, stealing two bases before scoring
what became the deciding run. Before that, he'd made a play in
right field that prevented an Expos run. It's almost enough to make
a guy wonder what Williams might do with more steady employment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not something I'm happy about,'' Williams said. ''But
it's not making me unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment precisely strikes the tone with which Williams has
gone about his work in his first season in Atlanta. Manager Bobby
Cox says he's never had a reserve player better suited for the
role, saying, ''He's the most ready, prepared player I've ever met
in my life. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   When given his chances, he has produced. Going 2-for-4 Sunday,
Williams' season average reached .278, climbing to .327 when in the
starting lineup. Facing the Expos' Carlos Perez, he pushed his
season average against left-handers to .360. This is his quiet
campaign for more playing time, a candidacy stacked against him
with the left-handed hitting Michael Tucker and Ryan Klesko making
over 80 precent of the starts against righties.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just have to try to beat the odds,'' Williams said. ''Since
I've only been playing in a limited fashion, I expect to play a
little more and obviously, Mr. Cox understands I want to play.
</P>
<P>
   ''So I want to be ready everytime I'm called upon. I don't care
what it is. I don't care if it's an opportunity to bring the bats
to the plate. If he calls on me, I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves down 1-0 in the third inning, Williams tied with
game with a two-out RBI single and then used Perez. He stole second
base on the first pitch and then stole third _ the third Braves to
do so this season _ two pitches later, after Perez neglected to
check him.
</P>
<P>
   Said Williams, ''I think that was part of his miscalculation.''
</P>
<P>
   He subsequently scored for a 2-1 lead and Atlanta would need no
more. That came after he had closed down a Montreal scoring threat
in the first, quickly running down a Brad Fullmer single to right
and getting it to the cut-off man in time to stop Jose Vidro from
attempting to score from second. That's generally what's happened
every five games, when Williams takes the chance he's offered.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that I must,'' he said. ''Let's say, the options are
limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
