<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUPMATCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. vs. Germany
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOALKEEPERS
</P>
<P>
   Kasey Keller, U.S. _ Certainly among the finest keepers in the
World Cup, he usually shines in big matches, as evidenced by
spectacular saves in a 1-0 win for the U.S. over Brazil in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Kopke, Germany _ Steady and sure-handed, doesn't have
the flair or dramatics of Keller, but has a more proven defensive
line working in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENDERS
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Dooley, Eddie Pope and David Regis, U.S. _ The new
three-back alignment has camoflauged past defensive problems and
given Pope and new citizen Regis the burden of some heady
man-marking assignments. Captain Dooley is 37 at sweeper but
invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   Lothar Matthaus, Christian Worns and Jurgen Kohler, Germany _
Germany has a new, but old, face in the 37-year-old Matthaus,
called up after injuries at sweeper, and after a national team
absence dating back to December 1994. Thomas Helmer has been
limited this week because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   MIDFIELDERS
</P>
<P>
   Brian Maisonneuve, Chad Deering, Cobi Jones, Mike Burns, Claudio
Reyna and Ernie Stewart, U.S. _ This is where the Americans hope to
use their speed, flexibility and numbers. Reyna is the creative
maestro, with Stewart acting more like a withdrawn striker and the
swift Jones causing havoc on the flanks. Burns, Maisonneuve and
Deering excel in defensive roles.
</P>
<P>
   Olaf Thon, Jens Jeremies, Jorg Heinrich, Christian Ziege and
Andreas Moller, Germany _ Moller could prove to be a handful for
the U.S. with his clever playmaking and timely passing. He might be
joined on attack by 1994 World Cup veteran Thomas Hassler. Ziege
has been hurt and may be replaced by Michael Tarnat, while Thon and
Jeremies will support the defense.
</P>
<P>
   FORWARDS
</P>
<P>
   Eric Wynalda, Roy Wegerle or Brian McBride, U.S. _ The most
troublesome position because it is the most unsettled. Wynalda has
been slow to heal from a knee injury, veteran Wegerle is a slow,
but better fit with the 3-6-1 formation and the untested McBride is
well-suited to tangle with Germany physically. If the offense needs
help, look for Preki Radosavljevic and his magical left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Bierhoff and Jurgen Klinsmann, Germany _ The perfect
compliment up top, with the powerful Bierhoff and the elusive,
fluid captain Klinsmann. But if Klinsmann, who has been injured,
can't go, Germany can call on Olaf Marschall and Ulf Kirsten, two
of the Bundesliga's top scorers last season. It sounds like a tall
order for the revamped U.S. defense, but it is for most everybody
else.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
