<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Making his Mark: Martin surges to fourth win of year
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Mark Martin never has won a Winston Cup
championship, but he made another bold step in that direction
Sunday, winning for the fourth time and dominating the field over
the final 51 laps in the Miller Lite 400 at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Martin never ran out of the top 10 and took the lead away from
Jeff Gordon on lap 150 and steadily pulled away. He built a
three-second margin with 10 laps remaining and took the checkered
flag 2.3 seconds ahead of Dale Jarrett. Gordon wilted to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first part of the race was a race for second,'' said
Martin, referring to Gordon's quick getaway. ``Then it seemed like
throughout the rest of the race they maybe lost the handle a little
bit, and we got ours a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   It definitely was a two-man contest from the green flag to the
checkered, with Jarrett, Jeff Burton and Jeremy Mayfield rounding
out the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jarrett finished second, he never was able to pressure
Martin, who after taking the lead, never strayed from his line,
which most of the way was the bottom of the track. Once he broke
into the open on lap 150, the challengers faded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark was awful good. I don't know what we could have done to
catch him,'' Jarrett said. ``We were good, just not good enough,
again. Mark's car went to the bottom a little better than I could,
especially on new tires. I just couldn't quite make it stick down
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin feared early that he would be chasing Gordon all day,
rather than being chased. Gordon pulled away easily and led 89 of
the first 100 laps. Then his advantage went away just as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we slowed up as much as they picked up,'' Gordon
said. ``Had Mark started up front where I did, he would have
dominated the whole event. We knew he had the best car, but we got
a little anxious there and thought we might be able to beat 'em and
hold 'em off. I knew once I got behind them it would be all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin knew it also.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few times when I got under Jeff that I couldn't
make it stick,'' Martin said, ``but the last time I did it, I got
pretty pumped up to go on and hang on to that thing tight and step
on the gas enough to make sure I got out in front of him. And we
made it stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
