<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Miller Lite 400 Notebook
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Richard Childress gave his new team alignments
an overall A, but he wasn't as happy with the weekend's results in
the Miller Lite 400 at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like the changes we made have us headed in the right
direction,'' he said of the crew chief swap that sent Larry
McReynolds to the Mike Skinner team and Kevin Hamlin to
Earnhardt's.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both teams communicated well today. But, Dale had to drive a
short track car on a superspeedway because of Saturday's crash. It
really hurt us because we think that was a real good car.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt finished 15th and Skinner was 29th.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like the other car would have been a top 10 car,''
Earnhardt said. ''But, we'll get 'em next time. All the guys did a
good job, worked hard as a team and that's what we're looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ''Finishing 15th is not that great, but it's better than not
racing, or not finishing. Next week will be better. We've got a
good car for Pocono, so we'll have to try to pick it up. We're
headed in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Mysterious debris
</P>
<P>
   Somebody needed a caution Sunday and made sure it happened,
throwing roll bar padding onto the track on lap 119. It wasn't Jeff
Gordon's idea. Just the opposite. It was a momentum breaker and
changed the complexion of the race. From leading by 10 seconds,
Gordon's car suddenly tightened and never was the same. It had the
opposite effect on Mark Martin, who was able to pit and loosen up
his car. Where did the bar come from? An investigation will be
made.
</P>
<P>
   The points race
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield finished fifth and retained his Winston Cup
points lead. He has 2,023 points, 26 ahead of Jeff Gordon, who
moved up a notch, third to second. Mark Martin moved from fourth to
third and Dale Jarrett improves to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Missing it
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace had one of those days he can't afford. He finished
17th Sunday, dropping four places in the Winston Cup points
standings, 68 points behind Mayfield. ''We just missed it all
around today, shocks and springs,'' Wallace said. ''You don't see
that too often. We started loose, loose and adjusted on that. Then
it pushed real bad. We just didn't have anything for them today.
</P>
<P>
   Good day for Burton
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton backed up his pole winning performance with an
eighth place finish, matching his season best. ''We had about a
sixth place car, and finished eighth because we were just too
tight. I hate a couple of those guys got by me, but that's the way
it goes sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
