<HEADLINE>
NO MISMATCH: ARGENTINA DEFEATS JAPAN, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOULOUSE, France _ It was halftime, and though Japan was already
trailing Argentina, 1-0, it was still a seller's market on the road
leading to the municipal stadium here.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 Japanese fans, some of whom had paid scalpers more
than $1,000 a ticket on Saturday, were already inside and cheering
louder than their Argentine rivals. But outside, there were still
hundreds of Japanese hoping to find a way into their nation's
first-ever World Cup match.
</P>
<P>
   Some were sitting on the sidewalk and holding up crumpled signs
in English or French: ``Want ticket,'' ``Cherche place.'' Others
with more energy and hope continued to question any pedestrian they
could find. But in the end, supply would not catch up with demand,
and Japan would not catch up with Argentina, either.
</P>
<P>
   The goal that striker Gabriel Batistuta scored in the 28th
minute Sunday would be the only goal of the afternoon, and it would
leave Argentina with three valuable points in Group H and Japan
with regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have any great sentimental feeling about this
being our first World Cup match,'' said the Japanese coach, Takeshi
Okada. ``We all knew that Argentina was stronger than us, but we
all believed we still had the possibility to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Argentina had more chances to score Sunday and was much less
hesitant to shoot in general, but this was no lopsided match
between a South American powerhouse and an overmatched Asian team.
Japan's national team is solid, and the influence of the many
Brazilians who have played and coached in Japan's domestic league
means that Japanese stars like 21-year-old midfielder Hidetoshi
Nakata also know how to please a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   What Japan lacked Sunday was not the ability to defend, pass,
dribble or cover ground in a hurry (``they run, run, run,'' said
Argentina midfielder Juan Veron). Rather, it was the ability to
finish, and that is what Batistuta still does as well as anyone in
the world, with the possible exception of a Brazilian named
Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving Argentina for the Italian first division in 1991,
Batistuta, 29, has scored more than 100 goals for his club,
Fiorentina. Though Argentina's coach, Daniel Passarella, chose to
leave him off the national team for much of 1997, citing tactical
concerns, the perplexed Batistuta ultimately decided against
striking back and withdrawing his name from contention. After
Passarella brought him back on the team in March, he arrived in
Toulouse as his nation's career leading scorer with 38 goals.
</P>
<P>
   He scored his 39th after a forward pass ricocheted off
midfielder Hiroshi Nanami and bounced free in the penalty area.
Batistuta quickly took control of the ball and, with a ruthlessly
efficient swipe of his right foot, pushed it over the outstretched
legs of the sliding goalkeeper Yoshikatsu Kawaguchi.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a young team,'' Batistuta said, ``and we needed to
break the ice.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Only one of Argentina's starters Sunday was over 30 _ defender
Roberto Sensini _ but it is not an inexperienced side. Batistuta,
Sensini and midfielders Ariel Ortega and Diego Simeone were all
members of the Argentine team that began the last World Cup
auspiciously by winning its first two matches. But after Diego
Maradona was expelled from the competition after testing positive
for ephedrine, the destabilized Argentines failed to win another
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult for all of us to recover after the shock
of Maradona's suspension,'' Batistuta said recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Maradona era is finally over in Argentina. For the first
time since 1978, he is not playing for his nation in the World Cup.
Yet despite all the embarrassment he has caused his country and
sport in recent years, there were still adoring banners hanging
from the stands in Toulouse, declaring in Spanish, ``Diego, thanks
for everything'' and ``Maradona. There will never be another like
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Argentine who now wears No. 10 is Ortega. Like Maradona, he
is small and fast and technically gifted, but despite some flashes
Sunday, the moments when he was most reminiscent of Maradona were
when he was being hacked or pushed to the ground by the
hard-tackling Japanese. But this World Cup is trying to be kinder
to creative players than World Cups past, and the Japanese paid for
their aggression by being called for 35 fouls and receiving three
yellow cards.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese still have much to learn about the world's most
popular game, but they and their enthusiastic fans are clearly
learning fast. The last time Japan played Argentina was in January
1995 in the Confederation Cup. It lost, 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Japan can play better than it did today,'' Passarella
said. ``But I know that Argentina can play better, too. The first
match is often one of the hardest, and we got what we wanted: three
points.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
