<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8621 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-TRIBUNAL-1     06-14 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-TRIBUNAL-1,300(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. CONFERENCE TO CONSIDER ESTABLISHING COURT FOR CRIMES AGAINST
HUMANITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In one of the most ambitious efforts ever undertaken to
extend the rule of international law, the United Nations will open
a conference here Monday to thrash out rules for an international
court to prosecute crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations envisions a kind of global Nuremberg _ a
permanent court where individuals accused of atrocities and
genocide can be tried and punished. But even before legal experts
and delegates from 156 countries begin debating the fine points at
the monthlong conference, the most basic issues of jurisdiction and
accountability remain deeply contested.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, the United States and other nations hope to rein in
the court's prosecutorial scope. While supporting the notion of an
international criminal court where a leader like the late Pol Pot
or Saddam Hussein could be held accountable for their actions,
Washington wants to limit the prosecutors' independence.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, and most particularly, the Pentagon,
fears that unless the court is in some way answerable to the
world's leading democracies, American soldiers around the globe
could be hauled before international judges on politically
motivated charges.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the permanent members of the U.N. Security Council _ the
United States, China, France and Russia _ want the council to
decide which cases should be prosecuted. Only Britain, the fifth
member, does not.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, at least 42 nations in what has been called
the ``like-minded group'' are battling for a completely independent
court, arguing that unless the court and its prosecutors are free
from interference from the Security Council, its authority would be
toothless.
</P>
<P>
   The view for a strong court is supported by many in the U.N.
leadership as well as 260 non-governmental groups and human rights
associations, which are already in town lobbying intensely to keep
the United States and other countries with reservations from
prevailing.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government, which is spending $3 million to sponsor
the event, and the city of Rome, which is its official host, are
keeping up the pressure with giant welcome signs all over the city
that say ``We expect concrete results.''
</P>
<P>
   It has taken 50 years for the United Nations to get this far
toward a criminal court. (The existing World Court, a U.N.
institution in The Hague, Netherlands, formally known as the
International Court of Justice, rules on disputes between
countries.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, the General Assembly created a commission to examine
the establishment of an international court modeled on those at
Nuremberg and in Japan after World War II. The cold war made
consensus impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But after Communism collapsed across Eastern Europe and the
Soviet Union, the proposal resurfaced in earnest as brutal ethnic
and religious conflicts exploded around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the Security
Council set up in 1993 an ad hoc tribunal in the Hague that is
trying people accused of war crimes in the Balkans. In 1994, a
similar ad hoc international tribunal was set up in Tanzania to try
people charged with taking part in the genocide in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   But a permanent court of independent judges with broad powers to
indict and prosecute _ without the Security Council's blessing _
has raised doubts in the State Department and the Pentagon. And
there is already fierce opposition in some corners of Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who heads the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, has vowed that any plan for an international criminal
court will be ``dead on arrival'' in the Senate unless Washington
had veto power over it.
</P>
<P>
   No country is openly opposed to the notion of an international
court. For one thing, it is difficult to argue against the basic
principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have seen this century is the disastrous effects of
impunity,'' said Hans Corell, The United Nations' special
representative to the conference. ``We need to have a court that
can act as a deterrent to future genocides and that can also punish
those responsible for committing them.'' On Sunday, Pope John Paul
II gave his blessing to the project.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the American resistance lies in an age-old reluctance to
surrender sovereignty. An American official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, expressed dismay over the idealism expressed by some
proponents of the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think that if they create a court which is totally
independent, everything will work out,'' the official said.
``That's unrealistic: these things work when governments such as
the United States use their clout to make it work.'' He added, ``If
there is going to be no role at all for the Security Council, then
we have a serious problem in Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   That view has prompted charges by some nations that the United
States and other powers are pursuing a ``neo-colonial'' policy in
which they alone determine where justice is needed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Americans are telling the world that the only
acceptable safeguard against frivolous suits is the Security
Council, that is simply a non-starter,'' said Emma Bonino, Italy's
European commissioner for humanitarian aid, who has long advocated
an international court to try grave human rights abuses. ``I cannot
believe that a major democracy with so active a peacekeeping role
would want to have an image of insisting that its soldiers be given
license never to be investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   There is room for compromise. Singapore recently introduced a
proposal to allow the Security Council to stop or postone a case,
instead of deciding which ones to prosecute. State Department
officials have suggested privately that the Singapore option could
be acceptable to the United States. But related issues remain
contentious, like whether the court's prosecutors would retain the
right to investigate charges even after the Security Council had
delayed a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the court's independence, including Canada and
Argentina, argue that the proposed treaty already has sufficient
safeguards to protect the United States or its allies from
politically motivated prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing American concerns about risks to its own servicemen
as ``specious,'' Canada's foreign minister, Lloyd Axworthy,
described American policy as ``an exercise in realpolitik.'' He
said that ``there is a real danger that we create a court to
satisfy our consciences, but it will be a court without power,
teeth or reach.''
</P>
<P>
   The mechanisms for setting a trial in motion are deeply
disputed. Some countries, including France, have argued in favor of
``state consent,'' whereby a country whose citizens are charged
with war crimes or other atrocities would have to consent before a
trial could take place. This is viewed by court proponents as
fatally obstructionist _ for example, Saddam Hussein would have to
give his consent before the court could investigate charges that
Iraq committed genocide against the Kurds. The United States has
not yet stated its position, leaving Washington the option of
supporting such a measure if it is dissatisfied with the way the
overall treaty is shaped.
</P>
<P>
   If, as expected, the conference produces a treaty, to take
effect it would have to be ratified by the parliaments of all
member nations, including the U.S. Senate. Nobody expects that to
happen any time soon. But there are risks to both sides if the
Americans choose not to sign the treaty in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Without U.S. support, the international court would lose
considerable authority. But if America refuses to take part, it
runs the risk of one day having its citizens investigated by an
international court that it does not recognize, but that has a
stamp of approval from much of the world.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the conference, which is being held in the headquarters of
the Food and Agriculture Organization, a marble palace built by
Mussolini, the U.S. delegation has to live with the paradox that on
some key issues of the court's jurisdiction its position is closer
to that of Iraq and Pakistan than such close allies as Britain and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   American human rights groups are among the most outspoken
critics of the U.S. position. Richard Dicker, associate counsel for
Human Rights Watch, called it ``lamentable.'' Dicker said, ``The
Clinton administration wants to see a court emerge, as long as it
is a court they can control.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other critical issues to be resolved. Though there is
broad consensus that the court should step in only when national
courts cannot or will not, and then only on major charges like
genocide, there are loopholes in the draft treaty.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it leaves open the possibility for the court to
prosecute the crime of ``aggression,'' which in the U.S. view could
be used by judges to prosecute American soldiers engaged in
military missions. Most legal experts predict the aggression clause
will be dropped, but it is one of hundreds of articles in the draft
that will have to be hashed out before a treaty can be produced by
the close of the conference on July 17.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the most optimistic delegates expect the next month to
go smoothly. ``If we look into the future, cooperation with an
international criminal court should be just as natural as obeying
rules of international civil aviation and the postal service,''
Correll, the U.N. representative, said. ``For humanity's sake we
need to cooperate, but of course, politically, it is not so easy to
come to an understanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
