<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-DONATIONS-C     06-14 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-DONATIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commissioner took money after vowing not to
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson accepted
contributions from senior State Farm officials despite a promise
not to take money from companies he regulates, a Palm Beach Post
review of campaign records shows.
</P>
<P>
   Also evident: Republicans backing challenger Tim Ireland are
taking five times as much ``soft money'' from insurance interests
as the Democrats in what promises to be the most expensive and
bruising Cabinet race of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he would return $100 contributions from two senior
vice presidents of State Farm, the largest insurer doing business
in Florida, after the newspaper asked about them. The contributions
are legal, but Nelson, running for a second term, has voluntarily
pledged not to take any money from insurers he regulates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They slipped through the net,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies and their officers are allowed to give no
more than $100 to a candidate for insurance commissioner. No such
limits apply on contributions to political parties, however.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP has already spent $230,000 on TV ads blaming Nelson for
rate increases up to ``300, even 400 percent'' _ charges which
Nelson dismisses as off base.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party of Florida has accepted $733,250 in
contributions from insurance interests leading to the Nov. 3
election, compared to $145,000 reported by the state Democratic
party.
</P>
<P>
   Some $164,500 of the GOP contributions came from Bankers
Insurance Group of St. Petersburg, Fla., a longtime party
supporter. The company has feuded with Nelson over regulatory
issues and once employed a private detective who admitted placing
an illegal tap on the home phone of a Nelson subordinate. Bankers
officials said they did not sanction the wiretap.
</P>
<P>
   Republican party spokesman Bob Sparks said a variety of
businesses have contributed, not just insurers, and there was no
direct link between those contributions and ads against Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no quid pro quo there,'' Sparks said. ``I don't
necessarily say we were saying in the ads that Nelson was the
industry's man. We were saying he hasn't done a good job in four
years and needs to be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson contends the GOP's acceptance of large company
contributions is significant: ``It says they are in the hip pocket
of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican candidate Tim Ireland hopes to capitalize on public
discontent over rising property insurance rates, particularly in
South Florida. An insurance agent and former state representative,
Ireland lost by less that three percentage points to Nelson in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to be the Cabinet race to watch,''
Ireland said. ``Expect it to be close. Expect it to be expensive.
And I'm expecting to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ireland called his party's ads ``a brilliant move,'' though he
conceded he might have allowed rates to rise as much as Nelson did,
or more, if that is what a free market dictated. He said he would
encourage more insurance companies to enter the market by reducing
paperwork and speeding up regulatory decisions. Eventually, he
said, competition tends to drive down prices and expand choices.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida Voter poll released this month shows Nelson, a former
U.S. congressman and astronaut, leading 43 percent to 28 percent
for Ireland, a loss of four points for Nelson since Republicans ran
ads against him in April in selected Florida markets including West
Palm Beach, Orlando and Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the same lead Nelson had a year ago. Republicans take
heart from their own polls, which show 70 percent agree with the
statement, ``Insurance in Florida is a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican party spent nearly a quarter of a million
dollars, ``independently'' of the Ireland campaign, on TV ads
attacking Nelson for property insurance rate increases since
Hurricane Andrew. Nelson responded with ads of his own in the same
markets. He says the average increase has been 109 percent, and not
all of that came under his watch. He says the GOP-led legislature
wouldn't even hear his bill to lower rates 15 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of soft money has been evident at an unusually early
point for a Cabinet campaign. The $230,000 the state Republican
party spent on the TV ads is more than the $196,000 that Ireland
has raised on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions from insurance companies, executives and agents
make up 26 percent of Ireland's total, more than twice that of
Nelson. Ireland says he proudly accepts money from the industry.
The figures include only companies with insurance in their names
and individuals who list their occupation. Givers of $100 or less
do not have to list their occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson says he accepts contributions only from agents as opposed
to insurance companies and officers. He has raised more money
overall, $1.7 million, but taken a lower percentage, 12.78, of it
from the industry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the State Farm executives who contributed to Nelson,
senior vice president Kurt G. Moser in Bloomington, Ind., said he
was not aware of Nelson's policy when he made the contribution in
September 1997. He said he was not solicited by Nelson's office.
</P>
<P>
   Another senior vice president in Bloomington, James E. Rutrough,
said he could not recall the circumstances of his gift, listed on
the same date. But he said it may have come during a trip he took
to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been an associate or friend of mine who was
working on someone's campaign,'' Rutrough said. He said he has
never met Nelson or anyone who works in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson aide Don Pride said the $100 contributions ``were legal,
but they were not in keeping with his policy.'' They slipped
through because the list used to check the contributions failed to
list vice presidents from out of state corporations. A more
comprehensive list is in use now, Pride said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson does not exclude gifts from others connected to the
industry, such as attorneys, marketing firms and brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Records show Nelson accepted $5,500 in 11, $500-contributions of
$500 each from reinsurance broker E.W. Blanch of Dallas and
associated companies.
</P>
<P>
   Reinsurance is coverage that backs up insurance companies.
Blanch ``led the effort to restore capacity to the distressed
Florida property market'' after Hurricane Andrew, according to the
company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Blanch split a $2,500 commission with another firm in 1996 for
acting as a reinsurance middleman for the state's Joint
Underwriting Association, said JUA executive director James Newman.
The firm also won business from ``three to five'' private companies
that agreed to take customers out of JUA, Newman estimated, but
said he could not immediately produce records showing how much
money Blanch made. Blanch officials did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance agents are not clearly endorsing one candidate or
another, said Hal Marsolais, executive vice president of the
Professional Insurance Agents Association of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``A majority of people think Nelson has a good chance of winning
and want to bet on a winning horse,'' Marsolais said. ``On the
other hand, Ireland only lost by a very narrow margin last time and
a lot of people think he can overcome that margin because his name
recognition is better this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for the Palm Beach Post Capital Bureau in
Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
