<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8644 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHEAT-SANCTIONS-501&AMP;A     06-14 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-SANCTIONS-501&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MAY LIFT BAN ON WHEAT SALE TO INDIA AND PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Md., Alaska, La., Wis.)  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under pressure from farmers, the government is
poised to re-allow the sale of wheat to India and Pakistan despite
economic sanctions by the United States against those countries for
their recent nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing wheat sales would seem to undermine Washington's moral
outrage against India and Pakistan, but a movement to skirt the
sanctions on wheat has caught on in Congress, and President Clinton
encouraged the movement on Friday as he sought greater flexibility
in exercising sanctions around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have long believed that food should not be used as a weapon
to influence other nations,'' Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Although many in Congress have denounced the nuclear explosions,
they are also sensitive to their important farm constituents as the
November elections approach. The congressional action in each house
was introduced last week by lawmakers from wheat-rich Washington
state _ Sen. Patty Murray, a Democrat, and Rep. George Nethercutt
Jr., a Republican, both of whom are up for re-election. The state
sends 37 percent of its wheat to Pakistan, which pays Washington
farmers about $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Murray and Nethercutt introduced bills to pass a waiver that
would allow wheat _ actually, wheat credits guaranteed by the
government and extended to farmers _ to bypass the sanctions, which
are automatically imposed on a country if it tests a nuclear
device.
</P>
<P>
   The Arms Export Control Act in 1994 cuts off trade credits,
private bank loans, loans from international institutions, and loan
guarantees to American companies doing business in the country in
question.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, politicians and foreign-policy analysts are
questioning the value of unilateral sanctions because they can
conflict with other national interests.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions imposed last month on India and Pakistan, for
example, came at a time when 11 percent of the world wheat market
was already off-limits to American farmers because of sanctions.
(There are 57 sanctions in place against more than 30 countries.)
Wheat prices have plunged to a seven-year low because of excess
supply, in part because of improved per-acre yield techniques but
also because of reduced exports. This tension has injected a new
urgency into the eternal questions of what purpose sanctions serve
and whom they hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of interests in any one country, not just the
one issue on which sanctions are based,'' said Sidney Weintraub, a
political economist with the Center for Strategic and International
Studies at Johns Hopkins University. ``The administration is trying
to take in the full range of interests, and not giving up markets
is one of the interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The halt in American wheat credits has prompted Pakistan to buy
wheat from Australia, said Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash. Every day
that the sanctions are in place, he said on Thursday at a meeting
of the Senate Appropriations Committee, ``we'll lose sales, and
they are sales we can't recover.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Appropriations
Committee, quickly decreed without a vote that the committee would
seek a waiver from the full Senate, provided it did not cost
anything.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee had a more heated debate.
That committee voted 7-5 on Wednesday to seek the waiver over the
objections of its senior members, including Reps. Robert
Livingston, R-La., chairman of the committee, and David Obey of
Wisconsin, the top Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Many said that the United States should stand firm on its
principle of exacting a price for what it considers a moral
outrage, regardless of the cost. Others, including many in the
administration, support a more pragmatic approach. This view holds
that the United States can influence a country more through
engagement, even on a limited scale, than by isolation.
</P>
<P>
   But complicating this picture are two other factors. Although
the law mandating sanctions was passed in 1994, the regulations to
implement them were never written. The Justice Department made an
internal ruling last week, in response to a request from the
National Security Council, that the wheat credits are covered by
the sanctions and would take an act of Congress to override. Thus,
the president cannot simply declare the wheat credits allowable.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, between the House committee vote Wednesday and the
Senate committee vote Thursday, the Congressional Budget Office
estimated that lifting the sanctions against agricultural products
would cost between $30 million and $50 million in government
subsidies for credits to the farmers. Many senators, though,
questioned whether the move would cost anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
