<SLUG> BC-IOWA-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
IOWA MEETING SHOWS BUSH MUST WORK HARD TO EARN GOP NOMINATION
<TEXT>
<P>
   By BENNET ROTH &QL; 
c. 1998 &QL; 
Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ If he runs for president, George W. Bush
may have to do some explaining to Lavon Zerley, a Republican
activist who showed up at her state party meeting this past
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for her assessment of the Texas governor, Zerley, a
73-year old farm owner from Jasper County responded, ``He was not
my favorite president,'' confusing the younger Bush with his
father, who served as president from 1988 until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   While recent national surveys show Bush to be among the
strongest potential Republican presidential candidates, it is clear
from conversations with GOP activists here in a state which pays
more attention than most to presidential politics that he still has
his work cut out for him in defining an identity separate from his
father.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the participants who showed up at the convention
that featured a number of presidential hopefuls knew more about
Bush than did Zerley, they were largely unaware of his positions on
hot button issues such as abortion and taxes. Most had never heard
him speak and several confused the Texas governor with his brother
Jeb, who is running for governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush did not attend the Iowa event, which was held the same
weekend as the Texas GOP convention in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know much about him,'' said Arden Augspurger
of Des Moines, who attended the convention his wife, Donna.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he governor of Texas or governor of Florida?'' asked Donna
Augspurger.
</P>
<P>
   The Augspurgers said they are currently backing former Tennessee
Gov. Lamar Alexander who made an unsuccessful bid for president in
1996. Although he has not announced another bid, Alexander has been
paying careful attention to the state that holds the first primary
caucus in the nation. At the event here Alexander not only feted
activists with a lavish barbecue buffet but also provided coffee
for them the next morning in his trademark plaid mugs.
</P>
<P>
   As with most of those who addressed the crowd of several
thousand, Alexander dished out a heaping dose of criticism of
President Clinton while stressing character and moral issues.
Alexander said Clinton had ``apologized for everything but turning
the downstairs of the White House into the upstairs of a fraternity
house.''
</P>
<P>
   The activists also heard from former presidential candidate and
magazine mogul Steve Forbes, who captured voter attention in 1996
with his call for a flat tax but now has put economic issues on the
back burner to stress social issues such as opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' newfound interest in social conservatives was attacked
as ``phony'' by Alan Keyes, who roused the crowd here by condemning
politicians of both parties as ``squish who don't stand for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Other prospective candidates who hadn't run before also showed
up including Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri, Sen. Bob Smith of New
Hampshire and Georgia Congressman Bob Barr, who has made a name for
himself calling for Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Christian conservative activist Gary Bauer, the head of the
Family Research Council, impressed the participants by inviting
Green Bay Packer defensive end Reggie White to appear at his
reception. White recently caused a stir by making insensitive
comments about ethnic groups and gays in an address before the
Wisconsin Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said what I meant and I meant what I said,'' said White.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer later told the crowd, ``I stood with Reggie White. No to
same-sex marriages. No to saying that way of life is acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some of the more prominent figures in the GOP did not
show up for the forum, including House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
Elizabeth Dole, and former vice presidential candidate Jack Kemp.
Former Vice President Dan Quayle also was absent, although his
wife, Marilyn, addressed the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   State GOP chairman Steve Grubbs said that the others including
Bush were invited to what was billed as the first national showcase
for presidential contenders. He said that Bush has indicated that
he would not consider visiting the state until after the Texas
gubernatorial election in November.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman said at this early point Bush was not hurting his
chances here but added that eventually he would have to spend some
time acquainting voters with his views.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not a known quantity in this state. He will have to come
to Iowa and give a good introduction,'' said Grubbs
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush has not visited the state, the amount of political
activity among GOP candidates in Iowa has been unusually intense so
early, according to Hugh Winebrenner, a Drake University professor.
According to Winebrenner's calculations prospective Republican
candidates have visited the state 112 days in 1997, and so far in
1998, almost double during a comparable period in the 1993-94
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Winebrenner attributed this early attention to the fact that for
the first time since the 1940s there is no ``heir apparent'' for
the Republican Party presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wide-open race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, where Vice President Al Gore is assumed
to be the front-runner, there have been far fewer visits.
Winebrenner has charted 27 days of visits by Democrats during this
period, with the most coming from Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota
and House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Winebrenner said that the Texas governor's famous name has been
an advantage for him but he added, ``I don't there is a good
well-defined image of Bush in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They think of him as a successful big state governor, the son
of a president who appears to be a bit more moderate than most in
the field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the more socially conservative activists, being
linked to President Bush is not an advantage. President Bush, who
was bested by evangelical leader Pat Robertson in the 1988 state
caucuses, was generally suspected of being too liberal and elitist
by the party's more conservative wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush was seen as a country club candidate. People would
assume that he (George W. Bush) would follow in his fathers
footsteps. That will not go over well with conservatives,'' said
Mike Jager, a businessman from LaPorte City.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas governor also has his fans here, particularly
younger activists looking for a fresh face to lead the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the boss,'' said Jason Gross, a 27-year old political
consultant from Indianola. ``A lot of people in Iowa perceive him
as congenial as his father but a bit stronger conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Larsen, a 29-year old schoolteacher, also said that it
may be to his benefit that Bush has not been spending time here so
early in the election cycle, arguing that he isn't subjecting
himself to criticism that comes with active campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   ``No news is good news,'' she said. ``Look at Dan Quayle. He
would be a great leader. But his image is already trashed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
