<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-COURT-BOS &LR;      06-14 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC TALKS TO BEGIN ON PERMANENT INTERNATIONAL COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE _ This is the first war crimes tribunal since
Nuremberg, where judges now preside over cases of the most heinous
crimes of the war in the former Yugoslavia: genocide, crimes
against humanity, torture, and rape.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a temporary tribunal, with a limited focus. On Monday,
delegates from more than 100 UN member countries hope to change
that, as they begin historic negotiations in Rome aimed at creating
a permanent international criminal court.
</P>
<P>
   A permanent court, intended to levy justice against the world's
despots and mass murders has been under discussion for nearly four
years. Now, delegates have a July 17th deadline by which they hope
to have hammered out a treaty creating a court that could be based
in the Hague by the beginning of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court would say no head of state, no defense minister, no
president, no general is above the law,'' said Christopher Hall,
head of the Amnesty International delegation at the Rome talks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet success at the Rome talks is far from guaranteed. While
countries agree on the need for a court, they remain deeply split
over its aims, particularly over how independent the court and its
prosecutors can be.
</P>
<P>
   So contentious is the issue that it has pitted allies against
each other and threatens to scuttle negotiations altogether. On one
side are Canada, Germany, Argentina, and about 50 other nations who
argue that a permanent court cannot be effective unless it is
independent. But the United States, China, Russia, and France will
accept a court only if it answers to the UN Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   And even if a treaty can be achieved this summer, ratification
in each country is far from assured. The US Congress is already
geared for battle: Senator Jesse Helms of North Carolina, who heads
the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, has said he is
``unalterably opposed'' to a permanent court.
</P>
<P>
   Still, proponents are cautiously optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world community has embarked on a great effort,'' said
William R. Pace, chairman of the Coalition for an International
Criminal Court, composed of nearly 800 human rights and other
groups that support the court. ``The chances of partial success are
great, the chances of complete failure, very small.''
</P>
<P>
   Added a US official at the Rome talks: ``We may be able to
arrive at a statute for a permanent court, but it will require
enormous efforts on the part of many governments to reach common
ground. ... We must approach these negotiations as pragmatically as
possible, and not as exercises in theory.''
</P>
<P>
   First proposed in 1948, the idea of a permament criminal court
fell hostage to the Cold War. But in 1989, Trinidad and Tobago
reintroduced the idea to the UN General Assembly. Since 1995, UN
member countries have been meeting to sketch out the court's
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will send out a warning that impunity can no longer be
accepted,'' UN Secretary General Kofi Annan said this month. He
will open the conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Creation of the ad hoc International Criminal Tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia in the Hague and its sister court, the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda, added a sense of
urgency. The growing pains faced by both ad hoc tribunals are one
reason delegates are anxious to get the permanent court just right.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Hague and Rwanda war crimes tribunals got off to a slow
start, hampered by a lack of funds and political will. The Rwanda
court has been mired by administrative mismanagement and
infighting. And the Hague court, until recently, had hardly any
defendants, as NATO troops in Bosnia were reluctant to arrest
indicted war criminals when Croatia, Serbia, and Bosnia refused to
turn them in.
</P>
<P>
   Most who advocate a permanent criminal court say that is because
the tribunals were temporary ones. Indeed, sentiments run high in
the corridors of justice in the Hague that unless delegates in Rome
can fashion a strong, effective, permanent court it is better not
to have one at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a toothless tiger,'' said a Hague prosecutor,
Graham Blewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Facing delegates in Rome Monday is a 175-page draft treaty, with
hundreds of items still in dispute. Divisions center on a few key
issues, most relating to how independent the court can be.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 50 ``like-minded countries'' envisions a court
in which prosecutors could initiate their own investigations,
without the consent of the country concerned or the UN Security
Council. A minority, including the United States, wants the
Security Council to give its consent before the permanent court can
act.
</P>
<P>
   That means that only the council could initiate cases, and that
it would maintain veto rights over what cases go to the permament
court. The United States also favors a country's right to refuse to
cooperate with the court, and wants limitations placed on the role
of the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   To do otherwise, the United States has argued, is to undermine
the role of the UN Security Council. And a new court with unlimited
powers could be a dangerous political tool. Washington fears US
troops, increasingly asked to serve in complex missions overseas,
could become the subject of politically motivated prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unreasonable for us to say, structure a court so the
reality of what the military is doing in the future is recognized,
so our military is not exposed to unwarranted prosecutions,'' said
a US official at the Rome talks.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the US view implies two levels of justice, one
for large states with troops around the world and another for
smaller states. The permanent court would never hear the My Lai
massacre, for example. And giving the Security Council the right to
launch investigations could politicize and weaken the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US position is a non-flyer, no one will buy it,'' said
Emma Bonino, the official delegate for the European Commission.
``This solution will make the court a useless tool.''
</P>
<P>
   The EC, Britain, and others favor a proposal put forward by
Singapore, which allows the court to investigate any issue unless
the UN Security Council says no. That means council approval would
be needed to halt cases, but not begin them.
</P>
<P>
   Also under dispute at the Rome negotiations is whether the court
would have jurisidiction over war crimes committed during an
internal, rather than an international, armed conflict. The United
States supports this position, but Pakistan, Turkey, India, and
Iran do not, arguing such conflicts are not the court's affair.
</P>
<P>
   And still unresolved is the court's ultimate power and how to
make states comply with it. Countries remain divided over whether
the court must have a state's permission before arriving to
interview witnesses, for example. The United States supports the
position that prosecutions can be allowed only if a home country
consents.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue the court must be able to be more sovereign than
the country itself: ``Would we need the consent of Pol Pot to make
an inquiry in Cambodia?'' the EC's Bonino said. ``That seems
difficult to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Hague, a defense lawyer, Michail Wladimiroff, said a
permanent court can be effective only if it can compel states to
comply. Wladimiroff, who represented Bosnian Serb camp guard Dusan
Tadic, says the defense and the prosecution had difficulty getting
countries to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you create a permanent court,'' he says, ``you must have
the mechanisms to enforce it. The tribunal was left to the
non-existent good will of the states. No one did anything to force
them to respect the court's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what may evolve in Rome over the next five weeks is
anyone's guess. There is a sense that if a permanent criminal court
is to be created, it's now or never. ``It's anathema at the UN to
talk of carrying it on,'' said Ruth Wedgwood, a professor of law at
Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   But others argue that it's better to continue the talks into the
next century than to create an ineffective court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to get it right,'' said Pace of the Coalition
for an International Criminal Court. ``There is a lot at stake
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
