<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS-BOS &LR;      06-14 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE WORKERS ARE FILLING WARCHEST OF ACTING MASS. GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 AND TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Anthony J. Del Vento doesn't fit most people's image of
a big-time political contributor. Yet, Del Vento, who earns $52,490
a year as a construction coordinator for the Massachusetts Highway
Department, is one of the most enthusiastic donors to Acting
Governor Paul Cellucci's gubernatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, Del Vento has contributed every year to the Cellucci
campaign. Members of Del Vento's family have chipped in as well,
including a son who also works for the Highway Department, most of
the time ``maxing out'' their contributions to the legal limit of
$500 annually and handing Cellucci a total of more than $5,000 in
campaign contributions over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Though Del Vento denies it, some of his colleagues believe that
his political activity helps explain his promotion in 1995, and at
least one has filed a grievance, which is still pending, alleging
that Del Vento was not the most qualified for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, employees say Del Vento simply figured out what
others have long suspected at the Highway Department: Campaign
contributions can help make a job secure and boost chances for a
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Del Vento's case is not an isolated one. Cellucci, who rode into
office with former governor William F. Weld on a platform of
cutting state government and ridding the public payroll of hacks,
is digging into the pockets of state employees like Del Vento to
build his campaign war chest.
</P>
<P>
   State employees account for at least $1 of every $14 contributed
to Cellucci's campaign, according to an analysis of records. As a
group, the $353,649 given by state employees constitute Cellucci's
single largest source of financial support.
</P>
<P>
   The Cellucci campaign, which has raised more than $5.1 million
to wage its run for the corner office on Beacon Hill, says the
contributions demonstrate broad-based approval from which to judge
the acting governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a surprise that people who share the philosophy of
government with Cellucci would want to support his political
candidacy,'' said Cellucci campaign spokesman Andy Antrobus.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers reveal that the acting governor is benefiting
from a patronage system that has placed scores of workers in state
jobs. The records show that some of those state employees, along
with their family members and the private companies with which they
conduct state business, are now among his most generous financial
backers.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more evident than at the Massachusetts Highway
Department, where the business of state government and campaign
fund-raising collide head-on.
</P>
<P>
   In promotional material, the agency is highlighted as a textbook
example of the Weld-Cellucci approach to government. Since 1990,
the number of state employees at the Highway Department has been
slashed by 25 percent, the budget has been reduced by $23 million,
and the agency contends that productivity is up. ``Doing More With
Less'' is the agency's motto.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in spite of the attack on state jobs at the agency,
employees have stepped up to support Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Highway workers have contributed at least $54,129 to Cellucci's
campaign since 1995 _ by far the most of any state agency.
Relatives of department employees have also donated at least $5,500
to the acting governor. Many of the employees have also contributed
to Cellucci's running mate, Jane Swift, who, records show, is
collecting money from state employees at a similar pace.
</P>
<P>
   Employees there insist that they give to Cellucci because they
are politically in tune with him.
</P>
<P>
   Del Vento says his political largesse had nothing to do with his
landing the job with the department in 1992 or the promotion he
received in 1995. He said he gives to Cellucci because, ``I like to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Perullo, a Highway Department employee who contributed
$1,380 to Cellucci over three years, gave this response when
questioned about his contributions: ``I believe in him and think he
is sincere and genuine. I believe in what he stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is also benefiting from the support of private
companies hired by the Highway Department, many of which now
perform work formerly done by state employees. Those companies have
contributed at least $67,720 to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   SPS New England in Salisbury, for instance, performs bridge work
for the Highway Department and recently won a contract to construct
a tourist information center on Route 495 in Chelmsford.
</P>
<P>
   The company has experienced a sharp increase in Highway
Department work, with payments rising from $6.72 million in fiscal
1996 to $10.96 million in fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As a group, employees of SPS contributed $20,425 to Cellucci
since 1995, an amount among the highest donated by private
companies. By comparison, employees of the state's largest auto
insurance company, Commerce Insurance Co., contributed $14,000 and
those from Fidelity Investments donated $12,900.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to contact SPS New England officials were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Close relationships exist between the Highway Department and
several of the politically active companies with state contracts.
Some Highway Department employees have left state employ to work
for the private companies.
</P>
<P>
   One firm, Middlesex Paving Co., was fined by the state Ethics
Commission in 1996 for illegally entertaining eight Highway
Department employees at corporate Christmas parties.
</P>
<P>
   Employees from Chelmsford-based Middlesex have contributed
$3,000 to Cellucci in the past three years. Robert Mabardy,
executive vice president and general manager of the company, said
the Highway Department contracts have ``nothing whatsoever'' to do
with the support. Rather, it is because of Cellucci's ``philosophy
and the way he runs the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Highway Department officials say there is no favoritism in the
awarding of contracts, noting that work is handed out only after
competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   As for the contributions from SPS New England and Middlesex
Corp., Cellucci spokesman Antrobus described the money as
``peanuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Highway Department is not alone in giving to Cellucci. MBTA
employees have contributed $18,313 to his campaign; workers from
the Massachusetts Port Authority have given $9,721, and Registry of
Motor Vehicles employees have donated $6,835.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci has also received at least $71,672 from county and
municipal workers. City of Boston employees have contributed
$21,000 to Cellucci, and Suffolk County workers have donated
$11,650.
</P>
<P>
   Support in Boston can be traced, in part, to Cellucci's campaign
chairman, former city councilor and Suffolk County Register of
Probate, James Michael Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   A lifetime Democrat, Connolly has earned the wrath of some
Republicans for helping give out patronage jobs to members of the
opposition party.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have landed jobs are former Suffolk County court
clerks Daniel F. Pokaski, who was appointed to the state-run Boston
Licensing Board, and Richard J. Rouse, who was appointed Suffolk
County sheriff. Pokaski gave $1,000 to Cellucci and Rouse gave
$700.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and Swift are not alone in tapping state employees to
finance their campaigns. The Globe reported last year that State
Treasurer Joseph D. Malone, Cellucci's opponent in the Republican
primary, has received generous support from employees who work for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign records indicate that Malone has received at least
$100,000 from state employees, primarily those who work for him at
the lottery and in the treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   A government watchdog agency lobbying for publicly funded
campaigns with $100 limits on individual contributions warned of
problems associated with large amounts of contributions from state
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something we do need to be concerned about,'' said
Joshua Friedes, executive director of Common Cause. ``Any time we
see large amounts of money being given by any interest, the public
should at the very least be aware that the candidate accepting
these large sums of money may in some sense be beholden to this
group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Government workers tend to be concerned. It's reality. We're
all concerned about our jobs. We're all concerned that we're viewed
as team players. So I'm not surprised to see these types of
patterns emerging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
