<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8660 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-IMPACT-SPI &LR;      06-14 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-IMPACT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE YEAR LATER, HONG KONG APPEARS TO BE IN DECENT HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Its economic vital signs weakened by Asia's lingering
financial flu, Hong Kong will get its first annual checkup under
Chinese rule at a two-day conference beginning Monday in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 China experts, business leaders and government
officials are expected to examine the economic and political impact
of Hong Kong's historic handover a year ago this month. ``Hong Kong
One Year After Transition'' is sponsored by the New York-based Asia
Society in association with the Hong Kong Trade and Development
Council and the Washington State China Relations Council.
</P>
<P>
   The prognosis is guardedly optimistic for the former British
colony despite a year of unexpected challenges ranging from
speculative assaults on its dollar-pegged exchange rate to
onslaughts of red tide and a deadly chicken virus.
</P>
<P>
   Economically, Hong Kong has been hit hard by Asia's financial
turmoil. It is experiencing its first negative growth rate since
1985 and the highest unemployment in 14 years. But its strong
economic fundamentals are expected to carry it through the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, a small dose of democracy administered
in May 24 legislative elections has helped rejuvenate the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, Hong Kong is holding its own, said Joe
Borich, executive director of the China Relations Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago there were a lot of doom-sayers out there _ in the
media, in Congress and elsewhere _ who said this can't possibly
work,'' said Borich, a former U.S. consul general in Shanghai.
``They thought Hong Kong was going to sink into the sea or
disappear into some sort of socialist morass. That patently has not
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In the year since the handover ended 156 years of British rule,
Beijing has studiously avoided any appearance of meddling in the
affairs of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, as the
territory is now known. Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa
insists his government is making its own decisions under the ``one
country, two systems'' concept enshrined in the Basic Law governing
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Secretary Anson Chan, Hong Kong's most senior civil
servant, had nothing but praise for Beijing during a visit to
Washington, D.C., last week. Chan will be a keynote speaker here
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no cause _ no cause, I repeat _ to in any way question
the exemplary manner in which (China's) leaders have left Hong Kong
alone and honored their promises of giving Hong Kong people a high
degree of autonomy ... And I say that without the slightest
hesitation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Daniel Fung, responsible for the Hong Kong
government's legal policy and human rights issues, agreed with that
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not received a single phone call (from Beijing) telling
me what to do, and if any of us did, it would be all over town in
no time at all,'' Fung said during a recent visit to Seattle. ``And
I'm not hearing from Mr. Tung either.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the conference will focus primarily on Hong Kong, the
handover also has had some profound effects on China itself _
changes that will likely become increasingly evident in coming
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions that Hong Kong's capitalist influence would
penetrate southeastern China's ``soft underbelly of communism''
surfaced even before the 1984 Sino-British accord on the colony's
future. Outlandish as that analogy sounds today, there is no
denying that Hong Kong has had a disproportionate impact on the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   It's now hard to tell, for example, where Hong Kong ends and the
neighboring boom city of Shenzhen begins. Nearby Guangzhou and the
entire Pearl River delta are flourishing, much of the growth
sparked by Hong Kong influence and investment. In Shanghai,
officials constantly compare their city to Hong Kong, some of them
predicting it will eventually surpass its southern counterpart as a
financial and commercial center.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong is the largest external investor in China. Its
companies and joint ventures employing an estimated 5 million
people on the mainland. In addition, some 1,750 Chinese enterprises
operate in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong does not exist in a vacuum,'' Borich said. ``Its
impact on China has been going on for 15 or 20 years. It's
primarily economic in nature, but there are also a lot of other
spinoffs from this economic fusion. You can see it in the rising
expectations and rising living standards throughout southeastern
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years down the road, I think it will be more a case of
China resembling Hong Kong than of Hong Kong resembling China,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Fung says Hong Kong can influence China in
innumerable ways. He likens Hong Kong to a modern-day Marco Polo
bringing to China ``the wonders of the free-market system, the
laissez faire economy, the rule of law, the level playing field,
the joint stock market and its derivatives, the benefits of clean
government as well as the free flow of information via the media,
the Internet and satellite communication ...''
</P>
<P>
   Fung's optimism is not shared by everyone, however. Martin Lee,
chairman of Hong Kong's Democratic Party and one of Tung Chee-hwa's
most vocal critics, insists it is much too early to judge whether
the concept of one country, two systems will be successful.
</P>
<P>
   Citing China's history of periodic, radical shifts to the left,
Lee cautions that Beijing's current hands-off policy may not last.
</P>
<P>
   ``A reliable assessment of one country, two systems is only
possible when China's conditions change, and change they will,
unfortunately,'' Lee said in a phone interview. ``History tells us
that the pendulum in China swings to the left about every 10 years.
The early summer of 1989 _ just after Tiananmen Square _ was the
last time. If it swings again and we in Hong Kong don't get caught
up in it, then we can say one country, two systems is working. But
if we have to swing with it, then it's too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The outspoken Lee, who was not invited to the Seattle
conference, is returning to Hong Kong's legislature after his and
other pro-democracy parties captured nearly three-quarters of the
popular vote in the May 24 elections. They now claim a mandate from
the electorate, saying the results reflect widespread discontent
with Tung's administration.
</P>
<P>
   But although Lee and his allies won 18 of the 20 directly
elected seats, they will still be a minority in the 60-seat
Legislative Council established last year under a three-tiered
system that critics say ensures a pro-Beijing majority. Still, it
marked a triumphant return for the democrats, many of whom were
unceremoniously thrown out of office when Hong Kong's previous
elected legislature was dismissed by the Chinese on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Fung predicted _ and Lee confirmed _ that more
fireworks can be expected in the legislature now that the democrats
are back in force.
</P>
<P>
   The democrats, for example, say they will push for an
acceleration of the election timetable, which does not allow for
universal sufferage in Hong Kong until 2007.
</P>
<P>
   There's even talk of abandoning the Basic Law, a prospect that
would likely bring a strong reaction from Beijing, possibly ending
its hands-off policy toward toward the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
