<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-VOUCHERS-ART-1     06-14 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-VOUCHERS-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOUCHER RULING GREETED WITH EXCITEMENT AND ALARM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ It was the last week of school, and students and
teachers were absorbed in final exams and celebratory field trips.
The biggest local story was the invasion of 100,000 motorcycle
riders for the 95th anniversary of Milwaukee's own Harley-Davidson
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the perfect time for an education bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Wisconsin Supreme Court ruled Wednesday that
taxpayer money could be used to send Milwaukee students to
religious schools, the most significant school voucher ruling in
the nation to date, the decision sent currents of excitement
through some parts of the community, and alarm through others.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents said it would completely transform education in
Milwaukee, letting parents choose where to send their children and
revitalizing parochial schools. One champion, Brother Bob Smith,
the principal of Messmer High School, a Roman Catholic school,
said, ``This is, in my mind, the equivalent of winning the Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents decried what they saw as the breakdown of democratic
principles, the crippling of the public schools, the ascendancy of
religious agendas in education, and what they feared might be an
exodus of good students from the public schools or a streaming of
whites and blacks to what would become essentially segregated
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will a Timothy McVeigh start the next church in Milwaukee and
see this as a profit-making venture and solicit enrollment and
succeed?'' said John Benson, the state superintendent of Public
Instruction, Wisconsin's highest education official, who called for
a moment of silence after the decision to memorialize the loss of
religious liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Much still needs to be determined about how the court's decision
will be implemented, but it may be that in practice the changes
will be more incremental than either the heraldic trumpets or the
apocalyptic pronouncements suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first blush we certainly were very concerned about it,''
said Alan Brown, the superintendent of the Milwaukee Public
Schools. ``Then when you start getting into the numbers, it doesn't
look as bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take years,'' said Dan McKinley, the executive
director of Partners Advancing Values in Education, a group that
has been behind the school choice movement and has been using
private money to send public school children to private and
religious schools. ``A lot of the schools that we work with are
struggling. Many of them don't have good science programs ... Many
of them can't retain good teachers. They have a long way to go
before they're really strong vital schools.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Parental Choice Program, begun in 1990 as the
nation's first voucher program, allows poor families to send their
children to the school of their choice, public or private, at state
expense. Currently about 1,500 students attend 23 nonsectarian
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The crusade to expand Milwaukee's program to include religious
schools, which make up the majority of the city's private schools,
was waged by an unlikely coalition of habitual political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   There was state Rep. Annette Polly Williams, a black Democrat
from Milwaukee's inner city, whose legislation created the program.
Frustrated with a public system with a graduation rate of 45
percent and a controversial busing program, Ms. Williams said she
wanted to give ``low-income families some power'' to choose
schools.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a group of conservatives, including the Bradley
Foundation in Milwaukee, the Institute for Justice in Washington,
and Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel investigating President
Clinton, who led the legal team two years ago, when the state
Supreme Court deadlocked on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed us to legitimize them,'' said Ms. Williams, adding
that she is wary of conservatives' desires to promote religious
schools and to include people who are not poor. ``We needed them
because they control the media, they control the money, they
control everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Their opponents included teachers' organizations, the American
Civil Liberties Union, the NAACP and black leaders who feared the
draining or de facto segregation of the public schools. The
plaintiffs have said they will appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court,
but the expanded program is expected to start this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Under the expansion, up to 15,000 students, or about 14 percent
of the 104,000 students in the public school system, can attend
private schools, nonsectarian or religious. At about $5,000 per
pupil, that could mean that more than $70 million would be siphoned
from the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   This prospect makes people like Donelle Johnson, a fifth-grade
teacher at Elm Creative Arts School, an inner city magnet school,
feel ``like my legs had been cut out from underneath me. You're
going to have to have layoffs and huge, huge classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Others teachers, like Gary Hanneman, chairman of the physical
education department at South Division High School on the south
side, worry that because many private schools do not have programs
for special education students and do not have to take such
students, the public schools will end up with more difficult
pupils.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and others suggested that these effects are likely to
occur slowly, giving public schools time to compete for students.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,400 of the 15,000 potential slots would be filled by
students who are already in private schools, either through the
state's secular program or through the privately financed program
led by McKinley. While 110 schools will participate this fall,
McKinley said Milwaukee's private schools currently have space for
only about 3,600 more students. He predicts that other religious
schools will spring up to eventually accommodate the 15,000 total.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
