<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRING ON THE BARRACUDAS FOR A REEL FEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This cousin of mine reached a life decision along about the age
of 15. He was a box boy in a small-town supermarket. He didn't have
any savings. His parents were not in a position to finance a
college education.
</P>
<P>
   So this was his decision. He was going to be the best box boy
this supermarket had ever employed. And he'd see how far this would
take him. He'd be the first one to work, the last one to leave and
if there was an extra task everybody else was avoiding, he would
volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   He moved up to clerk, assistant store manager, then he had his
own supermarket and pretty soon he was called up into the corporate
offices and played a major role in international expansion. He and
his wife moved into a two-level rambler on a championship golf
course in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Today he's comfortably retired in another part of the country
and golf is his main preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, that is not completely true.
</P>
<P>
   He has another hobby that borders upon obsession. He likes to
shop for groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was store manager, I was continually aggravated by the
barracudas, the cherry pickers who would show up each day to buy
the one or two top items we had on sale. The only things they ever
bought, it seemed, were items on which I made no profit,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? He is now a barracuda. Example. One recent day he
spotted a supermarket ad offering six-pack bundles of U.S. prime
strip steaks, ``limit of two per customer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So he went out and bought two packages, or 12 steaks,'' his
wife disclosed. ``But he made me get in a separate checkout line to
buy 12 more steaks. We shop there all the time. They know I'm his
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   My cousin stopped short of running out to his car, donning a
Nixon mask and returning to buy 12 more strip steaks. But he was
tempted.
</P>
<P>
   He is buying for two people. He has two freezers in the garage,
and both are jammed. His wife allowed us to inspect his pantry. It
looks like a newly filled shelf at the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   I asked if he really needed 12 boxes of macaroni and cheese, six
jars of peanut butter, 10 jars of jam or four giant boxes of
oatmeal. My cousin didn't reply. He just smiled. If a flaming
meteor strikes the Earth and destroys all the crops, livestock and
warehouses in America my cousin and his wife _ Mr. and Mrs.
Barracuda _ are good for at least 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Alice the Artist claims she sees a family resemblance. What do
you suppose she means by that? True, my cousin and I do share
Scottish grandparents. But I can't imagine buying 24 strip steaks
in one swoop through the checkout lines.
</P>
<P>
   Of course if my favorite seafood delicacy, halibut cheeks, were
on sale, I might test the store's indulgence. But to preserve my
reputation, I might ask Alice to wear the Nixon mask.
</P>
<P>
   Barracuda (or Halibut) Pie
</P>
<P>
   1 pound halibut cheeks
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 12-ounce can evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup clam nectar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon mustard powder
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen peas, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1 medium carrot, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 small red potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 pie crust, homemade or frozen
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure about barracuda. But you can use true cod or
halibut in this dish. If you don't have clam nectar on hand, mix
some anchovy paste with one-half cup of hot water.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl mix the cornstarch with one-quarter cup of the
evaporated milk. Stir until smooth, then add the rest of the milk,
the clam nectar, mustard powder, cayenne pepper and black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the potatoes in small cubes and boil in water, along with
the carrot slices, until tender. With a slotted spoon transfer the
veggies to a bowl. Into the same saucepan full of water toss the
halibut cheeks (or hunks of fish about 2 inches wide.) Bring water
to a boil, reduce heat and simmer five minutes. Remove fish and let
it cool.
</P>
<P>
   Grab your hat and hold on. We're about to make some fish pie!
</P>
<P>
   OK, heat the oil in a large skillet. Saute the onions and celery
for three minutes. Add the red pepper hunks, the garlic and
mushroom slices and continue cooking another two minutes. Pour in
the milk mixture and stir-cook until the sauce thickens. Then add
to the pan the potatoes, carrots and peas. Stir-cook for a minute,
then remove pan from heat and add the fish, flaking it with your
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Dump this entire mess into a round casserole. Top with the
uncooked pie crust. The fit on the casserole doesn't have to be
perfect. Shove a sharp knife into the crust to create two slashes.
Paint the crust with milk, then shove the casserole into a
preheated, 350-degree oven and cook until the crust is brown, 20 to
30 minutes. Let the pie sit outside the oven for five minutes
before cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Serves three to four. If you're still hungry, I think my cousin
has 32 packages of Jell-O pudding in his pantry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
