<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-VOUCHERS-ART-2ND     06-14 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-VOUCHERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MILWAUKEE: 15,000 total. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But questions about what religious schools are required to do
may temper some schools' enthusiasm for the plan. The law says
students can decline to take part in religious observances.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rules include abandoning religious observance, we may
not be able to participate,'' said Tom Hage, the principal of
Resurrection Catholic Academy, a school that has accepted so many
public school students whose tuition was privately subsidized that
they now make up about half the enrollment of 240. Hage said all
students attend church once a week during school hours.
</P>
<P>
   The program also does not require private and religious schools
to hire certified teachers or use standardized state curriculum and
tests, or to adhere to the same rules of accountability that public
schools do. It is not clear whether the state will try to change
those rules, or how changes would affect participation.
</P>
<P>
   It is also unclear how dissatisfied parents are with the
district, which, for all its problems, includes award-winning and
specialty schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is they're aren't that many parents you interview
who are really upset,'' said Emily Van Dunk, a research coordinator
for the Public Policy Forum, a nonpartisan group, which found most
parents say they are happy with their child's school, whether
public or private.
</P>
<P>
   Empirical studies have been less than conclusive. One, conducted
by a Princeton University economics professor, Cecilia Rouse,
considered politically neutral, found students in the school choice
program performed better in math, but showed no gains in reading.
</P>
<P>
   Rouse also compared ``choice'' schools with public schools that
had small classes and other enhancements and found the public
school students did as well in math and better in reading.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests to some on both sides that public schools can find
ways to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will probably become more market-oriented now in terms of
how we display to the community our successes,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents' views vary. Some, like Jennifer Evans, a religious
education director at a Unitarian church, a public school parent
and a plaintiff in the voucher lawsuit, said she feared some public
schools would be cash-strapped and left with students ``whose
parents didn't have the resources, whether financially or
emotionally or whatever, to get them into a different school.''
</P>
<P>
   Others like vouchers because they promote religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   But several focused on their own pragmatic circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Watts, who serves food in a public school cafeteria,
pulled her sons out of public school three years ago because
Marquess, now 11, was suspended several times for discipline
problems and Remy, now 12, had very low grades. With PAVE's help,
she placed them in Resurrection Catholic Academy, where they ``have
more one-on-one with the teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Coleman-Brown moved her sons, Kenneth, now 15, and
Trent, now 14, from public school to a secular voucher school to a
Roman Catholic school and back to public schools, depending on how
she felt about the teachers, the principal and her children's
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something doesn't work,'' said Ms. Coleman-Brown, an
administrative assistant for the county government, ``you move
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
