<HEADLINE>
MASS. RESIDENTS BEGIN CLEANUP AFTER HEAVY RAINS, FLOODING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 AND PATRICK J. CALNAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As torrential downpours gave way to scattered showers
Sunday in one of the decade's most severe rain storms,
Massachusetts residents pumped out water-logged basements, wrinkled
noses at raw sewage littering roads and rivers, and braced for a
predicted nightmare commute Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Flood warnings were still in effect late Sunday as
meteorologists forecast sporadic rain showers through Tuesday. But
even without more rain, Saturday's downpour was enough to mark the
June weekend as one of the rainiest on record. In Boston, 5.69
inches of rain fell Saturday, coming close to the record one-day
rainfall of 6.11 inches set Oct. 20, 1996. The previous single-day
record in June was 4.36 inches in 1881.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three days, West Mansfield had the highest
recorded rainfall in the state of 9.65 inches as of Sunday
afternoon, with Logan Airport reporting 7.10 inches as of last
night.
</P>
<P>
   And even when the rain stopped for a period Sunday, the water
kept pouring into swollen rivers and flooded roadways from
overtaxed drainage pipes. Almost every outdoor event in the state
was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen rain like this before, it's amazing,'' said
Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino, whose own Christmas decorations and
golf clubs were soaked when his Hyde Park basement flooded. ``There
are places that are flooding that never flooded before.''
</P>
<P>
   In Revere, police are investigating whether weather played a
part in a single-car accident that killed three people early Sunday
morning. Rhode Island police called the storm a ``contributing
factor'' in a head-on Cranston crash that killed 69-year-old Hilda
Scaralia. Across New England, police reported dozens of car
accidents and stalled cars in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people from a an apartment complex in Boston's Dorchester
section were treated at area hospitals for carbon monoxide
poisoning after becoming overcome by fumes from a gas-powered
generator, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Norwood, the Neponset River was 2 feet over flood stage at 4
p.m. and officials were also worried about severe flooding in
Milton, Dedham, Quincy, and Walpole. The Assabet, Blackstone,
Nashua, and Charles rivers were also threatening to overflow
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Maine, fast-rising water in the Saco River stranded 17
canoeists, some from Beverly and Worcester, when their boats were
washed downstream in Fryeburg. As the group slept, nine of the
canoes floated away and a canoeist called police on a cellular
phone to rescue the group. No one was hurt. On Sebago Lake, dozens
of boats sank or were tipped over as winds stirred up 4- to 6-foot
waves.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, a state of emergency was lifted late Sunday
afternoon, but many of the 17 other Massachusetts towns that
declared emergencies this weekend still had them in effect. Even
after the heavy rains let up Sunday afternoon, Salem, Saugus,
Norton, Plainville, Boxford, and North Attleboro declared states of
emergencies, largely because of flooding concerns, said officials
from the Massachusetts Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Nine temporary shelters for residents displaced by the storm
remained open in Boston, although few people were at them Sunday
afternoon. Flooding at West Roxbury's Star of David Rehabilitation
and Alzheimer's Center will keep 139 residents displaced until
later this week as staff workers try to drain 5 feet of water from
the ground-floor administration offices. All residents are in
sister facilities and are doing well, a spokeswoman said last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the rain tapered, scattered and small power outages
continued across New England, with most residents' power restored
by last night. Separate power outages were reported Sunday morning
in Cumberland and Burrillville, R.I., leaving about 3,000 customers
without power, according to Todd McLeish, a spokesman for Eastern
Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Electric and Boston Edison reported that about 300
homes were still without power Sunday afternoon in the Boston and
Merrimack Valley area, and expected most to have power restored by
early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported numerous lightning strikes of homes, but no
serious injuries. The Norwood police station was deluged with 5
feet of water, destroying valuable papers in the evidence room. The
Somerville police headquarters was also flooded, forcing officers
to operate out of a temporary unit until late Sunday. In Melrose,
the Middle School and Roosevelt Elementary School will be closed
Monday because of severe flooding, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sump pump rentals around Boston were booked solid for
the next three days as residents prepared to pump out thousands of
gallons of water in basements, some of which had never flooded
before.
</P>
<P>
   And in many basements and almost anywhere there was water, there
was also smelly raw sewage sludge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everywhere,'' said Janine Noble, a tourist from Houston
braving Sunday morning's rain to walk through Boston Common. ``It
was pouring out of manhole covers when we drove over them. It's
really brown and yucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Many communities' residents reported similar sightings as
overloaded sewage systems failed to handle the amount of volume
pouring into treatment plants. In many towns, the same pipes that
carry storm water carry sewage to treatment plants. When there is
too much water, the sewage does not have a chance to get to the
treatment plant. Instead, it mixes with the water and winds up
pouring into rivers, streams and, in some cases, up through manhole
covers onto roads.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a thick film of the sludge was seen on the Charles
River and in Boston Harbor. The Saugus River in Saugus and the
Rosemary River in Needham had severe sewage problems, state
Emergency Management Agency officials said. State workers will test
the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water is chocolate brown,'' said Bruce Berman, director of
the Bay Watch program for Save the Harbor/Save the Bay. ``I urge
boaters, swimmers, and fishermen to exercise care and caution.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman said efforts to clean up the bay have been good, but when
severe storms cause such massive dumpings of sewage ``this is a
sobering reminder of how much more we have to do to solve the wet
weather monster.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Water Resources Authority officials said they were
pleased with what the treatment plant did take in, and noted that
within a few days, most of the sludge would be gone.
</P>
<P>
   But until that happens, the commute to work, or a run along the
river, may not be the most pleasant-smelling one. Officials urged
caution this morning because some roadways are still expected to be
flooded. Construction will be ongoing on Archdale Road in
Roslindale, where a rising water table caused the road to buckle
over the weekend, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The MBTA had minor delays in the commuter rail Sunday night
because of the weather. Those delays may extend to Monday. Buses
shuttling passengers on the Green Line between the Reservoir and
Kenmore Square stops may still be operating Monday because of
flooding. Buses were also running between Wellington and Oak Grove
on the Orange Line Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And across the city, residents and commuters were expected to
look upward, hoping to glimpse any small sign of the sun. Knowing
that the rainfall was a record did not comfort many.
</P>
<P>
   ``My basement is completely flooded, everything got rained out
and the kids are going crazy,'' said Shandra Kelly of the South
End. ``I just want the sun to come out and dry everything off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
