<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-TAXCUTTERS-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON COLUMN: TRYING TO ENSURE OPTIMISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been a tough year for Republican tax
cutters. President Clinton effectively put the budget surplus
off-limits by claiming it for Social Security. Efforts to pay for a
tax cut by slashing spending have run into a wall of political
opposition. Other potential sources, like money that would be
generated by the proposed anti-smoking bill, are not yet certain
enough to be counted on.
</P>
<P>
   So it was perhaps not surprising when Speaker Newt Gingrich and
his top lieutenants lashed out in frustration last week at the
Congressional Budget Office, whose estimates of the United States'
fiscal condition over the past few years have proved consistently
too pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Angry that the budget office's projections have regularly
underestimated the room Congress has to cut taxes even after
dealing with Social Security's looming insolvency, Gingrich and his
team vented in the form of a letter to the House Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than just listing their criticisms, Gingrich and the
leadership team suggested that they would seek to cut the budget
office's financing if its tax and spending estimates were not
revised to show bigger surpluses in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CBO must address this problem,'' Gingrich wrote. ``If it
does not, I believe we must review the structure and funding for
the CBO in this appropriations cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure campaign brought a storm of criticism from
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago,'' said Rep. John Spratt Jr. of South
Carolina, the ranking Democrat on the Budget Committee, ``the
Republican Congress shut down the government, insisting that the
president use CBO estimates. Now the House Republican leaders want
to shut down CBO because they do not like CBO estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leader in the House, Dick Gephardt of Missouri,
called the letter ``just another blatant attempt by the Republican
leadership to artificially pump up the surplus to serve as a
political piggy bank for their grab bag of special-interest tax
cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the morass they risked being pushed into, the
Republican leaders on the Appropriations Committee sidestepped
Gingrich's demands. Rep. James Walsh of New York, the chairman of
the subcommittee that finances the budget office, agreed to put in
this year's spending bill a demand that the budget office report on
why its forecasts have proved wrong. But he took no steps to review
or cut the office's $25.7 million budget for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's criticism was brushed aside by June O'Neill, the
director of the budget office, who said that coming up with a
totally accurate surplus or deficit forecast for a $1.7 trillion
budget was no easy task in an ever-changing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBO is used to being a scapegoat and a punching bag,'' she
said in an interview. ``We're the accountants, and while your
personal accountant might be directed to provide an answer that's
beneficial to you, we can't do that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bashing the budget office is a time-honored tradition, indulged
in over the years by Democrats and Republicans alike. (Ms. O'Neill
noted that years ago a Democratic Congress had been miffed at one
of her predecessors, Alice Rivlin, now the vice chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board, and denied the budget office use of a car to
take officials around town _ a prohibition that remains.)
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has consistently pressed the budget office to adopt a
new way of estimating tax receipts, one that assumes that tax cuts
will unleash higher rates of economic growth and therefore generate
more revenue for the government.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case his pique seems mostly a manifestation of
frustration over how difficult it has been to accomplish something
that Republicans had assumed would be so easy: returning to
taxpayers at least some of the projected budget surpluses, which,
after all, are nothing but excess tax payments.
</P>
<P>
   And if there was a lesson for both sides, it was that budget
politics in the age of surplus are proving just as rough-and-tumble
as they were in the dark days when fiscal profligacy seemed
destined to reduce the United States to an economic has-been.
</P>
<P>
   Then the budget office usually took a dimmer view of the economy
than did presidents of either party, and deficit hawks praised its
restraint, accusing administrations of falling to the siren song of
someone called Rosy Scenario.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
