<HEADER>
A8668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-LEAKS-BOS &LR;      06-14 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-LEAKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNSEL'S ADMISSION ON LEWINSKY CASE SPARKS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 AND BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's surprise
admission that his office discussed the Monica S. Lewinsky case
with reporters has become one more subject for fierce and confusing
partisan debate in scandal-ridden Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Sunday amplified its call for an independent
investigation of Starr, while Steven Brill _ whose magazine article
sparked the latest controversy _ defended his contention that Starr
violated ethical and possibly criminal boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the independent counsel attacked Brill's article as
shoddy, and members of the Washington press corps bristled at
Brill's suggestion that they had been eager dupes of Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the crucial issue of the propriety and legality of
conversations between journalists and Starr's office remains a
matter of debate and disagreement. And as the argument rages, all
sides of the controversy are waiting to see how the latest
developments will affect Starr's long-running investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bombshell. It is grave. It is very serious,'' senior
White House aide Rahm Emanuel said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.'' He was referring to the article written by Brill for his
new media-criticism magazine Content.
</P>
<P>
   Released Saturday in time to dominate Sunday morning's
television news shows, Brill's 30-page article on press coverage of
the Lewinsky case assailed Starr's tactics and a scandal-hungry
media that became, he wrote, ``an enabler of Starr's abuse of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, White House aides expressed shock that Starr would
acknowledge his contacts with the news media in such a public forum
as a magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said that Charles Ruff, the White House
counsel, and David E. Kendall, Clinton's personal attorney, were
reviewing the article and weighing the next step. The aide said
that with Starr's acknowledgment, the issue has ``taken on a tone
of greater seriousness.''
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel's office reiterated its earlier
statement that Brill ``had recklessly and irresponsibly'' accused
it of ``improper contacts with the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The source of the controversy is Starr's interview with Brill,
in which Starr said that he and his deputy, Jackie Bennett Jr.,
gave reporters background briefings on the Lewinsky matter. Starr
defended those conversations as proper because they did not
directly deal with grand jury proceedings and were intended to
counter ``misinformation'' being spread about his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, Brill raised the possibility that Starr violated
Rule 6(e) of the Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure, which
prohibits government lawyers and agents from disclosing any
``material occurring before the grand jury.'' Brill believes the
rule prohibits ``leaking information about prospective witnesses
who might testify at a grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal precedents don't provide clear guidance on this matter.
Some courts, including the federal Appeals Court in Washington,
agree with Brill on interpreting the rule. But other courts have
taken Starr's less-restrictive view.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Brill hit the talk show circuit with a ferocity not seen
since William H. Ginsburg was heading up the Lewinsky defense. On
C-SPAN, he said that Starr ``did not dispute any of the quotes in
the article,'' and that the two disagreed on the applicability of
Rule 6(e). On CBS's ``Face the Nation,'' Brill wondered why Starr
and Bennett hadn't talked to reporters on the record if they
considered the conversations appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the furor, the idea that Starr's office was talking to
reporters is not a novel one. In February, Kendall appeared so
angry about a series of leaks in The New York Times that he hastily
arranged a sidewalk press conference, read a sharply worded
statement denouncing Starr, and stalked off.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of leaks from the prosecutor also has been discussed
in numerous media stories on the Lewinsky episode, and at one
point, Time magazine ran a cover story headlined ``Trial By
Leaks.''
</P>
<P>
   On MSNBC Sunday, Newsweek reporter Michael Isikoff, who broke
the Lewinsky story, intimated that leaks from prosecutors to
journalists _ from the federal to the local level _ are a fact of
life in both journalism and law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused Brill of ``slanted'' and ``selective'' reporting
that displays ``quite a bit of naivete'' about the relationships
between prosecutors and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post's Bob Woodward, who helped crack the
Watergate mystery a quarter-century ago, asserted that Starr was
within his rights to talk to reporters under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is within the guidelines when it's a public controversy''
and the goal is to ``give people direction'' about the path of the
investigation, Woodward said on ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue also became the subject of a spirited debate between
Jonathan Turley, a law professor at George Washington University,
and Stanley Brand, a former US House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it extraordinary,'' Brand, on ``Face the Nation,'' said
of Starr's actions. ``Whether they are `6(e)' or not, they are
inextricably'' woven into grand jury proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Countered Turley: ``There is nothing sinister about it. I'd be
suprised if the (Brill) article made it past the copy editor of a
small town paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Isikoff, whose role in helping Newsweek break the Lewinsky story
receives much ink in Brill's story, criticized that article as ``an
editorial more than anything else. He doesn't seem to think the
investigation was worthwhile. I do think the article is pretty
slanted. ... It doesn't address at all the evidence in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lucianne Goldberg, the book agent whom Brill puts in the
middle of the plan to peddle the Lewinsky scandal to the press,
reacted angrily in an interview on the Fox News Channel Sunday. If
Brill is setting himself up to be a media watchdog, she said,
``this dog won't hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill repeatedly was asked why he didn't spend as much time
scrutinizing the White House's role in manipulating the media as he
did Starr's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quickly decided the most important aspect of this story
wasn't the White House,'' he said on the CBS program, stating that
the White House spin was being drowned out by opposition leaks in
the days immediately after the story broke in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public recognizes what has gone on here more than
the press,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
