<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATS-COX     06-14 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conservationists work to protect bat habitat by driving stake
through vampire myth
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LEON, Mexico _ There's no bell, but a nearby rooster is
kind enough to crow at about the appropriate time, and the
straggling children dash into their sea-foam-green schoolhouse in
the Sierra Madre .
</P>
<P>
   Visitors Maria Jesus Teniente and Maria Luisa Franco are
tag-team teaching the class, giving the 20 or so fourth-, fifth-
and sixth-graders at Francisco Cirilo School an update on their
friend Marcelo el murcie(accent)lago _ Marcelo the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Do you remember when we were here before, the two teachers ask?
</P>
<P>
   Si(accent), the children say.
</P>
<P>
   They were here about 18 months ago. And they're back to
reinforce the message they delivered then: that the bats in nearby
Cueva de la Boca _ the winter home for a portion of the Mexican
free-tail colony that summers under Austin, Texas's Congress Avenue
bridge _ are benevolent, bug-eating critters that don't need to be
harassed out of the cave.
</P>
<P>
   The two teachers are affiliated with the Program for the
Conservation of Migratory Bats, called PCMM after its Spanish name.
Begun with wishful thinking, good intentions and precious few pesos
in 1991, the program, affiliated with the Austin-based Bat
Conservation International, now has a budget and a mission that
combines research, education and habitat preservation. Along with
Bat Conservation International, the program is plugged into a
network of similar groups across North America.
</P>
<P>
   The front line for all this work is rural schools such as this
one in Nuevo Leon and elsewhere in northern Mexico, a critical area
for migratory bats across the continent. By making the bat a
kid-friendly cartoon mascot such as the smiling Marcelo, the group
hopes to begin scouring away centuries of myth, superstition and
disproportionate fear directed at the animals.
</P>
<P>
   This prejudice has led to a precipitous decline in bat
populations through the region. A 1991 check found populations
dropping in eight of the 10 caves surveyed. Once home to as many as
6 million bats, making it one of the biggest colonies in the world,
Cueva de la Boca now has between 100,000 and 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   So, as Bat Conservation International does on this side of the
border, PCMM does on the other side, preaching the benefits of
bats: The representatives point out thatbats eat tons of
crop-eating pests. They identify the dramatic mass exits made by
Mexican free-tails as a potential tourist attraction. Another
species of bat pollinates the agave plant, from which tequila is
made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to show clearly that there are different bats. The
major fear is vampire bats,'' says Joaquin Arroyo-Cabrales, one of
the program's co-founders. ``Here there are no vampire bats, but
people fear them in la Boca.''
</P>
<P>
   The fear of vampire bats isn't entirely unfounded. Having the
habit of feeding on the blood of vertebrates, particularly
livestock, and employing an anticoagulant in their saliva to keep
the blood flowing , vampire bats have the potential to make their
food sources vulnerable to infection and disease, including rabies.
However, vampire bats usually don't forage far from where they
roost.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that vampires aren't among the nine species identified
as living in Cueva de la Boca hasn't deterred locals from trying to
eradicate them . Shotgun shells have been found inside the cave.
Kerosene-soaked tires have been set ablaze in caves, a particularly
destructive way of smoking out bats.
</P>
<P>
   Several other factors also contribute to the decline: Certain
pesticides, banned in the United States, poison the bugs that bats
eat. A phosphorous mine, now abandoned, used to operate just under
the cave floor. Dynamite is regularly used at a nearby quarry.
</P>
<P>
   But the cave is already something of a draw for tourists, and
that may ultimately be what restores the colony to something like
its size 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cueva de la Boca is an easy 45-minute drive from Monterrey, near
the town of Santiago, which is in the nascent stage of an
eco-tourism boomlet. Weekend traffic from Monterrey to Presa la
Boca, a man-made lake, and Cola de Caballo, a natural waterfall, is
heavy, and a fair number of visitors also trek to the cave, though
for the view, not for the bats.
</P>
<P>
   Round a corner on the winding road and you can't miss it. The
limestone cave's entrance is 100 feet high and almost as wide,
improbably rectangular in shape, like an airplane hangar blasted
out of the rock. It's a wind-sucker of a climb, nearly vertical, a
couple of hundred yards to the entrance on a trail rugged enough to
challenge a mountain goat. The payoff is the view, and it is an
astounding one.
</P>
<P>
   Such a setting attracts a fair number of romantic teen-agers ,
although the exertion of the climb (and the bat odor inside) must
dampen the mood for some. It also attracts vandalism. The inside
walls of the cave are thick with graffiti. Bat Conservation
International originally proposed a gate over the entrance of the
cave to keep people out but allow free access for bats.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea has emerged: a nature trail to the entrance, with
information along the way on bats and other native plants and
animals. With the backing of some business people in Monterrey, the
Mexican conservationists are on the verge of hiring an architect
for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Will it happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't doubt it,'' says Arroyo, standing inside the cave.
``The doubt may be when exactly. I was talking with (BCI's) Steve
Walker, and we said someday it will be nice to be down there in our
rocking chairs and see all the people up here watching the bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Deeper into the cave, where the smell gets stronger and the
powdery guano resembles lunar soil, teachers Teniente and Franco
don masks as a precaution against histoplasmosis, a disease caused
by a fungus that sometimes turns up in droppings. Here the ceiling
rises like a cathedral, high enough that it's impossible to spot
bats even with powerful flashlights.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there are not all that many of them to spot. When
the free-tails begin their nightly chow run around dusk, they form
a streaming column that hugs one wall before it disperses into the
night. The flapping wings make a sound like a light rain shower.
</P>
<P>
   But it's over in five minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   This is an improvement over the early '90s, Arroyo says, but
there's plenty of work remaining. Among the tasks facing
researchers is more extensive study of the bats' migratory habits.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo, who holds a doctorate from Texas Tech University, had
spent a portion of the previous week catching bats in another cave
in northern Mexico and taking small samples of membrane for DNA
analysis. It's hoped that the tracking of migratory patterns
through such analyses over generations will yield more data than
has been available from tagging bats with the hope of later
retrieving them.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to what is known about birds, knowledge of the
migratory habits of most bat species is spotty. remain a
combination of speculation and sheer mystery.
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly a summer colony at Cueva de la Boca, and it's
believed some of the Congress Avenue bats use the cave as a
stopover during migration.
</P>
<P>
   The bats aren't the only migrants in the region. About this time
of year, billions of corn earworm moths _ the top agricultural pest
in America _ ascend and catch winds that carry them far to the
north _ more than 250 miles in a single night, said Gary F.
McGracken, a professor of ecology and evolutionary biology at the
University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, those bugs lay eggs on corn, cotton and other
crops west of San Antonio. A few weeks after that, the young moths,
having feasted on the crops, continue the leap-frogging northward
movement, chewing up plenty of vegetation along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The bats fly at the same altitude as the moths, and the moth
migration begins at the time when female bats are pregnant and need
the most food. Thus, by interrupting the moth migration cycle at
the beginning, the Mexican free-tail bats have an agricultural
benefit far beyond their foraging range. Free-tails in just a
handful of Central Texas caves eat close to 2 million pounds of the
same migrating moths every night, biologists estimate.
</P>
<P>
   None of this matters much to the children of Francisco Cirilo
School, who occupy themselves decorating a huge banner _ using
paint, markers, crepe paper and whatever else is handy _ with
pictures of Marcelo, the lake and Cueva de la Boca. It's a crafts
project, but there's evidence the repeat visits are working: A bat
exhibit in Santiago drew more visitors than any other traveling
exhibit. The kids get Marcelo books, erasers, puzzles and rulers.
And they learn that Cueva de la Boca is one of a series of caves in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo brings in the poster made by schoolchildren near another
cave, Cueva de Quintero. The Cirilo kids snicker and declare that,
in their estimation, la Boca is considerably nicer.
</P>
<P>
   As the session winds up, a class of younger children _ not in on
the morning program _ takes a break . Even though she missed the
program, 8-year-old Savannah Kay knows about the bats: Her father
sometimes leads groups to the cave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they eat insects,'' she said. ``That's how they live.
That's their food.''
</P>
<P>
   The bat conservationists can talk eco-tourism and agricultural
benefit all they want, but many of these children have a simple,
practical reason for wanting to protect Marcelo. An energetic
10-year-old boy named Eli is asked if he likes bats. Si(accent), he
says. Why, he is asked.
</P>
<P>
   Because they eat mosquitoes, he says, and mosquitoes eat me.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
