<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REM-COX     06-14 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rem performs Sunday at Tibet benefit concert in DC
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ R.E.M. fans can stop holding their collective
breaths: the band is back and bold as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after losing longtime drummer and founding member
Bill Berry, the legendary Athens group made its first public
appearance as a trio here in front of 60,000 sun-toasted rock fans
at the second day of the Tibetan Freedom Concert. The eight-song
set included four new tunes from the closely guarded CD the band
has been recording in San Francisco and Athens, Ga., set for
release in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   R.E.M. was originally scheduled to play Saturday, but the
concert was abruptly cancelled shortly before their set when a
freakish bolt of lightening struck 11 concertgoers, leaving one in
critical condition. The band decided to reschedule, apparently
because of their deep commitment to the Tibetan cause.
</P>
<P>
   The look wasn't so new. Bassist Mike Mills, guitarist Peter Buck
and lead singer Michael Stipe took their usual spots front and
center, although Stipe created a bit of buzz when he walked out in
a tight, midriff baring top and hip-hugging sarong skirt. (``I felt
like being foxy,'' he later joked.)
</P>
<P>
   The sound, however, was very different. In what appeared to be
an in-your-ear answer to all those fans and critics speculating how
the loss of Berry's signature drumbeat would be handled, R.E.M.
opened its set with the new song ``Airport Man,'' featuring a
plethora of alternative percussion _ drum machine, bells, maracas
and a xylophone. The eastern-influenced song was as mystical as the
Dalai Lama himself, a slowly ethereal tune that was a vast
departure from the pop radio sounds of ``Losing My Religion'' or
``Man in the Moon,'' the only two ``greatest hits'' R.E.M. played
for the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The other three new songs R.E.M. rolled out in this sneak
preview were equally transcendental. Drummer Joey Waronker (Beck),
who will tour with R.E.M. in the fall, provided the beat.
</P>
<P>
   But the skins were certainly secondary in the set. After the
show, Stipe underscored the definition of the band he adamantly
stuck to when Berry left. ``This band is _ and will be until we
quit making music _ Mike Mills, Michael Stipe and Peter Buck,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the boisterous festival atmosphere, Stipe said the
group intentionally decided to try the new material at this gig in
spite of its introspective and somewhat private sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like dinner theater now,'' he quipped, when asked about
the new material. ``We aren't always going to be
bash-you-over-the-head rock. I hope people understand we like to
push the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans seemed to have liked what they heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're still good. I thought the new stuff kept the same sort
of feeling as (the band's last CD) `New Adventures in Hi-Fi,' ''
Jeff D'Agostino, a 36-year-old software engineer for NASA, said
after the short set. ``It sounded like there was a certain
weariness to the songs. I certainly wouldn't call it mosh pit
music. I'm anxious to hear the new album.''
</P>
<P>
   The only complaint after the band's set came from longtime fans
who were particularly upset with the horrendous sound in RFK
Stadium, where the concert was held.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should fire their sound man,'' said 43-year-old Alan
Stubbs, a government computer manager. ``I can't tell you whether
or not I like the new stuff, because I couldn't really hear it. But
I have every one of their albums, and I'll try this. You know
R.E.M. fans aren't just fans _ we're cerebral.''
</P>
<P>
   The set:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Airport Man,'' a new, bell-drenched tune with a heavy
Eastern influence.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Losing My Religion.''
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Suspicion,'' another new one, layered over eerie keyboards,
Peter Buck's fat Duane Eddy guitar, with a melody that sounded a
bit like Roy Orbison's ``You Got It.''
</P>
<P>
   4. The new tune ``Sad Professor,'' weaving the V-8 Rolling
Stones-inspired organ from ''You Can't Always Get What You Want''
with acoustic guitar.
</P>
<P>
   5. ''Be Mine,'' featuring a guest appearance from Radiohead lead
vocalist Tom Yorke.
</P>
<P>
   6. ''Parakeet,'' with Mike Mills on a slow and dark piano.
</P>
<P>
   7. ''E-Bow'' from ''New Adventures in Hi-Fi,'' also with Yorke.
</P>
<P>
   8. ''Man on the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
