<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELMS-U.N.-DUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS PULLS DIPLOMATIC LEVER TO MOVE CLINTON ON U.N. BILL
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a foreign embassy needs a favor from Congress,
diplomats can appeal to no higher authority on international
affairs than Sen. Jesse Helms. But private audiences with the
powerful North Carolina Republican, who heads the Foreign Relations
Committee, and his top aides are hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   So when Helms' staff members took the rare step of inviting
diplomats from 10 countries for coffee and cookies in the
committee's ornate briefing room at the Capitol last Wednesday and
asked them for help _ well, eyebrows went up. ``It was an
interesting phenomenon,'' said one European diplomat who attended
the 45-minute meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Helms has a plan to outfox his old foe, Bill
Clinton. And he thinks the Washington diplomatic corps can help.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, who is no fan of the United Nations, has oddly enough
begun lobbying on behalf of a bill that would pay nearly $1 billion
in dues that the United States owes the United Nations, something
Clinton himself has pushed Congress to do.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch. The legislation includes an anti-abortion
provision that the president so opposes that he is threatening to
veto the entire bill because of it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Helms cares so deeply about the bill is that it also
has provisions for overhauling the government's diplomatic
bureaucracy, which Helms sees as one of his most important
legislative legacies. The overhaul would fold the Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency and the U.S. Information Agency into the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   While Helms personally opposes abortion, he has criticized the
anti-abortion provision in the bill, which was attached at the
insistence of House conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been writing op-ed articles to press Clinton and has
indirectly enlisted Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary general, who
urged Clinton again last Monday to pay the back dues to the
organization. And with the briefing Wednesday, Helms and his aides
took their case to some of America's staunchest allies.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and the Senate have approved the bill, but Helms
is delaying sending it to the president in the hope that the
impasse can be resolved. Asked when that might be, the senator
said: ``When the president tells me he's going to sign it. The
president's been silent in seven languages on this. He can't have
his way every time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the effort to salvage a State Department overhaul and to
shield congressional Republicans from blame if the legislation
dies, Helms and his aides invited diplomats from Australia,
Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Britain
and the Netherlands to the Wednesday briefing.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted countries have a sizable financial stake in how the
dispute plays out. The United Nations owes the 10 nations more than
$500 million for contributions to peacekeeping operations. The
sooner the United States pays up, the sooner the United Nations can
pay them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helms is obviously trying to use us to pressure the
administration,'' said an official from one embassy that sent a
diplomat to the meeting. ``We don't want to get involved in the
partisan battle and we're not being narrowly mercenary, but
obviously we want to get our money.''
</P>
<P>
   The briefing was led by James Nance, a retired Navy rear admiral
who is not only the committee's staff director, but also Helms'
boyhood friend and alter ego. Helms did not attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A three-page memorandum, ``Status of the U.N. Arrears
Legislation,'' given to the diplomats describes Helms' views on the
legislation's status, the anti-abortion provision and Clinton's
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has refused any compromise and is demanding
total capitulation,'' the document says, meaning that the president
wants the provision on abortion dropped entirely. ``Helms now
blames the administration intransigence for the current impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-abortion provision bars federal financing for
international groups that lobby foreign governments to change their
abortion policies. Republicans say it is a watered-down version of
an executive order that Clinton struck down in 1993. The White
House says the provision still goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason for the veto threat: catering to `women's
groups,''' the memo said. ``White House is unwilling to make even a
symbolic concession on abortion that might anger these groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms has said this is the last chance for the U.N. payment
issue to be addressed this year. The memo states that the bill will
not be sent to the White House until Clinton agrees to sign it or
until ``the most uncomfortable moment for the President to veto
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms' aides said they hoped the briefing would unleash a quiver
of diplomatic cables back to foreign capitals, which would increase
pressure on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the half dozen diplomats interviewed said they had
dutifully sent dispatches to their superiors. But diplomats said
they were struck more by Helms' approach. ``They were definitely
trying to woo us,'' said one European official.
</P>
<P>
   At least one participant said the episode was a lesson out of
American Civics 101. ``This is how the system works in the U.S.,
except that we're the ones usually doing the lobbying,'' said one
European diplomat. ``We won't let ourselves be used.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
