</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNMENT-REPARATIONS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WILL PAY REPARATIONS TO FORMER LATIN AMERICAN INTERNEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The federal government has agreed to settle a
class-action lawsuit filed on behalf of 1,200 Latin Americans of
Japanese descent who were forcibly brought to the United States and
placed in internment camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs and their advocates said they were disappointed with
the settlement, announced on Friday, because the reparations the
former internees stand to receive are less than the amount paid to
Japanese-Americans who suffered the same fate.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which comes after four months of lobbying by
plaintiffs' representatives and negotiations between lawyers and
the Justice Department, will include an acknowledgment of
wrongdoing by the government and a letter of apology from President
Clinton to each of the plaintiffs. Those who file claims to be
included in the settlement will receive a payment of $5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   The government's offer marks a significant change from the
Justice Department's previous stance. The department had wanted the
case dismissed and did not want to conduct settlement talks.
Representatives for the plaintiffs said Bill Lann Lee, the acting
assistant attorney general for civil rights, who was appointed by
Clinton in December, was influential in that change. He agreed to
meet with them in February for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,264 Latin Americans of Japanese descent were taken by
U.S. troops from 13 countries, mainly Bolivia, Colombia and Peru,
during World War II. According to a 1982 report to Congress, the
arrests and transfers were carried out on the orders of President
Franklin D. Roosevelt to ``secure the Western Hemisphere from
internal threats'' and to supply the United States with bargaining
chips for U.S. citizens held hostage by the Axis powers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Civil Liberties Act of 1988, surviving
Japanese-Americans who were placed in internment camps received
reparations of $20,000 each. But Japanese Latin Americans were not
offered reparations under that law because they were not U.S.
citizens. Most of them now live in Japan or South America.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Toma, one of the lawyers who filed the case in 1996, said
the comparatively small amount of money for Latin Americans was
``another symbol of inferior treatment, of being discriminated
against once again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee called the episode an ``inglorious chapter in the nation's
history.'' But he said he thought the settlement was fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what you're hearing is, like many settlements, this is
a compromise,'' Lee said at a news conference here. ``And the
essence of a compromise is not having your highest hopes
realized.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Congress has the right to define a class of people as eligible
for reparations, which was a major legal issue considered by the
lawyers who pressed the case. An uncertain future in court, in
addition to the age of the surviving internees, played a role in
the acceptance of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   There is some concern that there will not be enough money in the
redress fund to cover the settlement, though Lee said the
government would find a way. The Civil Liberties Act expires on
Aug. 10, and most claims for reparations must be made by that date.
Those who are not satisfied with the settlement offer can opt out
of the case and pursue their own remedies.
</P>
<P>
   One internee who now lives in Gardena, Calif., Alicia Nishimoto,
was taken to New Orleans from Peru by ship with her parents and
five siblings in 1944. At a warehouse, she was told to strip and
was sprayed with DDT, put on a train bound for Texas with other
detainees and placed in a camp encircled with barbed wire. It was a
relief to see Japanese-Americans in the camp, she recalled, because
she had thought she would be taken to a jungle and killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, we are making history today,'' Ms. Nishimoto said
tearfully on Friday. ``But I would be lying if I said I were happy
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even to this day, I can't believe this happened to us,'' she
added. ``How can the U.S. government do this?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-LEAKS-5     06-14 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-LEAKS-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR ADMITS ROLE IN LEAKS TO PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the core of the bitter dispute over whether
Kenneth Starr improperly disclosed information about the
investigation of President Clinton are Justice Department
regulations and court decisions involving how much prosecutors may
tell the public and the media about their work.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, the Whitewater prosecutor, said in an interview with
Brill's Content, a new magazine, that he and his aides have given
information about the Monica Lewinsky matter to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The White House immediately responded that the article
buttressed its complaints that the independent counsel's office has
improperly leaked information to the press. But Starr said that he
and his prosecutors had not violated rules about grand jury
secrecy, and said that the actions were permissible because they
were done to protect his office from attacks that undermined public
confidence in his work.
</P>
<P>
   He was apparently referring to Justice Department regulations
that prohibit prosecutors from disclosing any information about a
grand jury investigation, but include an exception for instances in
which there is a need to reassure the public that an investigation
is being conducted properly.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with former and current Justice Department officials
suggest that it remains unclear if the exception in the department
guidelines applies to Starr's actions. The battle between Clinton
and Starr has become not just a legal but a political one, in which
both sides have sought to win the public's support.
</P>
<P>
   Different federal appeals courts have disagreed over the scope
and limits of the law that prohibits grand jury disclosures by
prosecutors. The Supreme Court has never directly addressed the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Starr told the magazine that he and his deputies talked to
reporters ``on background on some occasions'' _ that is, they spoke
on the condition that the resulting news articles not mention that
the information came from the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Starr said that those contacts were ``legal,
appropriate and consistent with Department of Justice policy,''
which provides for informing the public about the activities of
law-enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department policy to which Starr apparently referred
is in a manual given to federal prosecutors and contains a wide
variety of rules covering such divergent topics as how to handle an
arson case and what is an acceptable plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   The manual forbids a prosecutor to discuss many grand jury
matters, but offers three general exceptions. The one on which
Starr appears to rely, included in Section 1-7.530, allows for
disclosure ``about matters about which the community needs to be
reassured that an appropriate law-enforcement agency is
investigating the incident.''
</P>
<P>
   The other exceptions in the regulations are for the public
safety, that is to save a life, or when there has already been
substantial disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Justice Department officials said it was unclear whether
Starr's reasoning _ that he made clarifications to reporters to
protect the reputation of his office from unrelenting attacks _
qualified under the guidelines as a permissible exception to rules
against disclosing grand jury material. ``He might well be able to
make that argument,'' said one official who spoke on the condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors are occasionally disciplined or even
dismissed when they are found to have improperly leaked material to
reporters. Yet even in such cases, the underlying indictments are
never dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, a prosecutor who wants to speak in public or to a
reporter about an investigation must seek permission from
high-level Justice Department officials. As an independent counsel,
Starr does not report directly to the Justice Department and is, in
the first instance, the judge of his own behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno may remove Starr if he has behaved
improperly, but she has resisted all calls to criticize him. She
had no comment through a spokesman Sunday on the issue of the
magazine interview.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer who has already asked a
federal judge to hold Starr in contempt for allegedly leaking grand
jury material, reacted sharply Sunday to the magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are studying it carefully,'' he said. ``It contains
astonishing admissions and it has very serious implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr is quoted in the magazine as saying that none of the
comments to reporters on background involved grand jury
information, describing the material as relating to what witnesses
told agents from the FBI before they testified before the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine notes, however, that the District of Columbia U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals just last month issued an opinion
disputing that view as it offered a wide definition of what
constitutes grand jury material. But other courts, like the 3rd
Circuit Court of Appeals, ruled in 1990 that the secrecy policy is
only designed to protect what takes place in the grand jury room.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Justice Department officials also disputed one element of
the article, that Starr had maneuvered Reno into expanding his
jurisdiction to investigate whether Clinton lied about having had
an affair with Ms. Lewinsky and then encouraged Ms. Lewinsky to lie
about it. The officials said it was clear that the matter had to be
investigated by Starr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RADIO-CITY-RESTORE     06-14 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RADIO-CITY-RESTORE-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLEVISION TO RESTORE AND UPDATE ART DECO LANDMARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Radio City Music Hall, one of New York City's more
enduring show-business icons, will be closed for at least six
months next year for a $30 million restoration, the most extensive
in its 65-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Radio City's art-deco opulence and theatrical
spectacles attract 2 million visitors a year, its operator,
Cablevision Systems Corp., is convinced that its power as a tourist
destination and brand name has not been fully exploited.
</P>
<P>
   So while Radio City will be painstakingly restored for live
theater _ the Rockettes included _ it will also become a production
center for television specials. And Cablevision is planning to
expand the Radio City name to a cable channel, a record label and
an FM radio station.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation is to take place from March to September, during
which Cablevision plans to restore Radio City's block-long marquee,
with its six miles of red-and-blue neon tubing, and the legendary
backstage hydraulic system, which has transported elephants,
Rockettes and whole orchestras across and under the stage.
</P>
<P>
   According to a plan that is still evolving, Cablevision will
also replace seats, carpets, wallpaper and curtains; clean and
restore murals; enhance lighting and sound systems, and restore the
auditorium's pipe organ.
</P>
<P>
   A vast new gold-threaded curtain for the 144-foot-wide stage is
to be embedded with fiber-optic lighting that will generate a
rainbow of changingcolors and patterns. This will allow both the
curtain and the organ to be used in preperformance shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the work is finished it will be like going back six
decades and taking a walk through time,'' said James Dolan, the
chief executive of Cablevision. ``We're going to take the building
back to 1932, but bring its infrastructure forward past the year
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Cablevision leased Radio City Music Hall from its
owner, Tishman Speyer Properties, and bought the rights to both the
Rockettes and the Christmas pageant from Mitsubishi Estate Co.
Cablevision operates cable channels, produces television shows and
provides cable service to 2.6 million customers in the metropolitan
area.
</P>
<P>
   The music hall's revival is part of the master plan of Jerry
Speyer, the manager and part owner of Rockefeller Center, to
resuscitate what he has called ``the world's most famous address.''
He sees Radio City driving the center's nighttime activities in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   As architects for the project, Radio City has hired Hardy
Holzman Pfeiffer Associates, which oversaw the complex renovations
of the New Amsterdam and New Victory theaters on 42nd Street, and
the Rockwell Group, which has designed projects ranging from 60
Planet Hollywoods to Manhattan's Monkey Bar and Nobu restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most comprehensive renewals ever undertaken
in a theater,'' said Hugh Hardy of Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan said the cost of the project would be $30 million to $40
million.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior of the music hall and its public interior spaces,
as well as some furnishings, were designated New York City
landmarks in 1979 and the structure was designated a National
Historic Landmark in 1987. As a result of the city's landmarks
designation, the renovation work will require the approval of the
Landmarks Preservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The music hall renovation is part of an ambitious plan of
Cablevision _ which owns the 18,000-seat Madison Square Garden and
its 5,600-seat theater, and leases the 5,901-seat music hall _ to
consolidate the booking of its entertainment events under Radio
City's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ambition is nothing less than to relaunch Radio City as
the most prestigious, innovative and active theater in the world,''
said Arlen Kantarian, president of Radio City Productions. ``Radio
City is one of the most underdeveloped of brand names,'' said
Kantarian, who is expected to head Radio City Entertainment, a new
corporate entity that will centralize entertainment-event booking
for the Music Hall and Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Renovation plans also include a suite of television studios,
possibly in the nonlandmarked space above the auditorium that now
contains rehearsal halls for the Rockettes. The studios will be
used by Cablevision's American Movie Classics and Bravo cable
channels; the classic movie channel has already been taping its
introductory segments in the Music Hall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Plans for restoration of the marquee include a return to the
sequential lighting of the ``Radio City'' sign, which originally
blinked letter by letter. The architects will propose searchlights
to give the marquee opening-night glamour and will seek to install
touch-screen computer kiosks under the marquee that would offer
theatergoers information about future performances.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-year-old backstage hydraulic system with its three
70-foot-long elevators, which was studied by Navy aircraft-carrier
designers during World War II, has long since run out of
replacement parts. It will be overhauled and reconfigured so that
the mechanical systems can be computer-controlled, making possible
more stage effects of the kind used in Broadway shows like
``Phantom of the Opera'' and ``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   New carpeting and fabric panels are planned to replace the
originals in the Grand Foyer, and the three-story-tall mural by
Ezra Winter, which looms above the grand staircase, will be cleaned
of decades of grime and varnish and restored. Brighter lighting
will be installed, and five new concession stands are planned for
the ground floor and mezzanine levels.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-controlled lighting with color-sequenced programming is
planned to illuminate the auditorium's ``sunrise'' rings, which
radiate from the proscenium arch.
</P>
<P>
   Architects are also drawing up plans for a restaurant on the
mezzanine space overlooking Avenue of the Americas, to be called
The Radio City Club or The Marquee Club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
