<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARTMOUTH-PRESIDENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARTMOUTH CELEBRATES ITS DEPARTING PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ When James Freedman called his mother, the
impossible-to-please Sophie Freedman, to tell her that he had been
named president of Dartmouth College, her response was: ``Why not
Harvard?''
</P>
<P>
   At Dartmouth, meanwhile, a lot of people were saying: ``Why Jim
Freedman?''
</P>
<P>
   He was hardly the stereotypical Dartmouth man. Not only was he a
graduate of Harvard College and Yale Law School, but he was Jewish,
he didn't drink and he preferred reading to skiing, rowing, hiking
or any other outdoor activity. His idea of exercise was browsing
through a good used-book store.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 11 years, Freedman, 62, is stepping down, and this
past weekend, at his final commencement, the college community
showed how much minds had changed. It celebrated the self-effacing
idealist as the model for a new kind of Dartmouth man, and woman
(under Freedman, the student body has achieved increased gender
parity).
</P>
<P>
   The board of trustees thanked him for transforming Dartmouth
into a haven for intellectuals, and making it one of the top
schools in the Ivy League. The freshman class that will arrive on
campus this fall has the highest academic credentials in the
school's history, with median SAT scores of 1440. A perfect SAT
score is 1600.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's upped the intellectual ante,'' said Susan Ackerman, a
professor of religion, talking after a farewell dinner for Freedman
here Saturday night. ``The students are brighter and brighter, and
now they're not afraid to admit that they're bright. He's made it
OK to talk about books and ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth sent Freedman off with an honorary degree _ it also
awarded one to his wife, Sheba, who has a Ph.D. in human
development from Bryn Mawr _ an endowed chair in his name, and,
fittingly, first editions of books by two of his favorite writers.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman, a passionate book collector, did not contain his joy
Saturday as he showed off his gifts: The Collected Letters of
William Carlos Williams _ inscribed by the poet to his wife,
`Flossy dear from Bill, July 31, 1957' _ and James Joyce's
Finnegan's Wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finnegan's Wake!'' said Freedman, opening the book. ``Oh gosh,
I would have died for this.''
</P>
<P>
   He was relaxing with his wife at the president's home on campus,
sipping a diet soft drink and talking about how much he is looking
forward to having extended time to read, and write, again. He will
spend next year at Harvard working on a second book about liberal
education before returning to Dartmouth to teach, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got impatient at being at everyone's beck and call,''
he said. ``Every morning my secretary would hand me a card with my
schedule. It was like a dentist. There was somebody every
half-hour.''
</P>
<P>
   In another era, college presidents regularly stayed on for 20 or
30 years. But these days the pressures are such that many college
presidents endure less than seven years. Freedman lasted 16 _ five
at the University of Iowa, and 11 at Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman leaves to his successor, James Wright, the Dartmouth
provost, a vastly changed college. It is richer, with a $1.28
billion endowment, and the curriculum has been overhauled for the
first time in more than 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Dartmouth has also changed Freedman, forcing him to speak
out, despite a retiring nature. Early on, he took a stand against
The Dartmouth Review, a neoconservative off-campus student
newspaper. He talked publicly about his successful struggle with
cancer. And he spoke about the anti-Semitism in the college's past.
</P>
<P>
   In his first book on liberal education, Freedman wrote about
college as a time for young people to nurture their private and
public selves. He quoted Thomas Mann's ``Doctor Faustus.''
</P>
<P>
   The same quote, he said, could apply to him now, as he moves on:
``There is at bottom only one problem in the world and this is its
name. How does one break through? How does one get into the open?
How does one burst the cocoon and become a butterfly?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
