<HEADER>
A8694 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT &LR;      06-14 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   As an 80th birthday celebration, Jan Tofty, a Chicago friend,
took her mother to New York City for the first time, dazzling her
with sights and sounds from Fifth Avenue to the Battery.
</P>
<P>
   Mom, who lived all her life in northern Minnesota, gaped and
gasped in wonder at every turn, commenting on the staggering
difference between New York and home. But there was one thing that
apparently was familiar.
</P>
<P>
   At the corner of Madison Avenue and 57th Street, she said in
amazement, ``Oh, look, they even have hitchhikers in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter followed her pointing finger. There, arm raised,
was a woman hailing a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   _JOSEPHINE BASKIN MINOW
</P>
<P>
   After arriving at Kennedy International Airport on a red-eye
flight from the West Coast one morning, a co-worker of Jack Lucid
decided to go home, shower and see his 6-year-old son before
heading into the office. Soon after the man arrived home, his son
asked, ``Did you run to catch your taxi?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I did,'' his father said.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy wasn't finished: ``Were you late getting to the
airport? Did you just catch your flight?''
</P>
<P>
   His father was becoming increasingly puzzled by the questions,
but he acknowledged that he had just made the plane. How did his
son know about his timing on the Coast _ the late arrival at the
airport and squeaking onto the plane minutes before departure?
</P>
<P>
   No mystery there to a sharp kid. ``Because if you hadn't been
late for the taxi and the flight, I'd be playing with the new toy
you would have bought me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been many years since Ira Barrows lived in New York, but
according to his wife, Carol, he hasn't lost the attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The couple were recently in Manhattan waiting at the taxi stand
at Pennsylvania Station when they noticed another couple sneaking
to the front of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, but there's a line and it goes back there,''
Barrows said firmly. The couple grumbled and gestured but moved to
the end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a cab pulled up and the couple bolted the
line, threw their bags into the trunk left open by the passengers
just discharged, and started getting in. There was murmured
grumbling but no action. Barrows informed the driver that the
couple hadn't been first in line. The driver shrugged and prepared
to take off.
</P>
<P>
   Barrows' dander was up. He rallied the line to a concerted
protest. The driver gave in. He pulled the bags out of the trunk
and banished the couple from his cab.
</P>
<P>
   What Mrs. Barrows may not know is that although her husband
hasn't lost the New York attitude, the couple who cut ahead of the
line were undoubtedly the real thing _ true New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of real New Yorkers, there's Elaine Britvan's
2{-year-old grandson, Dylan, who was in a sneaker store with his
mother and grandmother. He wanted to go outside and play, and his
grandmother, to divert him, began counting ``1-2-3-4-5.'' He
carried on: ``6-7-8-9-10-11-12-Penthouse,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   It was a balmy evening and Clare Garfield was walking down
Lexington Avenue, carrying on an animated conversation with her
cousin about her love life. ``He's been back for four days and he
still hasn't called me,'' Ms. Garfield said. ``I don't know what to
think.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who had just walked by the two turned around. ``I'll tell
you what to think,'' he said. ``Next!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garfield took the advice and went on to a ``next.''
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER TIME
</P>
<P>
   I'm wasting nights
</P>
<P>
   In a whole new mode
</P>
<P>
   As up I sit
</P>
<P>
   As down I load.
</P>
<P>
   _JAY SULLIVAN
</P>
<P>
   Jean Cottam and Gregory Allen were having a quick bite at the
Carlyle Hotel before an appearance there by Bobby Short, when they
overheard an obviously exasperated waiter talking to himself.
``Viagra, that's all they talk about,'' he muttered. ``That's all I
hear, Viagra, Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I was walking home one evening along Third Avenue when I fell
into place behind two young men dressed in business suits. They
were talking about bad relationships, and each man was trying to
top the other's story. At the corner of 51st Street, they stopped
for the light, and one turned to the other and said, ``Look, you
don't know desperation like I've known desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   _PATRICIA RODENBURG
</P>
<P>
   A vendor selling sunglasses didn't take part in the street fair
on 52nd Street last month, but he had his marketing down pat.
``Sunglasses $6,'' he intoned, ``cheaper than you could get them at
the fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Too cheap? ``If you need self-esteem, $12,'' he offered.
</P>
<P>
   Arline Sciortino thought that both prices sounded like bargains,
but she already had sunglasses and, she said, her self-esteem was
pretty good that day.
</P>
<P>
   A school eye test revealed that Dr. Herbert Abramowitz's
granddaughter, Hannah, a second-grader, might need glasses. The
news didn't bother her in the least. She wanted glasses because her
classmates who wore them apparently got a lot of attention.
</P>
<P>
   She was taken for an eye examination, read the chart in the
doctor's office and was told that her eyesight was fine. Obviously
dissatisfied with the diagnosis, she turned to the doctor. ``How
many do you need to get wrong to get glasses?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's possible to exit the subway grinning. Stephan T. Mayo
didn't pay too much attention to the familiar ``Let 'em out _ step
lively! _ use all available doors,'' until the man next to him made
his own announcement. In a barely audible voice, he advised: ``And
don't use the unavailable doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Annette Horstman received a telephone call from the receptionist
in her chiropractor's office after her husband had made his first
visit there. The young woman wanted to know, for insurance
purposes, his date of birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``October sixth, 1914,'' Mrs. Horstman replied.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pause and the receptionist repeated, ``I need the
date of birth.'' Mrs. Horstman recited the information again.
Another pause. ``I need to know the exact date,'' the receptionist
said.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Mrs. Horstman was wondering if they were speaking the
same language. ``October, sixth day, year 1914,'' she enunciated
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   There was a sigh of exasperation at the other end. ``Look,'' the
receptionist carefully explained, ``my date is 3/20/80.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
