<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL GRANTS TO COLLEGES ARE RESURGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Maine, Va.)  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year the University of West Alabama will receive a grant of
$300,000 from the Department of Agriculture for research on the
disposal of poultry carcasses. The University of Maine will receive
$220,000, also from the Department of Agriculture, for research on
low-bush blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   These grants are among more than 200 federal outlays set aside
by Congress for specific colleges and universities without benefit
of competitive or merit review. Although the grants may or may not
meet genuine public needs, they are widely derided as pork-barrel
boondoggles.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Congress authorized $495 million for academic
earmarking for fiscal 1998, according to the 10th annual study of
the practice by The Chronicle of Higher Education, an independent
national newspaper. President Clinton, making limited use of the
line-item veto, reduced the appropriation to $483 million. The June
19 issue of The Chronicle, which reports on the study, will be on
newsstands beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   After appropriations dipped to $296 million in 1996 as
Republican legislators slashed earmarks as prime examples of
wasteful spending, the practice is on the rise again, according to
The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The peak, according to The Chronicle, came in 1993, when the
value of earmarks was placed at $763 million. Over the last decade,
nearly $5 billion has been spent on such projects.
</P>
<P>
   University leaders whose institutions benefit from earmarking
were muted in their criticism. Cornelius Pings, president of the
Association of American Universities, which has traditionally
opposed earmarking, said the increase was ``a bit troubling, but
not alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All colleges and universities together receive somewhere
between $15 billion and $16 billion from the federal government,''
Pings said. ``Earmarking accounts for only 3 percent of that
total.'' The other 97 percent, he explained, is for competitively
reviewed projects.
</P>
<P>
   James Savage, an associate professor of government at the
University of Virginia and the author of a book called ``Funding
Science in America: Congress, Universities and the Politics of the
Academic Pork Barrel,'' to be published next year by the Cambridge
University Press, said that the reason for the increase in
earmarking was that Congress has more money available because of
the booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they have, the more they get to earmark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Savage said the solution to the problem lay in electing
lawmakers who would fight the practice.
</P>
<P>
   But academicians must also be held responsible, Savage said.
``Peer review is the norm in academic life,'' he said. ``We have it
in tenure, promotion, allocation of resources and publication.
There is no such norm in politics, where the object is to get
elected and then help your friends. The leaders of higher education
must educate the politicians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
