<SLUG> BC-CALIF-CIGARETTES-512&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA WARNS: SMOKING IS HAZARDOUS TO YOUR SEX LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At a gala event, men in bow ties and women in
evening gowns eye one another across an elegant hall. The most
debonair young man gracefully lifts a cigarette to his lips. As
soon as it is lighted, it goes limp.
</P>
<P>
   The camera pans to take in a group of women laughing, and a
voiceover says: ``Now that medical researchers believe cigarettes
are a leading cause of impotence, you're going to be looking at
smoking a little differently.'' The tag line flashes on the screen:
``Cigarettes. Still think they're sexy?''
</P>
<P>
   This new advertisement, which began airing on television
stations throughout California last week, was developed in January,
long before the impotence drug Viagra made a splash in the national
media. The advent of the drug, however, is expected to turn this
advertising spot into the most topical of the state's new dispatch
of striking, savvy commercials and billboards designed to curtail
smoking. It is accompanied by a print advertisement depicting an
attractive man with a limp cigarette hanging from his lips.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the latest assault in California's blitz on
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In January, smoking was banned in bars and clubs throughout the
state, and individual cities are cracking down on smoking in public
places. Santa Cruz recently prohibited smoking in public bus and
movie lines, and Palo Alto curtailed smoking in ticket lines and
within 20 feet of building entrances. On June 4, San Francisco
moved to prohibit smoking in some public parks, following the lead
of Davis, where smoking is banned in public gardens and near
children's play areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some Californians think the latest measures are extreme. But the
state's decadelong assault on smoking may be working: Although 25
percent of all American adults are smokers, only 18 percent of
adult Californians smoke, and the state now has the second-lowest
adult smoking rate in the nation, after Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Through years of marketing studies, the state Department of
Health has learned that to some people, a flaccid cigarette is a
more horrifying image than a blackened lung. Kim Belshe, director
of the California Department of Health Services, which developed
the campaign, hopes it will be effective in reaching men between
the ages of 18 and 30, a group that has been particularly
intractable when it comes to changing smoking habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience has demonstrated that warning these guys that
smoking will affect their health later in life has not been a very
effective inducement to quit,'' Ms. Belshe said. ``Maybe warning
them about the effects on their sex lives will be more powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Research showing the link between impotence and smoking is not
new. In 1994, The American Journal of Epidemiology published a
study of 4,462 Vietnam veterans between the ages of 31 and 49 that
found smokers 50 percent more likely to be impotent than
nonsmokers. That same year, results of the Massachusetts Male Aging
Study, reported in The Journal of Urology, indicated that smoking
could worsen existing cardiovascular problems that lead to
impotence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Financing for the new California campaign comes from a 25-cent
tax on each pack of cigarettes, mandated by state voters in 1988
through a ballot initiative known as Proposition 99. Since the
initiative took effect, Ms. Belshe said, the state has spent about
$1 billion to counter the effects of tobacco advertising, more than
the combined anti-smoking expenditures of all other states in the
nation. In the past 10 years, according to the state health
department, California has seen a 30 percent drop in smoking among
adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could wave my magic wand and make sure that every state
was required to use an ad campaign just like California's, you
would have such a marked decline in tobacco use it would make your
head spin,'' said Ahron Leichtman, executive director of Citizens
for a Tobacco-Free Society, a nonprofit advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Others are less satisfied with California's performance. ``Their
anti-industry ads are about as strong as the cigarette dangling out
of the mouth of the person in the impotence ad,'' said Stanton
Glantz, a professor of medicine at the University of California at
San Francisco. He said that in the past few years the state had
been unwilling to go after the tobacco industry directly in its
advertising campaign, and as a result the rapid decline in
cigarette consumption experienced in the early 1990s has flattened
out.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Ms. Belshe said. ``Exposing the industry is absolutely
the center of our campaign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
