</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ENVIRON-ART-845(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODMAN, DON'T SPARE THAT TREE! 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDTON, South Africa _ ``What tree is that?'' calls Diane
Sheard, environmental education officer at the Reitfontein Nature
Reserve in the leafy Johannesburg suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue gum!'' her fourth-through-sixth-graders shout back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is it from?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we like it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No!''
</P>
<P>
   The Redhill Enviro Club is out for its Friday afternoon outing,
doing what so many budding environmentalists do here _ ripping up
plants. They won't chop down this eucalyptus tree today, because
it's 6 feet around. But they will don their mothers' gardening
gloves and tear up a lovely swath of flowering lantana.
</P>
<P>
   About 750 miles to the south, Rayno Frans is being dropped off
by helicopter for a week in the Riviersonderenberge Mountains east
of Cape Town. Frans, 27, is in an elite unit of the Ministry of
Water and Forestry Affairs. Bivouacking in the wild, he and nine
other environmental commandos work the peaks with axes and chain
saws, rappelling down sheer cliffs to stalk their prey. Their name:
The Alien Hit Squad. Their mission: kill pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   There's something different about environmentalism in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   While American and European children get ``green'' environmental
educations that turn them into tree-huggers who believe every
sapling is special, South Africans get a different perspective on
nature. The environment here is under threat not so much from the
smokestacks and parking lots of heavily industrialized countries,
but from ``exotics'' _ aliens from afar bent on stealing the
nation's water and driving out its native vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing irrational in this fear. The assault from
America, Europe and Australia is very real. Because Africa's animal
life _ from lions to crocodiles to malarial mosquitoes _ appears so
ferocious, many foreigners assume the whole environment is rugged.
In fact, the African landscape is quite fragile.
</P>
<P>
   The stunted thorn trees of the savannas, adapted to drought,
cannot compete with foreign giants like eucalyptuses and willows
with their deep taproots. Nor can they live beneath the pines that,
freed from the annual slowdown of snowy European and American
winters, grow wildly and blot out the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have invader problems in Australia and California,'' said
Cobus Meiring, a spokesman for the Ministry of Water Affairs and
Forestry. ``But nothing on this scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly fragile is the Cape Town area. There are more
species of fynbos on the tiny Cape Peninsula than in all the
British Isles. Fynbos is a sort of multihued gorse _ a short,
tough-leafed plant that thrives on summer fog. But along nearly all
the Cape's streams, it has been destroyed, pushed out by black
wattles, Port Jackson trees and Australian myrtle.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if choking off the native growth weren't bad enough, the
aliens suck up Africa's most precious resource: water. In some
watersheds, creek flow has been reduced by up to 60 percent, said
Christo Marais, a fynbos expert for Cape Nature Conservation, a
government environmental agency.
</P>
<P>
   Fynbos uses little water. But big aliens can absorb and
``sweat'' up to 500 quarts a day into the air. That dries up the
water tables that humans rely on for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   If a satellite photo could name species, it would show that most
of South Africa is covered with alien vegetation, virtually all of
it deliberately introduced. The vast corn and wheat crops north of
the Orange River are foreign imports, as are the wide lawns of the
suburbs, the purple jacarandas decorating Pretoria and the millions
upon millions of pines planted by timber and paper companies on the
south coast and in the Drakensberg Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry is careful to say that those aliens are OK _ they
provide food and jobs. It's only when they get out of control that
they are a problem. But plants get out of control so easily here.
</P>
<P>
   Even the national parks and the vast Karoo semidesert have areas
overrun by Mexican prickly pear. Ms. Sheard even has it on the roof
of her nature center here in Sandton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible, terrible plant,'' she said. ``We had it on
the grounds, so we chopped it up and threw it on the roof _ and new
buds shot up out of the dead pieces. Now we have to inject it with
poisons.''
</P>
<P>
   To clear watershed areas of aliens, the Ministry of Water
Affairs and Forestry has created South Africa's biggest public
works program. Only 2 years old, it already employs 40,000 people,
all from the poorest communities, to clear trees and brush for
about $6 a day.
</P>
<P>
   The best try out for the Alien Hit Squads. There, they can earn
$14 or more _ but pride is also part of the pay package.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guys put on their ropes and climbing gear and walk around
the townships like they're Indiana Jones,'' said Stephen Lamb, who
runs the squads. Along with mountaineering skills, they also get
lessons in running small businesses. The aim of the program is to
turn them into independent contractors, able to not only clear
vegetation, but build mountain trails, lead tourist hikes and so
forth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The hit squads have to kill all the pines along the crests of
the mountains, Lamb said, or they will reseed the valleys below and
undo all the work of the bigger teams.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how logical the need to fight the foreign hordes is,
there is no doubt that couching eco-enlightenment as a battle cry
somehow appeals to the South African psyche. Anti-immigrant
feelings related to humans are already strong here, and South
Africans come to revile immigrant plants easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alien plants are thirsty enemies,'' explains a comic book for
schoolchildren. ``Give aliens the chop!'' commands a botanical
garden poster showing how to identify and kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Not only plants are targeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you find one of these guys in a stream here,'' a guide at a
reptile park told his audience recently as he displayed a North
American painted turtle, ``you have my permission to take a rock
and bash in its skull. I'm a conservationist, but I'm a
conservationist of African species. This is an alien.''
</P>
<P>
   In upmarket suburbs like Sandton, xenophobia takes on a more
gracious air. There are ``indigenous only'' nurseries. At
Christmastime, they refuse to sell cedars or firs, saying their
silly customers have been brainwashed to think Tannenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your perception of a Christmas tree is programmed,'' said
Andrea Hepplewhite, an owner of Witkoppen Wildflowers here. ``I've
used a 6-foot baobab tree.'' And of course, indigenous trees are
better at attracting indigenous birds.
</P>
<P>
   Even more bizarrely, South Africans boast of finding uses for
alien corpses. A grocery advertises ``barbecue charcoal made from
invader blackthorn.'' Curio shops sell stationery made from Port
Jackson trees chopped down by the ministry's teams. And in the Cape
Town aquarium's ``World of Water'' exhibit is a picture of Kader
Asmal, the Minister of Water Affairs and Forestry himself, posing
on a fanciful bentwood bench. Its builders flank him, brandishing a
saw and an ax. The caption says it is ``made from alien wattle.''
</P>
<P>
   When South Africans are asked why they are so bloodthirsty about
aliens, they seem mystified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought every country had invasives they were trying to get
rid of,'' Ms. Sheard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it vents a little aggression,'' said Lamb. ``That
gung-ho thing _ give them the chop _ is kind of a marketing
strategy too.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's what it is, it works.
</P>
<P>
   Did Alyssa Rawnsley, 9, enjoy her afternoon at the nature
reserve killing aliens?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes,'' she said. ``It's like ``Independence Day'' _ only
with plants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
