<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EMOTIONAL MAJOR LEAGUE DEBUT FOR LEDEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One nice thing about a season in which the Yankees
have all but taken care of the big picture before mid-June is that
their runaway success allows time for the little portraits that put
a human face on what is otherwise a relentless machine.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case Sunday when the Yankees, en route to their
major league-best 47th victory in 61 games, enjoyed yet another of
those poignant touches that have helped differentiate the teams of
the 1990s in the Bronx from all the previous ``Damn Yankees''
successes most everyone loved to hate.
</P>
<P>
   This particular nice touch was painted by Ricky Ledee, a
24-year-old who seemingly spent a lifetime in the minor leagues
after signing with the Yankees at age 16. After being called up
from Class AAA Columbus last week, he made his major league debut
Sunday in the Yankees' 4-2 victory over the Cleveland Indians at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It took a lot of injuries to make the debut possible. Then it
took two torturous rainouts to make the reward at the end of a
nerve-racking weekend that much more palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they might send me back,'' Ledee said. But it was
real. Ledee played a major league game. And when it happened, the
players in a franchise more associated with Hall of Fame
accomplishments and World Series moments paused in appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You root for anyone who is called up to do well,'' said Derek
Jeter, whose major league debut seemingly came eons ago _ in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was special for me, personally, because I played with
Ricky in the minors in 1992. We've played together for a while.
He's a quality person, so I am pulling for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's tale wasn't necessarily as gripping as the drama being
provided by Orlando (El Duque) Hernandez, the pitcher who
kick-started his American dream by engineering a high-seas escape
from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee's story will probably never attract the attention of
Hollywood as did the saga of Joe Torre managing in his first
postseason against the backdrop of the search for a new heart for
his brother Frank.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't even provide the sort of comic relief that usually
accompanies any David Cone or David Wells saga.
</P>
<P>
   But Ledee, waiting all these years, will take it. For posterity,
for the fulfillment of a dream little boys still dare to wish come
true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know why everybody wants to be a Yankee,'' said Ledee,
who wonderfully wears his emotions on his sleeve and doesn't care
if his eyes brim over.
</P>
<P>
   Mention the opportunity, created when Bernie Williams was
disabled because of a sprained knee last week, and Ledee chokes up.
Speak of Ledee's father, Antonio, who encouraged him to play only
to die four years before Ledee signed, and the outfielder can
barely find enough words to show how much his father was a part of
this debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted me to be a professional ballplayer,'' Ledee said.
</P>
<P>
   How many minutes of the 2-hour-48-minute game did he remember
that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time, every time,'' Ledee said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Ledee was awash with emotion as well as the cheers of 25
family members from New York, New Jersey and his native Puerto Rico
in a game in which he went 1 for 3.
</P>
<P>
   He took care of some admitted nerves by getting the first major
league hit out of the way quickly, sending the first pitch he saw
from Cleveland's starter, Jaret Wright, into right field for a
single in the second inning. Ledee also walked, in the fourth. He
patrolled his left-field position well, making his first major
league catch special by grabbing a ball hit to the warning track by
Mark Whiten in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked comfortable out there,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee avoided being the next Matt Luke, the outfielder who was
called up by the Yankees last year, then was snowed out of his only
starting assignment, never to get a chance again.
</P>
<P>
   Now only time will tell whether he will be the next Andy Fox or,
even better, the next El Duque.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was the infielder who was asked to join the Yankees for a
cup of coffee in 1996 only to stay for most of that championship
season. All Hernandez has done is make two starts so impressive
that he dislodged Ramiro Mendoza from the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to project too much because there are obvious
things that are going to happen,'' Torre said. ``Bernie's going to
come back. Chili Davis is going to come back. But sure, you want to
have someone do well, to make themselves necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee now has a chance to do just that. His first game gives him
if not a long-term right, then at least an opportunity to try.
</P>
<P>
   Luke was watching his former teammate take that first step as a
Yankee that he was denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you anticipate your whole life,'' said Luke,
now a reserve with Cleveland. ``You think about it every day in the
minor leagues. When it's postponed like that, it can be a little
bit of a letdown. But to know you're eventually going to get it is
rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee knew because, Luke said, ``Ricky's a quality player, he's
a hard worker and there are only good things to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
