<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, June 15.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-TRIBUNAL (Rome) _ In one of the most ambitious efforts ever
undertaken to extend the rule of international law, the United
Nations will open a conference here Monday to thrash out rules for
an international court to prosecute crimes against humanity. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-SWEATSHOPS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Just as pressure is
growing in the West against the use of ``sweat shops'' in
developing countries, the Asian financial crisis is spawning such
desperation that more people than ever seem willing to accept grim
or dangerous jobs in such factories. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-EXORCIST (Paris) _ Foreign Journal: on the exorcist of
Notre Dame. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-NUKE (United Nations) _ The man who is expected to become
India's next foreign minister says that the end of the Cold War has
left a power vacuum from central Asia to Africa that his government
cannot ignore. It was this change in the global security
environment, he said, that ultimately triggered India's decision to
test nuclear weapons. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NORTHEAST-BILINGUAL (New York) _ As California moves to
dismantle bilingual education, some states in the Northeast are
embracing it and expanding it, and placing a greater emphasis than
before on learning English.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-WATERWAR (Keeler, Calif.) _ The dry bed of Owens Lake is
all that is left of a once-fertile farming and mining community.
There is not the slightest mystery about where the water went: For
85 years, gravity has pulled it through a 223-mile man-made
aqueduct to sustain the artificially verdant sprawl of Los Angeles.
But for the first time in the history of the longest-running water
war in the West, the Owens Valley may be on the verge of forcing
Los Angeles to put some of the water back. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-COMPUTE (Ossining, N.Y.) _ Their hands are knobby with
arthritis and their eyes milky with age. The jargon of computing
might as well be Sanskrit. Yet older Americans are clamoring for
computer instruction all across America. When classes fill as
quickly as they are posted, spillover sections are scheduled, but
the waiting lists keep growing. By Jane Gross.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-VOUCHERS (Milwaukee, Wis.) _ When the Wisconsin Supreme
Court ruled on Wednesday that taxpayer money could be used to send
Milwaukee students to religious schools, the decision sent currents
of excitement through some parts of this city, and sounded alarms
in others. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE-FLINT (Flint, Mich.) _ The people of Flint are tired
of both sides in the current strike against a GM parts plant here.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE _ At a Republican fund-raiser scheduled for
Tuesday night, Washington's convention center will be packed with
an assortment of donors. This feast of money comes as the House
debates legislation to overhaul the way political campaigns are
financed, and some of the proposals would substantially slow the
money chase in Washington. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-TAXCUTTERS _ It's been a tough year for Republican tax
cutters. Clinton effectively put the budget surplus off limits by
claiming it for Social Security. Efforts to pay for a tax cut by
slashing spending have run into a wall of political opposition.
Other potential sources, like the money generated by the proposed
anti-smoking bill, aren't yet certain. So it was perhaps not
surprising when Gingrich and his lieutenants lashed out in
frustration last week at the Congressional Budget Office, whose
estimates of the nation's fiscal condition over the past few years
have proven consistently too pessimistic. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT-SANCTIONS _ Under pressure from farmers, Congress is
poised to skirt the nation's sanctions on India and Pakistan by
allowing the sale of wheat to those countries. This would seem to
undermine the administration's moral outrage against India and
Pakistan. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-SACHS (New York) _ Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., Wall Street's
last big private investment bank and by many measures its most
successful, plans to announce on Monday that it will end its
130-year partnership and become a public company, according to
people close to the firm. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-MONOPOLY (Undated) _ The government's antitrust battle
against Microsoft Corp. has not tarnished the company's reputation
as an outstanding business that makes high-quality products, but
according to the latest New York Times/CBS News poll, a majority of
Americans do think that Microsoft is a monopoly and that the
Justice Department should continue to investigate its business
practices. By Steve Lohr with Marjorie Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   CNET-MINOR-MEDIA (Undated) _ A profile of CNet and its founder,
Halsey Minor, in the wake of the company's deal with NBC. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   EVANS-PUBLISH-MEDIA (Undated) _ Not long ago, Harry Evans lived
in the public eye. As president and publisher of Random House's
trade group, he came to symbolize the new era of glitz in
publishing. He is much less visible in his new job _ editorial
director and vice chairman of The Daily News of New York, U.S. News
&AMP; World Report, The Atlantic Monthly and Fast Company, a business
magazine. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COMPUTE (Washington) _ Nearly one year after President
Clinton announced a list of ambitious goals to foster the
commercial growth of the Internet, critics say that the
administration's contradictory policies on data encryption and its
slow progress on privacy controls have left the United States'
nascent electronic-commerce industry adrift on a rudderless ship.
By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ One of the most reliable human
characteristics is aversion to change. And when it comes to
embracing technology, it is a characteristic that even today's
newest celebrity class, business executives, seems to possess in
abundance. By Denise Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The proliferation of
prescription-drug pitches aimed directly at consumers has become
one of the hottest topics in advertising. So it was not unexpected
that a seminar on the subject, attended by more than 200 agency and
pharmaceutical-industry executives, should generate its share of
Zoloft zingers, the Rx equivalents of Maalox moments. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   LOTUS-SMARTSUITE (New York) _ This week, Lotus Development Corp.
will begin shipping Smart Suite Millennium Edition, which includes
the latest version of the 1-2-3 spreadsheet program. But does
anyone care? Battered by the relentless onslaught of the Microsoft
Corp., Lotus has seen its market share in desktop software dwindle
so low that many analysts no longer bother to track it.
</P>
<P>
   WASHPOST-MEDIA (Undated) _ A profile of Steve Coll, the new
managing editor of The Washington Post, who wants to take The Post
in new directions. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ It seems that Spanish-language
stations are increasingly using English.
</P>
