<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-NYT &LR;      06-14 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN STEALS THE SHOW AS BULLS WIN SIXTH TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Utah)  (lb) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Eight years ago, a sky-walking shooting guard
emerged from the shadows of Larry Bird and Magic Johnson, grabbed
the torch and gracefully elevated toward the rim. A new order had
come to what was becoming America's game.
</P>
<P>
   Six championships later, Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls
refuse to come down.
</P>
<P>
   They became champions of the National Basketball Association for
the first time that night against the Los Angeles Lakers, and they
were champions again Sunday night. Overcoming the resilient Utah
Jazz in the league's loudest arena, the Bulls took Game 6 of the
National Basketball Association finals, 87-86, and won the series,
four games to two.
</P>
<P>
   It gave them their sixth title in eight seasons and left the
rest of the league admiring a glowing dynasty, one that gets better
with age.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bulls trailing, 86-85, Jordan stripped Utah's Karl
Malone of the ball and hit a jumper at the other end of the court
with 5.2 seconds left for the last of his 45 points. The next
highest scorer for the Bulls was Toni Kukoc, with 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to clinch at home in Game 5 on Friday, Jordan and this
current crop of Bulls seized the momentum less than 48 hours after
they lost it at the United Center. In Game 6, they came back
against a team many believed had Chicago's number entering the
league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   And they did it without the full services of Scottie Pippen, who
left the game with 4 minutes 56 seconds left in the first quarter
because of back spasms. Pippen, who received treatment and returned
to start the second half, had received a cortisone shot on Saturday
and went through pregame warm-ups Sunday night looking unsure of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   So Jordan had to be special if not spectacular. His 45 points
came on 15-of-35 shooting, but he was a crucial 12 of 15 from the
free-throw line. Pippen and Ron Harper added 8 points each.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was brilliant in defeat, with 31 points, 11 rebounds and
7 assists. Jeff Hornacek added 17 points for Utah, but John
Stockton was held to just 10 points and 5 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls won their third straight championship for the second
time in the decade. Their two-year gap in 1994 and 1995 came during
Jordan's year-and-a-half experiment with minor-league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   At age 35, Jordan looked as strong and agile as he did the night
in 1991 when he performed a wondrous act of in-air artistry that
has become an indelible image of the NBA finals, rising for a dunk
with his right hand before switching to his left for a layup at the
last possible moment.
</P>
<P>
   He started slowly Sunday night, but eventually took over the
proceedings with his flair and fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls bounded out to a 17-8 lead with Pippen in the game,
using a 9-0 run to quiet the Jazz's wild mob at home. But the Jazz
fought back with an 11-1 run of its own, and led by 49-45 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls overcame all kinds of adversity. Beyond a hostile
crowd and Pippen's injury, Harper overcame a stomach ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Harper missed the morning shoot-around because he said he had
eaten some unsatisfactory room-service food from the team hotel. As
usual, it meant Jordan would have to carry the franchise again.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz led, 70-67, with 8:36 left to play in the game when
Jordan checked back into the game. He had had barely three minutes
of rest, including a timeout. If the Bulls were going to end it,
someone else was going to have to help.
</P>
<P>
   Kukoc quickly came through, dropping in a long 3-pointer from
the left wing to tie the score. At that juncture, it seemed smart
to get Kukoc in the flow.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he had erupted for 30 points in Game 5 and nearly
helped pull out a victory. But Jordan put his head down.
</P>
<P>
   He might have needed his teammates, but he did not care. He
drove the lane. He shot jumpers. If there was a loss, it would be
on him.
</P>
<P>
   Utah entered the fourth period with a surge of adrenaline after
Howard Eisley finally reappeared in the series. The reserve point
guard, who had played so badly behind Stockton, found Antoine Carr
under the basket for a dunk and Adam Keefe for a layup in the
closing seconds of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Those baskets enabled the Jazz to take a 66-61 lead into the
last 12 minutes of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If Pippen's injury was a bad omen, Jordan's receiving no rest in
the third period was particularly disconcerting. Twice he missed
the front end of free-throw opportunities, and he was being
hammered by the Jazz as he took flight toward the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the fourth quarter, he had played 34 of 36 minutes.
He nearly expended himself in the first half. At the least, his
right arm must have been sore from shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In the best sequence of the series, Malone and Jordan went back
and forth near the end of the second quarter. They were trading
improbable shots on both ends, from every angle available.
</P>
<P>
   A Jordan 3-pointer would be followed by a Malone fallaway on the
baseline. When they were double-covered, they found open teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Malone made 8 of 11 field goals in the first half and continued
his dominance in the third quarter. Luc Longley could not stop him.
Dennis Rodman tried, but ended up doing more theatrical flailing
and bumping than actually defending.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan took 19 shots in the first half. And while nine of them
fell, some were ill advised and forced. It was almost as if he were
worried about Kukoc becoming the go-to guy. The usually serene
Croatian pouted as he walked off the floor at halftime, having
watched Jordan throw up a 3-pointer and a halfcourt shot that both
missed seconds earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had a chance to create space in the third quarter. Utah
was up by 5 points and appeared ready to go on a run, but poor
execution gave the Bulls a chance to hang around until the end.
</P>
<P>
   This was not how Chicago envisioned things, with Pippen barely
able to bend over and Jordan chucking up everything as if this were
1989 and he had no help. Pippen, in fact, boasted after Game 2 in
Salt Lake City that the Bulls would not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get ready for the WNBA season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had to come back after all, but they didn't have to
stay long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
