<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-NYT &LR;      06-14 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN PREVAILS EVEN WITH PIPPEN IN PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The limping Scottie Pippen worked his way
through the pack surrounding a fatigued but elated Michael Jordan,
and embraced him with the most ginger of hugs when it was over.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it was a most powerful moment for a duo that
may never be together again if the Bulls dismantle. A second later,
Pippen, who played the game with severe back pain, was in tears due
to his emotions as the Bulls celebrated their sixth title in eight
years after Jordan put together a miracle performance that included
45 points. He led the Bulls in winning Game 6 of the National
Basketball Association finals, eliminating the Jazz, 87-86, Sunday
night at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been Jordan's greatest feat. He had to pull this off
as Pippen played on with his face pinched in pain due to a sore
back that left him limited at best, and absent for much of Game 6.
As much as he means to the Bulls, his problems spread like a drop
of ink in a pool of water during Game 6. Pippen's restricted
effectiveness touched every part of the Bulls' strategy, from the
team's rebounding to its defense, from the offense to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Without Pippen, Jordan was left to fight the fatigue of this
long series and long playoff run. Somehow, he managed to make up
the void left by Pippen. Somehow, Jordan managed to strip Karl
Malone with 10 seconds left, then come down to hit the game-winning
shot with 5.2 seconds to give the Bulls the title. Pippen had a
cortisone shot on Saturday, and felt some relief from the pain in
his back that crept up on him after taking five charges in Game 3.
The discomfort may have had something to do with a 2-of-16
performance in Game 4, an effort that belied a series effort that
had many proclaiming him the most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Now the player who had been a defensive menace to the Jazz
walked off the floor and disappeared into the tunnel leading to the
locker room with 4 minutes 56 seconds left in the first quarter.
All of the electric-stimulation he had before the game to loosen up
his back had not helped.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen underwent further treatment through the first half. He
returned to start the second half with a wince, only to leave
again. He came back with 9 minutes left in the game. Although he
was severely limited, Pippen's presence meant something. At least
he could function as a decoy.
</P>
<P>
   During Pippen's treatments throughout the game, his absence had
a trickle-down effect on the Bulls that went beyond the extra
minutes Michael Jordan was going to have to absorb. Throughout this
series, Pippen's quickness and defensive instincts had allowed him
to roam around the court like a free safety and disrupt the Jazz's
pick-and-roll.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's rover status had the Jazz pleading for illegal
defenses. But Pippen had been crafty enough to escape the call. No
other Bull was as clever. Before the end of the first half, the
Bulls were tagged with four illegal defenses. The Jazz connected on
three free throws off the technical fouls called after the first
illegal defense warning.
</P>
<P>
   Without Pippen to help support the offense, coach Phil Jackson
was left to look at a bench of players hardly capable of creating
the kind of shots and making the kind of drives so often associated
with the fluid all-star forward. Neither Jud Buechler nor Scott
Burrell were going to be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   It was going to be up to Jordan to grab the Bulls by the collar
and keep them in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan played all but two minutes in the first half, ending it
by hitting 9 of 19 shots for 23 points to keep the Bulls within
reach of the Jazz, down by just 49-45.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Pippen returned in the third quarter, he was more of a
decoy than a playmaker. The Jazz had to respect his presence, but
Pippen was clearly not himself. That was obvious mid-way through
the third quarter when he missed a layup that normally would have
been made via an explosive dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few minutes later, Pippen left the court and went to the
training room for treatment. Once again, Jordan would have to go it
alone. Jordan has always known how important Pippen has been to his
success and to his teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Scottie Pippen is a major reason why we're here,''
Jordan said before Game 5. ``I think he's a unique and creative
player. The harmony between us is incomparable. You can't compare
it to anything. It's just a rhythm you build with another player.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play without him is like a slap in the face for me.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Jordan, wondering how he would play next year if Pippen
bolted Chicago in free agency. This was before Game 5, when it
seemed as if the duo was destined to walk out of the United Center
Friday night with their sixth title.
</P>
</TEXT>
