<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     06-14 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHRISTOPHER SHAYS' MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 15:
</P>
<P>
   When Newt Gingrich was a little-known back-bencher in the House,
he promised open and democratic procedures if the Republicans ever
won control. Last week, as this page warned, the speaker betrayed
those principles and began his filibuster-by-amendment scheme to
block campaign finance legislation. We raise the matter again today
because it is time for reform-minded House members to revive the
petition that forced Gingrich back in April to promise an honest
game.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a majority of House members to demand a vote in defiance
of the leadership is always an uphill battle. But two months ago, a
petition to force a vote on campaign reform got 204 signatures,
just a handful short of the 218 necessary. Alarmed at the signature
campaign's momentum, Gingrich abruptly retreated and promised a
vote. Accepting his word, 13 House members, most of them
Republicans, took their names off the petition as a gesture of
respect. These are the first group of members who must now put
their names back on and urge others to follow their example.
</P>
<P>
   The person to lead this effort is Rep. Christopher Shays, who
sponsored a bill to outlaw ``soft money'' along with Martin Meehan
of Massachusetts. Until now Shays, R-Conn., has urged fellow
reformers to accept Gingrich's pious promises. He took his own name
off the petition in April. But Shays has to face the fact that
Gingrich is not going to change except under pressure. This week
the speaker's agents of destruction, Dick Armey and Tom DeLay, will
try to get Republicans to approve a parliamentary rule that would
allow unlimited amendments to campaign legislation. Their strategy
on the Shays-Meehan bill was revealed by Rep.e Ray LaHood of
Illinois, who told The New Republic magazine: ``We tried squelching
it first. Now we're trying to talk it to death.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay likes to equate campaign money with free speech. He is
famous for keeping a list of campaign contributors in his front
office, sometimes showing them to visitors. But the First Amendment
was not designed as a license for influence-peddling. The
Shays-Meehan bill, which is close to commanding bipartisan majority
support, would ban the open-ended donations to party treasuries
that made the candidate limits meaningless in the last election. It
would also curb fund-raising for independent groups that run
campaign ads two months before an election. Shays is not the only
Republican from the New York region to take his name off the
petition drive in April. So did Amo Houghton of New York, Marge
Roukema of New Jersey and Nancy Johnson of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   If these Republicans join with other moderates, and indeed with
all the Republicans who have condemned special-interest money in
the last two years, the Shays-Meehan bill can succeed. In 1990, a
young dissident representative declared that Congress had become a
``broken system'' in need of change. ``It is increasingly a system
of corruption in which money politics is defeating and driving out
citizen politics,'' Gingrich said back then. He did not mean what
he said when he talked about creating an unbought Congress. Now we
will see if Shays and the others are willing to back up their
commitment to reform with action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-WINSTON-NYT &LR;      06-14 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN WINS RACE; GORDON CRIES FOUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ As Mark Martin celebrated his victory Sunday
at Michigan Speedway, Jeff Gordon stood behind his trailer in the
garage and claimed there had been a conspiracy. For the second
straight week, Gordon fell victim to a strange turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he was leading the Miller Lite 400 when a yellow caution
flag slowed the race. It allowed Martin to catch up and eventually
pass Gordon, who finished third behind Dale Jarrett. At the time of
the yellow flag, which came on the 118th of 200 laps, Gordon's
Chevrolet was ahead of Martin's Ford by about 10 seconds; a full
straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports were that debris was spotted on the backstretch.
Gordon, on the radio to his pit crew moments later, said that he
saw something thrown out of the window of Jimmy Spencer's No. 23
car _ possibly a piece of roll cage padding.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nelson, the Winston Cup director, could be heard radioing
to the NASCAR trailer that he wanted the suspicious debris
recovered. He also demanded a thorough post-race inspection of
Spencer's car, and those of Bobby Labonte and Darrell Waltrip. They
were the three cars Gordon was about to put a lap down when the
debris was spotted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some people throwing things out of the window right
before the caution came out,'' Gordon said. ``So it makes me
wonder. But whatever it was, it wasn't worth throwing a yellow
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte said he saw the debris and ran over it. ``Usually I can
tell a seven-sixteenths wrench,'' he said. ``But I couldn't tell
what that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer and Waltrip were not available for comment. Their cars,
like Labonte's, were inspected and then allowed to be hauled away.
Their trailers were the first to leave the track. It was an early
sign that nothing out of the ordinary was discovered, but Jeff
Motley, a NASCAR spokesman, said that the tape from Gordon's in-car
video camera will be looked at.
</P>
<P>
   Motley confirmed that a piece of roll-cage padding was
recovered. Mike Helton, the vice president of competition, said it
could be easily torn out of the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know where it came from,'' Motley said. ``No one has
filed a protest.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR will not decide whether to assess any penalties until the
investigation is complete, Motley said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gordon was leading late in the Pontiac Excitement 400
at Richmond International Raceway when Rusty Wallace forced him
into the concrete wall, knocking him out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's victory, his fourth of this season, put him third in
the points race, two behind second-place Gordon and 28 behind the
leader, Jeremy Mayfield, who finished fifth Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
