6-14 -- In the Indonesian capital of Jakarta, Mrs. Tratiwoon stands
in the vast garbage dump where she makes a living scavenging
through rubbish and describes her dreams for her 3-year-old son:
She wants him to grow up to work in a sweatshop. ``He's not going
to get an education,'' says Mrs. Tratiwoon, ``so I don't know
whether he can even get a job like that.'' Indeed, the Asian
financial crisis is spawning such desperation that in the slums in
Indonesia and Thailand, many workers even speak of sweatshop jobs
as their greatest aspiration. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- June 14, 1998 -- CNET-MINOR-MEDIA, 6-14
-- Halsey Minor in San Francisco at the studios of Cnet, the
computer news and Internet company he founded in 1992. Minor has
always made his aspirations clear: He's not out to save the world;
he's going to conquer it and become the first media mogul of the
Internet, the Ted Turner or Rupert Murdoch of his generation.
``Ultimately, the history of the most successful media tycoons is
filled with bet-the-ranch deals and Hail Mary passes, not by
fastidious attention to quarterly earnings,'' says Minor. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 14, 1998 -- EVANS-PUBLISH-MEDIA, 6-14 --
Harold Evans, 70, left Random House last fall, and is now working
as editorial director for his friend, Mortimer Zuckerman. His new
job -- editorial director and vice chairman of The Daily News of
New York, U.S. News &AMP; World Report, The Atlantic Monthly and Fast
Company, a business magazine. One thing Evans has clearly been
studying is the field of journalistic talent. He is in charge of
hiring and firing at the publications. ``I'm looking at candidates
for every single slot for the business,'' Evans says. ``I always
want to know who is out there and who is good.'' (Linda Rosier/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 14, 1998 -- CHEER-THEATER-REVIEW, 6-14
-- Kevin Chamberlin and Mary Beth Peil in the revival of ``As
Thousands Cheer,'' the Moss Hart and Irving Berlin revue from 1933.
Sixty-five subsequent years after opening, the comic bite in Hart's
lines and in Berlin's lyrics still clicks crisply, and the work's
portrait of the pandering ways of celebrities and the journalists
who cover them remains spot-on. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LOS ANGELES -- June 14, 1998 -- HISPANIC-MEDIA, 6-14 --
Cuban-born actress, Maria Conchita Alonso with Dan Guerrero, who
produces her show for Telemundo Group Inc. With a rising number of
the nation's Hispanic television viewers now bilingual, a handful
of programs are being broadcast that use varying degrees of both
English and Spanish. Soon ad agency representatives in New York
will get a look at Telemundo's first Sony-backed season lineup.
Sony's acquisition of Telemundo is expected to receive regulatory
approval next month. (Chris Pizzello/New York Times Photo)
</P>
