<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-FINALS-COX0615     06-14 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-FINALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 0615 &HT;    Jordan for the ages: Bulls deep-six Utah
 &HT;    By Jeff Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY, Utah _ The greatest player in the history of
basketball refused to lose Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan sneaked behind Utah's Karl Malone for a steal,
then buried a 19-footer with 5.2 seconds to play that carried the
Chicago Bulls to their second NBA three-peat, 87-86, in a frenzied
Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's driving layup set that up.
</P>
<P>
   Only seconds before John Stockton made his bid to force Game 7.
All alone beyond the 3-point line, John Stockton turned killer.
Just like the old days, Karl Malone whipped a pass out of the post
and the old point guard squared up and fired a triple with 41.9
seconds that put the Jazz up by three.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton fired another three as the game ended but this time he
failed.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to the Bulls in jeopardy, Jordan took control for
better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   He put up 35 shots from the field and made 15, 15 at the line
and made 12, all worth 45 points, barely enough to carry a load
that included a sore-backed Scottie Pippen. Setting up what might
have been his last hurrah, he missed a point blank jumper for a tie
at 1:31, went to the line at 59.2 and locked it at 83.
</P>
<P>
   Malone bulled for 31 and Jeff Hornacek backed him with 17 for
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was hurting. On Saturday, he received an injection of
cortisone in his back to relieve a condition that hampered him in
2-for-16 shooting in game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen apparently hurt his back in Game 4 when he had his best
scoring performance of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Chip Schaefer said Pippen showed 30 percent improvement
from the soreness that bothered him Saturday and he started the
game well enough. So did the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   They built a 17-8 lead on nine straight points, two of them
coming when Pippen sank a 10-foot off balance shot in the lane. He
got up slowly and left the game two minutes later during a time
out, going to the dressing room for further treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago struggled without him, committing three illegal defense
calls and a 24-second violation. The Jazz out-scored them 11-1 and
rode a seven-burst by Malone to a 25-22 lead after a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz led by six before the Bulls recovered. At 30-26 Utah,
Jordan found a good rhythm with a series of jumpers against Shandon
Anderson and Bryon Russell. He made six straight shots, scoring 15
of 19 Chicago points, while Malone responded at the other end. The
sides alternated hoops, Jordan's take including his third triple of
the game, though only fourth of the series.
</P>
<P>
   At 45-all, Jordan missed his next three, but Stockton got a
layup on a nifty pass from Malone and Bryon Russell cut to a layup
as Utah went to the break ahead 49-45, the highest scoring first
half of the series. Malone had 23 points, Jordan 20 in the first
true showdown game between the game's last two MVPs.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was back for the third quarter but ineffective and the
game bogged down, the Bulls called for four fouls in 1:20, the Jazz
unable to get a hoop after Malone's drive to open the period, the
Bulls inching back to 53-51 when Rodman pulled Malone down three
times in a transition scramble on the floor, finally called for a
foul.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls got even, but Jordan missed a layup for the lead and
his team faltered. It was his 25th shot. They went to the fourth,
Utah leading 66-61.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
