<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/14/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PASSAIC, N.J. -- June 14, 1998 -- NORTHEAST-BILINGUAL,
6-14 -- A bilingual teacher, Luis Lobelo, teaching mathematics to
ninth graders at Passaic High School in New Jersey. One day after
Californians voted last week to effectively end the instruction of
immigrant children in their native languages, education officials
in New Jersey approved new rules meant to strengthen it, including
one that would allow bilingual classes for children as young as 3.
(Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HANOVER, N.H. -- June 14, 1998 -- DARTMOUTH-PRESIDENT,
6-14 -- James Freedman, 62, shown with his wife, Sheba, has retired
after 11 years as president of Dartmouth College in Hanover. At his
final commencement this year, the board of trustees thanked him for
transforming Dartmouth into a haven for intellectuals, and making
it one of the top schools in the Ivy League. ``He's upped the
intellectual ante,'' says Susan Ackerman, a professor of religion.
``The students are brighter and brighter. He's made it OK to talk
about books and ideas.'' (Paul O. Boisvert/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) KEELER, Calif. -- June 14, 1998 -- CALIF-WATERWAR-2,
6-14 -- Mark McCall's back yard abuts the dry bed of Owens Lake, a
crusty lunar landscape of brackish pools and flaky salts and toxins
that is the worst source of airborne pollution in the United
States. ``It's not that you can't breathe,'' he says. ``You just
don't want to.'' The land was at the center of a fertile farming
and mining community before water was siphoned off. In fact, the
rough grass that fills McCall's yard is so sharp, he says, ``that
you can't walk barefoot; it's like razor wire.'' (Ed Carreon/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) KEELER, Calif. -- June 14, 1998 -- CALIF-WATERWAR-1, 6-14
-- The dry bed of Owens Lake, a crusty lunar landscape of brackish
pools and flaky salts and toxins that is the worst source of
airborne pollution in the United States, stretches between the
Sierra Nevada and tiny Keeler, at the center of the picture. The
land was at the center of a fertile farming and mining community
before water was siphoned off. (Ed Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) OSSINING, N.Y. -- June 14, 1998 -- ELDERLY-COMPUTE, 6-14
-- At community centers, colleges and libraries across America,
Americans old enough to be the typical hacker's grandparents are
clamoring for computer instruction. Alyane Simpson, 74, at the
Ossining senior center, in a computer lab, owns a powerful 300
megahertz machine by Hewlett-Packard. ``My feeling is, the
technology is becoming more and more important,'' says Mrs.
Simpson. ``If that's the case, how can you be out of the loop?''
(Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MILWAUKEE -- June 14, 1998 -- EDUC-VOUCHERS, 6-14 --
Vivian Watts, who serves food in a public school cafeteria, pulled
her sons out of public school three years ago because Marquess, now
11, was suspended several times for discipline problems and Remy,
now 12, had very low grades. Her sons are now in a Roman Catholic
school with the help of The Milwaukee Parental Choice Program,
which began in 1990 as the nation's first voucher program. The
program allows poor families to send their children to the school
of their choice, public or private, at state expense. (Morry
Gash/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) GRESIK, Indonesia -- June 14, 1998 -- ASIA-SWEATSHOPS-2,
6-14 -- ``These are tough times. It's hard for anyone to make money
in Indonesia,'' says Mrs. Hanifa, 48, left, who runs a dress
factory in Gresik, where workers can earn roughly 35 cents a day
making red plaid dresses for little girls. ``And I'm paying good
wages, at least for around here,'' she says. Just as pressure is
growing in the West against the use of sweatshops in developing
countries, the Asian financial crisis is spawning such desperation
that more people than ever seem willing to take grim or dangerous
jobs in such factories. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) JAKARTA, Indonesia -- June 14, 1998 -- ASIA-SWEATSHOPS,
