<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: U.S. OPEN REVISITS GRAVEYARD OF LEGENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its towering cypress and pine trees, its view of the San
Francisco hills, its sprawling Spanish-style clubhouse above the
grassy amphitheater at the 18th green and its occasional fog off
the Pacific, the Lake course at the Olympic Club is one of golf's
most pastoral panoramas.
</P>
<P>
   But for three legends of the game, it has been a gloomy
graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan, Arnold Palmer, Tom Watson; each a legend, each a
dominant golfer in his era. Together, they won 24 major golf
titles, including six U.S. Open championships (Hogan four, Palmer
and Watson one each).
</P>
<P>
   But in the three previous Opens at Olympic, each finished
second.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, so near in 1955 to what would have been his record fifth
Open title, lost in an 18-hole playoff to Jack Fleck, an obscure
touring pro.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, after blowing a 7-stroke lead with nine holes to play in
the final round in 1966, lost an 18-hole playoff to Billy Casper.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's 45-foot uphill putt on the final hole in 1987 stopped
inches short of forcing an 18-hole playoff with Scott Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   That haunting history is enough to make today's dominant players
wonder whether there is an open grave at Olympic, where the 98th
U.S. Open will start on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fleck, Casper and Simpson left with the Open trophy, but the
conversations at Olympic are usually about how Hogan, Palmer and
Watson did not win.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan even thought he had won. Walking to the scorer's tent
after a par 70 for a 287 total and what he thought was the title,
he handed his ball to Joe Dey, then the executive director of the
U.S. Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for Golf House,'' Hogan said, meaning the USGA museum.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Gene Sarazen, working as a radio commentator,
congratulated Hogan on ``your fifth Open.'' In the locker room,
weary from that Saturday's 36-hole finish, he sat on a bench and
sipped a Scotch and water. But in those years, when the leaders did
not always go off last, the virtually unknown Fleck was only one
birdie away from tying Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Fleck good enough to tie you?'' Hogan was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must be good,'' Hogan said. ``He uses Hogan clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a pro at a municipal course in Davenport, Iowa, Fleck had
recently visited Hogan's new plant in Fort Worth, Texas, to pick up
a set of the new Hogan irons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only one he let in the factory,'' Fleck has said.
``He wouldn't let any of the big names past the front door.'' Hogan
even brought two new wedges to Olympic for Fleck.
</P>
<P>
   On the 18th hole, Fleck made a sidehill 8-foot birdie putt for a
67 that created the Sunday playoff, which Fleck won, 69 to 72.
Walking off the final green, Fleck turned to Hogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it, Ben,'' he said. ``I can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleck, who now owns and operates the Lil' Bit of Heaven golf
course in Magazine, Ark., would win only two more PGA Tour events _
the 1960 Phoenix Open and the 1961 Bakersfield (Calif.) Open, but
he had snatched Hogan's fifth Open.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years later, Billy Casper snatched what would have been
Arnold Palmer's second Open.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Palmer had been America's golf icon for nearly a
decade. He fired a 3-under-par 32 on the front in Sunday's final
round and was 7 strokes ahead of Casper, who acknowledged to Palmer
that he was just hoping to finish second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to help you,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer forgot to help himself. He bogied the 10th and the 13th.
At the short 15th, he plopped his tee shot into a bunker. With a
bogey there as Casper birdied, his lead suddenly was down to 3
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Casper has said, ``is when I thought, `Hey, I can win
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the long 16th, Palmer pulled his tee shot into high rough.
Choosing a 3-iron, he slashed at the ball, but it bounded only 50
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do it again,'' he said later, ``I probably
wouldn't hit a 3-iron.''
</P>
<P>
   With another bogey there along with another Casper birdie,
Palmer's lead was now 1 stroke. At the 18th he pulled his 1-iron
tee shot into high rough. Another bogey for a 71 dropped him into a
tie at 278 with Casper, who made a par for 68. In the Monday
playoff, Palmer led by two at the turn, but let it get away and
lost, 69 to 73.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Arnie, I'm sorry,''' Casper has recalled. ``He
didn't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Casper, however, was not Fleck. Considered one of golf's great
putters, he had won the 1959 U.S. Open at Winged Foot and would win
the 1970 Masters. His 51 victories on the PGA Tour are sixth on the
career list, behind Sam Snead, Jack Nicklaus, Hogan, Palmer and
Byron Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Watson, the five-time British Open champion, had not
won on the PGA Tour for three years. But after 54 holes at Olympic,
he was 1 stroke ahead of Simpson and Keith Clearwater. And as
Watson left the 13th green in Sunday's finale, he still led Simpson
by one.
</P>
<P>
   At the 422-yard 14th, Simpson holed a 4-foot birdie putt, but
Watson also birdied there with a 20-footer.
</P>
<P>
   At the 157-yard 15th, Simpson drained a 30-foot birdie putt to
share the lead. At the 609-yard 16th, he holed a 15-foot birdie
putt to take the lead. When Simpson finished with 68 for 277,
Watson needed a birdie on the 347-yard 18th to tie.
</P>
<P>
   After a tee shot into the sloping fairway, Watson had 113 uphill
yards to the flagstick. His pitching wedge landed on the green,
then spun back, settling on the fringe, about 45 feet away. His
birdie putt was on line, but it stopped inches short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have hit a 9-iron,'' Watson said later. ``I
had a breeze at my back when I stood over the ball, but as I hit
it, the breeze at my back was in my face. A gust of wind must've
come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson had also come up, big. As a reliable grinder on the PGA
Tour for two decades, he has won seven tournaments and more than $5
million in prize money. He was granted a special exemption by the
USGA for this year's Open.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1 stroke, Tom Watson finished second in that Open at
Olympic, just as Ben Hogan and Arnold Palmer had finished second in
the other two Opens at Olympic, the graveyard for golf legends. Who
will be interred there this time?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
