<HEADLINE>
A TEAM AFFAIR: NO MATTER WHAT, WINGS KEEP WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ED WILLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In Game 3, the Detroit Red Wings used a remorseless
team defense to choke the life out of the Washington Capitals in a
2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, they emptied their offensive arsenal at the Caps,
firing 60 shots at goalie Olaf Kolzig before winning a thrilling
5-4 shootout in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   And in Game 1, the Wings offered a completely lackluster effort,
but still found a way to record a 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The story line keeps changing in the Stanley Cup finals, but the
end results have become depressingly familiar to the Caps. They
come close. They are capable of making things interesting for a
moment or two. But in the final analysis, there's a gap between the
teams, and that gap is the difference between a very good team and
a champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing our game; we're playing Red Wings hockey,''
Detroit center Igor Larionov said.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit wing Brendan Shanahan said: ``I've never played on a
team that needed and relied on the contribution of all 20 guys. I
don't think we've stolen anything from them. We haven't robbed
anybody here. When you look at the puck possession, the scoring
chances and shots on goal, I think we're playing a good series. We
deserve to be where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is on the verge of their second straight Stanley Cup under
Coach Scotty Bowman. They can close the deal on Tuesday night in
Game 4 at the MCI Center. They can also record their second
straight sweep in the finals. The games, superficially at least,
may have been close. But you can't say the same about the series.
In building their 3-0 lead, the Wings have dominated virtually
every facet of play and have demonstrated a team game that is
remarkable for its depth and versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only need to look at the Red Wings' play, whether it's
along the boards or their composure or their grit, and we haven't
matched that player for player,'' Washington's Brian Bellows said
after Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   The only mystery about the series, in fact, is how the Capitals
have managed to make each game close when they have been so
thoroughly outplayed.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3, they mustered one shot in the first 25 minutes, and
that occurred in the game's opening minute. After Bellows scored
the lone Washington goal at 10 minutes 35 seconds of the third,
Washington did not record another shot on Wings goalie Chris
Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   That was hardly an isolated trend. All told, the Wings have
outshot the Capitals 125-68 in the three games. And, while Kolzig
has been stellar in the finals thus far, he has not been good
enough to make up the difference between the teams.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The architect of the Wings' dominance is Bowman, a 64-year-old
coaching wizard, who is approaching a milestone of his own. A
victory on Tuesday would give Bowman his eighth Stanley Cup ring as
a coach, tying the career mark set by his mentor, Toe Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Blake won eight cup titles with the Montreal Canadiens from 1955
to 1968. His last victory came in '68 against the St. Louis Blues
in Bowman's first year as a National Hockey League coach.
</P>
<P>
   Like Blake, Bowman grew up in the Canadiens' chain, coaching the
Montreal Junior Canadiens in the early '60s when Blake ran the
parent club. His office was just down the hall from Blake's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can compare the two records,'' Bowman said.
``He won eight cups in 13 years. No one one will ever do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Bowman isn't a worthy successor to Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so much confidence in the coach,'' Shanahan said. ``On
some teams, 10 or 12 guys might buy into the coach's system. On our
team, everyone has complete faith in what Scotty does.''
</P>
<P>
   Larionov said: ``I feel it's a privilege to play for this team
and Scotty Bowman. He's a legend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
