<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WIN YET AGAIN, 4-2 OVER CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This old dog continues to have his day _ Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll pitch every Sunday,'' David Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly one week after he pitched his first complete game of the
season, a two-hitter against the rookie remnants of the World
Series champion Florida Marlins, Cone pitched against a more
veteran, more explosive lineup and dominated the Cleveland Indians
in the Yankees' 4-2 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old right-hander pitched eight innings, allowed four
hits and one run on Kenny Lofton's eighth-inning home run, and he
struck out 12, half on called third strikes. Tino Martinez drove in
the first three Yankee runs with a sacrifice fly and a single after
Paul O'Neill put the runners in position to score with a single and
a double.
</P>
<P>
   It was just another ho-hum victory for the Yankees, their 10th
in the last 11 games and 47th against 14 defeats this season. Cone
has a major league-best nine-game winning streak that also is his
career best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the last two starts the extra rest has helped me,''
Cone said. ``It seems my stuff is sharper. I think the extra rest
at this point in my career is probably better than working on a
regular schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain, which postponed games the previous two days, provided Cone
extra rest before this start. A dog bite forced him to take extra
time before his previous game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dog bite I had on my finger probably helped me,'' Cone
said, bringing up the incident with his mother's Jack Russell
terrier, Veronica. ``It was a blessing. It gave me a little extra
rest, gave my shoulder a break. It also made me throw my fastball
and curveball a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   The dog bite, the pitcher explained, prompted him to use his
split-fingered fastball less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really paid off over the last two starts,'' he said.
``Maybe this old dog learned some new tricks. I've been kind of
stubborn throughout the years trying to feature everything I throw.
It's kind of nice to get back to the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Indians said Cone rarely threw his fastball. Manager
Mike Hargrove estimated that his batters did not see 10 fastballs.
Manny Ramirez, a .300 hitter, saw at least two of them, both coming
with two strikes from a sidearm delivery. He watched both go by for
strike 3.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing his sidearm, or three-quarters, delivery, Cone said:
``It's something I've always featured. The key for me is to be able
to throw some fastballs sidearm. That's what I got Ramirez with
twice. The book on me is when I drop down and throw from the side,
I usually throw sliders. I've got to be able to mix it up and keep
them off balance.''
</P>
<P>
   That Cone did with the Indians. He struck out Ramirez, Omar
Vizquel, Jim Thome and Mark Whiten twice each, and he got David
Bell three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I faced a young hitter in Bell and got him with some sidearm
sliders,'' the crafty Cone said. ``I don't think he's seen that
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, a .303 hitter who had averaged one strikeout every six
at-bats, acknowledged that Cone overmatched him with his guile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I really wasn't prepared for what he was going to
throw,'' Bell said. ``After my first at-bat I knew how he was going
to work me, but I didn't make an adjustment. I knew what I wanted
to do but wasn't able to do it. I knew he was going to throw
sliders. That says a lot about how good his slider is. I knew it
was coming and still couldn't hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance served as another dramatic step in Cone's return
from off-season shoulder surgery. His early starts this season did
not give the Yankees reason to think he would reach this stage. ``I
think we were too rash,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``I'm as
responsible or as guilty as anybody that we made too much of his
early starts. He was just gaining arm strength, and it's just
getting better for him now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Athletics battered Cone for 16 runs in nine and
two-thirds innings in his first two games. The resulting 14.89
earned run average has plummeted to 4.56. Cone has been especially
effective in his last four starts, allowing 5 earned runs in 30
innings (1.50) and striking out 35.
</P>
<P>
   The game was the first between the Yankees and the Indians this
season, outlasting two days of rain to get in one of the three
games scheduled. It was their first encounter since the Indians won
the division series in last year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That was why Cone didn't mind turning the last inning over to
Mariano Rivera, who squandered a 2-1 lead in the fourth game of the
playoff series the Yankees led by two games to one. Rivera gave up
a run on two hits and a groundout but earned his 13th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was important to get him into the game against
the Indians for obvious reasons,'' Cone said. ``It was nice to see
him close it out.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre altered the pitching rotation, taking Orlando
Hernandez out of the series in Baltimore and pushing him back from
Tuesday to Thursday against the Indians in Cleveland. Torre said he
did not want to push back Hideki Irabu and Andy Pettitte yet
another day. In addition, he said, ``Pettitte has pitched pretty
good in Baltimore.'' ... Torre said that Dwight Gooden, now with
the Indians, met with him on Saturday and apologized for comments
he made about the manager earlier in the year ... The Yankees plan
to have Derek Jeter play one minor league game, probably late this
week, to test his strained abdominal muscle before they restore him
to the active roster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
