<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAYES WINS A SHOWDOWN WITH FURYK IN THE BUICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ As the pressure mounted during the final holes
of the Buick Classic on Sunday, J.P. Hayes had reasons to doubt
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes had never won on the PGA Tour. He had never played in the
final group on Sunday. He almost lost his tour card last year. And
with so much at stake Sunday, Hayes was locked in a final-round
duel with Jim Furyk, one of the game's most consistent players, who
seemed overdue for a victory.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of giving in to the tension, Hayes answered every
challenge. He hit a marvelous bunker shot at No. 18 to help force a
sudden-death playoff. He made an 8-foot birdie putt on the first
playoff hole to clinch victory. And when J.P. Hayes left
Westchester Country Club Sunday night, he left as a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the first-place check of $324,000 and securing his place
on tour for the next two years, Hayes won the Buick Classic in
dramatic fashion by beating Furyk, who suffered another
disappointing defeat. In a rain-plagued event that was shortened to
54 holes, both Hayes and Furyk shot 3-under-par 68 Sunday to finish
at 12-under 201 for the tournament, three strokes ahead of Tom
Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday, Hayes' best finish this year was a tie for 42nd
at the Greater Greensboro Chrysler Classic, and he had missed five
cuts in eight previous events, including his last two. He retained
his tour card at qualifying school last fall, but he had won just
$16,712 this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Hayes played with the serene calm of someone who had been in
contention many times before, finishing up his second round by
completing five holes in the morning, then shooting the most
important round of his career. When it was over, he sounded almost
afraid to pinch himself, fearing he might wake up from a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, it's a tremendous feeling of satisfaction
to play like that under those circumstances,'' said Hayes, whose
previous best finish was a sixth-place tie at the Anheuser-Busch
Golf Classic in 1992. ``I don't think it has hit me yet. I'm not
sure when it will.''
</P>
<P>
   The disappointment had hit Furyk, who continued to play well but
fell short. It was Furyk's seventh top-10 finish this year, and he
has 20 top-10 finishes since the start of 1997, more than anyone
else. Yet Furyk has not won since the 1996 United Airlines Hawaiian
Open, and he has grown tired of accepting condolences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really disappointed,'' said Furyk, who overcame a
three-stroke deficit with nine holes to play only to lose. ``About
50 people have already congratulated me on a great week. But when
you lose in a playoff and finish second, second just isn't good
enough.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The dramatic finish came down to the par-5, 526-yard 18th hole,
which was also the first playoff hole. Hayes reached the 18th green
in regulation holding a one-stroke lead, but Furyk hit a tremendous
second shot, a 3-wood from 260 yards that landed 12 feet short of
the pin. Meanwhile, Hayes' second shot landed in the right-side
bunker in front of the green.
</P>
<P>
   With Furyk in position for eagle, Hayes knew he probably needed
a birdie just to force a playoff. And his next shot was divine, a
soft bunker shot from 15 yards that landed less than 2 feet from
the cup, as the crowd around the green roared. Hayes tapped in for
the birdie.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was Furyk's turn to respond, and he did, making the
12-foot putt for eagle to force the playoff. But perhaps because
Hayes had endured so much in his career, the prospect of a playoff
did not faze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was calm; I really surprised myself,'' said Hayes, who will
turn 33 in August. ``In that situation, I thought I'd be throwing
up all over myself. But I've been more nervous at Q school every
year than I was at any point today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes hit a good tee shot on the playoff hole, but Furyk's went
left, hitting a tree and settling in the first cut of rough. After
Hayes hit his second shot to the back collar of the green, about 60
feet from the pin, Furyk made a crucial decision. He decided to hit
a 3-wood out of the rough from 240 yards away instead of hitting
safely back into the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't live with myself in the morning if I had layed up
and made par,'' said Fuyrk, who had also made a costly three-putt
from 21 feet at No. 14. ``It probably was the wrong shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuyrk's 3-wood was a low line drive that went left into even
deeper rough. From there, he hit a wedge onto the green, about 40
feet from the pin. After Hayes chipped his third shot to 8 feet,
Fuyrk missed his putt about 5 feet to the right, leaving Hayes the
8-footer for the victory. He didn't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   When the putt went in, Hayes raised his arms and savored a
victory he will never forget. Then he called his wife, Laura, who
was at home in El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like she was having a party,'' Hayes said. Who
could blame her? The victory gave Hayes an automatic two-year
exemption on tour, and for the first time in his career he had
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means more than the money or anything,'' Hayes said.
``This will be the first year in eight or nine years that I'm not
going to fill out an application for qualifying school. I knew if I
could control my emotions, I would have a chance. For some reason,
it all came together today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
