<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRON-MEDIATION-NYT     06-14 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRON-MEDIATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTITUTE TO MEDIATE DISPUTES ON ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   (Eds: Note that Dr. Kirk Emerson is female, so ``Dr.'' has been
used in 2nd and later references.)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to curb the sharp rise in litigation over
environmental disputes, Congress has created the first federally
financed institute to encourage mediation as an alternative to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought there had to be a way to settle these things
without all of the parties going to court,'' said Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., who sponsored the legislation. ``The solution we came up
with was the institute.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly formed Institute for Environmental Conflict Resolution
will become an extension of the Morris K. Udall Foundation based in
Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was created in 1992 to honor Udall, the former
Arizona congressman who, during 15 terms in the House, was known as
a fierce advocate for environmental causes and was credited with
often finding solutions in compromises that would make Henry Clay
proud. (Udall is in hospital with Parkinson's disease.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we are doing what Mo would have wanted us to be
doing, although he probably would not have known what a
conflict-resolution mediator was,'' said Chris Helms, director of
the Udall Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   With an average of 1,000 environmental cases a year filed with
district courts, the need for an alternative has never been
greater, said Dr. Kirk Emerson, the institute's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can arrive at good ideas without the adversarial
process,'' Dr. Emerson said.
</P>
<P>
   After an initial appropriation of $3 million to pay for a staff
of 14, the institute will receive $1.25 million annually until
2002, when it is expected to be drawing enough client fees to
support itself.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea behind mediation is simple: If two parties are
brought together and can speak with professional but neutral
experts, the theory says, a solution might be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Although federal money has been used for mediation efforts in
environmental disputes, the institute is the first federally
financed organization dedicated solely to environmental mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the process cite the Snohomish River Basin
agreement of 1974 as a dispute in which mediation techniques were
first used to resolve a complex problem.
</P>
<P>
   When, in 1959, after a major flood, the federal government
proposed a dam on the Snohomish River in Washington, it seemed that
nearly everyone within 100 miles of the dam site had something to
say. Farmers favored the dam as a way to prevent flooding, local
tribal governments worried about the impact it would have on fish,
and kayakers thought it would spoil the great white water.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years these groups, each with different lawyers, battled
in the courts. The governor, Dan Evans, looked for an alternative.
He appointed a group of 10 citizens to review the case, and within
nine months they reached an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental cases take, on average, over two years to work
their way through the courts, Dr. Emerson said, and 10 percent of
the cases take more than five years to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to deal with these more efficiently and
effectively,'' Dr. Emerson said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her biggest problem would be choosing which disputes
get mediated. ``We would like at least to give everyone a hand _
point them in the right direction. We anticipate a tremendous
interest and we will need to make tough decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
