<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8844 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-N     06-14 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JORDAN STANDS ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1; repeating for all needing.)  
(lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ If this was the end, it looked suspiciously
like the beginning. Michael Jordan against the world, a celebrated
solo act. But even with his odds reduced by age, this wasn't the
place, or the time, for Jordan to surrender pro basketball
supremacy to a couple of reticent stars who only come out to play.
He willed it that way.
</P>
<P>
   He stripped the ball from noble Karl Malone in the post, then
stole the championship hopes of the Utah Jazz. A pullup jump shot
from 18 feet as the Jazz's Byron Russell backed away, fearful of
the drive, nailed down the Chicago Bulls' sixth title of the 1990s
Sunday night at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Another season ended, another championship won, as if it were
scripted by the writers of Jordan's television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it was a flu-ridden Jordan rising out of a sick bed
to carry the Bulls in the game they had to win here. This time, it
was Jordan, at 35 not the high flier he once was, lifting himself
and his team after Scottie Pippen turned up seriously impaired with
an injured back.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five points, the Bulls' last eight, the crushing jump shot
with 5.2 seconds remaining that won Game 6 by 87-86 and finished,
finally, the long and winding pro basketball season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead, laugh all you want,'' Karl Malone had told the
snickering news media after trustingly revealing how he soothed
himself back in Chicago before his breakout in Game 4. He rode
shotgun with an Illinois state trooper, and went off to help weigh
a few trucks.
</P>
<P>
   No more laughing at Malone, at his hobbies, at the Jazz. But the
truth is, the Jazz had the Bulls right where they wanted them
Sunday night, and let them get away. The overnight analysis of the
finals is this: Utah was a fine challenger, but not a champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz couldn't put enough distance between themselves and the
Bulls while Pippen was being worked on in the locker room, couldn't
hold leads in the second half, couldn't execute its half-court
offense when Jordan was lurking, waiting for the chance to strike,
deep into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tough bunch,'' Jordan graciously called the Jazz, as he
accepted his sixth most valuable player award in as many finals
appearances. But not tough enough for him. Chicago can breathe easy
and begin calling for more, and David Stern can resume hoping that
a more ratings-friendly team than the Jazz will step up or grow up
to carry the torch and the National Basketball Association into the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the owner, Jerry Reinsdorf will turn into Al Capone
if he doesn't come up with about $80 million to underwrite his
current roster for another go-round. No one asks why CEO Jordan
can't take $10 million less so Pippen can get fair market value,
and no one contemplates the impact on the sport's smaller markets
as the larger ones push salaries to unfathomable heights.
</P>
<P>
   That's what this summer's collective bargaining showdown will be
about, how viable an auto dealer entrepreneur such as the Utah
owner, Larry Miller, will in the coming years. How many more
Stocktons and Malones are out there, relishing the thought of
getting away from the big-market glitz? Most of the kids coming in
are blinded by Jordan's fame, and never see themselves spending a
decade or more hidden away where taxis and subways don't roll.
</P>
<P>
   This is Commissioner Stern's delicate balancing act of wanting
his big-ticket teams to produce the ratings the league can crow
about this spring without reaching the point where too many
franchises become the Montreal Expos. How to maintain national _
no, Stern would say global _ interest over the course of a playoff
season that is the equivalent of four consecutive Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The big numbers were being notched courtesy of the Jordan epic,
the possibility of its conclusion, the drama heightening Sunday
night with Pippen in the locker room, doubled over, and the Jazz
pulling ahead. When Jordan exploded for 15 second-quarter points
and a 23-point first half in a shootout with Malone that kept the
crippled Bulls close, you knew he had enough ego to believe he
still had enough left to win. You just wondered if had enough legs.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the first half, as Jordan twice ignored Kukoc and
hoisted 3-pointers, leaving Kukoc shaking his head with his hands
on his hips as the half ended, another thought came to mind. Jordan
obviously was leaving this game to no one, taking himself all the
back to the mid 1980s, trying to win something all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   People always pointed out that he never won a playoff game
before Pippen came along, when he was a one-man team.
</P>
<P>
   He won the game Sunday night. The title. The repeat threepeat,
giving him one more championship in the modern era than Magic
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He stands alone. If this is the end, then Jordan Sunday night
closed a circle of greatness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
