<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STREET-VENDORS-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SEEKS COMPROMISE WITH SIDEWALK VENDORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Officials of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration
said Sunday that they had opened negotiations with sidewalk food
vendors, whose carts are to be banned from much of midtown
Manhattan and the financial district next month.
</P>
<P>
   The move was a surprise from an administration that rarely
negotiates. Deputy Mayor Rudy Washington said the city had proposed
allowing vendors to continue to work on as many as two-thirds of
the streets planned for closing, provided the vendors limit the
number of carts on busy blocks. So far, the vendors have rejected
the terms. Negotiations with them and with their chief antagonists,
several business-improvement districts, are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Washington added that if the vendors did not agree and the
streets were closed to them, the city might sell franchises to
allow a few vendors to work on some of the more desirable corners.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said the franchises would be similar to taxicab
medallions, and would be offered for vendors who sell food,
souvenirs or other merchandise. ``When we get some order on the
streets, we'll talk about that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials had announced that the police would begin
clearing pushcarts, sidewalk sales tables and street artists from
144 blocks of Manhattan in an effort to ease congestion.
Washington, the deputy mayor for community development and business
services, said he intervened at the request of both sides, and
because of his background as the founder of a construction company.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hear people yelling, `They're putting us out of
business,' that gets my ears up and I pay attention,'' he said.
``We don't view this as a compromise. We want to avoid congestion.
If we can do that based on some agreement, that's fine with us.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials had said that the ban would apply not just to
food vendors, but also to street artists, sidewalk booksellers and
general-merchandise vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed change would also benefit those groups, Washington
said. Because of their First Amendment protection, street artists
and booksellers would be able to set up anywhere that food vendors
were allowed, he said. General-merchandise vendors also would be
able to stay where they are now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Washington met with vendors and with representatives
of several business improvement districts, which had asked the city
to impose new restrictions on vending. The blocks to be closed were
selected in May by the city's Sidewalk Vendor Review Panel, which
at the time consisted of three Giuliani administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   At the Friday meeting, representatives of the business
improvement districts said they would consider modifying their
request for a broad-based ban on vending, but said they would not
go as far as Washington had suggested in a map of streets to be
kept open that he had drawn for the occasion. ``I was just trying
to start a conversation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vendors said they would agree to a limit of two vendors on
each corner but only if all streets in the city were opened to
vending, even ones that are closed now.
</P>
<P>
   Washington said that was an unrealistic position since it would
be impossible to police. ``Basically, the vendors are saying, `Let
us do what we want to do,''' he said. ``The city will never walk
away from its authority to regulate the streets.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The vendors' representative at the meeting, Dan Rossi of the Big
Apple Food Vendors Association, said he was pleasantly surprised
that Giuliani was willing to talk. ``Usually when this mayor loads
a gun, he fires it,'' he said. ``The city realizes they went
overboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington said he was willing to bring the sides together again
before the official list of street closings is published this
month. Enforcement is to begin 30 days after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at the last minute, if these guys are willing to talk and
say, `We understand the city can't just throw laws away,' we're
willing to talk and so are the BIDs,'' Washington said.
</P>
<P>
   The vendors tried to build public support by marching down
Broadway two weeks ago. They contend that the ban would force 300
carts to move and put many of them out of business because they
would be limited to working in less busy, and thus less lucrative,
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Sidewalk Vendor Review Panel votes on requests for street
closings that are submitted by citizens or private groups. An
official of one business-improvement district, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the business groups were willing to
withdraw some of their requests ``as a means of bringing peace to
the issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
