<SLUG> BC-NY-WET-YEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK IS EXPERIENCING SECOND-WETTEST YEAR ON RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sense of gloom, endless drizzle and inescapable
dampness hanging over New York is more than a gnawing hunch.
Meteorologists made it official Sunday: figures show that New York
is experiencing the second-wettest year since records were first
kept in 1869. Only the first five months of 1983 were damper.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Koval, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University,
said that 30.08 inches of precipitation fell in Central Park
between Jan. 1 and May 31 this year, about 12 inches more than
normal. The series of storms that have drenched New York this
spring, he said, is the result of an unusual air pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storms that come up the East Coast are fed their energy by
the southern branch of the jet stream,'' Koval said. ``It has been
unusually strong this year between January and May.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight day Sunday, intermittent downpours and
drizzles soaked the area. Koval and forecasters from the National
Weather Service said a break in the dank weather is not expected to
arrive until Friday because a massive low-pressure system is
stalled over the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a persistent area of low pressure in the upper atmosphere
that is very slow-moving,'' said Art Kraus, a forecaster with the
National Weather Service in Mount Holly, N.J. ``As long as it stays
in the area, there could be moisture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's rainfall did not cause widespread problems, but it
flooded Route 35 in Hazlet, N.J., contributed to a partial building
collapse on Staten Island and threatened to cause flooding across
parts of northern New Jersey and New York Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service issued flood warnings for Ulster
County, N.Y., and the Passaic River basin _ parts of Morris,
Passaic, Essex Bergen and Somerset Counties _ in New Jersey. The
Passaic and its tributaries were expected to reach flood peak
Sunday night or early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Birkhahn, a spokesman for New York City's Department of
Buildings, said that rain contributed to the collapse of a wall on
the first floor of a two-family home at 45 Caroline St. on Staten
Island at around 3 a.m. Sunday. No one was hurt. City officials
also said lightning struck a two-story building at 200 E. 110th St.
in Harlem around 12:30 p.m. on Saturday. A 30-foot section of
bricks fell into a side yard after the strike, Birkhahn said, but
no one was hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
