<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WAESCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL WAESCHE, 84, REAR ADMIRAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Md., Pa., Ohio, Wash., La., Mo., Iowa, Neb., Texas,
Calif., Ky.)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Russell Randolph Waesche Jr., a retired Coast Guard
commander and transportation executive in the Midwest, died on May
28 at his home in Leawood, Kan. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was leukemia, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Waesche was born in Thurmont, Md., the son of a future
commandant of the Coast Guard. It was in 1936, the same year that
Waesche graduated from the Coast Guard Academy at New London,
Conn., that his father became commandant, a position that he held
until 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The son served in the Pacific and on convoy duty in the Atlantic
in World War II. He later commanded Coast Guard stations in
Philadelphia, Cleveland, Washington, Seattle, New Orleans and St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the service in 1971 he was the regional
representative of the Department of Transportation for Missouri,
Iowa, Kansas and Nebraska for six years. He retired in 1988 as
executive director of the Missouri and Kansas Public Transit
Associations.
</P>
<P>
   Waesche's wife of 60 years, Janet Thorn Waesche, died last
summer. He is survived by three daughters, Judith Romero of
Arlington, Texas, Marilla Pivonka of Mill Valley, Calif., and
Jillian Seaton of Wichita, Kan.; a son, Russell III of
Williamsburg, Ky; four grandchildren, and a great-granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PARADE-NYT &LR;      06-14 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S PUERTO RICO'S DAY ON FIFTH AVENUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite a steady downpour, Fifth Avenue echoed with
the syncopated beats of salsa, flamenco and hip-hop as hundreds of
thousands of people clad in every conceivable form of their
national flag danced, cheered and sang along Sunday at the 41st
annual Puerto Rican Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   Riding atop flatbed trucks festooned with the decidedly unethnic
advertisements of countless corporate sponsors, one band after
another played ``Que Bonita Bandera (What a Pretty Flag)'' as proud
Puerto Ricans, using another name for the Caribbean island,
chanted, ``Boricua! Boricua!''
</P>
<P>
   The entire parade route, from 44th Street to 88th Street, was a
sea of rojo, blanco y azul, thanks to the creativity of paradegoers
who had fashioned their flag, with its three red stripes, lone
white star and blue triangle, into beaded necklaces, capes, floppy
hats, sweatbands, head wraps, short shorts, face paint and
fingernail polish.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Mateo of Stamford, Conn., brought his sons J.J., 5, and
Eric, who turned 4 Sunday. Each had a gold hoop and a diamond stud
through his left earlobe, and a flag-printed bandana stretched over
his head. It was the family's first Puerto Rican Day Parade. ``We
moved up from Florida six months ago,'' Mateo said. ``We didn't
know about this parade, we just saw it on TV this week. It's great.
It makes you feel proud to be Puerto Rican.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin Nieves, 64, and his wife, Juaquina, 74, who both wore
plastic bags over their heads to keep dry, said they had flown up
from Puerto Rico to visit their two daughters, who live in the
Bronx. Nieves said he and his wife always timed their trips to
catch the parade. ``On this day,'' he said, pointing to the crowd
around him, ``all Puerto Rico is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchers from Mayaguez were out in strength, and from Aguadilla,
Guanica and Coamo. There was a band from the University of Puerto
Rico at Ponce. And San Juan's native sons and daughters, it seemed,
were outnumbered only by the residents of what Carlos Ortiz, a
spectator from 161st Street, boasted was ``the largest Puerto Rican
pueblo of all _ the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   Omar Esa, 17, of Brooklyn, eating a shish kebob, said he had
watched the parade since he was about 10 years old. ``I come
because it feels good,'' he said, ``and because of the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Felix, 46, also of Brooklyn, said she had come to the last
23 parades. ``As long as God gives me life, I will come to the
parade,'' she said. ``It doesn't matter if it rains. The rain does
not stop us. This is our day.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove that point, the parade began with a procession of
politicians, among them candidates for U.S. Senate and governor,
underscoring the growing importance of Hispanic voters _ who
accounted for one in five city voters in last year's mayoral
election _ in state politics.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before the march began, Geraldine Ferraro, a Democratic
candidate for Senate, received the endorsement of Fernando Ferrer,
the Bronx borough president. Ferrer accompanied Ferraro as she
marched, and she clearly enjoyed the near-fanatical reception given
Ferrer.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, who wore a guayabera, the traditional
embroidered white shirt, with a sash saying ``Gobernador Nueva
York,'' also was loudly cheered, but he gave as good as he got.
Dashing away from his security detail, he planted a kiss on the
cheek of Adela Otero, a hospital worker from the Lower East Side of
Manhattan who was completely charmed. She said she was a Democrat,
but Pataki had chosen well. ``I voted for him,'' Ms. Otero said.
And she would again, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered among the crowd were references to the NBC comedy
``Seinfeld,'' which set one of its last episodes at the Puerto
Rican Day Parade, but offended many because it showed the island's
flag being accidentally set on fire, setting off a riotous response
by paradegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Bert Nunez, 45, of New Brunswick, N.J., carried a poster saying,
``Jerry, you burned the wrong flag.'' Nunez said that an apology by
the network, and its announcement last week that it would not
rebroadcast the episode, were not enough to make up for the
offense. ``It's a shame that this parade has to be marred by
controversy,'' he said. ``The only thing I have to tell Seinfeld
is, `Viva Puerto Rico!'''
</P>
<P>
   The real-life crowd, as several people pointedly observed, was
far more tame than the one depicted on television. Police reported
no arrests in connection with the parade. About the only friction
was generated by the Police Department itself, when it told members
of the Latino Officers Association, a group that has been critical
of the department, that they would have to march behind the banner
of a rival, officially sanctioned group, the Hispanic Society.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, spokeswoman for Police Commissioner Howard Safir,
said, ``If officers wish to march behind the banners of any other
group, they can do so, but they will have to do so in civilian
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   But such machinations were invisible to the multitudes. What was
readily apparent was that the organizers of the parade had done an
impressive job of attracting major corporate sponsors, as evidenced
by the Hershey's Kissmobile, the giant inflated bottle of Palmolive
detergent, and the two ``official'' beers (one domestic, one
imported).
</P>
<P>
   At times, the commercialism overshadowed the participants _ such
as the dancing girls and musicians attired in hats and sashes
advertising Goya Foods, who turned out to be members of the Kip's
Bay Boys and Girls Club in the Soundview section of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   But there was plenty to smile about:
</P>
<P>
   _ Julio Diaz, better known as the man in the subway who dances a
particularly erotic merengue with a foam-rubber woman tied to his
waist and toes, who wore a special gold-lame outfit just for the
day;
</P>
<P>
   _ The pop singer India, who stopped a rendition of her hit song
``Mi Mayor Venganza,'' about a jilted lover's vengeance, to rush
over and greet Cardinal John O'Connor at St. Patrick's Cathedral;
</P>
<P>
   _ A very large Steve Guzman, from the Castle Hill section of the
Bronx, whose giant flag failed to entirely cover his bare torso,
and who ran from one side of the avenue to the other, patting his
prodigious belly and drawing enthusiastic cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking it all in was Judy Cortez, 23, visiting from Honolulu.
``My friends told me to come here and represent Hawaii,'' she said.
``This is awesome!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
