u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-FLINT-1STLD     06-14 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-FLINT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY GM BUILT LOOKS AHEAD WARILY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 5th graf to correct number of striking workers, inserts new
6th graf with negotiations update.) (lh) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ It is easy to overlook the two major highways
crisscrossing this city as just a pair of well-worn roads.
</P>
<P>
   But these roads are emblems of a rich slice of U.S. history. One
is named the Chevrolet-Buick, in honor of General Motors, which
began its automobile empire here, putting food on the tables and
cars in the driveways of generation after generation. The other
highway is called the UAW, a tribute to the labor giant, the United
Auto Workers, that rose here in a legendary 1936 sit-down strike on
the factory floor of a now shuttered GM assembly plant.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the roads are ordinary yet glaring symbols of just how
tightly this city is gripped by its two most famous offspring.
</P>
<P>
   ``GM owns Flint,'' said Brad Kirfan, who co-owns a chain of
convenience stores, ``and the UAW is the town sheriff.''
</P>
<P>
   The history that binds Flint, GM and the UAW is as long and
layered as the miles of factory smokestacks that dot this city's
desolate landscape. Depending on whom you talk to here, their
tortured relationship is either wholly or at least partially at
fault for the bitter tone of simultaneous strikes by 9,000 auto
parts workers at two GM plants.
</P>
<P>
   [Negotiations between the company and UAW locals at the two
plants recessed on Sunday without an agreement, and were expected
to continue on Monday.)
</P>
<P>
   The disputes have led to the layoffs of more than 50,000 auto
workers throughout North America. And they have focused the eyes of
the nation on Flint in a way that has not been done since the 1989
documentary ``Roger and Me,'' the film by Michael Moore that
chronicled his efforts to find out why Flint was losing tens of
thousands of GM jobs.
</P>
<P>
   These days, everyone here seems to think they have the answer to
what is going on in Flint. On one side are residents and GM
employees who say that GM is trying to abandon the town it built.
On the other side are small-business owners who talk in whispers
about how the UAW seems to be determined to drive Flint's largest
employer out of town. Both groups blame city officials for not
doing more to wrest Flint from under the shadow of the automaker
and the union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows it's coming,'' said Kevin Jennings, referring
to the widely held belief that GM is quietly preparing to close its
18 factories and offices here. Jennings, 30, is the manager of
Dale's Food for Health, one of only a handful of businesses
scattered in a three-block area of boarded-up storefronts in the
downtown section. ``I wish they would just leave and get it over
with,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Jennings was a boy, GM's presence loomed so large that
Jennings and some friends, also children of GM employees, nicknamed
the company Mother Motors. ``GM has left Flint with a plant
mentality,'' he said. ``Most people can't see past the lure of the
money and cars to even think of doing something different with
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is difficult to find anything here that has not been
created or influenced by the world's largest auto maker. GM and its
33,000 employees in Flint contribute about 60 percent to the local
economy. Many of the classrooms in the five colleges and
universities here are filled by GM employees and their families,
all of whom receive tuition assistance from the automaker. One of
the schools was started by GM to help train its workers for
management and engineering positions. Now privately run, the school
is the alma mater of at least 16 current GM executives, including
the two men who head the divisions that operate the plants on
strike.
</P>
<P>
   And with more than 41,000 GM retirees and surviving spouses in
the Flint area, GM and the UAW supply much of the customer base for
the city's growing health care industry. Auto workers enjoy one of
the most generous health care plans in the nation, paying for
virtually nothing even after they retire.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Woodrow Stanley says GM has been both savior and oppressor
to Flint. ``The very large presence of GM has retarded the growth
of this community,'' he said. ``It's not something you can change
overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how long the strikes linger or how they are resolved,
Stanley says the outcome for Flint is clear: ``There is no greater
microcosm of the auto industry than Flint. And if that industry is
steadily leaving America, as we're seeing, it only stands to reason
that they're going to leave Flint.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials predict that Flint will lose 11,000 jobs over
the next two years if workers do not win job security demands at
the striking plants and other factories.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to matter to almost no one that GM plans to invest $1.5
billion here through 2001, including a $500 million engine plant.
The flight from Flint is all that people here seem to talk about,
with many of them trading stories about how they plan to beat GM
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to New York; I'm going to be a singer,'' said
Tanesha Fanter, a 22-year-old welder walking the picket line. Ms.
Fanter, who lives with her parents, went to work for GM three years
ago straight out of high school. Last year, she earned $50,000. Ms.
Fanter said that although she supports the strike, she doubts GM
will always be in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be like everybody else,'' she said, ``stay here and
collect a paycheck, but it's not worth it. This work is hard. I've
got burns all over my chest. I don't want to spend my whole life
fighting just so I can keep working in a plant. There is more to
the world than GM and Flint.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
