u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOUSE-SCRAMBLE-650     06-14 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOUSE-SCRAMBLE-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SIGN IN THE SUBURBS: SOLD OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Buying a house was not how Ron Shriberg planned to
spend his Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Rising at dawn, he was quickly where he wanted to be, at a
marina in Bayville, N.Y., getting his speedboat ready for the
cruises of summer. But a sudden rainstorm forced him to head back
to the nearby home of his in-laws, where he and his wife were
spending the weekend. On the way, he passed an open-house sign in
front of a fetching four-bedroom Cape Cod-style house in Bayville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had that warm, appealing home look, something you could
move into and really feel comfortable,'' said Shriberg, a
29-year-old office-equipment salesman from Woodside, Queens.
</P>
<P>
   In the superheated real estate market of 1998, where he had
already lost a house to a cutthroat rival, Shriberg went into
overdrive. He rustled his wife, Laureen, out of her pajamas and
drove her over to look. Four hours after first seeing the house,
they made an offer of $260,000 that was accepted just moments ahead
of two rival bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that if we saw something we truly loved, we needed
to act fairly quickly,'' Shriberg said, not quite appreciating his
own understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in New York City, where co-ops and condominiums are
being snapped up soon after they go on sale, houses in New York
City's suburbs are moving faster than ice cream in July. Once an
aberration, the house that goes on the market and is spoken for the
same day is becoming routine. As a result, houses are selling for
more _ sometimes substantially more _ than their asking price, and
bidding wars that would warm the heart of a Sotheby's auctioneer
are becoming an everyday occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a market in which you want to dillydally,'' said P.
Gilbert Mercurio, executive vice president of the Westchester
County Board of Realtors. ``If you like the house and the price is
right, you should act, because if you don't act, it may be some
time before you find another property.''
</P>
<P>
   Many reasons are being given for the frenzied suburban market,
in which house sales in areas like Westchester and Fairfield
County, Conn., are up more than 20 percent from a year ago and
prices are up as much as 15 percent. The economy is humming, the
stock market is bullish, and interest rates for some types of
mortgages are below 7 percent. As a result, far more people have
the wherewithal to buy. Shriberg's fourfold jump in income over two
years allowed him and his wife to consider moving out of their
Queens apartment.
</P>
<P>
   With the co-op and condo market in New York City also sizzling,
it is easy to cash in an apartment and buy that longed-for Tudor on
a cul-de-sac where the kids can learn to ride a bicycle and kick
around a soccer ball. At the same time, more suburban homeowners
have the money to trade up to that bigger house with the guest
room, the third bathroom and the large kitchen they have always
craved.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the madness is fueled by a tight supply of
houses. The seven slow years of the late 1980s and early 1990s left
many houses languishing on the market. But about two years ago,
they began to move, and now the inventory, as they are referred to
in the real estate trade, is depleted.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of 1998, only 3,945 single-family houses in
all of Westchester were on the market, a 24 percent decline from
the 5,171 listed in the first quarter of 1997. As a result, the
average price of a house in Westchester _ $403,020 _ is 7 percent
higher than it was a year ago. In Nassau County, the number of
homes for sale has dropped from 8,132 in April 1997 to 5,979 this
April, and the average price is up 13 percent. In Fairfield County,
where inventory figures were not available, the average price of a
single-family house is $320,475, a 14.9 percent increase from a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In such a market, it helps to pounce.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Darlene Bandazian, manager of the Weichert Realtors office in
Ramsey, N.J., recalled how one of her agents received a listing on
a recent Saturday for a $290,000 house in Mahwah. He scheduled an
open house for the next day and, having no time to place a
newspaper advertisement, posted a dozen fliers on lampposts and
street signs. Fifty couples showed up, three of whom made offers.
The house was sold at its asking price.
</P>
<P>
   In such a market, it even helps to bribe _ legally, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Karla Renz-Mcleod and Steven McLeod of Forest Hills, Queens,
fell in love with a three-bedroom house in Stamford, Conn., with a
flagstone patio and a lush garden. But they mistakenly decided to
compare a few other houses before making an offer. By the time they
returned that afternoon, another couple _ in a Mercedes _ was
inspecting the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see the wife was making these motions like, `This is
where the second floor can be expanded,''' said Ms. Renz-McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   The McLeods put in a bid of $285,000 but couldn't match the one
by their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using cash for the deal, all inspections waived,''
said Ms. Renz-McLeod. ``How can you compete with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Vera Blendermann, a broker for Houlihan Lawrence in
Bronxville, told of a large Colonial on one acre that went on sale
on a Thursday for $1.5 million. A half-dozen written bids came in,
and when they were opened on Sunday, the highest was from someone
who had not only offered more than $100,000 beyond the asking price
but was also willing to put up enough assets to forgo a mortgage
approval and an engineer's inspection, and to close on the house
whenever it suited the seller.
</P>
<P>
   ``What better terms can you give than removing your mortgage
contingency, removing your engineering inspection and closing at
the convenience of the seller?'' Ms. Blendermann said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some buyers say they feel betrayed by sellers unable
to resist better offers. In March, Shriberg shook hands with the
broker on a $230,000 deal for a waterfront ranch house in
Oceanside, in Nassau County. Shriberg signed a contract and sent in
an $11,500 deposit, but the seller never put his signature on the
contract or cashed the check. Instead, the owner sold the house
privately _ no broker was involved _ to a remote acquaintance who
came up with $250,000 in cash. Though they got their deposit back,
the Shribergs were left in the lurch.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, people have a lot more money,'' Shriberg said.
``The seller's friend realized, `I better step up to the plate or
I'll lose the house.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though not every broker agrees, Mary Grimm, a veteran broker for
C.S. McClellan in Pelham, in Westchester, said the current market
is giddier than even the bustling market of the mid-1980s. And it
seems to touch most locations and price ranges. Denise Smith, a
spokeswoman for Weichert Realtors, said that sales are at their
most feverish in the ``classic suburban bedroom communities as
opposed to the more urban and rural areas.'' In western Bergen
County, N.J., for example, the hottest locations are Wyckoff,
Ramsey, Mahwah, Allendale and Franklin Lakes. In Westchester,
suburbs like Scarsdale, Larchmont and Pelham are hopping.
</P>
<P>
   The mania has changed the way brokers, buyers and sellers
behave. Rather than merely worry about how to best articulate the
features of a house, brokers have to concentrate on convincing the
suspicious buyer that the race is to the swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be on top of the market,'' said Jackson B.
Browning, president of Julia Fee Realty, which has offices
throughout Westchester. ``It's not a part-time job. They have to be
active, have to know what's coming on the market the minute it's in
the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lampl, a broker at Wykagyl/Rittenberg Realty in New
Rochelle, said she tried to avoid putting overt pressure on a
client she took to houses in Scarsdale and New Rochelle. But
experience provided a telling lesson.
</P>
<P>
   In Scarsdale, the Tudor was swarming with brokers _ upstairs,
downstairs, in the attic, in the yard. They peered, poked, sniffed,
opened and closed closets and then were briskly off to examine
other prospects. Ms. Lampl coolly escorted her pregnant client,
Gail Herman, through the frenzy, pointing out the three-bedroom
house's low taxes, good school district and proximity to the
Scarsdale train station.
</P>
<P>
   But the Scarsdale house vanished the same day, before Mrs.
Herman had even considered making an offer. Mrs. Herman, a
30-year-old school psychologist who has been living with her
stockbroker husband, Michael, in a one-bedroom apartment in White
Plains, was not disappointed. Just that morning, she had seen a
1940s white Colonial cottage with red shutters in a congenial
neighborhood in New Rochelle, a house with offbeat moldings,
dormered ceilings and lots of nooks and crannies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charming. Gail likes charming,'' Ms. Lampl had already noted.
</P>
<P>
   So Mrs. Herman took her husband, weary from a day of work, to
see the house that same evening. The next day, she showed it to her
mother. On the third day, she made an offer. It was too late, of
course. In the frantic market of 1998, three days might as well
have been three years. Someone else had beaten her to the punch.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Herman was stoic. ``There will always be another house,''
she said. But Ms. Lampl said she would not be surprised if Mrs.
Herman took a different tack the next time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts me in an awkward position,'' she said of the hot
market. ``I don't want to pressure people and don't want them to
feel they have to hurry up, but when things like this happen, then
the second time around they act a lot more quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
