<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN ENDORSES ACCOUNTING BOARD DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., La.)  (lb) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the fierce debate has been settled on how banks should
account for complex securities, the Federal Reserve Board chairman,
Alan Greenspan, has thrown his support behind the accounting rule
makers who rejected his recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 4 letter, Greenspan said that he was concerned about
legislation now pending in Congress aimed at weakening the power of
the rule makers, the Financial Accounting Standards Board.
</P>
<P>
   The bills were introduced after banks complained to legislators
about the accounting board's attempt to force companies to record
the value of financial derivatives in their financial statements.
Greenspan had joined the banks in criticizing the accounting board
for that proposal. And, the rule makers' opponents have been using
the chairman's past comments to help win support for the two bills.
</P>
<P>
   But in his letter addressed to Arthur Levitt Jr., the chairman
of the Securities and Exchange Commission, Greenspan said that he
approved of the way that accounting rules are now set by the
privately financed board, which works on the commission's behalf
and is known by its initials, FASB.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I have not always agreed with FASB's ultimate
conclusions, I have always felt that the openness of the process
allows all affected parties sufficient opportunity to contribute to
the debate,'' Greenspan wrote in the letter, a copy of which was
given to The New York Times by people who support the accounting
board. ``I share your concerns that pending congressional
legislation could disrupt existing accounting standards and impair
the ongoing accounting standards-setting process by subjecting it
to unnecessary pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   The accounting board voted to finalize the rules on derivatives
late last month, angering the banks and adding heat to the debate.
Derivatives are complicated contracts between two or more parties
where the contract's value is derived from a stock, an index or a
commodity.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Sen. Lauch Faircloth, who has introduced a bill that
would exempt banks from using the new derivatives rule unless
banking regulators approve, said he did not believe that
Greenspan's letter would affect the senator's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The aide, James Hyland, said that Faircloth, a Republican from
North Carolina, plans to hold hearings on the board in the
subcommittee that he heads in the Senate Banking Committee. Hyland
said that the accounting rule makers had ``put on a full court
press, saying that we don't want Congress involved in setting
accounting standards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They should not feel that they are immune to any congressional
action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another bill in the House would require federal securities
regulators to approve any new rule proposed by the accounting
board. The bill by Rep. Richard Baker, R-La., would also make it
easier for companies to challenge the accounting rules in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
