<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8871 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-300&AMP;     06-14 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BULLPEN SQUANDERS NOMO'S GEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ On a searing subtropical afternoon, Hideo Nomo did his
part. But the New York Mets' bullpen wasn't nearly as effective.
</P>
<P>
   What had figured to be a painless wrap-up to the Mets' four-game
series against the Florida Marlins turned into a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   A four-run eighth inning allowed the Marlins to tie the game,
4-4, and they won it by 5-4 with a two-out rally in the ninth
before 23,924 at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Mets to 37-27 and spoiled the first
scoreless outing of the season for Nomo (2-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very ugly game,'' catcher Alberto Castillo said.
``We just gave it away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins strung together three straight hits to win it, one
coming on a bouncer through shortstop. Rey Ordonez had moved to
cover second base on Edgar Renteria's steal attempt. Todd Zeile won
the game on a broken-bat single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' offense collapsed as much as their relief pitching.
From the sixth inning on, they were 0-for-7 with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   The hitting drought occurred with Butch Huskey, who has had a
balky right knee, in the dugout, benched in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't ask to be taken out,'' Huskey said. ``It wasn't my
decision.'' Manager Bobby Valentine said Huskey has a ``hobbled
knee.''
</P>
<P>
   The heat apparently made Sunday a bigger challenge for Nomo, the
Japanese right-hander acquired recently from the Los Angeles
Dodgers. ``These are not his favorite conditions to pitch, from
what I have heard,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the test, the Mets chose to wear black jerseys on this
humid 88-degree day, rather than their grays. Actually, Carlos
Baerga made the decision after Charlie Samuels, the equipment
manager, called out in the locker room for someone to make a
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lighter uniform,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nomo struggled with his control from the outset. With one out in
the first, Renteria singled, then stole second. Todd Dunwoody
walked. But Nomo got out of the inning when Zeile struck out and
Castillo threw out Dunwoody on the back end of an attempted double
steal.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Cliff Floyd doubled to open the inning and Ryan
Jackson sacrificed him to third. Then, with a drawn-in infield,
Baerga speared Craig Counsell's liner, and Nomo struck out Mike
Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Marlins reached base in the third with one out, but
Nomo struck out Dunwoody and induced Zeile to bounce to short.
</P>
<P>
   After Livan Hernandez, the World Series most valuable player,
retired eight straight batters between the first and third innings,
the Mets managed a run with two outs in the third. Luis Lopez was
hit by a pitch, then Edgardo Alfonzo doubled to the
left-center-field wall with Lopez racing home.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo did more clutch hitting in the fifth. Nomo beat out a
two-out infield single and Lopez doubled off the left-field wall.
Alfonzo hit a full-count fastball to right to score both runners.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo left after six innings. He allowed four hits, three walks
and struck out seven while throwing 93 pitches, 51 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a humid day, and he'd done some running,'' Valentine
said. ``I thought I'd turn it over to the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Little did he realize how dicey that would be. Mel Rojas and
Brian Bohanon were jolted for four runs in the eighth. Doubles by
Renteria and Zeile scored the first two runs, bringing in Bohanon.
He gave up a two-run home run to Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd keep throwing him inside until he proved he
could hit it,'' Bohanon said of Floyd. ``I just didn't do the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, the leadoff hitter, was a bright light in this emotional
rainstorm. The left fielder had a perfect game. He singled twice,
doubled, was hit by a pitch and walked.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was asked if this defeat will last a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we play again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Piazza, who missed the last two games with a
strained right shoulder, hit the ball hard during batting practice
Sunday and likely will play Tuesday, according to Manager Bobby
Valentine. ... Outfielder Bernard Gilkey, hit on the left eye
Friday night, also took batting practice but said he felt ``about
the same'' as the day before, when swelling around the eye affected
his vision. ... Armando Reynoso, who has been bothered with elbow
tightness, pitched in a simulated game Sunday, and was expected to
start Thursday for Class A Port St. Lucie, Fla. He will see catcher
Todd Pratt, who has had a nerve disorder in his right shoulder, and
who made his debut for Port St. Lucie on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
