<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RIGGING THE NUMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 15:
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans want to cut taxes, but some of them are queasy
about the spending cuts needed to make the numbers work out. It
would be so much easier if someone could just apply a magic wand to
make everything balance without having to face difficult choices.
Fortunately for the public purse, the rules now do not allow for
invented numbers. Instead, the nonpartisan Congressional Budget
Office estimates the budget effect of tax and spending proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The intellectual honesty of the Budget Office, and its
reluctance to assume that whatever the Republicans propose will
magically make the economy boom, has so angered Speaker Newt
Gingrich and the rest of the Republican leadership that they have
embarked on a campaign to intimidate it. A letter from the entire
GOP leadership to the key Appropriations subcommittee warned that
if the office did not immediately start to produce more palatable
numbers, ``we must review [its) structure and funding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have a point when they say that recent budget
forecasts have been too cautious. The strength of the American
economy has surprised economists and produced tax revenues well
above estimates. But it would be very risky to assume that the
``Goldilocks economy'' _ not too hot and not too cold _ will
continue indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans need to face the hard choices in putting
together a budget. They should stop trying to intimidate the
professionals who have served Congress, and the public, very well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980614.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-14 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GIULIANI-COLUMN-NY     06-14 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A SPOT TO HIDE FROM THE JOKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A hurricane sweeps up the Eastern Seaboard toward New
York City, packing 100-mile-an-hour winds.
</P>
<P>
   A bomb blast destroys a power plant, plunging Brooklyn and
Queens into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   A terrorist group vows to release nerve gas in a crowded subway
station, pushing the city toward hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Such crises could happen, and a metropolitan center like New
York is particularly vulnerable, which helps account for Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's plans for an emergency control center. As the
mayor explains it, the city needs the control center so that its
leaders can respond to disasters with all the speed and
effectiveness that cutting-edge technology can provide.
</P>
<P>
   So why is everyone laughing?
</P>
<P>
   No sooner were the mayor's plans for the $15 million command
bunker revealed over the weekend, than the visionary scheme became
a target for practically every would-be humorist in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Sliwa and Ron Kuby devoted four hours of their radio
program to lampooning the project on Saturday morning. During the
show, listeners participated in a name-that-shelter contest, which
produced such winning entries as ``Rudy's Nuclear Winter Palace''
and ``The Nut Shell.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Council speaker, Peter Vallone, joined in the
not-quite-harmless fun, noting that ``the mayor's actions are
increasingly bizarre.'' He added, ``If he wants to build a bunker
for the only people he trusts, all he needs is a phone booth.''
</P>
<P>
   A clearly delighted former Mayor Edward Koch declared, ``It's
the joke of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   In a highly symbolic business like politics, it is sometimes the
truly consequential blunders that matter, and sometimes just the
ones that make good sense metaphorically. Had George Bush ever laid
eyes on a supermarket scanner before that fateful day in 1992?
Probably he had.
</P>
<P>
   Did Dan Quayle know the correct spelling of ``potatoe''? Quite
possibly.
</P>
<P>
   Does New York City need a state-of-the-art emergency control
center, with enough water to last a week, a secure line to the
president and a ventilation system that can be closed in case of a
biological attack?
</P>
<P>
   Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   In the course of his eminently successful career, Giuliani has
already done more than his fair share of unsettling things. Whether
dressing up in sequins or harassing hot dog vendors, his actions
have often been characterized by an element of excess, a ``l'etat,
c'est moi'' quality that has left even his critics slightly agape.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely has he seemed, symbolically speaking, on such
dangerous ground.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that the center is, on the face of it, an outrageous
project, or even that its most grandiose elements are out-and-out
absurd. Who knows, maybe it would be useful to be able to hold a
video conference with the president during a bomb scare, a flood or
a really ugly sewer-main break.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that the project seems to speak too clearly to
the mayor's fears and, worse still, his hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has always governed as if from a bunker, with chaos
threatening from all sides and enemies all around. On some deep
level _ well, maybe not so very deep _ one senses that nothing
would please him more than having an antagonist truly worthy of his
energies instead of just a ragtag bunch of disgruntled taxi
drivers, street artists and unemployed strippers.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the news of the multimillion-dollar command center
got out, aides to the mayor did their best to quash the story. The
mayor was not building a Strangeglovian bunker, they said, noting
that it was going to be equipped with only a fold-out couch. They
also disputed charges that the bunker was being built in secret,
pointing to a one-line entry on page 995 of the city's capital
budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly laid out in the budget for anyone to inspect and
review,'' said Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Aides even objected to the term ``bunker,'' with its paranoid
Cold War connotations; it is ``not a bunker,'' insisted Jerome
Hauer, director of the city's Office of Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, at a news conference on Saturday, defended the bunker
with characteristic vigor, accusing critics of playing politics
with the safety of millions of New Yorkers. And he made a special
point of correcting the notion that in planning for disaster, he
was thinking about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for the benefit of the mayor,'' he said. ``It's for
the benefit of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   So will everyone please stop laughing?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-14-98 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
